<html>
	<head>
		<title>Government Sites</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/forums/index.html+Worth2.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth2.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>Government Sites</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						<br>The government has set up a number of Web sites which may be of great use to the 'Net-surfing investor. What's more, these sites tend to be clearly laid out, easy-to-use, and chock full of really useful content.<p>
Though not a source of direct investor information, the <a href="http://www.house.gov/armey.flattax/">The Flat Tax Home Page</a href> site, sponsored by Republican Congressman from Texas, Dick Armey, is worth a passing look for the true capitalist. In a few clear paragraphs and links, the Flat Tax site describes the crisis we face ("Our government is too big, and it spends, taxes, and regulates too much."), piquantly criticizes our current system of taxation ("perhaps the greatest ball-and-chain on America's freedom and prosperity"), and proposes a 17 percent flat tax "so simple [that] Americans can file their taxes on a form the size of a postcard." No kidding; the site shows a sample flat tax return form. Its brevity makes it look like a joke, but it ain't. The site also features links to the Constitution and Declaration of Independence. <p>
Another great source of Web info from the feds may be found at the <a href="http://www.fdic.gov/">Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) World Wide Web Home Page</a href>. The FDIC was established in 1933 to insure bank deposits and thereby "maintain stability and public confidence in the nation's banking system." The FDIC Web site, in addition to providing a range of information resources for the individual banking consumer, gives good, clear statistics on the state of the U.S. banking industry. These stats may be helpful for the investors following the banking sector, or as an indicator of the nation's overall economic status.<p>
The <a href="http://www.ftc.gov/">Federal Trade Commission (FTC)</a href> has also set up a useful and easy-to-navigate Web site. The FTC is the government's main watchdog for unfair commercial practices. The site recently featured information on how to avoid being drawn in by pyramid marketing scams, phony scholarship hawkers, and specious "wealth-building" rackets in real estate. Link to the government's <a href="http://www.financenet.gov/">FinanceNet</a href> page for a summary of how various agencies are spending your tax dollars.<p>
You know all those public information brochures that emanate mysteriously from Pueblo, Colorado? Well, they come from the <a href="http://www.pueblo.gsa.gov/">Consumer Information Center</a href>, which now has its own Web site. This comprehensive clearinghouse of consumer info documents--most of which are either cheap, free and/or online--has a lot of useful stuff for the would-be investor. Click on the "money" button to see documents on how to invest in Treasury securities, how to choose a broker, and how to avoid investment swindles. You might spend hours at this site looking at communiques on everything from credit cards to funerals. Oddly, there's even a rather thorough chronology of the U.S. Civil War! <p>
Perhaps the most useful source of macroeconomic data may be found at the <a href="http://www.bls.gov/">Bureau of Labor Statistics</a href> (BLS) Web site.  Click around the site for "economy at a glance," which gives key indicators like statistics on unemployment, earnings, productivity, and regional labor market data. Nifty lime-green maps pop up to accompany regional data. The BLS page is also a good place to get consumer price index (that is, inflation) data.<p>
No investor will want to surf the Web without at least glancing at the home page of the SEC--<a href="http://www.sec.gov/">Securities & Exchange Commission</a href>. Novice investors will want to click on "What Every Investor Should Know," while the EDGAR Database of Corporate Information will be useful to newcomers and wizened market players alike. The "Investor Education and Assistance" area contains an array of useful items. Would-be Warren Buffetts may access dense, full-text filings at a click.<p>
The <a href="http://www.occ.treas.gov/">Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC)</a href> has a multifacteed site on the Web. For those brave few who invest in derivatives, the OCC site offers a good overview of the derivatives market, though it's best if you're familiar with some of the derivative market jargon before diving in here.

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
					</font>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

