<html>
	<head>
		<title>Exchanges</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/forums/index.html+Worth2.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth2.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>Exchanges</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						<br>Most of the major securities exchanges have set up Web sites. These are often good places for the novice stockpicker to begin sifting around for investing information. Quotes, news advisories, educational areas, and abundant links are all pretty common. <p>
The New York Stock Exchange's <a href="http://www.nyse.com/">NYSE NET </a href> is more comprehensive than others and goes further in their mission to "educate and inform individuals about the capital raising process." (Click on "Visitors Center" for a look at the bustling trading floor!) Also check out the <a href="http://www.amex.com/">American Stock Exchange </a href>, and the <a href="http://www.cme.com/">Chicago Mercantile Exchange</a href>, which has a good glossary of futures and options terms (under the "About the Exchange" area).<p>
<a href="http://www.optionscentral.com/">OIC</a href> is the Web site of the Options Industry Council. The Council, which was formed in 1992, seeks to "educate brokers and investors on listed equity options" and includes five exchanges: Amex, Nysex, CBOE, Pacific Stock Exchange, and the Philadelphia Stock Exchange. The options world can be a confusing one so the OIC page is a useful place for newcomers to learn more.  <p>
Investors following Canadian companies should hook into the <a href="http://www.visions.com/">Canada Net Pages</a href>, which contains end-of-day quotes from the Toronto, Vancouver, Alberta, and Montreal stock exchanges (click on "Stocks & Bonds").

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
