	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>Mega Sites</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						<br>There are a couple of good mega-sites out there that either house or link to a vast amount of financial and business information.<p>
The <a href="http://www.cob.ohio-state.edu/~fin/">Ohio State University Department of Finance</a href> home page  not only hooks you into all the usual assortment of quotes and company profiles, it gives lots of free advice on where to go if you're engaged in advanced financial or economic research. "Couch Potato Investing" is worth a look for the less adept investor. Click into the "Financial Data Finder" to peruse the virtually limitless resources available via the Ohio State site.<p>
Canadian business journalist Mathew Ingram's <a href="http://www.want2know.com/invest/">High-Tech Investor</a href> provides quotes, news, and other predictable linkage, as well as lots of useful caveats and suggestions for the armchair security-picker. As Worth put it in <a href="/articles/Z960W02.html/">"Get There From Here"</a href> (April 1996), High-Tech leads you to a plethora of "interesting finds that many are likely to miss," such as the <a href="http://www.web.net/ethmoney/">Canadian Ethical Investment Web Site</a href>.
					</font>
