<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - Due Diligence (Part 1)</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Investor%20101>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investor 101</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>Due Diligence (Part 1)</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Knowing what to look for on a financial statement can help you spot troubles with your investment before it's too late. In Part 1, Worth walks you through three critical items--accounts receivables, inventory, and gross margins.<p>
By Jonathan Burton<p>
Had Andy Warhol worked on Wall Street, he might have predicted every stock would get 15 points of upside. Kendall Square Research, a supercomputer maker based in Waltham, Massachusetts, had its moment of glory in 1994. Between April and October, its share price nearly doubled, helped by positive earnings estimates from analysts and speculation that the company might become a high-tech star.<p>
But when Kendall Square announced in late October that it would report a third-quarter loss, the stock began a hasty retreat. The shares, which had closed at $24.25 on October 28, fell 32 percent the next day. Then, shareholders discovered that Henry Burkhardt III, Kendall Square's chief executive and founder, had dumped $1 million of his own holdings back in August. The share price kept skidding as more bad news hit: restated earnings--lower than originally 
reported--and withering revenue. By mid-April, the stock was down to $2.88 a share, and Burkhardt had departed as chief executive.<p>
The crash of this highflier shouldn't have come as a complete surprise--at least not to investors who know how to examine a company's financial reports and follow up with the right questions. As far back as August of 1993, Kendall Square's publicly available financial statements flashed a warning: The company was taking as long as five months to get paid by its customers. Shareholders could have spotted this red flag in quarterly reports and acted on it in time to avoid the beating the stock would take months later. But they had to know where to look.<p>
Trouble on a financial statement is not always easy to uncover. Some companies are better at explaining away accounting cosmetics than they are at selling their products. And not every number that raises a question is a sign of impending disaster. But the more an investor knows about how companies present their financial results, the better, and reading the public reports that companies prepare should be part of every investor's homework.<p>
Doing this doesn't require an accounting degree. A diligent investor can, in fact, gain essential information--the kind that could protect against a Kendall Square and some other recent flameouts--by concentrating on several critical lines in the public documents that any investor-relations office will mail out for free.<p>
But isn't this a job for securities analysts? Well, yes, but Wall Street doesn't catch everything--at least not right away. The Street also doesn't always say what it thinks, even if it knows. Brokerage-firm analysts are caught between a stock and a hard place. A Chinese wall theoretically separates securities analysts from the corporate-finance department, which helps companies issue new stock and debt. Supposedly, an analyst could blast a corporate-finance client with a negative report, but it doesn't happen too often. Analysts tend to dig deeper once a company or an industry has tanked, turning into investigators at the crash site who hope the morning after can offer clues about what happened and why.<p>
Yet, for obvious reasons, it's much better to ask why a stock is hot when it still is. Is its popularity sound or just a fad? Many factors can drive a stock up, but only fundamentals will keep it there.<p>
In Part 1, we'll zero in on three crucial entries in the financial statements that companies compile for Securities and Exchange Commission regulators in Washington and that current shareholders get regularly--quarterly 10-Qs and annual 10-Ks. The three lines cover accounts receivable, inventory, and gross profit margins. In Part 2, we'll take a look at three other important categories. Knowing how to interpret these items is fundamental to guarding against unexpected trouble in a stock. The flipside: Investors also can turn up buying opportunities when they discover balance sheets with strong numbers in these categories.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Accounts Receivable: The snare at Kendall Square</font></b><p>
Henry Burkhardt III was exuberant about Kendall Square Research, the supercomputer maker he started in 1986 with the backing of William Koch, millionaire yachtsman and America's Cup winner. Enthusiasm came naturally to the 49-year-old president and chief executive, who first made his name as a cofounder of Data General. His reassuring manner proved valuable when dealing with Wall Street's restless stable of stock analysts and investors. But on a cloudy day last August at the company's headquarters outside Boston, Burkhardt didn't have to sell anyone; Wall Street had done that for him. Analysts saw the company earning 45 to 50 cents a share in 1993, eclipsing 1992's $1.22-a-share loss. Revenues would nearly triple, to $60 million, they felt. They forecast a third-quarter profit of between 8 cents and 13 cents a share.<p>
Was Burkhardt comfortable with these estimates? A Wall Street Journal reporter asked him that in an August 12 interview.<p>
"Quite comfortable," Burkhardt replied. The next day, Kendall Square's stock spiked up 75 cents a share to $19.75.<p>
Nevertheless, a glance at Kendall Square's quarterly Form 10-Q for the second quarter ended June 26 would have revealed a disquieting element in this scene. It could be found on a single line on the balance sheet, the one that said "accounts receivable."<p>
Receivables tell how much customers owe a company. Veteran financial analyst Thornton O'glove, author of <i>Quality of Earnings</i>, says accounts receivable is a particularly important figure, one that can reveal a great deal about a company and its payment terms. "Watch it over consecutive quarters," he advises. <p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Computer maker Kendall Square Research showed this big jump in accounts receivable--a troubling sign.</font></b><p>
The same day Burkhardt was meeting with the Journal reporter, Nasdaq officials received Kendall Square's second-quarter filing. It showed that the company's accounts receivable had jumped 57 percent in the first six months of the year, to $20.9 million from $13.3 million. The increase was partly explained by the fact that the company's reported sales, or revenue, had also risen sharply. (These numbers looked even gloomier when they were later restated by the company. But for the purposes of this article, we want to focus on information available to shareholders at the time.)<p>
In addition to telling how much the company expects to collect from its customers, however, receivables reveal another important thing: how long the company is waiting to get paid. Investors can make this calculation through a two-step process. First, divide revenue by the number of days in the period. Then, divide the amount listed for receivables by this result. In Kendall Square's case, this calculation would have shown that the company was sending out bills and then waiting an average of 154 days to get paid--about five months.<p>
Faced with that answer, an investor might want to ask a few questions: Are customers disappointed in the product? Is the sales force extending payment schedules in an effort to inflate revenue? <p>
Michael Murphy, who as editor of the Overpriced Stock Service newsletter in Half Moon Bay, California, earns a living watching such things, says companies show this kind of patience with customers for only two reasons: "Either the product's not working, or the company has granted the customer extraordinary terms." Leniency, he says, lets some companies "maintain their revenue-growth pattern so Wall Street will keep their stock up." <p>
Kendall Square did have more to say on the subject in the June 1993 10-Q, attributing its growing receivables in part to "the granting of extended payment terms to certain customers." The company declined to answer further questions from Worth about its receivables, saying that officers familiar with the issue have left the company and are not available for comment. <p>
Allowing receivables to build is not uncommon among aggressive, expanding companies like Kendall Square. Also, receivables may fluctuate more at a company that sells relatively few big-ticket products, like supercomputers--because a single sale may represent as much as 5 percent of revenue.<p>
Still, an investor who notices that a company is taking a long time to get paid has reason to be wary and should investigate further. Is the company managing its credit well? What do customers and competitors think of the company's products? Are soft credit terms an attempt to make up for prices that are too high? Rising receivables are an especially important red flag for companies that sell products based on rapidly evolving technology or fast-moving fashion. For these reasons, receivables always merit close scrutiny.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>Inventories: Riding the Merry-Go-Round</font></b><p>
Merry-Go-Round Enterprises, the clothing retailer for dedicated followers of young men's and women's fashion, was looking natty as a company. It was March of last year, and the Joppa, Maryland-based outfit had just announced the acquisition of Chess King, a rival clothing chain, a move that would give it the biggest share of the young -men's clothing market. Merry-Go-Round told brokerage-firm analysts that the purchase would add $13 million, or 15 cents a share, to profits for the year. So some Wall Street analysts raised their earnings estimates for Merry-Go-Round. <p>
The company's stock rose $2.25, or 15 percent, to $17 on the day of the Chess King news. Merry-Go-Round was hot--$100 of its stock in January 1988 was worth $804 five years later. Last year, the chain owned 1,460 stores in 44 states, mostly under the Cignal, Chess King, and Merry-Go-Round names.<p>
But Merry-Go-Round spun out. The company lost $544,000 in the first six months of 1993, compared with earnings of $13.5 million in the first half of 1992. Last fall, Leonard "Boogie" Weinglass, Merry-Go-Round's flamboyant founder and chairman, who started the company in 1968, boarded up his Merry-Go-Ranch in Aspen, Colorado, and returned to management after a 12-year hiatus. But the ponytailed, shirtsleeved entrepreneur--the inspiration for the character Boogie in the movie Diner--couldn't save his company from bankruptcy. In January of this year, the company filed for Chapter 11 protection in Baltimore. Shares crumbled below $3. <p>
Was there any advance warning of all this? In Merry-Go-Round's annual report for the fiscal year ended January 30, one balance sheet item in particular stands out: "merchandise inventories." Inventory is unsold goods and considered an asset. As a rule, inventories should rise in tandem with sales. If inventories rise faster, it may be because the goods simply aren't selling. This is particularly true of companies in faddish or seasonal businesses--Merry-Go-Round's world.<p>
<p><a name="SUB4"><b><font size=+1>Inventories at fashion retailer Merry-Go-Round grew substantially in fiscal 1993. The annual report was a warning.</font></b><p>
The company's report showed that inventories on January 30 were $82.2 million, up 37 percent from $60 million a year earlier. That's well above the 15 percent sales growth in the same period, to $877.5 million from $761.2 million. This alone should have been a major cause for concern. It indicated the company's goods simply weren't selling as rapidly as it expected, causing its inventories to bulge. <p>
Merry-Go-Round officials don't see it that way. At that time, "the company was doing quite well," says a Merry-Go-Round spokesman. "We were anticipating additional stores and additional growth." But the spokesman also acknowledges that the company "bought for expected sales that did not develop."<p>
The inventory problem was more obvious a quarter later. Merry-Go-Round's May 1, 1993, 10-Q showed a 48 percent increase in inventories over its January 30 level and a 49 percent rise over the level a year earlier. Sales over the year, however, had gone up just 8.5 percent. <p>
Publicly available financial statements had confirmed a trend, but not the kind that Merry-Go-Round usually set. In the case of a retailer, an investor who spots rising inventories might consider a little field research. A trip to a store might provide some clues. Are customers buying? Is the merchandise on sale? With other kinds of companies, checking out the trade magazines may help, especially those issues that rate products against each other. If the quality, features, or price of a company's product are coming in for criticism, then the cause of rising inventories isn't exactly a mystery. <p>
<p><a name="SUB5"><b><font size=+1>GROSS MARGINS: The worm in the Apple</font></b><p>
War came to the personal-computer industry in June 1992, and prices of machines soon were dropping to bargain levels. <a name="NASD:APPL"></a><b>Apple Computer</b> watched this battle from its base in Cupertino, California, feeling reasonably confident that the war would have a much greater impact on <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> and the makers of IBM clones. Apple considered itself special, out of the fray. Consumers readily paid a premium for its products. <p>
But Apple wasn't as safe as it thought. Given a chance to buy less-expensive IBM-style machines, customers balked at high-ticket Apples. The uprising forced Apple to cut prices for its signature Macintosh computers. <p>
Shareholders, confident that Apple could withstand any challenge, remained loyal even when customers weren't. On June 1, 1993, Apple's stock closed at $57 a share, not far off its 52-week high of $65.25. Yet eight days later, when Apple said its earnings for the rest of the year would be lower than predicted, Wall Street finally pulled the plug. <p>
By the end of June, Apple's stock had lost almost one third of its value. In mid-July the company posted its first quarterly loss in two years--a bigger-than-expected $188.3 million shortfall. By then, shares had fallen to $27.50 each.<p>
Under normal conditions Apple might have offset the premium loss with aggressive cost cutting. But the PC wars had become so intense that Apple was being forced to lower prices faster than it could trim expenses.<p>
The result: A textbook case of shrinking gross margins. This was evident on Apple's financial report for the quarter ended on March 26, 1993--and made publicly available about two months before the stock began its spectacular decline.<p>
Gross margin is a standard measure of corporate health. It shows how much of a company's revenue is left over after manufacturing costs are subtracted. What remains is partly eaten by salaries, advertising, taxes, and other expenses as it sinks to the bottom line to become earnings, the kind of profit that investors care most about. Gross margins will often shrink if the company's cost of making its products goes up or if a company has to cut prices. Other things, like product mix, can also affect gross margins.<p>
<p><a name="SUB6"><b><font size=+1>Apple Computer was a surprise casualty of the PC wars, but rising costs and slow sales should have been a tip-off.</font></b><p>
But price cutting was what was happening to Apple, as its March 1993 10-Q showed. "I should have seen it," grumbles Michael Murphy, editor of the Overpriced Stock Service newsletter. "I looked at it and said, 'Well, they do have to get more aggressive about following these prices down,' but I didn't think they'd have to give up the premium." <p>
Apple's March 1993 10-Q showed revenues of $3.97 billion for the first half of its fiscal year versus $3.58 billion the year before, a gain of 11 percent. Directly beneath net sales, under the heading "costs and expenses," is the line "cost of sales." This shows what the company spent on materials and equipment to produce the goods it sold. Apple in this six-month period earmarked $2.4 billion to generate sales of $4 billion. The difference is the gross margin. 
The quick approach is to figure gross margin as a percentage of sales. To do this, subtract cost of sales from net sales, then divide by net sales. In Apple's case, the result is 40 percent--the gross margin as a percentage of sales for the first half. <p>
How did this compare with the company's gross margin a year before? A right-hand column gives matching figures for the six months ended March 27, 1992. Then, Apple's sales were $3.58 billion, and cost of sales was $2 billion. Using the same calculation as before shows a gross margin as a percentage of sales of 44 percent.<p>
The drop in Apple's gross margin as a percentage of sales alone wasn't a reason to dump the stock. But it did signal danger. William Slakey, director of investor relations at Apple, says that at the time, Apple gave up its price advantage to lift sales. "We altered our pricing strategy accordingly, and it did impact our gross margins," Slakey said. <p>
Indeed, sometimes a company will deliberately squeeze margins and lower prices in an effort to build market share. Apple set this goal, and for a time it worked. But this strategy succeeds only if costs come down, too. Investors who see this happening need to know whether the company plans to do anything to trim expenses or whether it expects increasing sales to offset the price cutting. Unless one of those things happens, the bottom line will suffer, with the stock price not far behind. At the end of the day, it's more important to make a buck than to make a sale. <p>
Sometimes, of course, financial deceit is so polished that even the most cynical analysts are duped. Reading financial statements isn't a certain defense against outright corporate fraud. If management is determined to lie, investors who read the financials won't catch it.<p>
But that's the uncommon case. More often, stocks fall because managers make business mistakes--mistakes that leave tracks in their corporate disclosures. Spotting the tracks is not a command to dump the stock and run. It is, however, a strong signal to telephone the company, its competitors, and its vendors with pointed questions, and to check on management by reading the annual proxy statement and news coverage. Then a decision to hold or fold can be an informed decision. Otherwise, investors will find that from a certain trusting distance, drowning and swimming look remarkably alike. <p>
In DUE DILIGENCE, Part 2: Even audited financial numbers can hide a host of troubles. Worth focuses on three critical items in a company's financial statement: quality of earnings, depreciation, and expenses. 
-------------------------------------------
This article appeared in the July/August 1994 issue of Worth magazine.<p>
Copyright 1994 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rights reserved.<p>

