<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - Technical Tools for Every Investor (Pt 1)</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Investor%20101>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investor 101</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>Technical Tools for Every Investor (Pt 1)</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Is your latest stock hunch genius or garbage? The numbers and charts of the technician can help you make the call. In this installment (the first of two), Worth looks at the tools of the trade and how techies use them.<p>
By Jonathan Butler<p>
What to buy, when to buy it, and when to sell it--these are the basic questions facing every investor. The pros have two answers: fundamental and technical analysis.<p>
Fundamentalists scrutinize balance sheets, talk to chief financial officers, and evaluate product lines to predict a company's performance and, by extension, its stock price. Technicians, on the other hand, don't care whether a company builds cars or roasts coffee or whether its bottom line is red or black. Instead, they use historical statistics of investor supply and demand to extrapolate future stock-price patterns. "I can put my feet up on my desk while all the analysts are out there digging away because I don't need to know what the story is," says Justin Mamis, chief market technician at Hancock Institutional Equity Services in New York. "All I care about is how people feel about those particular stocks as shown by their putting money in and taking their money out."<p>
Few people are as faithful to a single approach; most market professionals use both fundamental and technical analysis daily and recommend that amateurs do the same. "The individual has to use them both in common," says Edward Nicoski, director of technical research at Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis. "Because the market is an anticipatory device, you're typically going to see the turns in stocks more quickly looking at charts than by being a fundamentalist and reading the front page. However, if there's really something fundamentally wrong that nobody knows about yet, the chart's not going to help you."<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>You don't need to pick the absolute highs and lows to make a lot of money.</font></b><p>
Entire books have been written on the subject of technical analysis, and some people spend their lives learning the trade, but there is a basic core of information and tools--accessible and intelligible to the individual stock picker and 401(k) participant--that no investor should be without.<p>
Technical analysis dates back to the rice markets of 17th-century Japan. It tries to reduce the apparently random character of markets to statistical patterns predictive of future price trends among individual stocks, industry sectors, and market averages (it also applies in other markets, such as bonds, currencies, and commodities). The technician's premise, say Robert D. Edwards and John Magee in Technical Analysis of Stock Trends, the industry's bible, is that "prices move in trends and trends tend to continue until something happens to change the supply-demand balance."<p>
While the ultimate goal of technical analysis is to identify changes in the direction of stocks, Mamis notes that investors don't need to pick the absolute highs and lows to make a lot of money. "If you've made a Faustian pact with the devil to get out within 10 percent of the high all the time, that's all you need," he says.<p>
CHART WORSHIP
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Line, bar, and point-and-figure charts are the tools of the trade. But don't ignore the big picture.</font></b><p>
The technician's most important tool is the chart, which allows him or her to identify trends and patterns in a single stock or average, as well as to compare the two. There are three ways to graphically represent stock-price movement. The familiar line chart uses one number--usually the closing price-- to reflect the day's price movement. The bar chart, perhaps the most frequently used, shows the high, low, and closing prices within a given time frame, usually a day, week, or month. Most bar charts also include corresponding trading volumes along the bottom.<p>
Both of these charts plot the price at specific time intervals, whether or not prices have changed. The third type of chart, the point-and-figure chart, records a price only when it fluctuates by a predetermined amount, usually one point or more. Upward movements are plotted using the letter x, while downward movements are denoted by the letter o. This is a good way to track price momentum, but since point-and-figure charts disregard time and volume and are difficult to interpret, professionals recommend that amateur investors focus on lines and bars.<p>
In deciding to buy or sell a specific stock, technicians attempt first to fathom the big picture by assessing market sentiment and momentum. One key statistic they look at is the put-to-call ratio, which divides the number of puts (options to sell an asset at a specified price by a certain date) by the number of calls (options to buy an asset at a specified price by a certain date). Because a put is a bet that the underlying security will decline in price and a call a bet that it will rise, a low put-to-call ratio means that the consensus is optimistic--a negative sign for a contrarian. A high put-to-call ratio shows that the consensus is negative--a signal to start buying. Because calls typically outnumber puts, the ratio averages well below 1, usually around 0.8. Small fluctuations from this norm are not important, warns James Stack of InvesTech Research in Whitefish, Montana. "It's only meaningful when it's at an extreme reading," he says. This means a ratio below 0.7 or above 0.9.<p>
Another key measure of market psychology is the advisory-sentiment index, issued weekly by Investors Intelligence and available in Barron's and Investor's Business Daily, as well as in Worth (see Market Radar in the Need to Know section). The contrarian principle applies to this index as well: Last December, for example, before the recent market run-up, 59 percent of managers surveyed were pessimistic, the most negative reading in 13 years. Like the put-to-call ratio, advisory sentiment is most significant at extremes, particularly when the pessimistic reading is above 55 percent.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>Look for key signals that the trend is going to change. If the army's out of step, watch out.</font></b><p>
Next there is the question of market breadth. A rise in the Dow could be driven by a big jump in one or two major stocks, masking small declines in many other stocks. An investor needs to understand the underlying stock movement in an index because, as Martin J. Pring writes in Technical Analysis Explained, "generally speaking, the fewer the number of issues that are moving in the direction of the major averages, the greater the probability of an imminent reversal in trend."<p>
To get an idea of the breadth of a market move, there are two important indicators. The first is the advance/decline line, which tracks the number of stocks advancing over a given period (usually one day) minus the number of stocks declining. Since this measure includes thousands of stocks, depending on the market, it gives a more detailed picture than does a particular index, such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average, which tracks only 30 stocks.<p>
What technicians worry about is divergence, when a market average is going one way and the advance/decline line the other. Alan R. Shaw, technical research manager at Smith Barney and author of the section on technical analysis in the Financial Analyst's Handbook, sees this relation in military terms. "As long as the army [the overall market] stays in step with the generals (e.g., the Dow industrials), then the trend, by definition, is healthy and should sustain," he writes. "It's when the army shows signs of retreating that the technician becomes concerned about the viability of the underlying trend."<p>
<p><a name="SUB4"><b><font size=+1>Don't be fooled by mixed signals. Connect the dots for a clear picture.</font></b><p>
In August 1984, for example, the Dow hit several successive lows, but the New York Stock Exchange advance/decline line was hitting successive new highs. Investors attending to this data could have gotten in at the start of a three-and-a-half-year upward move that saw the Dow more than double.<p>
Measuring the difference between the number of stocks making new highs over a 52-week period is a good way to assess underlying support for the market's direction. When a market index hits a low (in the context of its recent trading levels, not necessarily an all-time low) but the number of individual stocks making new lows is not rising, a turnaround may be imminent. Conversely, when a market index rises without a corresponding rise in the number of new highs, a correction is likely. This occurred in April 1971: The Dow hit a two-year peak, but the high-low differential dropped dramatically and the market fell more than 15 percent over the next seven months. One year later, with the Dow again rising, the high-low reading headed south again, and a few months later, the market went into a two-year tailspin, losing about 45 percent of its value.<p>
"The lesson is that such divergences are never to be ignored," says Justin Mamis. "Time and time again, such divergences have represented key signals that the trend is about to change." Investors should remember that the new-high/new-low reading is meaningful only on a relative basis, that is, compared to recent levels.<p>
In the end, of course, investors want to know where a particular stock (or sector, or market average) is headed. The simplest way to come up with an answer is to use a ruler to draw a trend line. By connecting either the significant peaks or low points in a chart, an investor can visually assess whether the trend is up or down. The trick, or the art, lies in deciding which points to connect. Remember that the longer a trend has been in place, the harder it is to reverse. That is, the more points composing a trend line and the more gradual the slope, the more meaningful it is.<p>
<p><a name="SUB5"><b><font size=+1>It's all in the timing: The pros reveal how they decide it's time to sell.</font></b><p>
After determining the direction of the stock's price, the investor needs to figure out its trading range. Most stocks have periods in which they trade consistently within a certain price range, establishing lower and upper bounds between which a large turnover of shares occurs. These bottoms are known as "supports," and tops are called "resistances." For example, the investor who notices that a stock regularly moves between 20 and 40 can do well by buying in the low 20s and selling in the high 30s.<p>
Although these levels are determined initially by supply and demand, they can, as James Stack points out, become self-perpetuating as investors pick up on the pattern. "Support and resistance levels are most meaningful if they are perceived to be support and resistance levels by the investing public," he says.<p>
Stocks tend to stay within their trading ranges until something occurs to change the balance between supply and demand. When this happens on the downside, the previous support level becomes the new resistance level; on the upside, the previous resistance level becomes the new support level. Such is the case with the Dow Jones average reaching 4000, which before last February was a point of major market-level resistance. While a new resistance level has yet to be established as the market has continued to achieve new highs, 4000 is now the Dow's new support level. Its violation would spell big trouble.<p>
<p><a name="SUB6"><b><font size=+1>Good things come to those who wait--at least until a stock trades above its 200 day average.</font></b><p>
One benefit of charts is that they allow investors to view one variable in relation to another--usually a price index in relation to its moving average. (The moving average creates a smooth price history by tracking the average closing price over a given time period, dropping the earliest piece of data and adding the most recent one for every time interval.) While the trend of a moving average is important on its own, it is most useful as an indicator of support and resistance for the stock. Some pros recommend that investors sell as soon as a stock's line chart crosses below the moving average line, and buy when the stock rises above the average. Others recommend that investors wait until the average itself has changed direction.<p>
Because the moving average trails actual stock-price movements, the shorter the time period of the average, the more volatile it will be; the longer the period, the more meaningful the breakthrough. While traders use anything from 5-day to 500-day moving averages, most technicians recommend using a 200-day moving average. In fact, says Edward Nicoski, buying a stock trading above its 200-day average typically leads to positive returns, while buying it below this average leads to negative results. A 1992 Journal of Finance study of the Dow Jones Industrial Average between 1897 and 1986 found that when the market crossed above its 200-day moving average, it returned about 12 percent a year. When it fell below it, it lost 7 percent.<p>
<p><a name="SUB7"><b><font size=+1>The four-month mark is the most attractive to techies. Don't simply rely on highest relative strength.</font></b><p>
Still another important technical tool is relative strength, the measure of how an individual stock is faring versus the overall market. "Very often changes in trend, from good to bad or from bad to good, will be preceded by a change in the stock's relative performance," says Richard T. McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch in New York City.<p>
Relative strength is derived by dividing the price of the stock by the price of a market index. An upward-sloping line shows that the stock is outperforming the market over time; a downward-sloping line denotes underperformance. A stock is most attractive when its relative strength has improved for four months or longer, says William O'Neil, chairman of William O'Neil and Co., a stock-research firm in Los Angeles. But he cautions that investors shouldn't just jump on the stock with the highest relative strength, because by then it's likely to have gone too far. Rising relative strength does not necessarily mean a stock is going up--it may simply be declining less quickly than the market. For example, if General Electric were dropping by 5 percent while the S&P 500 were falling by 10 percent, GE's relative strength would be rising. "Thus it's inadvisable to use relative strength as a sole technical tool," writes Alan R. Shaw.<p>
Many technicians use the relative-strength line to identify attractive industry sectors before picking individual stocks. This information appears Mondays in Investor's Business Daily. Analyzing sector performance is an effective way to narrow the number of choices. And while it certainly doesn't ensure picking a successful stock, it does improve your chances. As Shaw puts it, "It's a lot easier [to pick a stock] if the tide of the group's behavior is supportive."<p>
This technique also can help you steer clear of the wrong stocks. For example, investors who noticed in 1992 that the restaurant sector violated a relative-strength uptrend in place for 12 years could have saved themselves dramatic losses over the next 3 years.<p>
One problem with using group charts to find individual stocks, says O'Neil, is that by the time you have identified a strong group, its leading stock is likely to be overextended. The leader, Mamis notes, may also distort the potential for the rest of the group. Still, he says, "group charts are helpful as a confirmation that your individual stock is not floating in thin air." In addition, McCabe, who uses group selection, warns that if the overall market is weak, the few groups that remain strong could be the next to capitulate to the trend.<p>
In TECHNICAL TOOLS FOR EVERY INVESTOR, Part 2: Seven of the most important charts technicians use to make their calls.<p>
-------------------------------------------------
This article appeared in the October 1995 issue of Worth magazine.<p>
Copyright 1995 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rights reserved.<p>

