	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - Technical Tools for Every Investor (Pt 2)</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Investor%20101>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investor 101</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>Technical Tools for Every Investor (Pt 2)</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Think of a chart as a map: It shows you where you can and can't go. There are seven key patterns technicians use to navigate the market.<p>
By Jonathan Butler<p>
Technicians have identified numerous price patterns--far too many for the amateur investor. But a few prominent ones can help an individual decide when to buy and when to sell. According to Piper Jaffray's Nicoski, it can be as simple as asking whether the chart is smiling or frowning at you.<p>
The typical price cycle has four phases. The first is accumulation, or consolidation. At this point, there is no positive news on the company, and only the first long-term investors are starting to buy. The stock price often dips slightly before going back up, creating a "smile" on the chart.<p>
The markup phase happens as business starts to pick up and more analysts and investors start paying attention. This interest becomes euphoric, driving the stock price up dramatically. As a rule, the longer the accumulation phase, the longer the mark-up period will last.<p>
At this point, some investors realize that the price has gotten ahead of itself and start selling. This is called the distribution phase, characterized by a frowning line. Pretty soon, the consensus catches on and starts selling, initiating the markdown phase.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>A price cycle is a long and bumpy road. Try to avoid the potholes.</font></b><p>
No cycle will be as smooth in practice as the diagram suggests. Instead, the cycle will be made up of shorter and choppier price patterns that can be divided into two types--reversals and continuations. A reversal--like the distribution and accumulation phases above--is a turnaround in the direction of a trend, while a continuation is only a temporary interruption in the larger trend.<p>
There are a few additional patterns all investors should understand. The head and shoulders pattern (see graph) consists of a series of three rallies and reactions, with the middle one being the most extreme. At the top of the chart, the uptrend is reversed only when the "neckline"--the line connecting the bottoms of the two shoulders--has been broken by the third downturn. The same pattern can be seen in reverse at the bottom of the cycle. At the top, the volume should fall off in the righthand shoulders; at the bottom, it should increase.<p>
The other kind of reversal to watch for is the double top and bottom (see graph), which looks like the letter M. The tip-off that it is reversing the trend is that the second top is accompanied by much less volume.<p>
To avoid selling a stock that is still in a broad uptrend or buying a stock that still has far to fall, the investor needs to watch for what are called continuation patterns. Instead of looking at these continuations as reversals, the investor should think of them as a period when the stock is catching its breath. Take triangles, for example: The right-angled descending triangle is composed of a series of descending peaks, the bottoms of which stay constant. This shows that support for the stock is not eroding and suggests that it will shortly continue its upward trend.<p>
The last two continuation patterns--the wedge and the flag--contain upper and lower trend lines heading in the same direction. The falling wedge is an interruption of an uptrend, while a rising wedge is an interruption of a downtrend. The formation of a wedge, which commonly takes two to eight weeks, is usually accompanied by a decline in volume.<p>
A flag, really a parallelogram shape, usually occurs during a sharp move in price and is preceded by heavy trading that quickly evaporates over the life of the countercyclical trend, usually one to four weeks. Martin J. Pring warns that if the volume does not ease, the larger trend may be reversed.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Other sources can help steer you in the right direction.</font></b><p>
Once you have identified a company that interests you, technical analysis of the stock and the overall market can help you determine whether and when to buy and sell. As McCabe puts it, the stock is the car and the technical chart is the map that tells you where you can and can't go. "You may have the greatest Ferrari or Lamborghini in the world," he says, "but if you have to go from New York to London, it won't do you very much good."<p>
There are several sources of chart information. The first is Investor's Business Daily, which has technical data on over 8,000 companies. To access these charts on-line, net surfers can sign on to Prodigy, which carries most of IBD's charts. Finally, TeleChart 2000, a CD-ROM product for home computers, provides access to 8,500 charts for only 99 cents a day.<p>
---------------------------------------------------
This article appeared in the October 1995 issue of Worth magazine.<p>
Copyright 1995 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rights reserved.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
