<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-How Good Is Your 401(k)?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Investor%20101>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investor 101</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-How Good Is Your 401(k)?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The answer could be "Not so hot." A first-ever rating of the 50 biggest plans, plus a strategy for getting better results.
By Jeff Blyskal<p>
Are some companies' 401(k) plans better than others? What's the best way to invest in one? Will my 401(k) be sufficient to make my retirement comfortable?<p>
These are crucial questions for at least 16 million working Americans. This type of corporate retirement plan held some $410 billion in assets at the end of 1992, almost as much as the investor dollars in all stock mutual funds. <p>
But not all 401(k) plans are created equal. These plans vary wildly from company to company, and while the plans provide some information to investors, it's hard to get a complete picture. <p>
Consider the 401(k) plans sponsored by <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears, Roebuck</b></a> and Amoco Oil. From 1990 through 1992, Sears employees could have put their 401(k) money into either Sears stock, a money market fund, or a balanced fund that split its investments between stocks and bonds. A Sears employee making $60,000 in 1990 and $70,000 in 1993 who kept roughly 75 percent of his retirement money in stocks and 25 percent in bonds or other fixed-income investments would have earned $5,547 on his 401(k) money during these three years. Much of that was due to a 97 percent return in Sears stock since 1990.<p>
An Amoco employee who followed a similar strategy would have earned just $1,783, largely because the oil company's stock returned just 1.7 percent since 1990. But it would be dead wrong to conclude that the Sears 401(k) was better. At the end of those three years, starting from zero, the Sears worker would have ended up with $23,375 in total 401(k) accumulations, versus $38,314 for the Amoco worker. <p>
So it goes in the Byzantine world of 401(k) plans. Rarely has the management of so much money been so misunderstood by so many. Investors who would never dream of buying shares in a mutual fund without monitoring the fund's performance and management techniques remain in the dark about the quality of their own very substantial retirement plans.<p>
Until now. Our exclusive survey of the nation's largest 401(k) plans is the first attempt to rate the quality of what is becoming the country's leading retirement- investment vehicle. The differences among plans are astonishing. For instance, some plans seem positively stacked against investors. Others make it surprisingly easy for an investor to reach retirement nirvana. The bottom line is this: How a plan is structured determines whether an employee's 401(k) will produce a comfortable retirement.<p>
Structure is what made the Sears and Amoco plans so different. Amoco allowed its employee to contribute about $9,500 more during three years than Sears did. On top of that, Amoco matched employee contributions with $11,349 in company money, about $9,000 more than Sears pitched in. <p>
Our study dissects the structure of the 50 largest 401(k) plans, clearly showing strengths and weaknesses. For example, some companies' plans take better care of the company than they do of the folks saving for retirement. Fully 40 percent of the plans required that the company's matching contributions be invested in company stock. That's great for a company interested in supporting its stock price with employee dollars, but it's not such a good deal for investors trying to lower their risk by diversifying. At least one company seems to be using 401(k) plans as a smoke screen to disguise cutbacks in the retirement plans of its workers.<p>
But our survey also demonstrates how attentive employees can make even a mediocre retirement plan work to their advantage. The fact is, most workers do themselves a disservice with their 401(k) plans. They put too little into the program, and they put their contributions into the wrong kind of investments.<p>
Tax-deferred savings plans of one form or another have been around since the 1950s, but the 401(k) as we know it today was created in 1978 when section 401(k) was added to the Internal Revenue Code. The previous generations of workers didn't have to think about savings plans as serious retirement vehicles, because most company pensions simply guaranteed a set monthly stipend for retirees. The onus in these plans--called defined-benefit plans --falls largely on the employer. The employer has to put aside enough money to meet its future pension obligations.<p>
Today, in many retirement plans, the onus has shifted to the employee. In what are known as defined-contribution plans--401(k)s are the best-known type --employees contribute their own pretax dollars (which compound on a tax-deferred basis), and companies may or may not match that contribution. The company has no obligation to provide any specific amount upon retirement; future benefits depend largely on how much money the employee contributes and on how profitably the money is invested. This is up to the employee, who picks from a menu of investment options offered by the company plan. <p>
Defined-contribution plans are now a big business. Today, 16 million employees contribute $36 billion a year to some 185,000 plans. Defined-contribution plans climbed from 30 percent of all pension assets under management in 1987 to 36 percent in 1992. By 1997, they're projected to grow to 43 percent, according to Access Research, a Windsor, Connecticut, market-research and consulting firm. "We expect another round of defined-benefit pension-plan terminations over the next three to four years, and any kind of government-mandated health care will lead to even more terminations," says Robert G. Wuelfing, president of Access. <p>
No one joins a company just to participate in the retirement plan, of course. And although a company may have to provide some kind of reasonable plan to maintain its competitive edge in hiring, the plans themselves don't compete with one another.<p>
As a result, 401(k) peformance has never been given the kind of scrutiny routinely given to mutual funds or stocks. Yes, companies are legally required to provide employees with such details as annual performance and matching contributions in their plan, but information about what's available elsewhere? Forget it.<p>
Understanding the numbers will get even more important in January when new U.S. Labor Department rules will all but require plan sponsors to give employees a variety of investment choices within their 401(k) plans. Stripped of their legalese, the rules say that a company offering its workers a minimum of three choices with varying risk and return profiles--such as a stock fund, a bond fund, and a money market fund--will avoid legal liability for disappointing investment results. The good news is, these new rules will give those who actively manage their plans a solid chance at beating the mediocre returns that 401(k) plans have traditionally delivered.<p>
To find the benchmarks of 401(k) quality and performance, we sent a detailed questionnaire to the corporate sponsors of the 50 largest plans in a database developed by Judy Diamond Associates, a Washington, D.C., publishing firm. Almost 85 percent of the companies provided the information we requested for 1990 through 1992. Eight companies failed to respond, with four--Kraft General Foods, American Stores, Abbott Laboratories, and <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eastman Kodak</b></a> --refusing to cooperate. Information on their plans was obtained from public documents on file at the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Department of Labor and from inside sources. The 50 plans, with combined assets of some $134 billion, manage one third of all 401(k) money in the U.S. They cover 2.2 million workers. <p>
After applying each plan's myriad rules, fees, and returns, we ranked them on one simple factor: how much money they would have accumulated over three years for a participant representative of many high-income Worth readers. (We assumed an employee whose salary was $60,000 in 1990 and steadily grew each year to approximately $70,000 by 1993. The median Worth reader had an individual income of $66,000 in 1993 and a household income of $108,000.) We also assumed that this representative reader was an intelligent investor who put 75 percent of plan assets into equities and 25 percent into fixed-income investments.<p>
Our methodology enabled us to compare plans on a level playing field for the first time. The results were surprising. Take the case of an IBM employee who follows our income and investing guidelines. By year-end 1992, starting from zero and making the maximum contributions to the 401(k), the employee's retirement nest egg would have grown to an estimated $22,261.<p>
Nothing shabby about that--until it's compared with what other employees at other companies could have amassed in their plans over the same period of time. With identical objectives, investment principles, salary, and economic and market conditions, an employee at Bellsouth could have made a nest egg grow to $34,993; at <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a>, to $38,265; and at Conoco it would have become a $45,007 jackpot.<p>
Why the wide range? We found from our study that most of the difference in total accumulation is attributable to the design of the plans themselves. IBM's simply makes achieving a comfortable retirement harder.<p>
We intentionally removed from our assessment most of the effects attributable to perfect hindsight. A plan investor who knew that this stock or that fund was going to go up could certainly have shown stupendous returns. Stocks have been stellar performers of late and have rewarded those plan participants who were smart enough to overweight their portfolios in equities. But tomorrow's investment returns aren't predictable on the basis of the past, so no investor should count on beating the averages when planning for retirement. For this reason, we put all of our model 401(k) participants into a sound portfolio of the kind we'd recommend for any investor saving for retirement. It's important to recognize what our study doesn't aim to accomplish, too. Many 401(k) investors have other corporate pension plans. Measuring complete corporate benefit packages is beyond the scope of this study. <p>
Since a plan's design has so much to do with its ultimate performance, we examined how the plans vary. There are two basic elements common to 401(k) plans: how much the employee can contribute to the plan and how much the employer will match.<p>
The IRS limits how much money an employee can contribute to a tax-deductible 401(k) plan each year. Three years ago, the maximum was $7,979; in 1991, it was $8,475; and in 1992, it was $8,728. The maximum in 1993 is $8,994. <p>
Many plans, however, cap an employee's contribution far short of the IRS maximum. <a name="NYSE:DAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10448"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Delta Air Lines'</b></a> plan, for example, straitjacketed our model participant with a 10 percent maximum employee contribution. That meant a contribution that was $6,267 less than that allowed by law over the three years. This is a crucial element in the Delta plan. A dollar barred is a dollar not earning a tax-deferred return. And a dollar not tax-deferred this year is an allowable contribution lost forever, because it can't be rolled into subsequent tax years.<p>
The ideal plan should allow an employee to hit the IRS ceiling. "Employees should put as much as possible into their plan to take advantage of the last government tax shelter available to them," says James H. Gately, senior vice president at mutual fund company the Vanguard Group.<p>
Similarly, the employer matching contribution should be as large as possible, because this amount is not subject to IRS limits. "Employers should be matching dollar for dollar at least 8 percent of salary," says Dallas Salisbury, president of the Employee Benefits Research Institute, a nonprofit think tank in Washington. "And if the company intends the 401(k) to be the stand-alone retirement plan, that employer contribution should be made without regard to what the employee puts in."<p>
How generous are corporate matches? Nationwide, most plans match the first 4 percent to 6 percent of employee contributions. But that's not dollar for dollar. The cash value of matches ranges from less than 25 cents to a match of more than a dollar. The largest group, 36 percent of our companies, fell in the 25-to-50-cent range, according to Buck Consultants, an employee-benefits consulting firm in New York. The stingiest of plans--14 percent of the companies surveyed by Buck--provide zero match. Add up all the numbers, and on average, employers kick in a not-very-impressive 25 cents for every dollar employees contribute.<p>
Some experts, however, argue that even a mediocre match should be put in proper perspective. "If you put in 4 percent and the company matches only 2 percent, you've just made a 50 percent return on your money," says Mike Bostler, a principal in Chicago's Performance Analytics investment-consulting firm. "What market will top that?"<p>
The best 401(k) plans of the 50 we surveyed climbed to the top not only because they let our model participant achieve the maximum annual contribution allowed by law but also because of truly generous employer matching contributions. Number-one-rated Conoco, for example, allowed deferral of up to 15 percent of income. Conoco also generously matched employees dollar for dollar on the first 6 percent of contributions.<p>
Delta's plan, on the other hand, earned its low ranking because management is tight with the buck on matching contributions and because it capped employee contributions prematurely. Delta matched only 50 cents on the dollar and only up to the first 4 percent of employee contributions. Thus, over the 1990 through 1992 period, Delta provided only $3,783 in matching contributions--one third of Conoco's $11,349.<p>
"We realize our plan was a little outdated," says Delta's plan administrator, Harvey King, "which is why we've made major changes. We're going from a plan developed in 1972 to a state-of-the-art plan." As of July 1, 1993, employees earning less than $55,000 were allowed to contribute up to 15 percent of salary, and ten new mutual fund options--including the Twentieth Century Select, Fidelity Contrafund, Merrill Lynch Capital, and Templeton Foreign funds--have been added to the list of available investment options. However, the paltry company match is unchanged.<p>
Participants in a plan that stringently restricts contributions don't have to roll over and play dead. Although getting an employer to boost the company match may be a pipe dream in today's belt-tightening environment, employees can and should lobby for the freedom to maximize contributions of their own money. <p>
Our study points up the value of that freedom. Compare the <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> and McDonnell Douglas plans, for example. Motorola makes no matching contribution, while McDonnell Douglas matched the first 8 percent of employee contributions with 37.5 cents to 75 cents on the dollar between 1990 and 1992. Yet the Motorola plan's total accumulation bested McDonnell Douglas's by more than $5,500. <p>
Blame it on McDonnell Douglas's 8 percent limit on employee contributions. That meant our representative participant could put only about $15,000 over three years to work in the McDonnell Douglas plan versus $25,000 at Motorola.<p>
The structure of McDonnell Douglas's plan also threw another curve at employees. The company match had to be invested in McDonnell Douglas stock. That funneled 37 percent of total contributions into a single investment. Our model shows just how bad this can be. McDonnell Douglas stock took investors on a ride guaranteed to send them straight for the airsickness bags: down 23 percent in 1990, up 53 percent in 1991, and back down nearly 29 percent in 1992. By 1993, the company's $9,000 in matching contributions was worth only $8,026. <p>
The problem here goes beyond the performance of just one stock, however. Forty percent of the plans in our survey required that the company match be put in the company's stock. Some 24 percent of all 401(k) assets are invested in the sponsoring company's stock. That much concentration adds unpredictable risk to a retirement portfolio. <p>
"An overconcentrated position in the employing-company stock is a very bad idea, because even very good companies can experience significant changes in financial position," says Chris McNickle, a principal in investment-management practice with the Greenwich Associates market-research firm in Greenwich, Connecticut.<p>
Want more evidence? Shed a tear for the poor folks in the Kraft General Foods plan. The stock of parent company <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> had been going great guns since 1989, and at year-end 1992 more than 53 percent of the 401(k)'s assets were invested in the company stock. This year, after the company was forced to slash prices on its brand-name cigarettes to defend against discount-priced competitors, Philip Morris stock plunged 39 percent. In just four months--and after our 1990-1992 rating period--participants at Kraft watched $320 million of their money go up in smoke.<p>
It's pretty clear why so many companies encourage 401(k) investors to hold the company's stock--but very few companies admit it as directly as General Dynamics. The company encourages participants to put all their eggs in the one-company stock basket. Starting in April 1991, the company began matching dollar for dollar if an employee put 100 percent of his contributions into General Dynamics stock, but only 50 cents on the dollar if the employee allocated his contributions to a diversified investment mix. <p>
"This was part of a concerted effort to revive the company stock value," says spokesman Al Spivak. The stock certainly needed reviving: General Dynamics suffered $639 million in losses in 1990.<p>
Nearly 11,000 participants--31 percent--took the bait. The extremely high-risk gamble paid off handsomely for the short term--during our study period--with the stock fund rising 63 percent in 1991 and another 69 percent in 1992. But General Dynamics stock--vulnerable to defense-spending cutbacks--has been on a roller coaster. It traded at $18.75 in 1982, rose to $89.25 in 1986, crashed to $19 in 1990, hit a high of $107.86 in 1992 and recently traded at $97.75. Talk about white knuckles. <p>
Companies benefit from 401(k)s in less obvious ways as well. Corporations have a lot to gain by switching from a defined-benefit pension plan to a defined-contribution 401(k), says Gary Blank, vice president at the Wyatt Company, an international employee-benefits consulting firm. Companies that replace the pension with a 401(k)--generally smaller firms and corporations in reorganization--can slash their retirement benefits costs by two thirds. A typical pension plan costs a company 4 percent to 6 percent of payroll, versus just 1.5 percent to 2 percent of payroll for a 401(k) plan.<p>
Large corporations such as those on our list can realize proportional cost savings even without terminating their traditional defined-benefit plans. For example, if a company is spending 6 percent of payroll on the pension plan and beefs up the benefits of that plan by 10 percent, the cost increase would be 0.6 percent of payroll. But 401(k) benefits can be boosted 10 percent at a cost of only 0.2 percent. On a $6 billion annual payroll, the savings come to $24 million a year.<p>
As the size of the 401(k) market has grown, plan administrators--banks, insurance companies, mutual fund companies, and accounting firms that invest these dollars--are all looking for a larger piece of the pie. "It's not the cola wars, but plan administrators are looking at each other and trying to be more competitive," says Rachel Farrell, vice president at Bankers Trust, which manages some $25 billion in 401(k) assets. <p>
Choice is the current battleground for the companies selling 401(k) plans. For the most part, plan administrators, the press, and mutual fund publicists have focused on the value of increasing the number of investment options. "Most of the newly diversified 401(k) plans are much more powerful than the 401(k)s they replace," U.S. News & World Report said earlier this year. However, most plans already offer four or more investment options, according to Buck Consultants.<p>
Our study found no evidence that simply adding more options to 401(k)s will increase return to investors. The real problem at most plans is that employees misunderstand and misuse the options they have.<p>
Of course, there are plans that absolutely offer too few choices. The Abbott Laboratories plan, for example, offered only two not-great options: a high-risk undiversified gamble on the company's common stock and a low-rate return on insurance-company fixed-interest investment contracts.<p>
In our view, 401(k) plans at a minimum should give investors enough options so that they can construct a balanced and diversified portfolio. That means providing at least one diversified general-stock fund, one growth-stock fund, and one fixed-income fund. (To see how the 50 plans on our list measured up on this score, see the Grading the Options column in "How the Biggest 50 Stack Up," on page 64.)<p>
But pure choice is not enough. Fully 28 percent of the employees who are eligible to participate in 401(k) plans simply never sign up. The remainder contribute far less than the maximum allowed by the IRS. Nationally, the average is just 4 percent to 5 percent of salary. More choice won't address these workers' biggest problem.<p>
Nor does a host of options necessarily lead to smart asset allocation. Most 401(k) participants put too much money into fixed-income instruments. Guaranteed investment contracts (GICs), an insurance industry product with a fixed return and high costs, account for 30 percent of the whole 401(k) pie. In individual plans the numbers can be significantly higher. At Du Pont, for example, 86 percent of plan assets are in GICs.<p>
The popularity of this instrument is easy to understand but wrongheaded. Insurance companies, the traditionally dominant plan advisor in the 401(k) market, sell GICs on the promise of a guaranteed return. An employee can buy a GIC that promises an 8 percent--or whatever--return.<p>
But 401(k) investors shouldn't even worry about the validity of these promises or exactly what is guaranteed about these contracts. There's no reason to be in GICs in the first place, given their low annual returns, currently about 7 percent. "That won't give you the growth you need," says Farrell at Bankers Trust, "and over the next year you'll see [new] GICs take a dive to 5 percent, making them even less attractive."<p>
An incredible 9 percent of all 401(k) plan assets sit stagnant in money market funds, at best barely matching inflation. "Plan participants invest way too conservatively," says Wuelfing of Access Research. "Over the last five years, professionally managed defined-benefit pension plans got a 12 percent average annual return while defined-contribution plans, which are managed by employees, got only a 9 percent return. That's because the pension plans are more heavily invested in equities."<p>
The proof is in the historic record of the last 67 years. According to Ibbotson Associates, a Chicago-based financial-data firm, between 1925 and 1992, U.S. common stocks provided an average 10.3 percent annual return--and that's accounting for the crash of 1929 and the plunge in 1987. Long-term corporate bonds returned only 5.5 percent annually over the same time span--not much when inflation gets subtracted.<p>
Despite this evidence, many employees avoid stocks because they fear risk. "If you're uncomfortable, you can reduce your exposure to stocks, but you have to recognize that you're making an emotional decision, not a financial one," says Greenwich Associates' McNickle.<p>
So how much of your 401(k) plan should be in stocks? The experts we polled recommended that at least 50 percent and as much as 100 percent of plan assets be invested in stocks. The conventional wisdom recommends that younger employees should be heavily in stocks--to take advantage of greater returns and the reduced risk over the long term--while workers with less than ten years until retirement should have their assets weighted toward fixed-income investments. That way, they won't get caught needing to withdraw funds in retirement just as the down end of an equity cycle hits.<p>
The conventional wisdom strikes us as too conservative, and it certainly ignores recent demographic trends. Employees should be planning not for the end of a working life at 65 but for a phased retirement that includes significant employment income that could well stretch to 85. It's premature, therefore, to convert from equities to fixed-income investments using 65 as a benchmark. And thinking about income instead of total return is a mistake anyway. A retiree can spend a dollar earned by selling an equity as easily as a dollar earned by collecting interest.<p>
But the kinds of stocks held in a 401(k) should change as 65 approaches and after. Older workers should have a smaller portion of their holdings in more aggressive equities, such as small-company stocks. <p>
Our 401(k) analysis conservatively aimed for 75 percent in equities, with 55 percent to 60 percent in a truly diversified portfolio and 15 percent to 20 percent in a growth-stock portfolio. We tried to put the remaining 25 percent in fixed-income investments. This mix will improve the performance of the average real-life 401(k) investor.<p>
Growing up as a stepchild of the investment industry, the 401(k) business has traditionally been dominated by insurance companies and money managers offering proprietary products. Historically, the managers of these products have generally charged more to manage money than is now the norm in the mutual fund industry. Those charges eat into an investor's return.<p>
We suspect that higher fees are still the norm in the 401(k) field, but it's hard to compare fees in this industry with those charged by publicly traded mutual funds. The two types of investment are under different regulatory agencies that enforce different standards. We certainly intend to pursue this question further.<p>
Whatever the case, additional options will mean that investors who correctly compare plan alternatives will be able to do better than in the past--if they wisely manage their 401(k) choices. The real payoff will come in retirement, when those annual returns add up to financial independence.<p>
Jeff Blyskal is a National Magazine Award-winning financial journalist.<p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

