	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>Banking </b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						<br>Have you ever found an unexplained service charge on your bank statement, or discovered that an overzealous bank employee had sold unwanted mutual funds to an elderly relative? If so, you probably registered a complaint and a request for redress. But what if you couldn't come to a satisfactory resolution?  <p>
The answer is an appeal to a higher authority: the FDIC, which regulates state banks, or the Comptroller of the Currency, which oversees interstate banking.  <p>
Before you open an account at a state bank, check out the <a href="http://www.fdic.gov/">FDIC</a>'s site and look over the consumer-rights files. You can also call the FDIC Consumer Hotline at (800) 934-3342 for information about deposit insurance and consumer-protection matters, and to get an institution's financial report.   <p>
If you wish to file a formal complaint, our list of <a href="/articles/I0101.html">Banking Authorities</a> includes the 50 state bank commissioner offices, as well as those in Guam, Puerto Rico, and the Virgin Islands. E-mail addresses, where available, are also included, although you cannot file a complaint online because a signature is required.  <p>
 <a href="http://www.occ.treas.gov/">The Comptroller of the Currency</a> also has a home page with general information about the agency and the banking system, as well as public documents and news releases. Complaints and questions can be E-mailed to the office at consumer.complaint@occ.treas.gov.The consumer hot-line telephone number is (800) 613-6743.  <p>

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
