<html>
	<head>
		<title>Unclaimed Property</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Investor%20Help%20Desk>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>Unclaimed Property</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						<br>Have you unwittingly abandoned money that's rightfully yours? Contact the Unclaimed Property office to find out.   <p>
By Dayana Yochim  <p>
Aunt Ida may be only a loving memory--but her portfolio has yet to be laid to rest. Unfortunately, before Ida passed she forgot to tell her relatives where to find it.  <p>
Short of conjuring up her spirit, you'll have to rely on the local unclaimed-property office to help you regain Aunt Ida's memory--and her money. Last year, according to the National Association of Unclaimed Property Administrators (NAUPA), more than $2 billion in abandoned goods was collected. Yet only one-third of it was claimed by heirs or other legal claimants, says NAUPA president Randy Ross.  <p>
It's not just stock certificates or silver dollars that are sitting in property offices around the country. Everything from false teeth and Swedish porn films to the patent for brass knuckles has been abandoned.   <p>
States are required to make a diligent effort to reunite rightful owners with their unclaimed assets. (How diligent may depend on the value of the property and the office's workload.) Some post a list of people with unclaimed property at the county courthouse or in the newspaper. Others set up booths at local fairs and run public-service announcements on TV. Or you could simply contact the appropriate state office using our list (click at right).  <p>
Here are a few things you should know before you set out on a treasure hunt for unclaimed goods:  <p>
1. Utility deposits, the contents of safe-deposit boxes, andmoney in checking and savings accounts are the most common abandoned items, according to unclaimed-property administrators.  <p>
 2. States will keep abandoned property--such as fur coats and silver sets--for about a year. Then the goods are sold at a public auction (stocks are sold on the open market). The proceeds are put in an escheat account until a rightful claimant comes forward. Few states pay out interest.   <p>
 3. To make a claim you must provide proper ID. If you contactan unclaimed-property office in a state where you formerly lived, an old utility bill or tax statement will do. Some offices accept a Social Security card as proof.  <p>
 4. If you are claiming a deceased relative's property, you'll have to provide information that will substantiate your familial tie. That done, the state will turn the property over to the administrator of the deceased's estate, who will determine which heirs are entitled to the property.  <p>
 5. Never pay a service charge. Some shifty characters will offer to track down abandoned property for you, charging a percentage (as much as half) of what they recover. There are also third-party treasurers who legally match claimants to their goods. If you contact the state office directly, however, there is no service charge.  
					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
					</font>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/helpdeskwhite.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<b>
					Search for abandoned goods by contacting one of these <a href="/articles/I0301.html">Unclaimed Property</a> offices.
					</b>
	
		
</td>
