<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Shackled or Free?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Shackled or Free?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Want to earn big gains in global stocks? Invest in nations that embrace free markets.<p>
By Jim Rogers<p>
Even the most serious investors sometimes grow panicky at the idea of investing overseas. I guess that for some people the whole idea just seems, well, too foreign. But the truth is that it's not really that difficult to develop a workable strategy for overseas investment. The central challenge is identifying the countries that are doing things correctly and are likely to be rewarded for it -- that's what I've made my business. And now there's a new study, orchestrated by the Fraser Institute, that provides an excellent frame-work for assessing which nations will prosper and which will merely plod along in the years ahead.<p>
The case for foreign investing is so strong that I am not even going to try to debunk the mass mania that has gripped the U.S. stock market of late. (Why try to bring people to their senses about this issue when they're already too far gone?) <p>
Foreign investments provide a degree of diversification (and therefore safety) that no portfolio of domestic equities can ever hope to match. This is particularly true if you view your personal finances in a holistic way. By virtue of living and working in this country, almost all of us are already strategically overexposed to the U.S. economy. Our personal wealth is heavily subject to local wages, local prices, local taxes, and local real-estate values. We all reside in the house of the dollar.<p>
Think about the situation this way: You already know you shouldn't load up your investment portfolio with stock in just one company (thereby putting all of your eggs in one basket). So why, following the same logic, would it make sense for you to hitch your personal fortune to any one national economy -- especially since it is now so easy to spread your investment risk around the globe? The options available today are plentiful. They include global mutual funds, currencies, and international stocks.<p>
Just as successful corporations come and go, so do successful nations. The turnover among economic powerhouses is more frequent than you might think: There's practically a whole new group at the top every generation or so. This phenomenon creates a lot of opportunity.<p>
What's more, there's a real logic to the turns of the global wheel. The formula for successful international investing isn't that difficult to decipher.<p>
Here's my advice: Scout for nations that are living up to the ideals and principles that made our country great -- namely, those with unshackled economies and free markets. Place your bets on these places. I promise that if you do this you will be amply rewarded. In fact, it's practically a sure thing -- as long as you stick to this principle and choose accordingly.<p>
Do you want proof? Take a look at the study put together by the Fraser Institute, a Canadian organization that examines economic and social issues. The study, conducted by an international team under the institute's direction, is an exhaustive report on how differing economic and political approaches affect economic growth rates. In particular, the study examined what impact economic freedom has on the income and wealth of nations (or, conversely, what role central planning, high taxes, tariffs, entitlement payments, and the like play in a country's economic progress -- or lack thereof). The researchers reviewed the performance of 103 nations in four major areas: money-supply growth and inflation; government operations; taxation; and restrictions on international exchange. <p>
What did they find through their study? Nothing that would surprise an experienced global investor. Nations that rate consistently high in economic and political openness have much better growth rates than those that are more statist or closed.<p>
The countries with systems that are most open, such as Hong Kong, Switzerland, Singapore, the United States, Canada, and Germany, all fell into the highest growth category during the 30-year period covered by the study. Those nations with the lowest rankings for economic openness, such as Somalia, Zambia, Hungary, Romania, Brazil, Syria, Uganda, and Zaire, were at the bottom of the heap in wealth generation.<p>
The study also found that when nations improve their level of openness by eliminating trade barriers, freeing financial markets, lowering taxes, and reducing governmental red tape (as, for example, Chile, Portugal, and Singapore have done) greater economic growth results. Countries that take the opposite approach, such as Somalia, Iran, and Venezuela, almost always suffer for it.<p>
The Fraser study concludes that "without exception, countries with either a high level of or a substantial increase in economic freedom achieved positive growth. Correspondingly, the overwhelming majority of countries with low and/or contracting levels of economic freedom experienced declines in per capita GDP."<p>
Countries often get religion about putting their houses in order. What is important is that they follow through and maintain their commitment to this strategy over the decade or so it takes to make a real difference. Thus, investors need to be aware that many political systems -- often those with shortsighted politicians whose electoral horizons are five years or less -- do not facilitate this sort of long-haul transformation.<p>
The study also found that a sound economic system is far more important than any short-term windfall or jackpot. Nigeria and Indonesia provide a study in contrasts in this regard. Back in the 1960s, both ranked among the top ten nations in oil production. Since then, however, Nigeria has bungled its wealth; the country is in deep trouble today. Indonesia, meanwhile, is brimming with prosperity. The essential difference is that Nigeria remained a closed economic system, while Indonesia pursued a more open approach.<p>
Or consider Ghana and Thailand, two agricultural economies. In the 1950s, Ghana was far richer than Thailand. But late in that decade, Ghana's politicians imposed severe trade restrictions in a misguided effort to protect the country's internal colonial prosperity. As a result, Ghana became an economic basket case, and only recently has it shown any signs of recovery. Thailand, in the meantime, implemented free-market economic policies, which led to robust growth.<p>
Then there are Venezuela and Chile. In 1975, Venezuela was relatively open economically, while Chile was bogged down in economic red tape. Chile eventually adopted many economic reforms that freed up its society and enabled its economy to grow. Venezuela followed the opposite course. Chile's average annual per capita growth rate since 1985 has been 4.8 percent. Venezuela's, on the other hand, has been negative 2.2 percent.<p>
Similar patterns exist in South Korea (up) and North Korea (down); Costa Rica (up) and Honduras (down); and Portugal (up) and Greece (down).<p>
What countries should an investor be looking at now? Which nations are pursuing a plan of action that could put them on top in the year 2010?<p>
Here are some of the places that I think an investor should take the time to research: Ireland, Denmark, Botswana, Portugal, China, New Zealand, Australia, Chile, Canada, Peru, South Korea, Ethiopia, Uganda, Mozambique, and Eritrea. <p>
I am especially impressed with the changes taking place in the Far East. Many Asian countries today have the formula right: Their governments' policies produce high savings rates and low taxes. These nations are going to be among the most formidable players in the global economy of the future.<p>
Chile is the tiger of Latin America. It's at the top of the heap in terms of promoting savings and investment and curtailing restrictions -- a policy that pulled it out of one of the most severe economic slumps ever seen in the Western Hemisphere.<p>
The openness of the political system that people choose for themselves makes virtually all the difference in their future. By recognizing this, investors can capitalize on opportunities far beyond their own backyards.<p>
Jim Rogers, a senior contributing editor, is the author of Investment Biker, published by Adams.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
international, abroad, strategy, world, worldwide

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

