<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-The Upward Zigzag</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-The Upward Zigzag</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The markets of Latin America will take investors on a bumpy ride, but the destination could be grand <p>
By Jim Rogers<p>
If you still believe that Latin America is a lousy investment -- the home of tin-pot dictators, banana republics, hyperinflation, bankruptcies, and currency collapses -- you might want to review what has been happening in some of the equity markets south of the Rio Grande.<p>
An investor who put $1,000 into Chile's market index on January 1, 1986, would own $43,600 worth of stock today -- almost 11 times the growth of the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index. During the same period, Colombia's equity market would have transformed $1,000 into $32,228, and Mexico's would have produced $14,501. Note that these are dollar returns, which makes them even more impressive given the region's reputation for weak currencies.<p>
I'll grant that investors in Latin America frequently experience hair-raising moments. Argentina's market soared 175.9 percent in 1989, tumbled by 36.6 percent in 1990, and then blasted up 396.9 percent in 1991. The annual standard deviation for U.S. stocks, based on the S&P 500, has been around 15 percent during the past ten years. (Standard deviation measures volatility over time; the higher the standard deviation, the more volatile the market.) In comparison, during the past ten years, Mexico's market has had a standard deviation of nearly 70 percent and Argentina just over 60 percent, according to a report prepared for the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.<p>
It's easy to forget that Latin America does have a rich economic history. Early in this century, Argentina was among the wealthiest countries in the Western Hemisphere. Peru was tops 300 years ago, and Mexico has had periods when it possessed a fair amount of loot as well. It's also easy to forget just how big Latin America is -- a market of 500 million people, mostly of one religion and one language. (Brazil has 162 million Portuguese speakers, but Portuguese and Spanish are close enough to preclude real barriers to understanding.)<p>
The equity markets of Latin America have become huge, too. The six largest listed $360 billion worth of stocks by the end of 1995. Brazil's market -- the So Paulo Stock Exchange -- is the biggest, with a total market capitalization of $143 billion.<p>
Few Americans realize how significant the fall of the Berlin Wall was to the rest of the globe and especially to Latin America. Without the benefit of Communist financing, the civil wars that plagued this region began to dry up. Statist Latin-American governments, meanwhile, had already begun to discredit themselves with policies that produced a series of debt crises. These countries were ripe for reform, and the people began taking the reins of government back into their own hands. Bureaucracies shrank, tariffs tumbled, currencies stabilized, foreign investors began pouring in money, and democracy flourished.<p>
Today, Chile is the best-managed country in the Western Hemisphere, bar none. That's because it did all of the things you or I would do if we were running an economy: It began privatizing industry, creating incentives, eliminating tariffs, making its currency freely convertible, and playing to its economic strengths by focusing on its comparative advantages. All these measures have taken time to pay off, but today, Chile's currency is the only one in the Western Hemisphere that rises against the U.S. dollar.<p>
Consider this: In 1975, Chile, with a population of ten million, was bankrupt -- just like Cuba, a nation of approximately the same size. Cuba is still a mess, but Chile is now brimming with financial health. These days, any Latin-American politician who isn't seeking to emulate Chile is likely to have a brief career. You don't see too many people pointing to Cuba as a model of anything -- except of what not to do.<p>
Latin-American economies depend predominantly on natural resources. Manufacturing plays only a small role -- and rightly so. Argentina wasted a lot of time trying to protect its inecient pharmaceutical industry -- a country of 35 million can't afford the cost of develop-ing research-intensive drugs. It finally realized it was better off leaving that job to <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a> and focusing on exports of wine and other agricultural products. Soaring worldwide demand for commodities such as oil, cocoa, sugar, and copper should benefit Latin America greatly in the years ahead.<p>
Free-trade-zone groups and common markets are also developing, such as MERCOSUR, which includes Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, and Uruguay, and ANDEAN, which includes Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela. There's even a movement afoot to make the entire Western Hemisphere a free-trade zone. The first meeting toward this end occurred in late 1994, and the goal is to complete the task by 2005.<p>
Latin America won't be a smooth upward ride. I have money invested in Argentina, but the country valued its currency too high too soon. I am expecting a devaluation that will hurt my investment, but I'll just ride it out.<p>
Latin America knows what it wants, however, and its citizens won't put up with the balderdash to which they were subjected in decades past. Too many of them have been to Miami and seen what democracy and prosperity can do.<p>
I also like Latin America because it has a tradition of raising capital and using it to make more capital. And it is ahead of Africa -- another emerging continent -- when it comes to infrastructure and the collective wisdom of how prosperity is created.<p>
Which countries should you consider investing in?<p>
If you're the type for a tightly run ship, then head for Chile. Ecuador has vast oil reserves and agricultural possibilities, but its commitment and currency don't seem as strong as they might be. Drug money still corrupts Colombia, but if drugs are ever legalized, it certainly would be the best place in Latin America to invest.<p>
While much remains to be done in Argentina to overcome decades of mismanagement, the country has an industrial sector and a vibrant agricultural base, which exports many products. It may be able to tap oil in the South Atlantic. I worry about its 1997 congressional elections, though, which pose a political risk to what would otherwise be a bright investment situation.<p>
For a real chance at a financial moon shot, Venezuela is probably the place to go. Venezuela is at the bottom now -- a total economic mess. But it has an impatient and wizened populace, which means its assets won't get much cheaper. This resource-rich nation should also prosper greatly as commodities prices continue to rise.<p>
Peru was in similarly dire economic straits five years ago. The fanatic Maoist Shining Path was at war with the government of President Alberto Fujimori, which appeared to be in danger of collapsing. In 1992, the leader of the terrorists was finally caught and jailed. Fujimori set in place tax and tariff reforms, privatized 51 state-owned industries to bring in $3.6 billion, and brought down hyperinflation. Still, as is usual in these situations, a post-reform recession set in. Class warfare might well have resulted. Fujimori boldly ignored political pressure to relent and stayed the course of his reforms.<p>
By 1994, barely two years later, Peru had achieved the highest economic growth rate in the world -- 12.9 percent. In those same two years, the number of Peruvians living in poverty declined from 53.6 percent of the population to 45.8 percent -- a drop no welfare state has ever been able to achieve. This June, the government plans to enlarge its "citizen-participation program" to offer more shares of Telefonicas del Peru on favorable terms to lower-income Peruvians. A total of 18,500 people have taken part in the program, and the government's goal is to sell half a million Peruvians shares in its own telephone system by the year 2000. Peru's story offers persuasive evidence of the power of free-market reforms. Its story is as remarkable as Chile's.<p>
Brazil, which always has been and always will be the next great country in the world, has finally stopped printing money. No kidding. These are the folks who invented indexing to compensate for inflation rates of hundreds and thousands of percent a year. Yet today, Brazil's currency is reasonably stable against the dollar -- a situation that underscores just how powerful the changes taking place in this region have been.<p>
Any analysis of Brazil, though, must take into account the likelihood of its splitting into two parts over the next several decades: the industrial, Europeanized south, and the lackadaisical, laid-back north. At some point, the south will tire of supporting the north.Brazil is still the largest and most populated country in Latin America. While it has a huge gross domestic product of $890 billion, its per capita income of $5,600 ranks among the lowest in the region.<p>
Will Brazil continue to accept economic reform? It has privatized many state industries and loosened restrictions on direct foreign investment to boost long-term investment. The Brazilian congress is currently debating the troublesome issues of taxes and social security.<p>
Costa Rica is often touted as a great place for Americans to honeymoon or retire, but keep in mind that it has gone bankrupt four times in its short history. This seems to be a country that always fouls itself up. El Salvador might be a better bet in Central America.Mexico is a special case. Every time our southern neighbor has gotten in financial trouble, the U.S. has bailed it out with a big wad of dough. Consequently, unlike Chile and Peru, but like the spoiled child of a rich parent, Mexico has never really had to learn its lesson. The $20 billion to $50 billion we recently put into Mexico (the U.S. government won't say exactly how much it was, so I suspect it's closer to $50 billion) was supposed to rescue the Mexican economy. Instead, it subsidized Mexican interest rates, which bought votes for the ruling party, the PRI.<p>
If Mexico ever truly went bankrupt -- a position from which honest and sober reform might be possible -- I might consider investing in it. From such a base, Mexico could become an economic powerhouse. Mexico's strengths include abundant oil, a huge market of 95 million consumers, a developed agricultural industry, a brisk tourist trade, a large labor pool, and a friendly neighbor with a gargantuan consumer appetite.<p>
The world's major exchanges now recognize the importance of Latin America. In addition to Brady bonds, the principal of which is guaranteed by U.S. Treasury bonds, new instruments in Chicago and New York allow investors to take a position in the currencies and indexes of Latin America. In addition, many Latin-American stocks are now trading in New York. Latin-American mutual funds from U.S. fund families are an option, but pay careful attention to the fund manager's background and experience. You might end up with someone who, five years ago, couldn't have told you where Uruguay was.Latin-American countries are nowhere near their full potential. The alert investor should find many opportunities to hit home runs while our own economy is lucky to bunt out singles.<p>
Jim Rogers is a contributing editor and the author of Investment Biker (Adams).<p>
KEYWORDS: Internatonal Investing, International Economy, Internatoinal Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
