<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Deficit Denial</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Deficit Denial</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The deficit doesn't matter-- unless you want economic growth, lower taxes, and national security <p>
By Jim Rogers<p>
Quit worrying about balancing the federal budget, I'm often told. Avoiding deficits is no prescription for prosperity.<p>
Economist Walter Russell Mead has said so more than once in the pages of this magazine. In the April issue, he wrote that when it comes to deficits the U.S. "ranks at the top of the class among developed countries. As a percentage of [gross domestic product], our estimated budget deficit [2.3 percent] is lower than Japan's, Germany's, France's, and the United Kingdom's." He added that "talk about the budget deficit is to American politics what sand is to the proverbial ostrich: a comforting darkness into which one can plunge when the perils and pressures of the real world become too much to face."<p>
Frederick C. Thayer, professor emeritus of public and international affairs at the University of Pittsburgh, goes a step further: Reducing the national debt is actually a dangerous idea. Each of the six major U.S. depressions, he notes, occurred either during or after a period of government austerity. This includes the years from 1817 to 1821, when the national debt fell 29 percent; the years from 1823 to 1836, when the debt fell 99.7 percent (to $38,000); and the years from 1920 to 1930, when the debt fell 36 percent. The last of these, of course, produced the worst calamity of all: the Great Depression, which began in August 1929.<p>
Thayer also notes that during World War II federal budget deficits ranged from 20 percent to 31 percent of the economy's total output as measured by the gross domestic product. He concludes that there is simply no evidence that government penny-pinching helps sustain national prosperity. <p>
Guess what. I disagree.<p>
Before you shake your head and say, "So what else is new, Jim?" consider the possibility that these deficit apologists may be missing some critical points. Mead is wrong to compare the U.S. with nations that don't play the same part in the global economy as we do. Thayer errs in failing to recognize how much the role of our economy has changed.<p>
Throughout much of its history, the U.S. was a second-tier player in the world economy--like Canada is now. These days, though, we're first among the first-tier players. We're the only world superpower. Superpower status changes everything. It means that we are the nation that has issued most of the world's trading and reserve currencies, the store of value that other nations hold to back their own currencies. In fact, in 1994, 57 percent of the world's currency reserves (not including the U.S.'s) was held in dollars. <p>
This doesn't mean that Germany has a huge vault somewhere full of stacks of U.S. money. It means that the Bundesbank, Germany's central bank, owns tens of billions of dollars of our Treasury's securities. The Bundesbank pays a great deal of attention to the interest it gets on these securities, especially in relationship to the value of the dollar. After all, a falling dollar could negate the interest the German bank earns--or even cause it to lose money. Given this risk, the Germans must constantly ask themselves if they shouldn't sell off their U.S. holdings and buy from, say, the Swiss or the Japanese, each of whom have safer and historically stronger currencies.<p>
All told, foreign central banks now own about $550 billion in Treasury securities--nearly $165 billion more than the U.S. Federal Reserve itself. The foreign holdings equal about 11 percent of the U.S. national debt; the Bank of Japan alone probably owns around 40 percent of that total.<p>
All of these dollars--or dollar equivalents--out there mean that we have become very dependent on the judgment of foreign investors. If these folks decide, for any reason, that dollars aren't a good thing to own anymore, we'll be in so much trouble that even the deficit apologists will be wishing they were ostriches, with their heads buried deep in the sand.<p>
The foreign creditors who buy our debt are savvy, tough-minded folks. They are not playing with mad money; they want to see real returns on their investments. So they watch us very carefully to see if we're keeping our financial house in order. They continually ask themselves: Can we bank on the U.S.?<p>
The answer has obviously remained yes. But the foreigners also have some reasons for feeling edgy--the biggest reason being what has happened to the U.S. debt during the past 25 years.<p>
The national debt has risen almost 13 times over since 1970, from $381 billion to $4.9 trillion (in current dollars). In 1970, we paid only $14.4 billion in interest to service this debt, but in 1995, we paid $232.2 billion, more than 16 times as much. Consumer prices, meanwhile, rose by a factor of 3.93 from 1970 to 1995.<p>
In 1970, 16 percent of our personalincome-tax revenue went to pay the interest on this national mortgage; by 1995, the figure was 40 percent and rising.<p>
What we don't seem to understand as a nation is that even if the annual deficit goes down it's still a deficit--and we're not making a dent in the total debt. We still have to pay more interest year after year.<p>
For most of us, such huge numbers are meaningless--whether the figure is $50 billion or $500 billion. Here's another way of looking at it: Since there are 264 million of us, the cost of paying the interest on the national debt comes to $880 per person. That's $3,520 annually for a family of four. Back in 1970, a family of four had to pay just $284 on the national interest bill. So the bill has risen by a factor of more than 12, nearly twice the rate of growth in the gross domestic product. This disparity will only increase.<p>
Life is already tight. Real wages are stagnating. Can we afford to keep paying more and more each year for the interest on the debt?Some economists maintain that national budgets are qualitatively different from household budgets, that nations don't obey the same rules. After all, no household is allowed to print its own money to pay bills.<p>
On the other hand, if we print too much money--and increase the total supply of dollars--the sharpies at places like the Bundesbank will get very angry, knowing that we are undercutting the value of the dollars they hold.<p>
Keep in mind that it wasn't that long ago that England was the richest, most powerful country in the world. The pound sterling, respected everywhere, was the world's reserve currency and medium of exchange, just as the dollar is today. But the British made the same mistake we're making. They assumed that the world's confidence in the pound could never be shaken. By 1976, the United Kingdom was so awash in inflation that it couldn't find buyers for its long-term government bonds. <p>
What is the overall cost we could pay for our deficit spending?<p>
HIGHER TAXES. As long as we rack up deficits, the government will have to keep raising taxes to pay for the interest on the debt.<p>
HIGHER INFLATION. When politicians become afraid that another tax increase will get them tossed out of office, they'll try printing money to pay off the debt. This adds to inflation.<p>
CREDIT SHORTAGES. In Sweden and Italy--countries with big budget deficits--the government so crowds out other borrowers that businesspeople have difficulty obtaining credit. <p>
RISING INTEREST RATES. As our currency becomes unattractive, the government will have to raise the interest rates it pays to lure buyers for its bonds. Since the government is the most creditworthy borrower, everyone else will be forced to pay yet higher rates.<p>
LESS INVESTMENT IN PRODUCTION. Where would you rather put your money: in a solid currency such as the Swiss franc or in a business that has to wrestle with inflation, higher taxes, high interest rates, and capital shortages? <p>
A LOWER STANDARD OF LIVING. That long slide we've all felt over the past 25 years is traceable directly to the deficit. Since 1985, real per capita economic growth in the United States has lagged behind that of the other industrial nations by more than 43 percent, according to Bankruptcy 1995, a book by Harry Figgie.<p>
Pogo had it right: We have met the enemy, and he is us.<p>
This country had quite a ride in the 1950s and 1960s, when the economy boomed thanks to an unusual confluence of good fortune: cheap raw materials, cheap government, technological advancement, a non-litigious atmosphere, an utter absence of foreign competition (ours was the only major economy that hadn't been ravaged by World War II), and a naive willingness to pollute our air and water. We were rich, and we were prosperous. And we thought the economic growth we were achieving could go on forever.<p>
When things began to slow down in the 1970s, as they inevitably had to, we refused to face reality. Instead, we decided to try to jolt the economy back to its "natural" growth rate by borrowing money. We let the monkey climb onto our backs, and as long as we keep feeding him more bananas, the load will get heavier and heavier.<p>
The sad truth is that throughout history no superpower that has gotten so deeply into such a hole has ever worked itself out. Without a crisis, it's too easy for politicians to put off the day of reckoning year after year. But sooner or later, the market requires such profligates to bite the bullet; one day it decides, in its collective fashion, that it would rather own Swiss francs or German marks. It won't be fun for the U.S. when that happens.<p>
-----------------------------Jim Rogers is a contributing editor and the author of Investment Biker (Adams).<p>
KEYWORDS: International Economy, International Investing, Internatonial Banking

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

