<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Land of Opportunity</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Land of Opportunity</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Africa may appear foreboding and mysterious to most Westerners. But it's also a place to get rich.  <p>
By Jim Rogers  <p>
The paths to wealth in the 19th century were certainly romantic. To encourage economic development, places such as the United States and Argentina gave citizens and immigrants vast tracts of raw land -- in return for little more than a promise to develop this resource. Thousands took advantage of the opportunity, becoming the owners of tens of thousands of acres, which a few decades later came to be worth millions. It sounds exciting, fanciful, and aeons away from the cusp of the 21st century -- except that this sort of opportunity still exists today, found in the only emerging continent left: Africa.  <p>
 Last year, when I outlined some of the following thoughts about Africa in a speech in Washington, I was met with shouts of outrage. Several well-dressed government bureaucrats even left the audience in protest. If there's one lesson I've learned over the years, though, it's to ignore any investment advice from the U.S. government. <p>
 It's true that many people with business degrees still board planes for economic adventure in underdeveloped parts of the world. The Far East is a popular destination nowadays. And even the former Soviet Union, for all its uncertain prospects, gets a fair share of fortune hunters and carpetbaggers. Rarely, however, does anyone embark for Africa with the idea of getting rich. <p>
 This is so even though Mozambique, having suffered two decades of civil war, will virtually hand over one of its old Portuguese plantations to a pioneer willing to restore it and work the land. In Zambia, it's possible to obtain -- in return for expertise and a modest amount of capital -- 20,000 hectares (50,000 acres) of land so rich you don't have to fertilize it. (In some parts of Africa, you can just about sprinkle some seed and wait a few months for your crop to come up.)  <p>
 Africa also carries another enticement: its vast natural resources. Commodities have been in a bear market for 15 to 25 years, depending on which one you use as a yardstick. So they are overdue for a comeback. Sugar is now priced 85 percent below its 1974 peak of 66 cents a pound; gold is down 55 percent from its peak (1980); coffee is down 72 percent (1977); and cocoa is down 80 percent (1977). None of these severe drops accounts for the ravages of inflation. Currently, the prices of many natural resources scarcely cover the costs of production.  <p>
 It's hard to believe, but as late as the 1950s, Africa was a net exporter of natural resources and commodities, and had abalance-of-payments surplus. In 1957, though, Kwame Nkrumah "liberated" Ghana from colonial rule, becoming the first of Africa's many liberators -- all of whom embraced the statist religion of Communism/socialism. Three decades of mismanagement and strife followed.  <p>
 Like people all over the world, though, many of Africa's 800 million residents have become fed up with their wrecked economies and wretched standard of living. Increasingly, they have demanded free elections and free markets. As recently as 1989 there were only three democracies in Africa with open and free markets. Today, there are more than 30. Likewise, the new generation of African leaders knows that its people once governed themselves quite admirably. Consider Egypt, Zimbabwe, and Ethiopia.  <p>
 If Africa interests you as a place to invest, do a lot of reading, ask questions of your local embassies, and go there and look around. I invest in public markets, so I personally would start with the former English colonies, such as Zambia, Zimbabwe, Ghana, Botswana, Namibia, and Malawi, as these have a tradition of operating stock markets, whereas the former French colonies in Africa do not.  <p>
 Botswana, for instance, balances its budget each year and has had trade surpluses for the past 14 years. It has two years' worth of foreign-currency reserves in the bank. Contrast its finances with those of the United States, which hasn't balanced its budget since 1969, hasn't had a trade surplus since 1975, and has become, by far, the world's largest debtor nation.  <p>
 The best way to take full advantage of Africa, though, would be to go there and run your own farm or business. Examine your resistance to the idea for a moment, and you'll understand better why Africa is such a great buy. Don't forget: The chief characteristic of a bear market is that no one wants to buy at the bottom. Nevertheless, by the time you've built a decent house, whipped your land into shape, trained your labor force, set up communications and transportation links, and established markets for your goods, you'll be able to sell out -- if you still want to -- at the top of the coming commodities boom to some knucklehead who has more money than sense and wants to be an African land baron once it has become ultra-chic to do so.  <p>
 It doesn't take lots of capital. African labor is incredibly cheap, and once you have the land, you can borrow or sell equity in your business privately or on the emerging stock exchanges. A dollar goes 30 to 50 times further in Africa than it does here. <p>
 If, however, glorious adventure does not entice you, the next most advantageous way to invest in Africa is to open an account there and buy stock directly on the local exchanges. The third-best way to invest is to buy American depositary receipts on U.S.stock exchanges. The last and least favorable investment method is to buy one of the African funds that have started recently. <p>
 It's odd that people as adventuresome as we are supposed to be are not more interested in Africa. On my motorcycle trip through the continent from 1990 to 1991, from Tunis through the Sahara down to the Cape of Good Hope, I didn't see a single American backpacker. I did, however, run across many European, Japanese, and Australian travelers. The same is true for settlers coming into Africa: lots of other nationalities, but few Americans. <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a>s are scarce, but you'll see lots of Toyotas.  <p>
 Not that Africa will be without problems. The Conference of Berlin in 1884 -- when the European powers assembled to carve up Africa to suit themselves, paying little attention to the continent's historic, tribal, ethnic, religious, and linguistic configurations -- created artificial borders that will continue to be redrawn, sometimes violently.   <p>
 I cannot tell you precisely where to go. Much depends on your temperament and background, and part of the fun will be discovering what suits you. Morocco, Tunisia, and Egypt have developed stockmarkets and more open economies, while oil-rich Libya and Algeria are still closed.  <p>
 A settler in Africa obviously should make an effort to find a locale free of coming political turmoil. If Nelson Mandela were 55 years old instead of 78, I would consider South Africa a superb place to live and invest. It has the best infrastructure on the continent, an educated labor force, many natural resources, and a long and fruitful history of capitalism. Personally, however, I am afraid that after Mandela is gone the struggles between South Africa's 11 official ethnic groups may lead to its being the next Zaire, not the next California.  <p>
 Less adventuresome settlers might consider Ghana, Namibia, the Ivory Coast, Tanzania, Zambia, Botswana, Zimbabwe, and Malawi.<p>
I wouldn't go to Nigeria, the country with the largest population in Africa, as it won't develop until after it divides into two or more countries. The same is true of Zaire, which could easily break into four parts.  <p>
 An example of what's occurring in this part of the world is Mozambique, which the World Bank classifies as the poorest country in the world. The ruling Frelimo party, which led the country to independence from Portugal in 1975 and declared itself Marxist two years later, ditched Marxism in 1990 and is now selling off significant chunks of the economy -- a ship-repair yard, copra and tea plantations, factories, breweries, and hotels -- and wooing foreign capitalists. Between 1989 and 1995 the government restructured (mainly through privatization) 547 formerly state-owned companies. Enron, the gas giant, has invested $700 million infacilities to export natural gas to neighboring South Africa. <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> moved in in a big way in 1994 and sold about 60 million cans of soft drinks in Maputo in its first year of operation.  <p>
 Ethiopia, meanwhile, may blaze the way for 21st-century governance, as its constitution provides that any of its nine member states may legally pull out of its union at any time and for any reason. Thus, the states must all get along; if the other eight treat one badly, it may well leave.  <p>
 Today, Eritrea is one of the most free markets in the world. To its credit, Eritrea's leaders have decided to rebuild its railroad system with purely domestic resources and have refreshingly stated that their goal is to become completely independent of foreign aid soon. Throughout my African travels I found that the wisest people understood that the only true beneficiaries of foreign aid to Africa have been well-connected apparat chiks, Western advisers, and Mercedes-Benz dealers (even if the country didn't have passable roads).  <p>
 Now, if you will indulge me, I'd like you to examine two countries, one in the closing decades of the 19th century, the other in the closing decades of the 20th. Both possess substantial natural resources, including fertile soils, regular rainfall, and sizable mineral deposits. But their economies have been devastated by political instability, huge debts, government mismanagement,the corruption of state officials, civil war, and difficult relations with neighbors. During these unruly decades the leaders of both countries have been periodically assassinated.  <p>
 Agriculture is the most important sector of the two nations' economies, employing over 80 percent of the workforce of each. But each government has recently acted to rehabilitate and stabilize its economy by undertaking currency reform and raising producer prices on exports. In the past few years, both economies have turned in solid performances based on continued investments in the rehabilitation of their infrastructures, improved incentives for production and exports, and gradually improved domestic security. The rest of the world, however, still sees both countries as rude and barbaric.  <p>
 If at the end of the 19th century you'd emigrated to the first, you'd have come to the United States, where you had a chance to make a tremendous fortune, as did a tidal wave of immigrants.<p>
If today you emigrated to the second, you would be investing in Uganda. This African nation is supposed to be the worst ofthe worst, the former fiefdom of the blood-drenched cannibal Idi Amin. But it is now a beacon of capitalism.  <p>
 Since Idi Amin left in 1979, Uganda's exports have increased hundreds of times despite the horrible bear market in commodities during this period. This leap is just the beginning of the story. <p>
 Jim Rogers is a contributing editor to Worth magazine and the author of "Investment Biker" (Adams).   
KEYWORDS: International Politics, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

