<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Sound as a Dollar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Sound as a Dollar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Like it or not, we're all currency traders, and these days the dollar looks like a bad bet<p>
By Jim Rogers<p>
A hundred and fifty years ago banks, as well as governments, printed money that could be traded and used for payment of debts. Even 70 years ago anything could be, and was, used as money__gold, silver, grains, gems. But in the 1930s, the United States and the United Kingdom made it a crime to settle debts with anything other than the dollar and the pound sterling, respectively. Today, it's practically a definition of a sovereign nation that its government controls a single national currency.<p>
This may seem academic, but only because most people don't realize they trade currencies every day. When we buy a Swatch watch, a <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony</b></a> Walkman, or a Mercedes-Benz, we're swapping dollars for Swiss francs, Japanese yen, and German marks. The more valuable the dollar is against these currencies, the fewer dollars the watch, the gadget, or the car will cost.<p>
Unfortunately for all of us currency traders, since 1966 the dollar has declined about 64 percent against the mark, 72 percent against the yen, and 73 percent against the Swiss franc. <p>
During that time, the Dow Jones Industrial Average has risen from 1000 to about 5000. American investors note with pride that $1,000 invested in the Dow 30 years ago would today be worth, with the dividends reinvested, $18,494. But $1,000 placed in a German savings account, with interest reinvested, would be $17,467 now__about the same, but at far less risk. And if you'd bought the German equivalent of the Dow Jones stocks, you'd have $41,637, mainly because of the currency difference.<p>
Currency fluctuations, then, affect our daily lives and hopes for the future. Over time, a strong currency helps us live decent lives, while a weak one makes that harder to achieve.<p>
So, if a falling currency is such a terrible thing, why do countries allow it to occur? The political rationale in the U.S., regardless of party, is that a falling dollar makes our exports cheaper, increasing foreign sales, improving our balance of payments, and creating jobs. That has sometimes worked, but only in the short term. In the long run, a falling dollar encourages investors, central bankers, global businesses, and currency traders to sell dollars and dollar-denominated assets and invest in more-stable currencies. This reduces investment in the U.S. and causes the dollar to keep falling.Before investing in a foreign currency or country, an investor should look at four indicators about a particular nation: (1) its balance-of-trade figures, that is, its net exports; (2) its national savings rate; (3) the surplus or deficit of government spending; and (4) its net foreign-currency reserves.<p>
The balance of trade signals whether a country is selling more than it's buying__as well as what it's buying__which over time is as important as whether a household spends less than it takes in. The savings rate will tell you if money is available for investment, which keeps an economy strong. As for the surplus or deficit, a government, depending on how prudent or profligate it is, can stabilize or ruin an economy. Finally, foreign-currency reserves indicate if a country can weather a financial storm. For example, Mexico, with small reserves, has seen its economy repeatedly implode when the government couldn't pay its debt or support the peso, causing investors to take flight.<p>
I used these same indicators in order to produce an A-list for global currency investors.<p>
SwitzerlandThe Swiss learned early that if they wanted to run the world's bank accounts, they needed a sound currency. Eighty percent of the Swiss franc is backed by gold, and it's also cushioned by a huge foreign-currency reserve. Moreover, if Europe adopts a single currency, the Euro, in 1999, as scheduled, the Swiss aren't likely to convert their franc. This could create a European flight to the franc as the last stable currency, driving up its value. Indeed, the Swiss franc recently hit a nine-year high against the deutsche mark. For sheer safety, the Swiss franc beats all other currencies hands down.<p>
GermanyThe deutsche mark also ranks high on the list. Twice in this century the Germans have experienced the terror of hyperinflation. The wheelbarrows of cash it took to buy bread, the hourly adjustment of restaurant prices, and the murderous politics that inflation helped produce are burned into the German collective memory. As a result, the Bundesbank's mandate is simple: Maintain the value of the D-mark.<p>
Sadly, in 1990, Chancellor Helmut Kohl, approaching an election, bought East German votes by exchanging one West German mark for every two East German marks, while the black-market rate__the best barometer of currency values__was eight to one. Pumping billions of marks into the economy has increased inflationary pressure. This bears monitoring, especially since Kohl has begun to appoint "easy money" types to the traditionally tightfisted board of the Bundesbank.<p>
The German government is also pushing for the establishment of the Euro in 1999. Prosperous Germans are worried that swapping D-marks for Euros could mean a loss of value, and German newspapers warn their readers not to invest in bonds with maturities longer than four years. <p>
Denmark, the Netherlands, and Austria have all linked the value of their currencies to the D-mark. As a result, they are relatively stable, comparing quite favorably to the rest of the world's currencies.<p>
FranceFrance has also tied its currency to the D-mark. Fifteen years ago, it declared it would support the franc fort, much as Germany supports a strong mark. But its success has been mixed, and French politicians must cut expensive social programs and a bloated civil service to make the economy more competitive. The fate of these planned cuts is in doubt, as is the future of the franc. <p>
LuxembourgTiny Luxembourg, with only 400,000 citizens, has the lowest debt in Europe__only 7 percent of its GDP, compared with 65 percent in the U.S. <p>
SingaporeSingapore has the world's highest savings rate at 40 percent (the U.S. rate is 4 percent), a booming high-tech, high-wage economy, and an authoritarian government that forces everyone to contribute to his or her own retirement fund. <p>
New ZealandSeveral years ago, New Zealand, racked by devaluation, government debt, and over-regulation, made a contract with its central bank to keep inflation under 2 percent no matter what. After a bout of unemployment and a recession, the bitter medicine has worked; the N.Z. dollar is now solid and well respected, and the economy is productive. It's an election year, however, a good time to see if the country will stay the course.<p>
JapanFor decades the Japanese yen has gone from strength to strength, as has the economy and trade balance. The savings rate is consistently high. But the party that has governed Japan since World War II is fracturing, and various politicians and factions are vying for power and votes, which they may try to influence by using government spending to boost the stagnant economy. <p>
There's also a demographic risk. Japan is experiencing a massive wave of retirements, but its birthrate has been too low to provide enough new workers to support the elders' retirement benefits. In addition, Japanese society has never welcomed immigrants. These factors will create a huge strain on the Japanese economy and may affect the value of the yen in the next decade.<p>
IrelandSome countries are comers whose currencies may well appreciate considerably over the next few years__just as the yen, D-mark, and N.Z. dollar have over the past decade.<p>
Ireland is such a nation, even though debt is 91 percent of GDP. The savings rate is rising, as is foreign investment, and it has one of the best-educated populations in Europe. Most important, there is a shaky peace in Northern Ireland. If the peace holds, the future of the Irish pound, or "punt," looks bright.<p>
ChileChile's peso, and its people, suffered through the 1970s. But the return to civilian rule and the privatization of the social-security system in the 1980s have sent savings and investment rates skyrocketing. Consequently, productivity has improved and the peso rose more than 5 percent in 1995.<p>
TaiwanThe Taiwan dollar is, statistically, solid as a rock. Taiwan holds $100 billion in net foreign-currency reserves, the economy is vibrant, and it's the richest nation in the world on a per capita basis. However, there is a huge political risk: China, which regards Taiwan as a renegade province, and whose rhetoric and behavior have grown increasingly aggressive. <p>
MalaysiaOne of the Southeast Asian Tigers, Malaysia is blessed with natural resources (oil, timber, rubber, palm oil) and has a strong agriculture sector, a growing manufacturing base, and an authoritarian government committed to conservative monetary policies. <p>
To end where I began, the Swiss franc seems to be the best bet over the next 20 to 40 years. I expect most currencies to decline against it.Of course, many people believe that Swiss banks won't take their money unless they are fabulously rich or have been properly introduced. Well, as "the Indiana Jones of finance" (Time magazine's phrase), I'm here to tell you that few international investments are as easy to make as buying Swiss francs.<p>
Instead of skiing in Vail this year, try the Swiss Alps. Walk into a Swiss bank with proper ID (your passport) and a check in dollars. You'll find the Swiss banker as eager to open an account as a NationsBank officer in Nashville is. <p>
Or try the beaches of New Zealand. Just remember, anyone who wants to create, preserve, or pass on wealth needs to learn about the world's sound currencies, particularly as the greenback becomes less and less of one.<p>
Jim Rogers is a contributing editor to Worth magazine and the author of Investment Biker (Adams).
KEYWORDS: International Investing, International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

