<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-The Specter of Inflation</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-The Specter of Inflation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Reports of inflation's demise are highly exaggerated:  It's alive and flourishing in many world commodity markets  <p>
By Jim Rogers  <p>
Have you been paying attention to the price of grain lately? Or the crop forecasts for 1996? I have even though I live in Manhattan and have no plans to take up sod busting. I pay attention to commodities because it's my conviction that the average farmer has a better handle on what's going on in our economy today than anyone in Washington or on Wall Street.  <p>
 This is especially true when it comes to inflation. The big-city experts, with their fancy computers and econometric models, tell us inflation is no longer a serious threat to our economy. They, Investing Strategiesvesting, Eattribute this critical change in the financial environment to several factors, including the Federal Reserve Board's cautious control of the number of dollars in circulation, ongoing improvements in corporate productivity, and, perhaps most important, the globalization of the world's economies.  <p>
 In a paper entitled "The End of the Inflationary Era," Roger Bootle, an economist at the securities firm HSBC Greenwell, recently wrote that U.S. workers can no longer demand higher wages (and therefore drive up prices), because they risk losing their jobs to less selfish folks in foreign lands. Similarly, U.S. companies can no longer pass on aggressive price increases, because they also risk losing out to foreign competition.   <p>
 Though I have become an increasingly lonely voice on this subject, I don't believe that inflation is dead. In fact, I think it will become a serious problem in the next few years.  <p>
 Why? Partly because the threat of foreign competition is overstated at least when it comes to the supply of goods and materials. Truth is, the developed world's imports from emerging economies aren't much higher now, as a percentage of gross domestic product, than they were in the late 1980s. Foreign workers and foreign companies simply aren't in a position to supply enough goods to function as an effective check against inflation.  <p>
 Then again, foreign consumers may indeed stand ready to give us some competition on the buying side. That would mean a world wide sellers' market. And we all know what happens to prices in a sellers' market: They go up.  <p>
 The message I see coming out of the grain belt affirms this view. Commodity prices are near a five-and-a-half-year high, and are more than 20 percent above where they were in 1993. Corn futures recently hit a 7-year high; wheat prices are higher than they have been in 15 years.  <p>
 Despite cheap labor and the mechanization of giant farms out west, the inventories of corn, rice, wheat, barley, oats, and soybeans are all at their lowest levels in recorded history.This has happened even though the last five annual crops have been among the largest ever. Throughout 1995, the stocks-to-usage ratio for grains was about half its historic level.  <p>
 Why are grain supplies so low? I suspect it's because the new economies of the Pacific Rim, impoverished for so long, can now afford grain, and they're buying it in record quantities. Back in the 1972-to-1973 season, Asians imported 39 million tons of grain. In the 1986-to-1987 season, sales grew to 64 million tons. This year, Asian buying is up to 80 million tons.  <p>
 Russia also may soon come on board as a major purchaser. The Russian infrastructure is falling apart, crippling production. The Russian grain harvest this year is the worst in a long time; it will probably have to import commodities, rather than export them, as it has done in recent years.  <p>
 While grains directly account for a small portion of consumer prices in the U.S., compared with other countries, their indirect effect is much greater. The situation today, in fact, is eerily similar to that of the 1970s, when there were shortages of virtually every major commodity. Many of today's commentators are under the impression that the oil shock caused the spiraling inflation of that period. But get out your chart books. You'll see that the prices of corn, wheat, and other grains rose first, followed by other commodities. Oil was actually the last to take off in price after corn prices had already tripled.  <p>
 Today, supplies of zinc, cotton, and oil, as well as grains, are again near all-time lows. Take cotton prices, which not long ago were the highest they have been since the War Between the States. V.F. Corp., the undergarment manufacturer, recently tooka hit in profits because it didn't, or couldn't, pass on the price of raw material to its customers. To V.F., that's real inflation, and the price of the stock dropped because of it.  <p>
 Keep in mind, too, that new production requires time to establish often years and years. Suppose zinc is in short supply. It takes a while for people to (a) realize that zinc is becoming profitable,(b) find a new supply of zinc, (c) raise the money to open a zinc mine, and (d) bring the zinc on stream.   <p>
 Bottlenecks in supply will occur in the 1990s because major investment flows haven't been directed toward the production of raw materials over the past 15 years. That is, investors have not been putting new money into investments such as zinc mines, sugar plantations, and corn farms. Instead, they've been putting their money into the stock market. Yet as the demand for basic commodities has grown, the relative supply has tightened.  <p>
 Suppose each of the two billion people of China and India starts consuming a mere extra quart of gasoline per week as these economies boom. That's an additional 1.7 million barrels a day enough toraise the world price by 10 to 15 percent.   <p>
 Increases in the price of basic goods are also the true source of upward pressure on wages. When the necessities of life become more expensive, workers ask for higher pay launching the vicious cycle in which demands for higher wages prompt companies to raise prices, which in turn causes further pressure on wages.   <p>
 The dollar's chronic weakness could also add to the inflationary pressures on our economy. Not only do luxury items such as French wines and Mercedeses rise in price as the dollar sinks in value,  but so do the prices of <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyotas</b></a> and Nissans, and ultimately Chevys and <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fords</b></a> as U.S. automakers take advantage of reduced price competition.  <p>
 Other forces are at work, too. In the early 1990s, Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, created a large new supply of dollars to save the American banking system and to reelect George Bush. He succeeded in his first goal but failed in the second.  <p>
 Now Greenspan has cut back a bit. Still, economists such as Milton Friedman note that it takes a few years for liquidity to flow through the system. Like a pig in a python, a surge of liquidity is working its way to the surface and will contribute to the inflation of 1996 or 1997.  <p>
 While Greenspan was acting to boost the supply of money in the U.S., the so-called tight-money Germans created a huge new supply of deutsche marks. To buy votes when the two Germanys merged, the West Germans created four times more marks than were economically justified to convert the East German mark into the West German. <p>
 Not to be outdone, the Japanese banking authorities topped off the bubble economy of the 1980s with hundreds of billions of extra yen. Lately they have again been pumping enormous liquidity into the world's markets. Thus, the three largest economies on the planet, the three that jointly constitute the world's reserve currencies, created a vast new pool of money.  <p>
 "The world is enjoying a situation of significant liquidity creation," Henry Kaufman, the economist, recently told Barron's. "This liquidity explosion is not generating price rises in goods markets, or wage increases, as yet. But it is a powerful force behind price escalation in financial assets, which is another form of monetary reflation."  <p>
Thus, in the 1990s we have worldwide low production capacity, worldwide growth in demand, worldwide low inventories, and a worldwide surge in liquidity. To anyone trained in global economic patterns, this mixture can have only one outcome.  <p>
 How might an alert investor play a resurgence in inflation? <p>
 Start by noting that the world's largest grain producers are the U.S., Canada, Argentina, and Australia. Note also that India, Indonesia, and Russia are the largest importers.   <p>
 Investors obviously can buy futures and options in the agriculture markets. Another course might involve purchasing the common shares of well-run seed, farm-machinery, fertilizer, and other companies in raw material areas. I believe these will be good bets over the next few years.  <p>
 A still more aggressive strategy would be to acquire shares in international farming companies on local stock exchanges in places such as Malaysia and New Zealand or the currencies of the major grain-producing countries. Farmland in Iowa or Latin America may be another smart option.   <p>
 Most of these strategies require professional help, as well as a close eye on the weather, since too little or too much rain can ruin a nation's farm crop.  <p>
 Forewarned is forearmed. The wise investor will look behind today's headlines and expect the unexpected in this case, there turn of inflation.  <p>
 Jim Rogers is a contributing editor to Worth and the author of Investment Biker.<p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Economy, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
