<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-The China Play</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-The China Play</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Rogers<p>
If the 19th century belonged to Britain, and the 20th century to the United States, then the 21st century will surely belong to China. My advice: Make sure your kids learn Chinese.  <p>
I realize this view runs counter to certain popular perceptions. My column isn't called The Other Side for nothing.  <p>
 China certainly does have a long list of problems. It is run by a dictatorship--a hopelessly incompetent and corrupt one at that. Its trade barriers make a mockery of free trade, its labor is cheap and untrained, and it doesn't have the money to buy much of what we capitalists sell. The central-banking system is weak. Inflation is soaring.   <p>
 China is big, but the bulk of its populace lives in the crowded east; the west is mainly a vast desert. The Chinese lack both adequate natural resources and capital. The country's best and brightest have fled during a 100-year brain drain. The remaining Chinese, with an annual per capita income of $361, have a commercial tradition that consists of 46 years of communist rule and, before that, centuries of whimsical leadership by quaint emperors. This is the civilization that invented gunpowder and gave the world the compass, yet it left it to the West to make constructiveuse of these inventions.  <p>
 To top it all off, the Chinese save a third of their income. How can a country grow into a solid capitalist economy if its consumers are so goofy? Shouldn't they spend what they earn, as we do?  <p>
 Against this backdrop of backwardness, though, let's review some of the things that China has going for it. First, the obvious. China's population numbers 1.2 billion--a fifth of the world'sinhabitants living in a landmass the size of the continental United States. China is not only big but booming. Its gross national product has risen by more than 11 percent annually for the last several years, placing it among the world's fastest growing economies.  <p>
 The tens of millions of prosperous overseas Chinese are by no means a liability, but rather a tremendous asset. Not only do most still consider themselves Chinese, but they're also still considered Chinese by China. If they ask for one, they get a Chinese passport--even the fifth-generation emigrant in a Beverly Hills high school who has never even seen a chopstick. The overseas Chinese, with their immense capital and Western expertise, are generally enthusiastic about contributing to China's development--they recognize the  potential for profit.   <p>
 Then there's what the Chinese call "the Asian way," which is rooted in Confucian principles, but which also has a lot to do with plain old common sense. The Asian way involves strict discipline: Everybody in the family works hard and takes care of one another. The code also values frugal living and saving, so the Chinese save and invest 30 to 35 percent of their income.   <p>
 Can you imagine what that can do for capital formation and for a society's ability to compete internationally? Here in the U.S., we save about 4 percent of income, and instead of having a private pension program that invests in our country's future, as does high-growth Chile, we have Social Security, which is a Ponzi scheme and a joke.  <p>
 According to the Asian way, commonsense virtues lead to riches, and riches lead to freedom--which is pretty much the same thing Plato meant when he said that countries go from oligopoly to democracy. Consider this: Taiwan had a wretched military dictatorship for years, but now it has the largest net foreign-currency reserves per capita in the world and is becoming democratic. South Korea has followed the same path.  <p>
 Let's also not forget that China is a big, big market, one attracting tens of billions in foreign investment. To build a strong economy, it helps to have a large home base. In the U.S. we depended on our domestic market for over a century of high growth. In Europe, achieving the equivalent of a large home market was the major point behind the Common Market. The underlying thrust of NAFTA was to expand our own market, preparing North America for the 21st century. But the world's biggest single market is China, and hard by it, Asia itself, with 60 percent of the world's population. <p>
 The Chinese government still calls itself communist, but it started its own deregulation 17 years ago. It's continuing to give its commercial sector the structure it needs to grow and compete internationally. In early 1994, China reformed its trade, foreign exchange, and tax systems. Last year, it announced a series of important changes in its economic legal system, strengthening commercial, central-banking, insurance, and securities law.  <p>
 Unfettered by the central government's nutty notions and restrictions,the Chinese are good business people. Back in the 1970s, China imported cotton. In the 1980s, the government deregulated agriculture, and within a few years China was exporting cotton.  <p>
 Here in the West, it's hard to conceive just how big the Chinese market is. A current goal of the Chinese government is that each resident receive one more egg every four days. The extra chickens required to achieve this goal will annually consume the equivalent of the entire grain crop of Australia, itself one of the world's largest grain-producing countries. China is also planning to add the equivalent of an entire Baby Bell's worth of telephone lines every year. As China grows, its demand for goods and services will significantly increase.  <p>
 Now stand back for a minute and take a panoramic view of the economic map of Asia. Do you see what I see?  <p>
 Consider: China has abundant labor but lacks both capital and undeveloped natural resources. Japan, meanwhile, has all the capital in the world but no natural resources and little labor. North of China sits Siberia, brimming over with natural resources but without labor or capital. There's a potential partnershiphere: Japanese capital, Siberian natural resources, and Chinese labor.   <p>
 Pipe dream? I don't think so. On a recent motorcycle ride through Siberia, I saw Chinese workers operating Russian enterprises in Khabarovsk and Blagoveshchensk with the benefit of Japanese capital and management. As near as I can tell, this golden triangle could become the most productive and prosperous arrangement on the planet.  <p>
 Another thing: Like the Japanese but unlike the North American and European markets, the Chinese are virtually one ethnic group. The Han constitute 93 percent of the population. This means the potential for racial strife and other forms of conflict in China is low.   <p>
 Today there are about 2 billion people worldwide who can speak English and about 1.5 billion who can speak Chinese. Two hundred years ago there were only a few million people who spoke English, and it took many decades for our language to reach its present worldwide influence. The Chinese are starting from a far larger base. We can be sure that hundreds of millions more will speak Chinese by the year 2020, when China has the world's largest economy.  <p>
 One country the U.S. should be emulating is Australia. Today every Australian schoolchild must learn either Chinese, Japanese, Korean, or some other Asian language.  <p>
 On the other hand, just because China is going to be the major superpower of the 21st century doesn't mean a foreign investor can just throw money in China's direction and make a killing. In 1994, 50,000 foreign-funded investment vehicles were formed in China, bringing the total to 222,000. Nevertheless, 72 percent of China's people are rural farmers and workers with income saveraging $120 a year. For the time being, smart marketers are concentrating on establishing their future base by selling in large cities where incomes are higher and they can hope to sell typical consumer goods.   <p>
 For now, productivity levels in China are close to the worst in the world. New foreign enterprises expect to exploit cheap labor. Instead they find their labor budgets bursting because Chinese workers have so little training. Often employers have to import more managers for Chinese factories than they do in other developing countries.   <p>
 In the 1980s almost any foreign product would sell in China simply because it was foreign. Not today. The Chinese consumer now demands quality and won't stand for an exotic label that merely masks cast-off foreign goods. Companies that do their homework, however, that choose Chinese partners with great care and that come to know this market well, have been able to move to profitability within two years of start-up and to pay back their initial investment within five years. China's plans now call for $100 billion a year in equipment and technology imports, with up to a quarter of a trillion dollars to be spent--before the end of the century--on infrastructure.  <p>
 I'm often asked how to invest in China. Deng Xiaoping, China's preeminent leader from 1978 to 1993, the man who tripled its gross national product and transformed China, is near the end of his life. Not until succession is established will the situation become clear. With the wild inflation China now has (between15 and 20 percent a year), there could well be disorder and unrulinessin its markets after his death.  <p>
 I'm going to bide my time. When China's political and economic problems seem to have reached their lowest point, I'll want to step in and act. I'll buy overseas Chinese public companies who have set themselves up with mainland Chinese partners, companies that follow the Western tradition of keeping an honest set of books and sharing their profits with their stockholders. I'll try to find companies that are well-wired into the ruling establishment and that know how to maneuver in this very different land. You can find such companies all over the world, in places like Singapore, Kuala Lumpur, and San Francisco. An example might be Hong Kong-based C.P. Pokphand, an overseas Chinese company that is now the largest single foreign investor in China.  <p>
 And then I'll hang on and probably never sell those stocks. Prime, well-run Chinese companies will be in my estate--and I plan to live a long time.  <p>
 Some Americans are afraid of Chinese military intentions. But is China truly belligerent? Even though 14 countries border China, in over 4,000 years of civilization it hasn't had a tradition of conquering other peoples. The Chinese have never invaded Indonesia; they've never needed to. Even 2,000 years ago they didn't invade Africa or take slaves; they traded with the Africans. Look at the record of other civilizations that attained as much power: Rome conquered, as did Persia, Spain, the Netherlands, England, and Portugal. Remember, the Chinese developed gun powder and horses, the super weapons of their day.  <p>
 Another reason China will tend to be peaceful is its one-child policy. No country in the world has ever had such a policy, and no one knows how this bold experiment will turn out. Nevertheless, I suspect that after two generations of Chinese couples having only one child--who will likely be spoiled and the only apple of the couple's eye--mamas and papas aren't going to send their precious darling to some God-forsaken foreign land to die for the greater glory of Chinese expansion. Such sacrifices will be made only when a couple has several precious darlings.  <p>
 It's been six years since either our president or vice president has visited Beijing, and neither the president nor the premier of China has been invited to Washington since 1988. Both sides are ignoring the deeper reality--that neither country can enjoy peace and prosperity without a constructive Chinese-American relationship.  <p>
 Jim Rogers is the author of Investment Biker, recently issued in paperback by Adams Publishing. He cofounded the Quantum Fund and has taught finance at Columbia University.  <p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
