	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Personal Adviser:  The Most From the Lease</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Personal Adviser:  The Most From the Lease</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						How to drive a hard bargain in today's market of short, sweet auto leases<p>
By Roy Furchgott<p>
How can you tell if you're getting a good deal on your car lease? Compare two car leases currently offered on a pair of luxury sedans, the BMW 740i and the Jaguar XJ6, both of which were chosen as outstanding values by IntelliChoice, a Campbell, California, company that evaluates lease deals. Both leases run 36 months and charge $699 a month -- but the two don't cost the same. <p>
Because of differences in their structures, after 36 months the lease on the BMW would cost you $30,414, while the Jag's would cost only $27,358. And depending on the used-car market, you might be able to knock another $4,451 off the Jag's cost, making it a total of $7,507 less than the BMW, a 25 percent difference -- but we're getting ahead of ourselves. The bottom line is that a lot of factors determine the quality of a car lease. And the most visible ones may not be the most important.<p>
The first lesson for lessees: Don't focus on the monthly payment to determine if you're getting a good deal. That's what many marketers count on, but it's not the critical factor in the quality of the deal. The most important factor is the car's purchase price. Shop the price of the car as if you were buying -- the lower that cost, the lower your monthly payment.<p>
Look for cars that have dealer incentives. The car manufacturers make their money by moving cars off the lot, even at a low price. Sometimes they give dealers money that they can pass along to the consumer -- or keep. Older and less popular models are prime candidates for incentives, but dream machines aren't exempt. In our comparison, the Jaguar scores points because the manufacturer kicks in a $4,552 discount to the dealer, at least some of which is lopped off the car's price. Don't rely on the dealer to tell you about an incentive -- check Automotive News Weekly or the manufacturers' Web sites. If you want a more complete report, current incentives, or a detailed accounting of a specific model's cost and features, contact IntelliChoice (800-227-2665), which will prepare a Just-the-Facts Report for $14.95, or for $4.95 at its Web site (www. intellichoice.com). <p>
The flip side of a car's purchase price is its residual value. A car lease forecasts how much less your new car will be worth at the end of the lease. Most leases today are closed-end -- which means the lessee has the right to buy the car at a specified cost, set in writing when the lease begins. The Jaguar's residual value is set at $25,619. If the bottom falls out of the Jag market, and the car is worth less than that when you return it, it's tough luck for the dealer. On the other hand, if it's worth more, you can sell the car, pay off the residual, and keep the difference. <p>
That's what makes the Jag a potentially outstanding deal. IntelliChoice estimates that the used XJ6 will be worth $30,070 after 36 months, which is $4,451 more than the lease's estimate of $25,619. If you sell the car for $30,070 and pay the $25,619 to the dealer, you can keep the difference, which is equivalent to six lease payments.<p>
For an even better deal, ask Steve Landau, product manager for IntelliChoice, about the sport-utility-vehicle lease he signed two years ago. His 24-month lease on a Jeep Grand Cherokee Laredo costs $215 a month, and the residual price is $20,800. But Laredos like his bring more than $25,000 on the used-car market. If he buys the car at the end of the lease, then resells it, he may clear more than $4,000, equivalent to 18 months of payments -- almost his entire lease.<p>
So what are the new residual-value leaders? "Two years ago it would have been sport utilities, but pretty much that's not the case right now," says Art Spinella, vice president of CNW Research, which tracks lease activity. But there are some promising exceptions in the oversize four-wheeler class: the Chevy Suburban, the Chevy Tahoe, the GMC Yukon, and the Ford Expedition. <p>
New models are a risky but sometimes rewarding bet. "The used-car-market demand for three-door pickup trucks is huge, but there aren't any because they're new products," says Spinella. "Those will be worth far more than their current residual value." Three-door models include extended-cab pickup models like the Ford F-150; the Chevy S-10, C1500, and K1500; and the GMC Sierra and Sonoma.<p>
High-end models tend to hold value worst (which makes them good deals as used purchases), but some specific models whose styling changes little year to year can beat the odds, like the Lexus ES 300, a perennial residual-value champ, as can cars that draw special-interest buyers, like the Jaguar. Regardless of the market, low-mileage, well-kept cars usually top the list.<p>
Even if you find a car to lease with a fair purchase price and a reasonable residual value, there are often little time bombs hidden in the agreement. To keep the monthly payments low, lease companies often try to wring out extra cash in up-front or back-end charges. For instance, a lease may require first and last payments in advance, so you have to lay out three payments at once. Another favored ploy is to offer to reduce the monthly payment through a "capitalized cost reduction"; in other words, the dealer cuts your monthly payment by whatever amount you are willing to put down up front. <p>
These options defeat one of the main attractions of leasing -- no down payment. Unfortunately, most leases do require some money up front, but they can vary tremendously. In our BMW vs. Jag comparison, the BMW loses a few points on this score: The Beemer requires $5,000 down, the Jag $2,200. <p>
Back-end charges tend to be far more punitive. A lot of leases give you a great deal -- provided you drive the car 10,000 miles or less a year. If you exceed the limit, you'll pay penalties. "We have yet to find any significant percent of people in a 10,000-mile lease who didn't pay for extra mileage," says Spinella. Some leases will let you purchase additional miles at the start of your lease at a discount. For instance, one Chrysler lease charges 8 cents a mile for each additional mile paid in advance and 15 cents for each mile over if you wait until the end; some companies charge a penalty of as much as 25 cents per mile. Many of the pay-in-advance deals will refund any of the additional miles you don't use. <p>
Likewise, there are usually penalties for "excessive" wear and tear, often defined as more wear than is "reasonable." One former leasing executive says she knows someone who lost a $500 security deposit because of a chipped headlight. Find out exactly what "excessive" and "reasonable" mean and if you are entitled to an independent assessment. <p>
Resale charges (sometimes called disposition fees), which cover the costs of anything from paperwork to tuning and cleaning the car for resale, aren't unusual. Make sure the lease spells out what they are and how much you will be charged, or, according to the former executive, you could get socked for a $350 wash and wax. <p>
Now that leases are shorter -- most car-company leases run three years, max -- what is happening to all of those off-lease cars? Well, they go back on the market, either as used cars or as second leases. That's right, you can now lease formerly leased cars. A 1994 model BMW 740iL runs $638 for a 36-month lease, while the 1996 goes for $769 -- a difference of $4,716 over the life of the lease. But there are additional concerns with off-lease leases. For instance, since you are responsible for upkeep, you'll want to make sure fast-wearing items are in good shape. "Make sure it has a new set of tires on it," said Spinella. "It's one of the things people overlook. You can negotiate it with the dealer." <p>
Whether buying or leasing a used car, you can stack the risk of repair in your favor by checking a car's history. Dealers cherry-pick the best off-lease specimens for their own lots. For instance, Bob's Lexus would want to keep an off-lease Lexus that might bring more than market price, not only for the income but because it can help boost the dealership's reputation and raise the price of other used cars on the lot. The cars Bob doesn't want go to an auction for Lexus dealers only. <p>
Finally, the cars the Lexus dealers don't want go to a general-dealer auction. So if you're looking at an off-lease Lexus at a Hyundai dealership, you can bet there are better used Lexi out there. Ask your dealer for the Carfax report on that car, which will often reveal a car's origin, as well as information about mileage and other factors. Most dealers will provide the report for free, or you can contact Carfax at 703-934-2664. <p>
Maybe the best news for lessees is that car dealers are losing some avenues for sneakiness in setting up leases. The Federal Trade Commission recently cracked down on five major car companies for ads that offered low monthly payments but buried hefty additional costs in what the FTC called "mouse print." In addition, the FTC now plans to require dealers to provide complete, understandable figures on lease payments. That should eliminate such "deals" as the one cited by the FTC in which the GMAC SmartBuy plan offered a Buick Regal for a tasty $2,000 down and $249 a month for 30 months. Not bad -- except for the $11,677.68 balloon payment at the end of the lease that the fine print required.
KEYWORDS:
Smart consumer, automobile

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

