<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-All In the Timing</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-All In the Timing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						At least the bargains on airline tickets have a consistent ETA<p>By Roy Furchgott<p>Dave Barry once joked that "airfares are now assigned by a machine called the Random Air Fare Generator, which is programmed to ensure that on any given flight (1) no two people will pay the same fare, and (2) everybody else will pay less than you." In reality, airline-ticket prices are generated by yield-management systems -- computers that look at historic booking patterns, compare how many seats are sold with how many should be sold at that time, and offer discounts accordingly. On top of that, there are yield-management professionals -- people who spend their days second-guessing the computers and setting prices themselves.<p>So, how does the thrifty traveler outwit the computer and predict a big sale? It's simple, though a closely held industry secret. "I'm probably breaking some law by telling you this," says an executive who until recently helped set ticket prices for a major carrier. "An airline offers a sale six to seven weeks before a heavy travel time." So, if you want to travel on the Fourth of July, start looking for a sale around the end of May, when fares should be 40 percent to 50 percent below list prices. The sales are typically advertised as lasting only three days, but don't let that scare you. "Never be afraid of a three-day sale," says the airline exec. "They usually get rolled over into a week or more." <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
