<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Flying Under the Radar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Flying Under the Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Something good in fine print: Consolidators' bargain airfares are the real deal<p>
By Rudy Maxa<p>
You'll find the ads plastered on lampposts in downtown Manhattan and in the travel sections of big-city newspapers -- boxes of small, dense type with airline-ticket prices to cities around the world. "Airfare Busters," "Special Airfares," and "24 hr. Discount Airfares" read headlines on flyers and ads that trumpet "scheduled service" but never name the airline willing to fly you from, say, the East Coast to Paris for $479 round-trip with few restrictions. <p>
Is this scam city? No, it's just the semi-secret world of consolidators, the bottom feeders in the hotly competitive arena of airline-ticket sales. Once shunned by many travel agents and viewed warily by travelers, consolidators are now getting respect as consumers begin to understand there's a time and place for these tickets -- as long as you know their limitations. <p>
Consider these round-trip fares offered by consolidators in September and October: New York to Tokyo, $850; Los Angeles to London, $528; Chicago to London, $429. Advance booking is not usually required for these rock-bottom fares, and you often don't have to stay over a Saturday night or a minimum number of days. And which airlines deal with consolidators? Almost all of them, including United, Delta, TWA, Northwest, USAir, British Airways, Virgin Atlantic, Air France, Malaysian Airlines, and Thai Airways.<p>
Larger consolidators buy blocks of seats at deep discounts months ahead of time from carriers whose computers tell them there are likely to be a lot of unsold tickets on particular flights. Or they have contracts with carriers that allow them to buy tickets that carry generous commissions (as high as 40 percent instead of the customary 10 or 12 percent) or at fixed fares, which means they can sharply discount the retail price of the tickets. Or they offer unsold seats on low-cost charter flights.<p>
"Once, we were considered gray-market dealers," says David Scott, president of Euram Flight Centre, a consolidator based in Washington, D.C., that has been in business 17 years. "But today, we're used by all the major travel-agency chains and independents. It's really been driven by public demand. As passengers become more savvy, we've grown in popularity."<p>
Generally, consolidator tickets are the best buy when you want to travel abroad -- most tickets are to Europe, Asia, and Africa -- on short notice and can't qualify for a 14- or 21-day advance-purchase fare. And while you usually can't get a cash refund for an unused advance-purchase ticket bought from an airline, you sometimes can on a consolidator ticket, though often with a service charge taken out of the refund. Most tickets are for coach seats, but some discounters sell business- or first-class seats at about 20 percent below the full fare. Consolidator tickets are sometimes available for domestic travel, but not often, simply because airlines already discount their prices so much there's not much wiggle room. "Domestic carriers themselves put out bargain fares from time to time, and it doesn't make it worthwhile for consolidators to be involved in that market," says Terence Mascarenhas, owner of Up and Away Travel, a New Yorkbased consolidator that's been in business since 1984. <p>
If a consolidator does sell domestic tickets, they're usually for coast-to-coast travel. And there are bargains to be found there as well. Up and Away Travel, for example, offers a round-trip fare of $299 on TWA from Boston, New York, Philadelphia, Atlanta, Pittsburgh, or Washington, D.C., to any major city in California. No advance purchase is required, and passengers accrue frequent-flier miles, which is not always the case on international flights. A few airlines have even granted some consolidators the right to sell tickets between selected city pairs at deep discounts with a three-day advance purchase.<p>
There's still a slightly underground feel to the work of consolidators, probably because airlines never allow consolidators to place their names in their ads. Airlines don't want to anger passengers who paid a higher fare or discourage potential passengers from calling the airlines directly. After all, a major carrier makes a nice profit on the last-minute ticket buyer, who pays at least twice as much as someone who booked ahead.<p>
Some consolidators, such as Euram and Up and Away, are happy to hear from the public; others will sell only through travel agents, who, of course, add a few dollars to the price of the ticket for the service. If you need to fly abroad on short notice, always ask your travel agent for a consolidator ticket; if your agent doesn't deal with consolidators, find another travel agent. <p>
Does this mean you should always wait until just before you travel to buy a discount ticket? Absolutely not. If you know your itinerary months ahead of time, you may pay no more for an advance-purchase ticket than you would later for a consolidator ticket. And you'll be assured of flying the airline you want on the date and time you want. Since consolidator tickets are primarily useful when you're traveling on short notice, they're of special interest to business travelers, who usually can't book ahead.<p>
How much can you save? The numbers change all the time, but according to prices cited in Consumer Reports Travel Letter, passengers can save $100 to $199 per ticket on domestic and European travel and $400 or more on trips to Asia. The best deals to Europe are in the summer, when retail prices are at their peak, while the savings to Asia are generally good year-round. <p>
If you're a frequent candidate for consolidator tickets and want to know everything about the industry, get a copy of Kelly Monaghan's Consolidators: Air Travel's Bargain Basement, which is available for $8.95 at travel bookstores or from the Intrepid Traveler (call 800-356-9315). If you want to know about consolidator flights and approximate fares around the world, subscribe to Jax Fax, a monthly travel-marketing magazine that lists thousands of such flights, from the obscure (Burkina Faso to Chicago for $1,390) to the more common (Tokyo to Washington, D.C., for $755). A one-year subscription is $15 (800-952-9329). Remember that many of the fares quoted in Jax Fax are "net"; they're what a travel agent pays, so you're likely to pay a slight premium. <p>
And how do you protect yourself from a fly-by-night, seat-of-the-pants consolidator? Always pay for your ticket with a credit card and, if you're not familiar with a consolidator that sells directly to the public, use a travel agent who knows consolidators. Get your ticket in hand as soon as possible, verify it with the airline, and make sure the initials in the "Status" box on your ticket are either OK or KK.<p>
Other concerns: Consolidator tickets generally link big cities with other big cities, so if you're looking for a consolidator ticket between Birmingham, Alabama, and Helsinki, you're out of luck. You may find yourself holding a ticket on a third-world carrier you've never heard of, particularly on flights to Europe; a carrier that serves the Near East or Africa will drop you off during a stopover in Europe. If you're not sure you want to fly a lesser-known carrier, always ask which airline you'll be on; if you don't like the answer, keep shopping. If your flight is canceled for mechanical reasons, the airline may not be willing to endorse your ticket over to a rival carrier. If you're on a charter flight and there's an equipment problem, there may not be another aircraft available quickly.<p>
And, finally, a more personal concern: The passenger sitting next to you may hate you if he or she finds out the bargain price you paid for your ticket.<p>
KEYWORDS:plane, travel, cheap

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
