	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Expat, Phone Home</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Expat, Phone Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Callback service makes it cheaper to dial from abroad<p>
By Russ Baker<p>
Expat, Phone Home<p>
If you've ever found your phone calls from a foreign hotel costing almost as much as the room itself, relief is on the way. The overpriced international call is being challenged by a feisty bunch of telecom start-ups. A program dubbed callback service allows you to call from a foreign location to the U.S. or elsewhere at more reasonable U.S.based rates. The system is simple: You trigger a U.S. phone, and it calls you back.<p>
Here's how it works: You sign up with a callback company before leaving the U.S. If you know where you'll be staying, you notify the service of the phone number of your foreign hotel. In many cases, you record a message, such as "Please connect me to Mr. Smith's room." Then, when you're in your hotel room and ready to make some calls, you dial a U.S. number provided by the callback service, punch in a code, and hang up (that call isn't long enough to register as completed with the local telephone company). Within seconds, the phone in your hotel room will ring, and you will be hooked up to a U.S.based outbound line and able to dial any other number at much lower rates.<p>
Callback rates compare favorably not only to what hotels charge, which can be several hundred percent higher, but also to other dialing options, including calling cards issued by foreign phone companies or by your long-distance carrier. On a recent visit to Mexico, I found the callback service charging a flat 68 cents a minute, compared with <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>'s calling-card rate of $2.10 for the first minute and $1.76 for each additional minute (plus a $2.49 charge per call). <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> Direct is about the same. On a ten-minute call, I'd save a whopping $13.63, or two-thirds, with callback. Generally, you'll save the most with callback service from developing countries, which tend to jack up the price of long-distance service as a means of subsidizing cheap local service.<p>
Perfect it ain't. Almost no regulations or laws govern the callback companies, and a few are on the roguish side. Before you plunk down a deposit of several hundred dollars on your credit card, ask around for advice. One way is to visit the Web page of San Francisco based M. J. Scheele & Associates (<A HREF="http://www.callbackinfo.com/callback">www.callbackinfo.com/callback</A>), a consulting firm that specializes in analyzing the callback business. If it lists a company, there's a good chance it's legit. Key issues to research include the sound quality (a few offer a good price but poor reception) and whether the service has the right technology to handle fax or modem calls. And some start billing when you trigger the callback, not when your ultimate call goes through. <p>
While in Mexico, I discovered another potential problem with callback: The push-button phone in my room wasn't a real Touch-Tone, which is required for the service to work. A portable tone dialer, available for under $20 at most electronics stores, allows you to transmit Touch-Tone sounds through a rotary handset.<p>
Many of the callback services have a monthly fee, often about $10 or so, which you can earn back with just one long call. Shop around. Some firms will give you a credit to try the service. And prices are dropping fast: The callback company that charged me 68 cents a minute from Mexico now wants just 49 cents a minute.<p>
That's because callback's popularity is causing competitors to sprout like weeds. In 1996, callback spending is expected to exceed $500 million -- a lot of money to spend on rum swizzles and tchotchkes rather than telephone calls home.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

