<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Tightwad Tips for Millionaires</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Tightwad Tips for Millionaires</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Buried within the cheapskate newsletters are smart nuggets fit for a Gates.<p>By Ken Kurson<p>I made what may have been my very first financial observation on a Halloween many years ago. After an evening of continual disappointments, I asked my dad, "Why do the biggest houses always give the shabbiest treats?" His answer, proved right a thousand times since, was simple: "You don't get rich by giving stuff away." <p>While that didn't explain our own family's habit of rewarding trick-or-treaters with a penny each, it did provide a critical lesson: Everyone, rich or poor, likes to save a buck.<p>As it happens, there are dozens of newsletters devoted to achieving that end. Every month, editors cobble together novel ways to save pennies on trifles and hundreds on big-ticket items. Some pepper their practical advice with lectures on the evils of materialism, others speak to the sanctity of thrift, and still others embrace simple living with near-religious devotion. But all agree that the term "cheapskate" is a compliment.<p>Hard-core adherents to what has become known as the frugality movement comb these penurious publications for tips, typically contributing their own money-saving ideas to form a sort of tightwad jam session. The suggestions range from obvious (buy used clothes instead of new) to insane ("I have been toying with the idea of purchasing a steer and having it slaughtered for my family's consumption"). But in between are plenty of creative, interesting ideas for saving money, time, and hassles.<p>I spoke to the editors of 6 newsletters, pored over 4 books, and consumed 31 issues of 8 newsletters -- from Living Cheap News to Bottom Line Personal, which tosses serious investment tips into its brew of money-saving ideas -- to bring you the following list of the best these publications have to offer. Some of them will save you a significant amount of money; some are good for a laugh.<p>If you're buying a new car, do so at the end of the month. The dealer is usually less anxious about covering monthly overhead costs then and is motivated to sell in order to avoid paying another month's interest on the borrowed inventory. Furthermore, salespeople may be participating in a bonus plan that kicks in based on the number of sales made in a month. If he's nearing his quota, your salesman may settle for less commission on your car than he would have at the beginning of the month. Also recommended: Shop just before closing -- when the salespeople are eager to make a deal and the rust bucket you're trading in will get a less thorough examination -- and buy in September or October to get deals on end-of-model-year autos. (Tightwad Living)<p>Bigger is not always cheaper. Grocery stores are hip to the fact that shoppers automatically associate a larger size with a lower cost per ounce, so they've begun to price some popular middle-sized containers higher than both the small and the large. Remember to compare on a per-ounce basis. (Simple Living News)<p>Many foreign travel agencies are less than reputable. To avoid losing your deposit, always charge your reservations on a credit card that offers protection from sudden bankruptcies and bogus deals. (Living Cheap News)<p>If you're prescribed a new drug, ask the doctor to give you samples. Make sure you don't waste your money on medication that may produce side effects. Failing that, ask your pharmacist to sell you only one week's worth of the drug, so you can try it out. (Tightwad Living)<p>It's a point that bears repeating: Percentage increases can be deceiving. An 8 percent mortgage is actually 14.29 percent more in interest than a 7 percent mortgage; a rise in the prime rate from 4 percent to 4.5 percent is an interest jump of 12.5 percent. (Tightwad Gazette)<p>Lots of stuff can be put to work for purposes far different from what you read on the label. Toothpaste is slightly abrasive, so it makes an excellent grout-scrubbing agent. A spritz of hair spray will help take the static cling out of nylons (spray lightly before wearing). A few drops of fabric softener added to water will take the static out of blinds and help keep the dust off the top of the refrigerator. And shaving cream works wonders as an eyeglass-cleaning solution. (Simple Living News)<p>Examine your insurance closely and regularly. Alter it as your life changes -- for example, a five-year-old car may no longer need comprehensive coverage. And stay away from service contracts! (Tightwad Gazette) <p>Did you send your kid to summer camp this year? You might be able to claim the child-care tax credit for a portion of a day camp's tuition. Numerous conditions apply, so check with your accountant. (Bottom Line Personal)<p>If you rent a truck, do so at midweek at midmonth -- and not in the summer. (Tightwad Gazette)<p>Do your homework before bidding in an auction. An experienced auction attendee, Dean King, formerly of The Penny Pincher's Almanac and author of From Paper Clips to Printers, recommends deciding on a few things you'd be happy with before the start of an auction. "Be prepared to pounce if nobody bids," King says. "I got a late-19th-century oak desk for $350 that way." King also recommends that when you're buying computer equipment call a store in New York City first. Because of the 8.5 percent sales tax, New York City computer stores often have to offer rock-bottom prices to compete with the mail-order warehouses. Once you get the store price, call the warehouses and use the store price as leverage.<p>Some states offer an auto-insurance discount for drivers who take a skills-refresher course aimed at older drivers. (Cheapskate Monthly)<p>Do you rent out a residence that you own for two weeks or less over the course of the year? The income you receive is completely free from federal tax and doesn't even need to be reported to the IRS. It'll be too late for Atlanta residents to use this advice during the Olympics, but others take heed: If you live near a hot tourist spot, plan to take your respite during the event so you can use the tax-free income to pay for your own vacation. (Bottom Line Personal)<p>When returning any goods purchased through the mail, ask vendors to provide postage. They usually will, but only if you ask. (Simple Living News)<p>Some banks have begun to add insurance charges to cover the stuff in your safe-deposit box. This coverage is optional, though invoices don't always disclose that fact. If you already insure your valuables with a rider on your homeowner's policy -- and if you don't, you should -- cross out the insurance charge on your bank's bill and pay only the rental fee and the tax. (Bottom Line Personal)<p>Use the lobby phone for long-distance calls from hotels. Some hotels charge 25 to 55 percent of the cost of the call for the convenience of using the in-room phone. (Cheapskate Monthly)<p>
Household remedies are a staple of thrift newsletters. This one, tested on my own clogged drain, works quite well. Pour one cup of baking soda into the drain, followed by one cup of vinegar. Immediately pour a full pot of boiling water down, and use a plunger if necessary. It's not only much cheaper than a commercial drain unclogger but also far less toxic. (Tightwad Gazette)<p>So you've saved a couple bucks on Drano and a couple hundred on your taxes. You've learned to replace expensive items with cheap alternatives that function just as well. Clearly, your thrift has freed up some cash for a splurge -- I hear there's a lovely crystal turtle at Tiffany's...<p><p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Family Finance, Telecommunications Industry, Insurance Industry, Travel Industry, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
		<a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  
		<a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  
		<a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
		<font size=-1><i>&copy; 1996 Capital Publishing Limited
		Partnership</i></font>
		

		</center>
	
