<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Lost in the Translation</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Lost in the Translation</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Lost in the Translation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> LOST IN THE TRANSLATION <p>The fine print on consumer documents can read like a foreign language. Here's how to speak like a native.  <p> By Alan Siegel  <p> When it comes to deciphering your obligations and rights, determining what you owe, and learning what you need in order to comparison shop, most business documents aren't a lot of help. The vast majority of consumer contracts and statements are confusing, uninformative, even misleading. You have to deal with industry jargon, hidden charges, dense legalese, and microscopic text apparently designed for maximum density.  <p> After studying 30 typical consumer documents, from cable-television  bills to leasing agreements, I chose four that demonstrate the problems consumers face. Here are some guidelines, based on those documents, for avoiding mistakes and saving money.  <p> CIRCUMLOCUTORY CELL-PHONE BILLS. Some cellular-phone companies charge a hidden fee (usually three dollars per month) to provide a detailed bill. I paid the fee for years before I noticed an "optional features" charge and asked customer service about it. The company promptly volunteered to remove it and credit me retroactively because I'd been "such a good customer."  <p> When you sign up with a cellular provider, it's a good idea to keep the first bill you get so that you can compare it with later statements and detect any fees that have been tacked on. For your regular phone service, put one bill aside and, with the help of the phone company if needed, make sure that every charge is reasonable and proper. That establishes a baseline for detecting dubious charges. In 1993, Pacific Bell paid out $34 million to customers after a consumer group called Toward Utility Rate Normalization sued it for slapping unwarranted late charges on unsuspecting callers.  <p> ELLIPTICAL ELECTRIC BILLS. All the jargon on an electric bill boils down to four items: the billing period, the meter reading for that period, the charge per kilowatt hour, and the amount due. Be skeptical of noticeable upticks in any of these four categories and any monthly service work or late charges, says Ken Gordon, a staff attorney for the New York State Citizen's Utility Board. Ignore all the other noise that comes with the bill. Several companies, such as New York City's Consolidated Edison, include a graph of the average customer's use, but this is more confusing than helpful: For a city customer the averages are of all Con Ed residences in the city, from a Manhattan studio apartment to a four-bedroom house in Queens.  <p> MONSTROUS MEDICAL BILLS. The New York Times reported in 1993 that the average hospital bill contained almost $1,400 in "unnecessary charges." At the same time, these bills have become so full of incomprehensible codes and euphemisms that it has become increasingly difficult for patients to read them and spot mistakes. <p>While it is nearly impossible to comparison shop when it comes to health care, there are a few things the wary consumer can do. If you don't recognize a listing on the itemized bill, ask the hospital directly. (Marti Ann Schwartz, the author of Listen to Me, Doctor, reports that she was charged for a circumcision after her daughter's birth.) Pause when you see vague charges like "personal hygiene" (a toothbrush) at $5 a day, or $15 for a "thermal therapy kit" (an ice bag). Finally, if you're unsure about an item and the provider won't listen, contact Med Resolve (800-397-5359), which will audit your bill and help recover unwarranted charges for a fee. (The cost, based on the amount of the hospital bill, starts at $50.)  <p> ARCANE AUTO LEASES. Suppose you decide to end the lease on a1995 <a name="NYSE:HMC"></a><b>Honda</b>. Here's part of what the termination clause says: "I agree that the payment liability upon early termination will be...the amount, if any, by which the sum of the Adjusted Lease Balance as described in Item 8, plus one Base Payment, Item 3A, exceeds the Realized Value, as determined in accordance with Item 15..."  <p> And so on and so on, ad nauseam. This language was so bad that it led to a 1993 lawsuit  in which Betty Lundquist of Westport, Connecticut, sued Security Pacific Automotive Financial Services, claiming the company's standard lease violated the terms of the Consumer Leasing Act. Lundquist lost, but the judge hearing the suit deemed the lease "confusing, unduly complicated, and unnecessarily convoluted."  <p> Most leases have more problems than fuzziness, though. Critical information -- the car's price, the interest rate, and the amount the dealer agreed to pay for the trade-in -- does not appear on most contracts. Only the monthly payment, which may be inflated by hidden charges and manipulations, shows up.  <p> Before you leave the lot, make sure you understand all the important points and have them in writing: the trade-in value, the cost of the car, the interest rate. Don't be pressured into signing right away; take the lease home and study it.  <p> There is some good news. Twelve car lessors, including <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a>Motor Credit and <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a> Auto Financial Services, have started printing full-disclosure contracts to simplify their leases. Five states -- New York, New Jersey, Florida, Washington, and Maryland -- have now passed laws mandating disclosure of a leased vehicle's cost. And the Federal Reserve, which is responsible for enforcing truth-in-lending laws, has proposed a regulation that would do the same nationally.  <p> The fact that car leases -- traditionally among the most inscrutable of consumer documents -- are getting clearer is a hopeful sign. Perhaps one day customers will be able to trust all their statements without having an attorney reading over their shoulder.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
