<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - The Art of the Meal</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Smart%20Consumer>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>SMART CONSUMER</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>The Art of the Meal</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Get a good deal at better restaurants with a discount dining card. The newest ones let diners save without feeling like cheapskates. <p> By John Mariani  <p> It may well be true that there's no such thing as a free lunch, but how does 25 percent off sound? This is the idea behind a fast-growing company named Transmedia Network, which issues acard that lets members dine at some of the top restaurants in the country at a guaranteed 25 percent discount. The key to the program's popularity is what it doesn't involve: coupons, advance notice to matre d's and waiters that you'll be paying less than full price, and limits on menu choices and dining times.  <p> It works because restaurants like it, and here's why: Let's say a restaurateur needs $50,000 to renovate his kitchen. Rather than ask for a loan from a bank (notorious for rejecting risky businesses like restaurants), he applies for the money from Transmedia, which gives him the money outright--it's not a loan, so no interest is charged. In return, Transmedia receives from the restaurant double the face value of the cash in the form of food credits to be used by Transmedia cardholders.   <p> The $50,000 cash infusion for the restaurant becomes $100,000 in food credits, which cardholders dine out on. Since a restaurateur's food and beverage costs rarely add up to more than 30 percent (with most other expenses fixed), the hundred grand in food credits is really only costing him $30,000. In the meantime it puts alot of new customers in his seats and allows him to renovate his kitchen.  <p> <p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Even waiters like this discount card.</font></b><p>  <p>As for the cardholder, let's say she goes to the restaurant with a friend and racks up $200 worth of food and wine. When she presents her Transmedia card for payment, the bill reads $200, and she is taxed and is expected to tip on that amount. Transmedia records the sale as well as a 25 percent credit and forwards both to the member's Visa, MasterCard, or Discover account.  <p> Transmedia makes its money from a $50 annual fee from cardholders, from the spread between food credits and the 25 percent discount, and by franchising the concept around the United States and licensing it in Europe. Launched in 1984, the Transmedia program is now offered in more than 5,000 restaurants across the U.S., the Caribbean, South America, Australia, and Europe. At a time when business-meal tax deductibility has been cut to 50 percent from 80 percent, the program is attracting more and more corporate accounts, including 2,000 Prudential Securities executives.  <p> <p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Restauranteurs use the discount card to reel in fresh customers. The downside is when regulars plunk down the card.</font></b><p> <p>By and large, restaurateurs who have participated in the program are quite happy with it, especially the ease with which they can get cash and attract new customers all at the same time."It's been working wonderfully," reports Roberto Donna, chef-owner of Galileo, one of Washington's priciest Italian restaurants."It gives people who think we're too expensive a chance to try us out. Some people are simply scared to walk through the door, but with the discount they can afford us, and we've found 40 percent of them come back to dine here again." Donna also reminds his service staff to pay extra attention to Transmedia customers, who now form 4 percent to 5 percent of Galileo's business, so that they will not feel embarrassed by presenting a discount card.   <p> There are drawbacks for the restaurants, however. "We do get new customers, of course, but some of our old customers also use the card to get that discount," says one restaurateur. Even worse, from the restaurant's point of view, is that the discount applies during peak hours and to meals that are already offered at a special rate. On the other hand, if you're carrying the card, this no-ifs-ands-or-buts policy has enormous appeal.  <p> <p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>Thrifty diners aren't limited to second-rate restaurants. Even the best establishments now honor the card.</font></b><p> <p>Traditionally, the best restaurants have been wary of joining dining-card programs because they don't want to be thought of as discount houses. A look through Transmedia's directory (updated and sent out to members every six weeks) suggests that this program has broken through.   <p> In Washington, D.C., you can eat at Occidental Grill, a favorite of local lobbyists. The New York list includes the wildly popular and theatrical Tatou, Bellini by Cipriani (an offshoot of Venice's Harry's Bar) in the theater district, the lavish Sign of the Dove, the perpetually packed Coco Pazzo on the Upper East Side, and even Chanterelle, which just received four stars from the New York Times. Philadelphia's choices include the superb La Truffe, the baroque DiLullo Centro, and the beautiful Meiji-En, a Japanese restaurant overlooking the Delaware river.   <p> A similar program called IGT (In Good Taste) is good for discounts on a wide array of goods and services, including plane tickets, clothing, jewelry, and concert tickets, but its choice of fine-dining restaurants is not nearly as extensive as Transmedia's. Membership is $48 for the first year and $25 a year thereafter. For informationon IGT, call 800-444-8872; for information on Transmedia, call 800-422-5090.  <p>  <hr>  <p>This article appeared in the February 1994 issue of Worth magazine.Data updated in December 1995.  <p> 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
