<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - Cracks in the Foundation</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Smart%20Consumer>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>SMART CONSUMER</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>Cracks in the Foundation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Sinking foundation? Leaky roof? That new-home warranty can givehomeowners a false sense of security. It may be coming apartat the seams, too.  <p> By Kathleen Murray  <p> Several years ago, James Blythe's $150,000 home in Warrenton,Virginia, started listing to port. Cracks fissured the walls;doors and windows could no longer be closed in their warped frames. <p> Blythe took comfort in his ten-year new-home warranty, whichhe assumed would cover the $34,000 in damages his house had sustained.But his confidence may have been misplaced. Home Owners WarrantyCorp. in Arlington, Virginia, which insured Blythe's builder,went bankrupt last October after state insurance regulators discoveredthe company was short $45 million.  <p> Home warranties were created in the 1970s to pay for repairsto new houses if the builder was unable to do so. To secure coverage,builders paid warrantors a premium, which was passed along tobuyers. A typical warranty provides ten years of coverage againstmajor structural flaws and mechanical defects and shorter periodsof coverage for less serious problems. By 1994, HOW, the largestof six national home-warranty companies, covered 2 million newhomes with ten-year warranties, commanding half the market. <p> **Homeowners filing claims may find themselves settling forless--60 cents on the dollar less.** <p>HOW wasn't the only large warrantor to experience financial difficulties.In 1993, the next-largest home-warranty company, Home BuyersWarranty Corp., based in Aurora, Colorado, was placed under supervisionby state regulators after the insurance company that backed itfailed to meet a new, higher capital reserve requirement. Thecompany resumed normal operations in September of that year,after the insurance company received an injection of new capital. <p> Blythe is one of about 1,500 homeowners with HOW warrantieswho have filed warranty claims that were not settled as of lastOctober. And because HOW is paying only 40 cents on the dollaron claims for homes built in the last decade, these people maybe stuck paying for thousands of dollars in repairs. More than1.5 million other homeowners will wind up with completely worthlesswarranties should the company go out of business.  <p> **Look who really benefits from warranties.** <p>This does not surprise homeowner advocates. According to JordanClark, president of the United Homeowners Association in Washington,D.C., the purpose of warranties is less to indemnify new-homebuyers than to provide cheap protection for developers. For example,warrantors often charge builders just $600 for a ten-year policyon a $300,000 home, leaving themselves vulnerable to big losses.And though home warranties are supposed to cover all major structuraldamage, many warrantors try to avoid payment by including a clausestipulating that a house must be unsafe, uninhabitable, or unsanitaryto qualify for a claim. According to R. Jean Fischer, founderof the Ridgemere Institute, a home-warranty consumer group inNashville, this practice violates insurance laws.  <p> "Warranties are deceptive and give the homeowner a false senseof security," says D. Brent Lemon, a Dallas attorney who hasfiled dozens of cases against HOW. They may even limit a buyer'srights. For example, in Texas, homeowners by law get four years'worth of protection against construction defects, while the averageten-year warranty provides two-year coverage. If Texas homeownersaccept the builder's warranty, they lose the more extensive state-mandatedprotection. <p>  <p>**Read the fine print, check the soil.** <p>In an effort to protect themselves, warrantors have begun toclarify their contracts. Residential Warranty Corp., for example,"now makes a point of writing limited' continuously throughoutits warranty," says Tom Bothell, a company spokesman.  <p> Federal and state oversight of this business is lax, so it'sup to home buyers to protect themselves. Read the warranty carefullyand be sure you understand the extent of its coverage. Most warrantiescover only defects in manufacturing and materials for one yearand don't cover such nonstructural damage as flooring or furnitureruined by flooding. However, a home insurance policy can be usedto fill in those gaps. <p>  <p>Anyone signing a contract on a new home should check the builder'sreferences, licenses, and insurance. Fischer recommends thathome buyers review floor plans and code inspection reports, talkto architects and local inspectors, and pay an independent soilengineer the few hundred dollars it costs to determine if thehome is built on solid ground. <p>  <p>Homeowners should also hire an independent engineer to inspectthe house. It's not cheap--anywhere from $500 to $1,500--but"considering your house is likely to be the biggest investmentyou'll make," says Fischer, "it's worth the money."   <p>  <hr>  <p>This article appeared in the October 1995 issue of Worth magazine. <p> Copyright 1995 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved. <p>
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
