<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - Hit the Info Highway</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Smart%20Consumer>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>SMART CONSUMER</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>Hit the Info Highway</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Car-lease shoppers have begun cruising the Internet. Armed withinsider information, they're turning the traditional hagglingprocess into a contest between equals.  <p> By Ellen DePasquale  <p> In increasing numbers, potential car buyers are becoming potentialcar leasers, and thousands of them have turned to a new resource:the information superhighway.   <p> Leases now account for 30 percent of all deliveries of new cars,up from just 7 percent a decade ago, according to Business TrendAnalysts, a Commack, New York, marketing research firm. It'sonly natural that leasing information should sprout up on theInternet.  <p> The Internet helped David Goldstein, owner of a software-productioncompany in Seattle, make his decision to lease. While waitingin a car dealership to look at a $13,700 Plymouth Neon last February,Goldstein noticed an ad in a local paper for a leasing deal onan Infiniti. That night, he downloaded some numbers to his homecomputer from several online services and crunched out some leasingcosts. He found that his monthly outlay would be the same forpurchasing the Neon as for leasing a $24,325 1995 Infiniti G20.  <p> **Before you can crunch the numbers, you have to find out whatthey are.** <p>"I was able to plug in the figures I had and determine that theInfiniti payment should come to $208 a month," Goldstein says."The dealer came back with $210, which I accepted." Indeed, luxury-cardealerships seem to be the best place to hunt for leasing bargainspartlybecause of manufacturer subsidies and partly because of strongresale values, both of which help lower monthly payments.   <p> If leasing seems worth pursuing, the first step is to find outhow much the dealer paid for the car which will determine howmuch he's willing to take for it.   <p> CompuServe offers car data sheets that include the manufacturer'ssuggested retail price and dealer invoice prices as well as chargesfor available options. Each sheet, provided through an agreementwith Automotive Information Center in Acton, Massachusetts, costs$1.50. Prodigy and America Online, as well as CompuServe, provideaccess to magazines such as Car and Driver and  Consumer Reportsthat have information on car values. The online services alsoprovide user forums, such as CompuServe's Automobile Forum, wherepeople around the country offer tips and opinions on leases andcar models.  <p> **After finding the best wheels, go back online to learn tohaggle for the best deal.** <p>With price information in hand, a shopper can then check outFinanCenter's Auto, Boat, and RV Loan Department, a divisionof Banker's Portfolio Exchange in Tucson, Arizona (the Internetaddress is http://www.financenter.com/resources/autoloan/index.htm).This site helps calculate the cost of leasing a car and offersa downloadable page of key clauses in lease agreements, whichillustrates various ways in which contracts can be written. Italso identifies points that should be specified and negotiatedwith the dealer, such as charges for excess wear, early termination,and excess mileage.  <p> Those who decide to lease can then use the Internet to set upa deal through the Auto-By-Tel web site (http://www.autobytel.com).This service maintains a database of dealers who pay a fee toAuto-By-Tel to receive requests from potential buyers or leasers.Prospective leasers enter their name, address, phone number,and type of car desired; a dealer in the area will then callwith his or her leasing terms. Armed with all the other informationgleaned from the Internet, leasers will be ready to negotiate.The leaser has to go to a dealer showroom only to sign the papersand pick up the keys. Thanks to the Internet, the traditionalhaggling over price has become more of a contest between equals. <p>  <p>MEANWHILE, ON YOUR LOCAL DRIVE <p>You don't need to go online to get help with a car lease. TheCD-ROM Popular Mechanics' New Car Buyers Guide 1996 ($29.95 fromBooks That Work; 800-242-4546) offers similar information tohelp shoppers make up their minds about a car lease. It providessticker prices and dealers' invoice prices as well as lease-versus-buycalculations.  <p> There are also several software programs that can help in understandingthe leasing process, the terms, and the monthly-payment calculation.The best are Expert Lease ($99.95 from Chart Software; 800-418-8450),a stand-alone application that includes MSRP and dealer invoiceprices, and AutoFinII, a spreadsheet that works with Lotus 1-2-3and Microsoft Excel ($49 from Village Software; 800-724-9332).Both of these programs can instantly calculate how changing oneelement of a lease affects monthly payments. Given data suchas the length of the lease, any capitalized-cost-reduction payments,residual value, and the interest rate, they will calculate anexpected monthly payment to compare with a dealer's offer.  <p>  <hr>  <p>This article appeared in the December/January 1996 issue of Worthmagazine.  <p> Copyright 1996 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved.  <p>   <p> 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
