	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - Get a Yearly Financial Checkup</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Smart%20Consumer>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>SMART CONSUMER</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>Get a Yearly Financial Checkup</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						You wouldn't put off a yearly physical. Why treat your financeswith any less regard? The experts offer eight ways to keep yourwallet healthy, wealthy, and wise.  <p> By Bruce Upbin  <p> At the start of the new year, it's easy to let money mattersget lost in the shuffle. Now is a better time than later to straightenup your financial house. We asked the experts for their besttips. Follow these and save:  <p> **Get health benefits in tip top shape.** <p>Most companies circulate forms that let employees adjust benefitplans each year. Pay attention--many have a Thanksgiving deadline.It may be the last time workers can take advantage of one oftoday's most cherished benefitsemployer-provided flexible spendingaccounts for health care costs. Many large corporations let employeesset aside as much as $3,000 in pretax salary to pay for non-reimbursablemedical expenses. By using pretax dollars for physicals and eventhe cost of traveling to the doctor, workers can cut non-reimbursedmedical expenses by 40 percent or more. These plans are particularlyadvantageous if you are expecting your medical bills and insurancecopayments to increase this year, but keep in mind they do notcover payments for elective cosmetic surgery.  <p> Individuals should sit down with their checkbook, add up howmuch they spent on medical costs this year, and sock that amountaway in a flex plan for 1996. "If you want to switch from youremployer's indemnity plan to its health maintenance organizationor preferred-provider plan, you'll probably want to lower yourflex-account balance because you won't be paying as much foroffice visits," says Martha Priddy Patterson, chief employee-benefitsanalyst at KPMG Peat Marwick in Washington, D.C. Also, be sureto spend whatever is left in the 1995 flex account--leftoverbalances cannot be rolled over into 1996 plans once the yearis out.   <p> Two-earner households should also consider having one spousesign up for the other's health plan if each is now covered separately.Many companies who let employees drop company-provided healthinsurance will refund a portion of unused benefits back to employees.Before exiting, however, workers should make sure employers willlet them reenter, in the event of a layoff, divorce, or death.A company's benefits department can give more details about thisoption, but workers should be ready with proof that a spouse'splan will cover them.  <p> The self-employed should tally up their health care costs andget set to write them off.   <p> **Save the most for your golden years--before it's too late.**<p>As Senator Bill Bradley hollers that inadequate retirement savingsis a "major security issue for Americans," Congress continuesto take aim at retirement savings accounts, as it has for thelast ten years. From limitations on IRA contributions to thenew 20 percent withholding rule on certain plan distributionswhen taxpayers leave their place of employment, retirement accountshave gotten whacked.   <p> Put away the maximum allowed in these plans (currently $9,500for 401(k) plans), and consider after-tax contributions as well.Also, explore other retirement-savings accounts such as SEPsor Keoghs if you earn income from projects separate from yourjob.  <p> **Step-up home security to reduce your insurance premiums.**<p>Don't wait until a policy is up for renewal to begin cuttinginsurance costs. Insurance agents often slash premiums for homeimprovements or reduced auto usage before a policy's anniversary."Installing new wiring or a burglar or smoke alarm can slice2 to 5 percent off your premium," says Loretta Worters, a spokeswomanfor the Insurance Information Institute in New York. "More sophisticatedalarm systems can get you a 15 to 20 percent discount." Car poolersand home-office workers should also negotiate cheaper automobileinsurance by arguing that they have a shorter than typical commute. <p> **Update all your financial documents--from insurance to pensionforms--to account for family changes.** <p>Marriages, divorces, deaths, and births all should be properlyreflected in financial paperwork. "Double-check trusts, wills,life insurance policies, and pension forms to ensure that allintended beneficiaries are listed," says Jeff Saccacio, a partnerwith Coopers & Lybrand in Los Angeles. And indicate childrenby their full name to avoid mix-ups from remarriages and adoptions. <p> **Stop the bank from sucking up your money.** <p>Stop paying high fees for bank services. Sky-high bank fees continueto silently suck up depositor money. Since 1990, the percentageincrease in regular checking-account fees has risen three timesthe rate of inflation, according to a 1993 study done by U.S.Public Interest Research Group, a consumer-watchdog organizationin Washington, D.C. "Recent bank mergers spell even higher costsfor consumers because larger banks charge more for their greatervariety of services," says Edmund Mierzwinski, a U.S. PIRG spokesman.Many bankers are eager to lower or eliminate fees for customerswho consolidate several accounts at their bank. Also, considerusing a mutual fund that gives check-writing privileges for monthlychecks amounting to $250 or more, but watch out--these checkscan carry a $2-per-check fee and create a tax bill since theyrepresent shares sold.   <p> **'Tis the season for generosity--even if it's not entirelyaltruistic.** <p>Consider a fat holiday gift to kids. Now is when many parentsconsider shifting wealth to their more lightly taxed offspring.The IRS lets taxpayers give $10,000 each to as many people asthey wish, tax free. It's a smart way to keep estates under the$600,000 mark, after which assets are taxed from 37 percent toas high as 60 percent. Trustees who make annual gifts to existingirrevocable life insurance or education trusts must mail beneficiariesa notice stating that a contribution was made on their behalfand specify the amount, or they won't qualify for the exclusion. <p> **Rethink your investments.** <p>High-income taxpayers should take advantage of the spread betweentheir top tax rates and the 28 percent capital-gains tax by investingin top-shelf growth stocks or growth funds. New York financialplanner Norman Dawidowicz also suggests that investors ask fundmanagers or their bankers to pay out interest on liquid accounts,such as money markets, every six months instead of quarterly.While the interest income won't be immediately available, makingthis move by November 1 means the payout would be scheduled forApril 1996, effectively shifting tax owed to next year.  <p> **Don't drown in debt--consolidate it.** <p>Borrowers who pay 15 percent interest in dealer financing fora $25,000 car, or 18 percent or more on a $10,000 credit cardbalance, should consider cutting that cost by consolidating thisdebt into a 8.5 percent home-equity loan or credit line. Cardholderswho roll over balances, as 65 percent do, will save $950 transferringa $10,000 card balance at 18 percent to a home-equity loan at8.5 percent (not including loan fees). Also, up to $100,000 inhome-equity interest is still tax-deductible.   <p>  <hr>  <p>This article appeared in the November 1994 issue of Worth magazine.Data updated in December 1995.  <p> Copyright 1994 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved. <p>
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
