<html>
	<head>
		<title>Scouting the Web</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>Scouting the Web</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						Cyberspace holds more financial and business data than you could
ever use. Here's Worth's guide to 25 key financial sites.   
<p>
 By Ted C. Fishman  
<p>
 Six months ago the hydra-headed cyber-thing called the World
Wide Web was best known as a playground for connoisseurs of certain
Danish photographs. No more. The Web has rapidly evolved into
the most prolific and democratic provider of investment and personal-finance
information ever. About 2,000 Web sites offer advice, data, and
financial services, and the number grows daily.   
<p>
 For investors, there are two primary benefits to this technology:
virtually unlimited access to financial data, and a research
medium that weaves together disparate sources of information
through hot links.  
<p>
 Because one never knows just what lies beyond the next hot link,
the Web is terrific for generating investing ideas through sheer
serendipity. The problem is that it can be bewildering to navigate,
so it helps to have a reliable guide, at least until you get
your sea legs. So we scouted out some sites that will save you
time, and maybe money. Good hunting!  
<p>
 ON-RAMPS FOR THE CYBER-SAVVY  
<p>
 *CNNfn, The Financial Network http://cnnfn.com 
<p>
*Dow Jones Business Information Services http://dowvision. wais.
net *Reuters NewMedia http://beta.yahoo.com/headlines/ current/business/summary.html<p>
<p>
 These are the best of the business news sites, and all are free.
Reuters and CNNfn usually have more breaking news, while Dow
Jones puts sections of The Wall Street Journal online. The paper
is free, and stories about the companies covered in the news
are linked to background information in Dow Jones's databases.
CNNfn is allied with Nexis-Lexis, the leading electronic archive
of newpapers and magazines, which allows users to search for
previous stories on current topics. The Nexis-Lexis database
is also available separately; it's exhaustive and expensive.<p>
<p>
 *American Stock Exchange http://www.amex.com 
<p>
*Chicago Mercantile Exchange http://www.cme.com 
<p>
*MarketPlex of the Chicago Board of Trade http://www. cbot.com/mplex.htm<p>
<p>
 Most of the world's major financial exchanges have a presence
on the Web (excluding the New York Stock Exchange). These three
set the standard, providing information--ranging from statistics,
to basic educational materials on stocks, futures, and other
derivatives, to quotes on their contracts, some of which are
delayed. The Board of Trade and the Merc sites supply agricultural
statistics on grains and livestock, as well as links to the government
and news agencies that collect them.  
<p>
 *GNN Personal Finance Center http://gnn.com/gnn/GNNhome.html<p>
<p>
* PR Newswire http://www.prnewswire. com/cnoc/prnewswire.html<p>
<p>
 GNN, the Internet-only offshoot of giant America Online, has
one of the best-laid-out sites, and its personal finance areas
are among the liveliest on the Web. Recent articles include "The
Bag Lady Syndrome," on the fear of poverty felt by many financially
secure women. GNN also tracks 30 or so of the new finance-related
sites that spring up every week. PR Newswire has long been the
world's primary outlet for corporate public relations, posting
press releases in quantity, from companies large and small. This
is public relations, mind you, not journalism, but it's still
a good place to see what's on the front burner at the companies
and industries you watch.   
<p>
 *Briefing by Charter Media, Inc. http://www.briefing.com 
<p>
*University of Michigan Gopher Site gopher://una.hh. lib. umich.edu:70/00/ebb/indicators/ei.txt<p>
<p>
 Data heaven. Both sites offer summaries of virtually every economic
indicator under the sun, and then some. Briefing charges for
some of its stuff. The University of Michigan site, though not
technically a Web site, is accessible from the Web and free.<p>
<p>
 *Quicken Financial Network http:/ www. intuit.com/quicken  
<p>
 Intuit's latest release of its Quicken personal-finance software
is designed specifically to take advantage of the Quicken Financial
Network and comes bundled with a customized version of Netscape's
Web-navigating software that will take you right to the site
and let you browse it for free. For $9.95 a month, users get
seven free hours of Internet access, one of the cheapest Web
on-ramp deals. The Quicken site, like the software, includes
tools to help you balance your books and keep your tax records
up-to-date. It also supports online banking, with links to major
banks. The Network is linked to a sister service for mutual fund
investors, which mantains detailed ratings, price histories,
and analyses of more than 5,000 funds, plus free access to the
databases of Morningstar Mutual Funds, the premier ratings service.<p>
<p>
 *Insurance News Network http://www. insure. com 
<p>
*Quotesmith Corporation http://www.insure.com/Quotesmith  
<p>
 Insurance News Network offers reliable news, ratings, consumer
information, and statistics on the insurance industry. Recent
postings summarized crash tests on popular cars. INN also provides
Standard & Poor's Insurance Ratings and Insurer Reports, a good
resource to determine if your insurer can and will pay out when
you need it. Quotesmith offers free and confidential price-comparison
charts for term life insurance.  
<p>
 *Securities and Exchange Commission http://www.sec.gov  
<p>
 Find out if that cold call came from a broker with the wrong
kind of record. The SEC site lists every enforcement action the
agency takes. It also holds the largest online repository of
corporate information, the EDGAR Database. EDGAR includes the
statements companies must file with the SEC whenever they take
actions that could affect their stocks.  
<p>
 *Internal Revenue Service http://www.ustreas.gov/treasury/ bureaus/irs/irs.html<p>
<p>
 An assortment of resources is available for the beleaguered
taxpayer, including copies of every form and instructions on
filing (electronically if you like) and getting help. If browsing
here is too much fun, try checking the tax tables.  
<p>
 *Debt Counselors of America http://shops.net/ shops/ GET_OUT_OF_DEBT<p>
<p>
*TRW Information Services http:// www.trw.com/iss/isdiv.html<p>
<p>
 Debt Counselors of America is a not-for-profit organization
for those with credit and money-management problems. Its site
offers software to help people sort out their affairs, details
on credit and money scams, and advice on debt consolidation.
TRW, the nation's largest credit-reporting service, gives a straightforward
account of how it compiles its reports, as well as instructions
for reviewing credit records and correcting them if necessary.<p>
<p>
 *PAWWS Financial Network http://pawws.secapl.com 
<p>
*Quote.Com http://www.quote.com 
<p>
*MIT StockMaster http:// www.ai.mit.edu/stocks.html  
<p>
 PAWWS and QuoteCom provide current price quotes on stocks and
other instruments for less than it costs to subscribe to dedicated
quote vendors. Both services offer delayed quotes for free. Prices
vary, depending on the services ordered, but $50 buys a package
of information that exceeds most individual investor's needs,
including a large variety of reports and stock ratings. PAWWS
will also keep track of your portfolio--free if you use its specified
discount brokers. MIT's site is a storehouse of historical stock
and mutual fund charts detailed enough to please the most hard-core
technical trader. Its data files can be incorporated into your
own charts and spreadsheets.   
<p>
 *THE GNN/KOBLAS CURRENCY CONVERTER http://bin.gnn. com/  cgi-bin/gnn/currency<p>
<p>
*OLSEN & ASSOCIATES http:// www. olsen. ch/foreign/websvcs.html<p>
<p>
 For investors who trade foreign currencies or own investments
denominated in them, this site provides weekly updates on 56
different currencies and can convert any of them into any other.
Olsen & Associates is a Swiss firm that advises currency traders.
Its site (free for now) provides market analysis, historical
data on currencies, and models for long-term trading.  
<p>
 *WWW Virtual Library: Finance and Investments http://www.cob.ohio-state.edu/dept/fin/cernh.htm<p>
<p>
*Financial Data Finder http://www.cob.ohio-state.edu/dept/fin/
osudata.htm 
<p>
*Wall Street Directory http://www.wsdinc.com  
<p>
 Enter here for the deluge. Together, the first two "hot lists,"
compiled at Ohio State University's Department of Finance, bring
together more than 1,000 sites related to economics and finance,
all sorted by category. The still broader Wall Street Directory
contains more than 2,500 entries, with an emphasis on commercial
sites. Go here to shop for brokers, fund groups, financial software,
and premium news and quote services.  
<p><p>
<p>
"Scouting the Web" appears in its entirety in the February 1996
issue of Worth in the archives.  
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
Data as of February 1996.  

