<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - Dialing Deals</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Smart%20Consumer>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>SMART CONSUMER</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>Dialing Deals</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Think you can save a bundle by hopping over to one of the much-hypedphone plans? That's what the long-distance carriers want youto think. They've spent more than $1 billion to convince you. <p> By Kathleen Murray  <p> The rate skirmish among long-distance phone carriers is beginningto look like the Hundred Years War. AT&T, MCI, and Sprint collectivelyspend more than $1 billion a year trying to steal each other'scallers with promises of big savings. But all that advertisingmoney disguises very small distinctions. The competing discountplans offer "savings [that] really are comparable," says CharlesBain, a researcher at Washington, D.C.based TelecommunicationsResearch & Action Center, a public interest group that trackslong-distance rates.  <p> The Big Three have each marketed new, less expensive callingplans. AT&T's True Savings will cut 25 percent from its standardrates if you make at least $10 worth of long-distance calls ina month, 30 percent if your bill is over $50. MCI's New Friendsand Family discounts MCI's standard rates by 10 percent oncemonthly charges hit $9.5020 percent for calls to other MCI usersspecified on the Friends and Family list customers give to thecompany. Sprint Sense, eschewing discounts, has gone to a flat-rateplan, charging customers 10 cents a minute for night and weekendcalls and 22 cents a minute for daytime calls.  <p> The resulting phone-bill differentials are minimal. A recentTRAC survey shows that for 50 long-distance calls a month, mostlymade at nights and on weekends and totaling about 522 minutes,MCI will bill $58.94, Sprint $57.63, and AT&T $58.54. The discountplan offered by a rapidly growing new phone company, LDDS, basedin Jackson, Mississippi, is comparable.  <p> **Once you've picked a plan, stay on top of it. To get the bestrate you've got to ask for it.** <p>Naturally, the carriers insist these savings are a big deal."Even if it's only $3 [a month], that still adds up," says ChrisMannella, MCI's director of brand marketing. "We've still gotthe lowest rates out there."  <p> That may be, but standard rates are going up at all the majorphone companies, even as they steadily drop in the various savings-planrates. This is a crucial distinction, because carriers do notautomatically give current users their lowest rates. In fact,Recent studies by PNR and the Yankee Group, two consumer-researchcompanies, show that two thirds of long-distance users may stillpay standard rates.  <p> According to TRAC, there's also little difference in the voicequality of the major services. So why take the time to switch?Ken McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action, a consumer-advocacygroup in San Francisco, says because of the intensifying competition,now is a good time to evaluate your long-distance service, ifyou haven't done so in the last six months. A heavy useronewho spends $150 a monthcould save more than $500 a year overthe standard rate.  <p> **No one service can claim to be the lowest. Night owls anddaytime dialers are served best by different plans.** <p>AT&T commands 60 percent of the market and charges the higheststandard rate. A person billed at that rate who paid $57.87 monthlyfor long-distance service could reduce that to $41.27 by switchingto AT&T's True Savings plan. To get the best deal, start by askingcarriers specifically for discount-plan rates. Once you havethe competing plans, look at your own calling pattern. "No oneplan or company is best for everyone," McEldowney says. MCI'sNew Friends and Family plan, for example, is often cited as thelow-cost leader. But that assumes you're calling other MCI customersthat you've listed as regular contacts.  <p> If you make a lot of calls during the day, a plan like Sprint'sMost II, which offers volume discounts of up to 35 percent, maycost less than the Sprint Sense flat-rate plan. Flat rates, includingLCI All America, LDDS Home Advantage and Matrix SBN Flat Rate,may be cheaper if your call volume is light or if your callsare coast-to-coast.  <p> Alternatively, if you travel abroad frequently, you might findAT&T worth the slightly higher cost. American travelers oftenreport that AT&T makes it easiest to dial the U.S. direct fromoverseas as well as get access to American operators.  <p> **Figure out your phone habits before you let your fingers dothe walking.**  <p>McEldowney recommends looking at bills for at least three monthsto determine your calling pattern. For the most recent TRAC studyof rates, services, and features, send a stamped, self-addressed,business-sized envelope and $3 to TRAC, P.O. Box 27279, Washington,D.C. 20005.  <p> Currently, all carriers face intense rate pressure as the BabyBells and even cable companies get set to offer long-distanceservice. So, once you've found the right plan, relaxuntil thenext round of discounts.  <p> Toll free numbers for customer service and opening an account: <p> Frontier (Allnet) <p>(800) 783-2020  <p> AT&T <p>(800) 222-0300 <p>(800) 235-0900 (Spanish)  <p> LCI <p>(800) 524-4685  <p> LDDS WorldCom <p>(800) 275-0100  <p> Matrix <p>(800) 282-0242 <p>(800) 890-0323 (Spanish)  <p> MCI <p>(800) 444-3333 <p>(800) 950-HOLA (Spanish)  <p> Sprint <p>(800) 746-3767 <p>(800) 877-0280 (Spanish)  <p>  <hr>  <p>This article appeared in the July/August 1995 issue of Worthmagazine. Data updated in December 1995.  <p> Copyright 1995 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved. <p>
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
