	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 1 Rm W/Ocean Vu to Rent Cheap</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Smart%20Consumer>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>SMART CONSUMER</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>1 Rm W/Ocean Vu to Rent Cheap</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Making hotel reservations has just become easier--and cheaper.Hotel consolidators are buying up blocks of rooms in cities bothhere and abroad. When they go on a shopping spree, it saves youmoney.  <p> By Rudy Maxa  <p> Once upon a time, there were two basic hotel-room rates: thegeneral or "rack" rate and the package rate. Today, the lodgingindustry is a consumer crapshoot.  <p> Your best deal may be to book through a relatively new groupof wholesalers called hotel consolidators, who buy large numbersof hotel-room nights and pass the savings along to last-minutecustomers. Whether you are in San Francisco, Washington, London,or Paris, consolidators can save you a lot of money. And whena particular hotel or every hotel in an entire city--here orabroad--is sold out, a consolidator may be your best shot ata bed for the night.  <p> Consolidators require nothing more than a credit card number;most use it to guarantee your reservation, and you pay the hotel.Cancellation policies vary, but most require a 24-hour notice. <p> **Here's where you can save a C note a night.** <p>Here are some representative savings:  <p> Hotel Reservations Network (800-964-6835) offered a room atthe elegant Rihga Royal in Manhattan for $237 a night, includingthe 13.25 percent hotel tax (all prices and availability areas of July 1995). When the hotel was called directly for a weeknightroom, the rate quoted was $295, before tax. The consolidator'srate amounted to a savings of about $100 a night.  <p> The Essex House overlooking Central Park said its lowest rate,a national corporate rate for a double with no view, was $243,excluding tax. HRN offered a tax-inclusive rate of $189, savingalmost $91 per night. And while the recently renovated DrakeSwissotel on Park Avenue said over the phone that its cheapestweeknight rate was $224, not including tax, HRN offered a tax-inclusiverate of $160--nearly $100 per night less.  <p> In Beverly Hills, California, the Summit Hotel on Rodeo Driveoffered a "special promotional rate of $150 a night," excludinghotel taxes of 14 percent. HRN charged $113, including tax, fora room on the same night--about $60 less.  <p> **They're (nearly) everywhere you want to stay.** <p>HRN, based in Dallas, lists rooms in most major U.S. cities,as well as some in Europe, including London and Paris. HRN  isopen Monday through Friday, including most holidays, from 8 a.m.to 6 p.m. Central time.  <p> The catalog of properties from New Yorkbased RMC Travel Centre(800-782-2674) includes hotels in all major U.S. and Canadiancities (except Honolulu). Rates for the Essex House and the Drakewere identical to those offered through HRN. An oceanview roomat the trendy Shutters on the Beach in Santa Monica, California,cost $275 a night, but $400 before tax if you had reserved throughthe hotel. RMC is open for business Monday through Friday from9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Eastern time.  <p> Among other consolidators, Quikbook (800-789-9887), which callsitself "America's Number One Hotel Discounter," advertises discountsof up to 70 percent in 21 U.S. cities. Room Exchange (800-846-7000)promises discounts in all major U.S. cities, the Caribbean, Mexico,and Hawaii. You prepay for your room and receive a voucherwhichis fully refundable if you cancel 48 hours before arrival. Thecompany also has started listing European and Asian properties,such as London's Dorchester ($285 plus a 17.5 percent tax, orabout $80 below the regular rate) and Hong Kong's deluxe Peninsula(starting at $259, about $100 less than the hotel rate).  <p> **You can also save off the beaten path.** <p>There are also regional specialists, such as Central ReservationService (800-548-3311), which offers reservations in Miami, Orlando,Tampa, and New Orleans as well as for some New York and Los Angelesproperties. California Hotel Reservations (800-576-0003) specializes,naturally enough, in California and recently added Portland,Oregon, and Seattle to its portfolio. Atlanta-based Hotels Plus(800-235-0909) specializes in discount hotels in England andmainland Europe, as well as the Middle East and South Africa. <p> As in any bargain hunting, shopping around pays off. And justbecause one consolidator has nothing available on the date youwant doesn't mean another won't.  <p> **Dial direct to get an even *better* deal.** <p>Calling a hotel directly for a room is often (but not always)better than calling a central reservations number, because localsrespond to day-to-day business conditions. For example, whenI called a reservation clerk at Ma Maison Sofitel in Los Angeles,she said that, since business was slow that day, she'd extendthe weekend rate of $129 before taxes, $30 less than the normalweekday rate. (HRN offered a tax-inclusive rate of $148.)  <p> Hotels will often give you a corporate rate even if you don'twork for a corporation, so always request it (unless there'sa lower rate). Also, watch for advertised specials, such as Hilton's1995 summer rates for its foreign hotels, which undercut theconsolidator prices.  <p> In the United States, hotels often equal or undercut consolidators'rates on weekend stays.  <p> As in any bargain hunting, shopping around pays off. And justbecause one consolidator has nothing available on the date youwant doesn't mean another won't.  <p>  <hr>  <p>This article appeared in the October 1995 issue of Worth magazine. <p> Copyright 1995 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved.  <p>  <p>
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
