<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 12/04/96 -- John Westergaard, president of Westergaard Publishing Corporation</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>12/04/96 -- John Westergaard, president of Westergaard Publishing Corporation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, December 4, John Westergaard chatted live about microcap stocks and the market in 1997. Westergaard has been described by Louis Rukeyser of "Wall Street Week" as America's leading "guru" of small cap stock investing. He is president of Westergaard Publishing Corporation and its investment banking affiliate, Westergaard Financial Services. The following is an  transcript from the evening's chat, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed are Mr. Westergaard's, and do not necessarily reflect the opinions of Worth OnLine, Worth, or Capital Publishing.<p>
WorthEdit3:     Good evening. Welcome to Worth OnLine's weekly chat show "Conference Call," where each week we bring you leaders in the world of money and finance. Tonight, we're joined by John Westergaard, president of Westergaard Publishing Corporation and its investment banking affiliate, Westergaard Financial Services. Mr. Westergaard, I'd like to start off by asking if you'd take moment to explain your unique investing style?<p>
Westrgaard:     The idea is that one looks for the dream that is motivating the founder and management. The approach is thematic. What's the big idea into which a company is playing.<p>
Rbn3:     In the past you liked an alarm monitoring company, Response USA (RUOK), do you still?<p>
Westrgaard:      Response USA (NASD: RUOK) is a good example. It's playing into the general fear of crime and therefore the need to have protection electronically of one's home and business. It's also playing into the home healthcare market where people at home need a device to alert caregivers when there's trouble.<p>
NVaze:     How about Platinum Technology (NASD: PLAT)? Is it a strong buy?<p>
Westrgaard:     Don't know the company. Have management send me a file and I'll take a look. <p>
Rbn3:     Response USA fell from 9+ to 3- in the past 3 months. Why?<p>
Westrgaard:     Rbn3, I can't answer that because I don't understand the collapse of the microsector this fall. RUOK is a strong buy at these levels. Check Westergaard Online. We'll follow up.<p>
Worldpaul:     Any news on ACTV (NASD: IATV),what were the results of the test market for the network?<p>
Westrgaard:     Can't say much, Worldpaul. Management is not saying a lot. I know the test results have been good, but when the L.A. rollout will be announced, I don't know.<p>
LzPowell:     You are hot on ADDM (OTC issue) but I have had reports that their "computer" advertising board does not hold up.<p>
Westrgaard:     Lz, not true. You're going to see some big news re advertisers on ADDM. The key will be calculators designed as products -- coke cans, Mars Bars, etc. The ad board is not important.<p>
TG568:     Bought Navistar Intl. (NYSE: NAV) at 15. Should I sell?<p>
Westrgaard:     Would accumulate the stock here. Don't sell.<p>
Rbn3:     You follow restaurants on your page, any thoughts on Elephant and Castle Group (NASD: PUBSF)?<p>
Westrgaard:     Roger Lipton does all our restaurant work. Maybe you should get him on here, Worth?<p>
Lepsteidad:     w/20K,best bet=Hi yield,blue,or growth stock?<p>
Westrgaard:     Lepsteidad, what???<p>
Lepsteidad:     With $20,000 to invest, go with stocks with high yield, blue chips, or small companies for growth?<p>
Westrgaard:     Leipsteidad, you've got a shorthand there that sounds like it's designed for the floor of the mercantile exchange.<p>
Rbn3:     Are microcaps too vulnerable to short raids to be viable for the small investor?<p>
Tombases:     Does the amount of closely held shares give a clue as to the future price movement?<p>
Westrgaard:     Rbn3 and Tombases: Short raids can be a problem with thin markets, no question. As for closely held shares, I like it when management owns a lot of stock.<p>
Tombases:     A follow up please:  Define "a lot of stock" as a percentage,  i.e.  25 percent, 40 percent?<p>
Westrgaard:     25 percent or more.<p>
Dog149:     How do you feel about biotech?<p>
Westrgaard:     Dog 149: I love Life Medical Sciences (NASD: CHAI). Basic technology out of the Technion in Haifa.<p>
AFurman105:     What's happening with Graham Fields?  We heard it was hot.<p>
Westrgaard:     Graham Fields (NYSE: GFI) is a top favorite of mine. Smith Barney issued a 22-page report today. This is a play on home health care.<p>
APurner:     Anything in the banking sector?<p>
Westrgaard:     We don't follow banks. I've tended to get my head handed to me over the years in financial type stocks.<p>
Cuff Star:     You ought to check out Sterling Bank Corp. (NYSE: STL), it's going for a ride.<p>
Westrgaard:     Cuff - I used to keep my account there but have no thoughts on the stock.<p>
Worldpaul:     Mr. Westergaard, do you think there will be a surge in price when ADDM comes off the pink list?<p>
Westrgaard:     As for ADDM off the electronic bulletin board, yes I think it will go bananas.<p>
LzPowell:     Do you follow REITS?<p>
Sesample:     What do you think of New Mexico & Arizona Land (AMEX: NZ)?<p>
Lepsteidad:     Internationals look good now? <p>
Westrgaard:     REITs - no. NZ - no. Internationals? I read that to mean the international oils. I like the small cap domestic producers.<p>
Carlyfro:     Mr. Westergaard, I would be most interested in your thoughts about Thermo Tech Technologies (NASD: TTRIF).<p>
Westrgaard:     Carly - Thermo Tech Technologies has always intrigued me. I'd like to get to know the people better.<p>
DJeffer500:     Expect small caps to rocket due to the January factor.  What are your top three, Mr. Westergaard? Why?<p>
Westrgaard:     DJ -- as for the January factor, be very careful this time around. I'm suspicious that the market has already topped out and January could be very dangerous.<p>
LSobczyk:     Do you think Orthologic Corp. (NASD: OLGC) is a good buy now?<p>
Westrgaard:     LS - I love OLGC at these levels. A major company in the making.<p>
LFISKY:     Any thoughts on Olympus Ventures, Inc. (NASD: OLPV)?<p>
IKEMICKI:     Lots of people are talking about Vical (NASD: VICL), do you follow the company?<p>
AVVV:     What are your views on Morgan Products (NYSE: MGN)?<p>
MiGerk:     How about Sun Microsystems (NASD: SUNW)?<p>
Westrgaard:     No thoughts on Olympus, Vical -- ask management to send me a due dilly file and I'll take a look. Don't follow Morgan. Don't know Sun Micro but my gut tells me they're going to clean up in the next several years due to the year 2000 date conversion problem. Are you all familiar with the Y2K problem? Come to www.westergaard.com to find out.<p>
Rbn3:     You seem to be a bibliophile -- any stock play on that theme?<p>
Westrgaard:     I'm not a collector of books but I read a lot, mostly history and biography.<p>
IKEMICKI:     How about K-Mart (NYSE: KM)?<p>
Westrgaard:     Best way to play K-Mart is to buy ADDM.<p>
APurner:     Mr. Westergaard, any thoughts on Delta Airlines' (NYSE: DAL) interest in Continental (NYSE: CAI)?<p>
Westrgaard:     I like the Delta-Continental merger from a passenger's perspective. Delta is a premium airline and Continental has come a long way but I'd still feel better with Delta running the show.<p>
ALAgrief:     What's your opinion on Toys R Us (NYSE: TOY) stock as a Christmas gift for a child?<p>
Westrgaard:     ALA -- Stock is a cute idea, better than some dumb toy. <p>
ALAgrief:     Thanks, Mr. Westergaard -- you're right, toys and flowers are short shelf life items!<p>
APurner:     Mr. Westergaard, which sectors do you feel will be attractive in '97?<p>
Westrgaard:     AP - I believe the microcap market is going to do well with a focus on stocks where you have visibility through 1998. Check out Magal Security Systems (NASD: MAGSF) -- revenues this year $18mm, next year $27mm, 1998 $40mm. Predictable in my view.<p>
CONFED ED:     Do you think Netscape (NASD: NSCP) will go down in '97?<p>
Westrgaard:     Confed: I'd rather own AOL (NYSE: AOL) than Netscape.<p>
CONFED ED:     Concur, but I have puts on Netscape.<p>
Westrgaard:     Puts on Netscape may be o.k.<p>
LzPowell:     Other than you, who has a good solid stock picking philosophy?<p>
Westrgaard:     Lz - as for good stock picking philosophy, my favorite is Bill Nasgovitz at Heartland Funds.<p>
DJLMCC:     Did I miss any comments about SGT?<p>
Westrgaard:     DLJ - No, I haven't commented on SGT. It's a '98-99 story is my sense of it. Very big!!!<p>
TOXIC5JAY:     Mr. W. Do you plan to start another mutual fund? I owned your old one. Your fund would have made a lot of people wealthy. Please consider another one. You're great.<p>
Westrgaard:     No, no more mutual funds for me. I spent too much time listening to other people's ideas and lost my own creativity.<p>
VICKI NO E:     Mr.  West do you like BioSource Int (NASD: BIOI)?   GREAT company!!!!!!!<p>
Westrgaard:     Vicki - Have BioSource send me a file.<p>
GSLECK:     I used to work at ERA in '73 . Is anyone (other than you) still around? Follow Innovus? Worked with George Howick, now just invest on my own -- am doing OK.<p>
Westrgaard:     George Howick is one of the finest people I've ever worked with. He's now a professor at DePauw.<p>
Triinv1010:     Any thoughts on Y2K? Who are your favorite players, if any?<p>
Westrgaard:     Trinn - Strategia (OTC issue) looks interesting on the Y2K problem. A bulletin board stock about to come onto Nasdaq.<p>
Scillitani:     Where do you think the market is going? 1 month, 6 months, 1 year?<p>
Westrgaard:     I'll be making a major market prediction this weekend.<p>
Scillitani:     How do I get your predictions?<p>
Westrgaard:     Go to www.westergaard.com and register and you'll get a daily E-mail. No charge.<p>
DJeffer500:     Will the prediction be on www.westergaard.com?<p>
Westrgaard:     I'll be holding a press conference at 10:30 on Friday at 11 West 42nd, 4th floor, in connection with a Y2K Conference I'm co-hosting.<p>
DJeffer500:     Will you recap Conference on www, since I won't be there?<p>
Westrgaard:     Will recap my ideas, yes.<p>
TOXIC5JAY:     I have two kids starting college in 2 years. What 1 stock or fund would you suggest?<p>
Westrgaard:     E-mail me at john@westergaard.com with your question.<p>
GSLECK:     Follow Tarrant Apparel Group (NASD: TAGS) -- small private label retailer??<p>
Westrgaard:     TAGS - retailers have also been a weak spot for me as I said earlier with financials.<p>
Worldpaul:     ACTV -- how do you feel about their school learning program they have?<p>
Westrgaard:     The school learning is very interesting but the big play here is sports in my opinion.<p>
DJeffer500:     Mr. W, your 3 favorite midcaps poised for a breakout?<p>
Westrgaard:     I put up a list of my six favorites for 1997 today. Three are ADDM, CHAI and MAGSF.<p>
FSandonato:     What about gold, please respond.<p>
Westrgaard:     I've never been a gold bug, but concern over the Y2K problem could make me one.<p>
JOR7733:     How about CEL-SCI (NASD: CELI)?<p>
Westrgaard:     CEL-SCI has done an astonishingly good job. Can't argue with success.<p>
JOtt5149:     Do you have a favorite sector going into 1997?<p>
Westrgaard:     My favorite sector is the micros. They'll do well in the face of a poor blue chip market.<p>
DJeffer500:     Call me naive. What are some micros?<p>
Westrgaard:     DJ - micro caps are stocks with less than $300mm market caps.<p>
FSandonato:     Stock of the year?<p>
Westrgaard:     Stock of the year? Life Medical if clinicals substantiate what we believe on their hair restorer.<p>
CWJ9:     Has this bull market run out of steam?<p>
Westrgaard:     The market for the 20th century hit its high last week.<p>
Connie C R:     Hit its high because of the Y2K problem?<p>
Westrgaard:     Yes.<p>
JhnnyFv:     What is Y2K problem? Please explain.<p>
Westrgaard:     Y2K is year 2000 date compliant issue. See our site for details. www.westergaard.com<p>
WorthEdit3:     I'm afraid that's all the time we have this evening. Mr. Westergaard, thank you so much for taking the time to join us this evening. It  has been a pleasure having you with us.<p>
Westrgaard:     Thank you all. I hope you'll all visit Westergaard Online at www.westergaard.com. <p>
WorthEdit3:     And thank you, everyone, for stopping by "Conference Call" tonight. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
