<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 11/13/96 -- James Dines, the editor of "The Dines Letter"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>11/13/96 -- James Dines, the editor of "The Dines Letter"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On November 13, 1996, Worth OnLine featured James Dines for  "Conference Call." Dines, who last appeared on this live chat show in July, is the editor of "The Dines Letter." He is also a contributing advisor to Decision Point's Top Advisors Corner on AOL. His most recent book is called "Mass Psychology." The following is an edited transcript of the evening's chat. The opinions expressed within are those of Dines, and do not represent the views of Worth OnLine, Worth magazine, or Capital Publishing.<p>
 Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat show series. Our guest tonight is Mr. James Dines, who will make a brief statement and then the floor will be open for your questions. Mr. Dines, the floor is yours.<p>
DinesLtr:     Our last signal was a "buy" on 31 July 1996, right near last summer's Bottom. Shortly after Mr. Dines' last appearance on Worth OnLine, on 17 July 1996, he warned that the market was getting "drastically Oversold." At that time he was also bullish on gold, and just in the last few days they have been rising strongly. He still favors blue-chips such as Placer Dome, Barrick, and Getchell Gold. For growth, Euro-Nevada and Franco-Nevada. For high current income Battle Mt. convertible preferred. Lower priced speculative buys are Agnico-Eagle on the New York Stock Exchange at 13 and Laramide (LAM.TO) at $1.20 (US). Favored oils are Royal Dutch, Texaco and Exxon. In banks, Bankamerica has been favored but is due for a profit-taking pullback, whereas JP Morgan looks ready to move up from here. Pre-Paid Legal Services an amazing growth stock. In high-techs, Cascade, Fore Systems, Xylan, Vitesse Semiconductor, Cambridge Technology and Advanced Fibre Communications. Mr. Dines new book "Mass Psychology" has already been called a "classic," as have his first two books. Book describes "profit inversion," wherein investors will change their goal from profit-seeking to "getting out even." All gamblers secretly want to lose, which is why they keep gambling until they do lose, and "Mass Fear knows no price" so people will sell out at the lows "just for the money." Now open for questions.<p>
HRay984392:     Are you still bullish on pre paid legal?<p>
DinesLtr:     HRay: Yes.<p>
WALLSTLOVE:     How about a contrarian viewpoint in gold? Everyone is down on gold now. Buy now, right?<p>
DinesLtr:     all Street Journal published very bearish article a few days ago reflecting mass pessimism and a clear buy signal by the Dines Theory of Positive Negativism. They are still buys now as in our opening statement.<p>
Amboy69:     What about GLG?<p>
WALLSTLOVE:     Gold just seems stuck at the 380 range, though.<p>
DinesLtr:     Do not make the mistake of confusion the action of gold bullion with gold stocks. Amateurs assume they move together, which is logical, but if the world were always logical it would be men who rode sidesaddle. See opening statement listing some of our favorites. Homestake will move with gold bullion prices because it does not hedge in gold futures markets. The others are okay, but believe you could do better, especially Laramide (LAM.TO).<p>
DCDCKC:     How about silver bullion/coins (specifically silver dollars) in a major bear market?<p>
DinesLtr:     Our Major buy signal for precious metals on 9 Nov 92
predicted that stocks would outperform bullions, and there has been no change. Coins will move with bullion markets, and believe you could do better with silver shares such as Silver Standard (SSO.V) or Coeur d'Alene.<p>
DCDCKC:     Opinion/recommendation on Argosy and Bralorne-Pioneer on Vancouver Exchange?<p>
DinesLtr:     DCDCKC: They should be market performers, but are not on our Supervised Lists.<p>
RQTBL1:     Nothwithstanding today's move, since the untimely demise of Mr. Penna, the market for AEM has been acting debilitated. How do you assess the stock's future price potential.<p>
DinesLtr:     RQTBL1: Agnico-Eagle (AEM) has a very solid and growing reserve picture, so despite the loss of Mr. Penna our buy signal at 3.88 on 30 Sep 91 still stands.<p>
RQTBL1:     On a relative basis do you believe AEM will outperform the XAU? Thank You!<p>
DinesLtr:     I believe so.<p>
WALLSTLOVE:     How about S. African shares? I own Blvoorich.....<p>
DinesLtr:     Blyvoor and other South Africans have been underperforming the entire international spectrum of gold mines, although ASA got above 40 today. South Africa going through transition period, and will have problems with labor unions, but longer term should do well. Their mines are typically extremely deep, so their costs are in danger of getting too high until the price of gold goes up substantially, so miners are shifting exploration toward the rest of Africa. The Dines Letter strongly believes in international diversification of a gold portfolio because even if South Africa closes down, that loss of gold production should send gold prices elsewhere soaring.<p>
CITYOFCH:     Opinion on ECO please?<p>
DinesLtr:     Echo Bay should be a market performer, relatively unexciting until they build up their reserve position, and meanwhile have declining Relative Strength and is below Moving Averages. Let's see how it performs in period of current gold strength.<p>
Amped INTL:     Are the Russians still dumping enough gold into the market to hold prices down?<p>
DinesLtr:     Amped: Russian dumping is not holding gold prices down, it is the central bankers who have sold all of their other reserve heirlooms and want to sell their gold either to give to charity or to exchange for interest-earning US government bonds -- in other words exchanging the world's safest reserve asset (gold) in exchange for US government bonds (paper from the world's largest debtor). When this house of cards caves in, central bankers who did it to us will probably have been safely dead by then. <p>
WALLSTLOVE:  ECU can't get act together=exploding gold reserves.<p>
DinesLtr:     ECU is not the main factor. Egomaniacal Americans think that our own inflation rate is the sole determinate of gold prices, whereas inflationary fears elsewhere in the world, especially central Europe and Asia, are sparking most of the buying, from former communist nations who only recently have been allowed to buy gold. ECU is just another pathetic effort to replace gold, which already is the world's universal currency, echoing American efforts for a constitutional amendment for balanced budgets instead of allowing gold to enforce it. There is a fearful day of reckoning coming, with all of the world's major currencies backed only by paper for the first time in history, as outlined in my second book "The Invisible Crash."<p>
TV CRUNCH:     Mr. Dines, you called the last turn in the bond market. Are bonds a buy now?<p>
DinesLtr:    TV CRUNCH:  We turned bullish on bonds again right on the bottom, a lucky shot, and we continue to look for lower interest rates, but reserve the right to reverse ourselves at any time. Indeed, we have just this week cashed in our profits with a sell signal on the Dow-Jones Utility Average at 234.84, and some bank stocks look
ready for a Technical Correction.<p>
WALLSTLOVE:     What small cap stocks do you recommend?<p>
DinesLtr:     Our Supervised List #5 consists of "penny" stocks,
containing several low-priced golds. Repadre Capital Corp (RPD.TO) has a superb Uptrend, we have already mentioned Silver Standard and Laramide, but also like Pan American Silver (PAASF), TVX Gold also solid, and should be producing 1 million ounces per year by the end of this decade. We have recently added Chase Resources (CQS.TO) and International Pursuit (IPJ.TO).<p>
RV15181:     Call options on AOL?<p>
DinesLtr:     America Online (AOL) is a company in transition and has
been in the headlines lately. The stock has been leveling off in the 25-35 area, but it is below its Moving Averages and has declining Relative Strength. It's probably a solid bet longer term, but I do not see a clear reason that would send it higher on a short-term basis to warrant buying call options. Why not buy call options after the next
setback in the gold stocks?<p>
RQTBL1:     Has your opinion changed RE: IMF sale of gold bullion, in light of recent dialogue?<p>
DinesLtr:     No. Countries like Canada and Belgium have been steady sellers of gold because they have been bearish on it, which is a classic buy signal by the Dines Theory of Positive Negativism. Idea of selling gold to give proceeds to charity will continue to crop up reflecting the ignorance of the need to link paper currencies to an item of value, be it gold, silver or oil. See my second book "The Invisible Crash" for an in-depth discussion.<p>
HRay984392:     Some of us missed your opening statement; brief review?<p>
DinesLtr:     Are you asking me to describe the universe and give two
examples? Our buy signal for the Dow-Jones Industrial and Transport Averages luckily issued at last summer's rock bottom are still intact, but we have just flashed a DJU sell signal at 234.84, and additional sell signals might be forthcoming after further strength. If DJI gets down to 5960 and DJT 1980 would be sell signals, while a drop by the Dow-Jones Bond Average to 101.0 would likewise be a sell signal. Still extremely bullish on gold, silver & platinum shares, but not bullions, an for specific recommendations get a printout of this or be here earlier at our next appearance. Nobody asked about platinum, and my favorite in the world is Stillwater Mining on the American Stock Exchange with a superb deposit in Montana. Has anybody read my book "Mass Psychology"? How many of you have noticed that Mexico's peso has been crashing to new lows? The liars running the Mexican currency blame that on "armed revolutionaries" instead of confessing that they are running the printing presses full blast, not only so that they could steal more money, but also to continually devalue the peso in order to give their exporters an advantage. My second book "The Invisible Crash" predicted "The Coming Competing Currency Devalutions" and here they are. To attract people to a cheapening peso they send interest rates soaring, which is a catastrophe for business and unemployment that drives the poor to crime that only makes business worse. It provides US demagogues with a reason to avoid free trade with Mexico, harming both sides of our borders, not to mention providing a reason for the very existence of armed revolutionaries! Linking the peso to gold or silver would be a major solution, driving interest rates way down, but we do not know how to convince them. A revolution is a shout to the deaf. (The above is from the latest Dines Letter, and echoes our concerns about other currencies internationally.)<p>
RQTBL1:     Yes, I read your book, but I am having trouble applying its precepts.<p>
DinesLtr:     Which precept in particular troubles you, for example?<p>
RQTBL1:     I cannot understand how to analyze  the criteria for "Mass Spark" nor how to apply it?<p>
DinesLtr:     That is a good question, and a sophisticated point. A "Mass Spark" is that specific moment when the Mass shifts direction, and is more readily observable in the wheeling of a flock of birds or school of fish where no signal has ever been detected. We have never found a way to predict it but can detect it as it is happening, as we did when we flashed out buy signal last summer, when The Herd
got excessively pessimistic and something suddenly "snapped" that sent stocks reversing upwards. My "Mass Psychology" book is the first serious effort in the field but is hardly definitive. Hopefully, somebody who reads it will be able to build on the areas not yet understood by anybody.<p>
DGeorge164:     Mr. Dines, I enjoy your newsletter. I have been a subscriber for the past year. Do you offer an online service over the Internet?<p>
DinesLtr:     Thank you. And glad you are enjoying The Dines Letter. As it turns out we are in the process of studying going online, so if you drop us a note we will let you know of our decision.<p>
DGeorge164:     Homestake Mining has not moved ahead since your initial buy signal in December '93. Are you still bullish on this stock?<p>
DinesLtr:     Yes. Homestake will move with gold bullion, and is
included in portfolios as a hedge of gold bullion catching up with the leading bullishness of gold mining shares. Homestake is one of the very few gold shares that has not moved up, but will do exceptionally well when gold bullion erupts because they do not sell gold forward in the futures markets. <p>
We have been bullish on oils all the way up and believe that Netanyahu will trigger an explosion in the Middle East. Furthermore, we mention in the last Dines Letter that here in San Francisco we are informed that raccoons are growing longer hair than usual, local bees are unusually aggressive, rodents are accumulating larger stores of seeds, so this could be an unusually severe winter that uses more petroleum products.<p>
FNTIES:     Is Coke a good stock to hold on to?<p>
DinesLtr:     Coca-Cola in superb Uptrend, and would place stop loss just below the October low at 47-5/8 at 46.<p>
ROY1R:     Pegasus Gold has dropped from $15 to $10 in the last 3-4 months, is it now a buy?<p>
DinesLtr:     Pegasus is not one of our favorite gold stocks, however it is resting at an important Support Area at 10, so if there is going to be an upside reversal it should come from around the 9 to 10 area. An Upside Breakout at 11 would be encouraging, while a rise to 13 would be an Upside Breakout that could reverse its declining Relative Strength.<p>
KArmant112:     Would you recommend selling AT&T to buy Lucent? Some people are saying Lucent has more potential<p>
DinesLtr:     AT&T is in a Downtrend and we do not envision much more than a rise toward the 40 area. While Lucent is in an Uptrend, it has risen from 30 to 51 since July, and is overdue for some profit taking. Prefer to buy on a possible dip toward the low 40s, but if there is an upside breakout to 52, that might send it higher. Keep in mind with estimated earnings of only $2 it already has a rich Price Earnings Ratio of 25.<p>
RQTBL1:     An obvious corollary would be the move to  precious metals from paper currency. If such cannot be predicted, are we not all in the midst of a gigantic guessing game?<p>
DinesLtr:    Since nobody knows the future for certain, all efforts at discerning the future contains elements of guessing. However, in The Dines Letter we have been looking for the Mass Spark to come from the arena of Mass Fear. Many people worldwide hold US paper dollars because they trust them more than their own paper currencies, but at the first whiff of fear there should be an
electronic stampede out of paper currencies and into precious metals. While we cannot predict when it will happen, we can certainly observe the earliest indications of its advent, probably featuring collapses in paper currencies, which is why The Dines Letter spends so much time on international currency markets. Note that strength in gold mining shares in recent days coincided precisely with declines by the US dollar in Tokyo, and also the Mexican peso, which need close observation to see if they get enough out of hand
to trigger a Mass Spark out of the stock market and into gold. Do you understand? To order The Dines Letter, call 800-84-LUCKY. To order "Mass Psychology" call 800-550-1000.  Thank you.<p>
WorthOnLne:     Well, that Concludes this edition of "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. Thank you for joining Worth OnLine and Mr. James Dines  for this evening's chat. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Mr. Dines for being our guest.<p>
DinesLtr:     Thank you and may you live every day of your life.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

