	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>10/30/96 -- Victor Flores, portfolio manager for the San Antonio-based United Services Global Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, October 30, Victor Flores joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call," our live online chat show. Flores is portfolio manager for the San Antonio-based United Services Global Investors. As geologist/chief investment officer, he makes more than 20 site visits a year to find suitable stocks for the company's World Gold Fund and Gold Shares Fund. Year-to-date, Flores's U.S. World Gold Fund (which buys non-South African gold equities) is up 26.2 percent. Following is a transcript of the evening's event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed are those of Victor Flores, and do not express the views of the Worth OnLine, Worth magazine, or Capital Publishing. <p>
WorthOnLne : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat show series. Our guest tonight is Victor Flores (SN:USFlores). The floor is now open for the first question.<p>
Mmlm2      : Any comments on copper prices? I don't believe the China diversion theory. <p>
USFlores   : Mmlm2: Our opinion is that China did contribute to both running up the price of copper by withholding inventories and then to the decline by betraying Sumitomo.<p>
Caboman2   : Hello Victor, Do you have an opinion on Alta Gold? <p>
USFlores   : Caboman: We hold Alta in the World Gold Fund, compared to the valuation of similar companies Alta is undervalued. We have a target for the company up around $6. <p>
ZJEW       : Your comments on Ashanti?<p>
USFlores   : ZJEW: Ashanti has been a tough one because the stock has performed so poorly. I have visited the site twice; it is truly one of the greatest gold mining assets on Earth but it has been harder than they thought to bring the production up to planned levels. They have now completed the merger with Golden Shamrock which gives them a great growth profile. This is an 18 month story, but I would buy Ashanti with that view. <p>
Rebel boy1 : Your thoughts on Bema Gold's latest drilling announcement?<p>
USFlores   : Rebel: Bema's latest release was disappointing because it was low grade.<p>
EWS Leong  : What is your 1, 3, 5 year outlook on gold?<p>
USFlores   : EWS: Our view on gold continues to be constructive, driven by strong demand from the emerging markets.<p>
DCDCKC     : Victor, your comments on Aurizon/Toronto and Gold Canyon/Vancouver.<p>
USFlores   : DCD: We like Aurizon because it is an undervalued producer for its size. Gold Canyon we are not particularly fond of.<p>
Hallkcj    : How does Conseco look?<p>
USFlores   : Hall: Sorry, I don't follow Conseco.  <p>
KIT31KAT   : Opinion on Rea Gold?<p>
USFlores   : Kit: We like Rea. The start up at Mt. Hamilton mine has been tough, but the company has a good growth profile from Bisset in Canada and Uruguay.<p>
Caboman2   : In your opinion, is there any hope for Benguet?<p>
USFlores   : Caboman: Not too fond of Benguet. <p>
AVTinc     : How do you feel about gold Nusmatics<p>
USFlores   : AVT: Gold coins are a different world from gold stocks.<p>
Mmlm2      : At what price will copper stabilize? Any opinion on ASARCO? I am loaded on calls.<p>
USFlores   : Mmlm: Lots of copper questions. Inventories are down, copper still in backwardation, copper is good for a bounce here up to perhaps $0.90. Hold your Asarco calls. <p>
Ggruntt    : Opinion on BMG?<p>
USFlores   : Grunt: We hated the terms of the deal to acquire Hemlo; issued too much stock. Now the company is a buy for its moderate growth. <p>
AVTinc     : USFlores then your projections for gold mutual funds?<p>
USFlores   : AVT: I love the US World Gold Fund. Other well managed funds include Scudder and IDS. The gold funds will continue to do well if the industry continues to make significant discoveries.<p>
Cleotis69  : Feelings on Santa Fe Pacific Gold?<p>
USFlores   : Cleo: Santa Fe has a great deal of capital expenditure ahead. I would buy in the $9-10 range.<p>
Mkttmr4298 : When is the XAU going to move to the upside?<p>
USFlores   : XAU will move when gold moves. It is an index of large companies.<p>
Walt205    : What do you think of Fidelity American Gold? If you have an opinion. <p>
USFlores   : Walt: Fidelity American gold is very well-managed.<p>
DLarva7924 : Do you feel this is a timely venture into gold stocks, Mr. Flores?<p>
USFlores   : Dlarva: everyone should have 5-10% of their portfolio in gold stocks. It is a good diversifier. <p>
JGCFP1988  : Any comments on Golden Star Resources and near term potential?<p>
USFlores   : JGC: Golden Star has done a great job of capitalizing on the potential of gold exploration, but it is a difficult stock to value because it is always ahead of itself (stock price).<p>
Walt205    : I would like to get into a small, speculative gold company with realistic prospects. Ideas?<p>
USFlores   : Walt: Argosy Mining, great exploration project in Slovakia (AGO on Vancouver).<p>
DErnst3660 : The only demand for gold now is in India. What if Russia releases all its gold?<p>
USFlores   : Strong demand for gold throughout Asia, not only India. Russia has been accumulating, rather than selling, its gold (what little it has).<p>
DErnst3660 : The Russians can get gold from the ground at a fraction of our cost and they have plenty.<p>
USFlores   : The Russian gold industry has been in decline for decades. They have no capital for infrastructure or development.<p>
DErnst3660 : I don't believe that.<p>
USFlores   : Just look at the statistics of Russian gold production.<p>
Al2bert    : What is your opinion of Crystallex?<p>
USFlores   : Crystallex has done a good job of turning itself around. I have a lot of respect for the new CEO. Worth (no pun) keeping an eye on.<p>
Mmlm2      : Saw on AOL a major dumper of 20,000 oz silver. Any comments?<p>
USFlores   : Mmlm 20,000 oz of silver is a drop in the ocean.<p>
RGKEG      : Who are the Russians selling to?  Somebody is buying.<p>
USFlores   : RGK Gold producers (not just Russia) are selling to consumers of jewelry around the world.<p>
RGKEG      : The amount Russia has been dumping?  With no effect on price? Somebody must be holding.<p>
USFlores   : RGK: Russia is not dumping. They're production and reserves are small. Little impact.<p>
DErnst3660 : Jewelry doesn't account  for that much gold. Gold is stuck until something big happens.<p>
USFlores   : DEm: Correct, Gold is rangebound $380 - $400. Jewelry demand accounts for 75% of gold demand worldwide.<p>
DErnst3660 : I am not wearing the gold I own.<p>
USFlores   : DEm: You don't, but millions of Chinese, Indians, Europeans, Latin Americans are.<p>
DErnst3660 : Can they really afford to buy enough to drive prices up?<p>
USFlores   : DEm: Yes, by about $10 per year. <p>
RGKEG      : $10.00 a year? Big deal. Jewelry demand alone is not going to help gold in the long run. What about its value in relation to currencies, looking forward?<p>
USFlores   : RGK Jewelry demand will not lead to run in gold prices, but will support $10/year increase.<p>
Mmlm2      : Back to copper: if lime inventories decline 13000 again to 120k tons, any run in copper?<p>
USFlores   : MMlm: Yes, there is a possibility that a further drop in inventories will lead to a bounce.<p>
RogerDee99 : When do see South African gold stocks prices improving?<p>
USFlores   : Roger: this is a 18 to 24 month process. South African gold stocks will move with better US$ gold prices and with further restructuring.<p>
Cleotis69  : Gold is coming to major support, do you see upside before downside?<p>
USFlores   : Cleo: Gold very well supported by physical demand at $380. <p>
PEACHMO    : Victor, any opinion on Redfern Resources?<p>
USFlores   : Haven't followed Redfern for a while. Couldn't say.<p>
Cleotis69  : Why the break in January over $400.  Was it pure hype or demand?<p>
USFlores   : Cleo: driven by speculative demand. Gold fell when the physical market did not support<p>
RGKEG      : The downside here seems negligible.<p>
USFlores   : RGK: $10 per year is great for gold stocks.<p>
WALLSTLOVE : Mr. Flores, how about South African mining shares?<p>
USFlores   : WallSt: South Africa stocks look attractive, but currency is treacherous.<p>
Cigar64    : Any opinion on Homestake?<p>
USFlores   : Cigar: Homestake needs to find or buy something to continue growing. Not there yet.<p>
TNorth1662 : Hi, Victor. What are your thoughts on BEMA Gold, short & LONG TERM? Thanks.<p>
USFlores   : TNorth: Success of Bema will depend on drilling at Cerro Casale in Chile. So far it is big but very low grade. Need to hit some high grade to make it minable.<p>
DErnst3660 : U.S. producers are sitting on tons of gold they have mined but can't sell have not sold<p>
USFlores   : Dem: Not true, US producers sell every last ounce they produce.<p>
WALLSTLOVE : Mr. Flores, another way to play gold is put stock in your mutual fund company which I own, it seems to be stuck in a trading range though.<p>
USFlores   : Wallst: You are right. US Global Investors, symbol GROW. Stuck in a range because investors don't understand our situation. Have a look at our third quarter earnings when they are released!<p>
Sailmann   : Mr. Flores, do you have an opinion on Chase Resources? <p>
USFlores   : Sailmann: Chase is drilling a low grade copper property in Philippines. Not impressed.<p>
Cvtcvt     : Mr. Flores: any thoughts on silver mining stocks?<p>
USFlores   : Cvt: Most silver mining stocks are overpriced.<p>
DErnst3660 : SSC is not overpriced.<p>
USFlores   : DEm: I beg to differ I believe SSC is very overpriced.<p>
WALLSTLOVE : any plans for any new funds?<p>
USFlores   : Wallst: Stay tuned!<p>
Xuming     : Any opinion on CALVF on Nasdaq? <p>
USFlores   : Xuming: If CALVF is Caledonia, not impressed.<p>
Xuming     : It is Caledonia. The stock has fallen sharply of late, but the company is still doing a lot of drilling. Potential? <p>
USFlores   : Xuming: Would not own Caledonia.<p>
JOEBOSIR   : Mr. Flores, any opinion on Glamis Gold or Horsham?<p>
USFlores   : JOE: Glamis is OK, some growth, but already in the price. Horsham: buy Barrick instead.<p>
RLamon9684 : How are you reading Midas now  -- Euro and Franco Nevada?<p>
USFlores   : RLamon: Midas discovery growing: own Euro and Franco.<p>
Mi2501     : What about Echo Bay?<p>
USFlores   : Mi: Echo Bay has no growth. No growth = declining stock price.<p>
TNorth1662 : Mr. Flores, What do you think will happen to AGNICO EAGLE now that they have lost Mr. Penna.<p>
USFlores   : TNorth: Just met new Chairman, same management team is there.  Agnico will do fine.<p>
JOEBOSIR   : Mr. Flores, heard something today on CNBC about European countries selling gold reserves privately.<p>
USFlores   : JOE: Lucille Palermo from Van Eck Fund was explaining why the gold market got spooked. She went on to say (I agree) that further European gold sales are unlikely.<p>
DErnst3660 : I will continue to short gold until it hits $365/ounce.<p>
USFlores   : DEm: I would cover at $386.<p>
Devpuck    : If interest rates continue to fall will these stocks continue to take the gas pipe?<p>
USFlores   : Dev: On the contrary, low interest rates are great for gold which is great for gold stocks.<p>
Mmlm2      : Again on ASARCO, do you think with a book value of 45 the price at 26 is attractive? Can they be a takeover? Interest rates will rise after Clinton wins.<p>
USFlores   : Mlm: I don't think of Asarco as a takeover.<p>
Mmlm2      : Why?<p>
USFlores   : Mlm: Our view is that rates will rise after the election, regardless of winner.<p>
Cvtcvt     : Mr. Flores: do you know anything about Goldbelt, recently mentioned in the Gold newsletter?<p>
USFlores   : CVt: Goldbelt is trying (so far without success) to develop a project in Kazakstan. I would stay away from Kazakstan.<p>
Devpuck    : It appears to me that there is an inverse relationship between price of gold and interest rates. DO YOU AGREE?<p>
USFlores   : Dev: low interest rates good for stocks in general. Good for gold because gold does not produce income. Good gold price = good gold stock prices.<p>
Devpuck    : But in the recent period of DECLINING interest rates these stocks have gotten WHACKED. Gold is down over 50% from 1979 levels... I don't get what you are saying??<p>
USFlores   : Devpuck: not related to interest rates. Related to industry fundamentals.<p>
Devpuck    : If interest rates continue to fall (experts think they will)  will these stocks still be in the tank? Why if the price is low will gold stocks do well?? <p>
USFlores   : Devpuck: Gold is down 50% because it was driven to $800 by speculators.<p>
Devpuck    : It has nothing to do with interest rates or inflation... Is that your claim???????<p>
USFlores   : Dev: Correct.<p>
Devpuck    : Interesting.<p>
USFlores   : Dev: Back then (15 years) gold was driven by speculation re: inflation and interest rates. Today it is driven by jewelry demand.<p>
Devpuck    : But there will be speculation now that interest rates will fall even further in next few months.<p>
USFlores   : Dev: Hard to say. Our economist predicts an upward bias in rates post election.<p>
TGFGNUT    : If you haven't already discussed American Barrick, please do.<p>
USFlores   : TGF: Barrick is still the best managed gold company in the world. Still growing, still a buy.<p>
Mmlm2      : Does it pay to buy puts and calls on T-bills?<p>
USFlores   : Mlm: We do not use puts and calls to manage our T-bill exposure.<p>
WGeffeney  : What impact does South African social unrest have on future South African gold prices?<p>
USFlores   : WGeff: Social unrest has little impact, there are other alternatives (dollars, marks, etc).<p>
DLarva7924 : Would you agree that it will be a long time before there are significant variations in gold?<p>
USFlores   : DLarva: our view is gradually rising prices at $10 per year.<p>
TGFGNUT    : What should gold stocks do if there's a recession in 1997?<p>
USFlores   : TGF: Better question is: what will gold do in '97? If we have a slowdown in '97 then rates will come down.<p>
Trac16cat  : Russia is setting up a gold exchange..... Impact?<p>
USFlores   : Trac: Probably small. At least it reiterates our view that Russia is not a seller.<p>
Cvtcvt     : Mr. Flores: I'm interested in your thoughts on Miramar also...<p>
USFlores   : Cvt: Miramar is not a stock we have liked, even though it has done well. Their Con Mine in Canada is a high cost producer.<p>
RLamon9684 : International Pursuit/buy or sell?<p>
USFlores   : RLamon: International Pursuit. Drilling low grade copper deposit that will never be mined. SELL International Pursuit (IPJ on Toronto).<p>
WGeffeney  : Any general feeling on South African gold shares in future?<p>
USFlores   : WGeffeney: Industry finally restructuring. This is good. Buy some. <p>
Mmlm2      : I am skeptical on all these Canadian gold stocks. Any comments?<p>
USFlores   : Mmlm: Investors have made LOTS of money by judiciously investing in them.<p>
PEACHMO    : Victor, any opinion about geologist/CEO John Grieg BC?<p>
USFlores   : Peach: I like John Grieg. A solid fellow.<p>
BANKFUND   : Any thoughts on chances Canyon Resources/Phelps will get big Montana permit?<p>
USFlores   : Bankfund: I think there is a very good chance. McDonald Meadows is a great deposit which happens to sit on State land. The state will get a royalty if the mine is built.<p>
RLamon9684 : Rlamon  Your thoughts on El Callao?<p>
USFlores   : RLamon: Not crazy about El Callao.<p>
Jcolb747   : What is the outlook for gold and/or related stocks/funds?<p>
USFlores   : Jcob: Outlook for gold: good, with gradually rising prices. Gold Fund: depends on gold.<p>
FAMSEVEN   : Your thoughts on Bema Gold?<p>
USFlores   : FAM: Lots of folks on the line tonight asking about Bema. Will depend on whether the drilling in Chile hits some high grade zones. I think their project is not minable at current grades.<p>
Inagy      : Mr. Flores, what are your thoughts on Battle Mountain Gold?<p>
USFlores   : Inagy: Hated Hemlo deal: issued too many shares. Now that it's declined it is a buy.<p>
TGFGNUT    : Mr. Flores...Any quick rules of thumb to determine fair value of a gold stock?<p>
USFlores   : TGF: Market capitalization per ounce of reserves. Should be less than $250 for senior gold producers, less than $125 for medium size companies, less than $50 for exploration.<p>
RLee968757 : Mr. Flores, any word about United Services Gold Shares? <p>
USFlores   : RLee: Gold Shares dependent on successful restructuring of South African mining industry.<p>
Inagy      : Mr. Flores, what are your thoughts on Hecla Mining?<p>
USFlores   : Inagy: They did a very poor job at Grouse Creek, must prove to the market they can develop properties properly. Wouldn't buy yet.<p>
Inagy      : Hecla is at 10 year low at 5 3/4. What price is a good buy? <p>
USFlores   : Inagy: We might be close on Hecla! <p>
JMccu42574 : Does not GLG have 3 million in cash, no debt?<p>
USFlores   : JM: GLG just raised a lot of money to bill the Indian Rose project. I would not consider it. A takeover candidate at these prices.<p>
RLamon9684 : Is Joutel worth a fling? <p>
USFlores   : RLamon: Not interested in Joutel's Cuban stuff, but the stuff in Canada is not too bad.<p>
FAMSEVEN   : Heard about change in mining laws in China, mining industry supposedly on fire.  <p>
USFlores   : FAM: The process of changing China's mining law has gone very slowly. We still have no precedent, no projects successfully developed by Western companies. We'll see...<p>
RLee968757 : Do you see any light at the end of the tunnel in South Africa?<p>
USFlores   : RLee: Yes! The restructuring is underway. New companies being formed with potential for growth and more efficient corporate structures<p>
Mmlm2      : Mr. Flores: Do you see any downside for ASARCO below 25?<p>
USFlores   : Mmlm: Asarco: looks good, could go lower. Just kidding. Stock well supported in low 20s.<p>
BANKFUND   : Mr Flores: Is Canyon Resources a buy before they get the Montana decision?<p>
USFlores   : BankFund: Of greater importance is the startup at the Briggs Mine in California. If Briggs works well, Canyon a buy even before Montana decision. Montana is gravy!<p>
Trac16cat  : Your opinion on Alta Gold?<p>
USFlores   : Alta: buy with a $6 target.<p>
WorthOnLne : Thank you for your time Victor.  You did a fantastic job! That Concludes this evenings "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Mr. Flores for being our guest this evening.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
