	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 09/25/96--James Glassman, "Social Insecurity"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>09/25/96--James Glassman, "Social Insecurity"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, September 25 at 8 P.M. EDT, James Glassman, a noted expert on the Social Security system, joined Worth OnLine for our live chat show, "Conference Call." A political commentator who appears regularly on CNN and PBS and a columnist for the Washington Post, Glassman is the author of "Social Insecurity," which appeared in the September issue of Worth. Following is a transcript of the live event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed are those of James Glassman, and do not represent the views of Worth, Worth OnLine, or Capital Publishing.<p>
WorthEdit3 : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's new live chat show series. Every week we give readers the opportunity to chat with the leaders in money and markets. Check our site (Keyword: Worth) for a calendar of upcoming events.  Tonight Glassman will be talking about why he thinks it's time to do away with the biggest government program and let people invest for their own retirement. Good evening, Mr. Glassman. It's good to have you here tonight.<p>
JKGlassman : Thanks, it's get to be online. I've never done this before.<p>
WorthEdit3 : I think tonight should be an exciting time, then! I'll open the floor to questions.<p>
RWaldock   : I have a question.  If we put retirement in stocks, won't that tank bonds?<p>
JKGlassman : Not at all. First of all, I would guess that a great deal of retirement money would go into bonds. Any retiree would be foolish to put his or her nestegg exclusively into stocks.<p>
RWaldock   : How would we make up the deficit without being able to raid social security?<p>
JKGlassman : Well, we're about to be in that position anyway. Starting in 2012 or so, we'll be paying out more from the Social Security fund than we take in. So Social Security won't be a means to balance the budget, but a way to unbalance it.<p>
WorthEdit3 : In your article, you talk about the need for Social Security reform. What's do you view as the biggest fault with the current system?<p>
JKGlassman : I see two completely different problems with the system. First, I believe it is intrinsically immoral. It's a Ponzi scheme. The people who came in early got paid by the people who came in later. There is no link between work and reward. But Americans believe that there is. They have been deceived by their own government. <p>
Second, and probably more important, the current system discourages thrift, savings, looking to future and self-reliance. Instead we look to the government for sustenance. All of us! Not just the neediest. This is a sad state of affairs.<p>
RWaldock   : Do you see Social Security becoming another form of welfare if there are not changes?<p>
JKGlassman : Social Security already is a form of welfare. It is not truly a retirement system, the way that your company pension plan or 401 (k) is. Instead, young people, currently working, pay the retirement and widowhood stipends of older people. It's welfare, but worse, it's not means-tested.<p>
RWaldock   : If it IS means tested, then it IS welfare!<p>
JKGlassman : Well, we can get into all sorts of semantic hair-splitting, but the point is that it's welfare that goes to mainly to people who don't need it -- in the sense that they can take care of themselves.<p>
North bro  : Question? What is the best mutual funds at this time?<p>
JKGlassman : North bro asked about best mutual fund. Turns out I just did a column looking at that question. I used my own parameters, which I won't go into here, but my answer was Fidelity Contrafund. By the way, my assessment of the best mutual fund focussed on two things that many investors ignore -- and that they'll need to keep in mind if Social Security is privatized: low risk and a good track record over a long period of time.<p>
DEITHA     : What do you think of the so-called inflation bonds announced today?<p>
JKGlassman : I am very enthusiastic about the inflation-linked bonds that were announced today. It's one of the major accomplishments of this administration. The idea was originally Milton Friedman's! These bonds will be especially important if Social Security is privatized. What they do is guarantee that your nestegg will not be depleted by inflation. The bonds will pay a real return determined by the market (maybe 3% for a long bond) PLUS an inflation adjustment based on the CPI. Anyway, I love the things and plan to buy some myself. <p>
RWaldock   : Jim, what would happen to the bonds if there is DEflation? <p>
JKGlassman : I have not checked the details, but my understanding is that the bonds will pay a minimum inflation premium of 0% -- though don't hold me to that. Also, I think the chances of deflation are close to nil. It's a risk I would be willing to run even without the guarantee. I think that the bond will actually force government to be *more* resonsible in holding down inflation. This, by the way, was the argument of Milton Friedman.<p>
RWaldock   : Back to Social Security, so many people get Social SecurityI, including tons of "crazy" kids' abuse of the system!<p>
JKGlassman : The disability portion of Social Security, to which you refer, is an utter disaster. Something has to be done about it. It has become a major scam, and, as you point out, it is abused by parents of perfectly healthy young children, as well as by drug addicts and alcoholics. But that's a topic for another time.<p>
BoBo462917 : Jim, what would happen to the S&P 500 if Social Security was privatized?<p>
JKGlassman : BoBo, you ask what would happen to the S&P 500 if Social Security were privatized. My guess is that the change would be very bullish for the markets. More money would pour in as a result of private investors putting their former-Social Security money into stocks. But, even more important, privatization would bring new people into the stock market and would increase the investment (even the non-Social Security investing) of those already in the market. This was the experience in Chile!<p>
BoBo462917 : Would the rise in the value of the SP500 be warranted? Or would it just be a supply and demand phenomenon?<p>
JKGlassman : Well, the increase in stock prices (just as the increase in the prices of everything else) is always supply and demand phenomenon.But there's no doubt that one result of increased demand (that is, more investors buying stock) would be to increase supply (that is, more new businesses issuing stock).<p>
BoBo462917 : So this isn't the environment for the value investor. It's a momentum paradise!<p>
RWaldock   : Wouldn't the S&P become the Nifty 500?<p>
BoBo462917 : Exactly RWald<p>
JKGlassman : Oh, I wouldn't say that the value investor would not benefit. With more people buying stock (and putting more money into the market in general), a lot of overlooked value stocks may become popular. I don't believe, by the way, that stocks stay "value" or "growth" throughout their lives; they go through phases. Certainly, some value stocks would become growth stocks.<p>
BoBo462917 : What are the odds of a portion of Social Security being truly privatized in a Clinton administration? Or even a Gore administration?<p>
JKGlassman : Good question, but it requires a kind of long answer. First, I think that Clinton likes the idea of privatization. He's sent signals that he understands and appreciates what happened in Chile. The problem, however, is that, if Social Security is privatized, the underpinnings of the welfare state, so beloved by Democrats, will be loosened. Don't forget that the Clinton administration wanted the government to take control of more of the economy (through Hillary Clinton's health plan). Privatization would mean the govt would control less, and the dominos might fall. So, I doubt that reform would occur in a Democratic White House with a Democratic Congress.<p>
JKGlassman : Let me ask the rest of you a question. I assume some of you are young -- in 20s and 30s. Why aren't you outraged by the current system? Why haven't you mobilized politically? Do you think that young people ever will? They are the victims of the current system. They pay out a big chunk of what they earn to people who don't necessarily need it, and they (young people) have almost no chance of benefiting from the system. Aren't you angry?<p>
BoBo462917 : I have watched the baby boomers move through the system in such a destructive way that I've become numb. As real estate prices shot up, I found myself a new person in the real estate market. As an investor, I come in after a 12 year bull. Medical care is next. So is Social Security.<p>
RWaldock   : Perot is talking about generational accounting, and they won't let him speak! <p>
Treyb69    : I'm 26 and outraged!  People over 50 control 80% of all wealth, why am I paying their CC?<p>
Hoser lv   : (age 39) Yes, I'm outraged.  I intend to leave the U.S. when the economy collapses.  You?<p>
SfwIII     : I'm early forties, I'm outraged, and I don't think that even I will see a penny.  I do think that privatization will happen, but it will take the actual disaster.<p>
Treyb69    : WHy can't they do something as simple as means testing?<p>
RWaldock   : I don't think means testing is fair for Social Security<p>
Treyb69    : And when the actual disaster happens, it'll be too late.<p>
BoBo462917 : When the boomers come of age, there will be no chance of altering the entitlements portion of the budget. <p>
DEITHA     : Must re-educate older people. Social Security is not an insurance program - it is welfare on back of children.<p>
Hoser lv   : Trey - agree that means testing will become essential ... but I won't be here.<p>
Treyb69    : Means testing is fair, Social Security is a social insurance, not a savings plan (in current form).<p>
SfwIII     : Means testing proves that it is welfare, and not a pension.  That is why they can't do it. <p>
JKGlassman : Let me jump in here on means-testing. The answer to Social Security in the past has always been some tweaking: raising the retirement age, increasing taxes, maybe means testing. But that makes Social Security an even *worse* deal than it is now. If you are 35, when you retire, if there is Social Security at all, you will be getting a return of negative 1.5 percent on your contributions. With means-testing, etc., you return will be even *more* negative.<p>
Treyb69    : It is welfare, it'd be cheaper if we just all realized that.<p>
RWaldock   : Jim, I thought the less you paid in, the more you got out and vice versa???<p>
JKGlassman : Good point. Social Security is already means-tested to a great extent. But not the less you pay in, etc.<p>
Treyb69    : Either scale it back to support just the most needy, or privatize it and make it work.<p>
Smk122346  : JK: Because there is no true trust fund, how much Social Security overfunding for the deficit takes place?<p>
JKGlassman : Currently we take in about $50 b. more in revenues from Social Security than we pay out each year. That $50b goes to reduce the deficit, and, in return, special bonds go into the trust fund. <p>
SfwIII     : The point is that it is a tax.  It is not an investment, you don't get a return any more than you get a return on your sales tax.<p>
DBaird5147 : You guys are nuts! Social Security was supposed to keep you from becoming homeless! Not easy street.<p>
JKGlassman : Let me respond to DBaird...the true purpose of Social Security was *never* made clear. Some people think it's a safety net, but many, perhaps most Americans see it as a large part of their own retirement nest egg. <p>
Treyb69    : Not to knock the elderly, but who could ever think they'd be taken care of, and they didn't have to take care of themselves?? <p>
Valhal     : JK: I've read that Chileans, with their private plan, 
             now have a larger nest egg, after only<p>
JKGlassman : As believe that in a free society, all of us have the obligation to take care of ourselves. Now, clearly, some people can't, and we ought to have some kind of welfare at retirement for them. But why construct a system in which 260 million americans are forced to participate in order to take care of maybe 10 or 20 million who can't help themselves.<p>
Treyb69    : Yes, we ought to take care of those who don't, but not people earning 75k a year on investments and pensions, etc.<p>
DEITHA     : Social Security was never meant to be full support - only supplement, I think.<p>
Valhal     : My problem with Social Security is that it is such a drag on the economy. Do you agree?<p>
Smk122346  : Does not deficit reduction, regardless of who created it, benefit young and old alike?<p>
JKGlassman : Yes, deficit reduction helps eveyrone. But let's not confused deficit reduction with what some of us want to do with Social Security. <p>
Treyb69    : If we just do the first level of privatizing, every person under age 35 is a millionare by retirment.<p>
JKGlassman : What we want is for individuals themselves to take care of their own retirements, not to have the government do it for us. It's not more complicated than that. <p>
Treyb69    : That creates tremendous investment and a growing economy, not by giving handouts.<p>
SfwIII     : I think that the government investing Social Security money in equities, as some have proposed, is worse than now.  It gives the government effective control over the companies, even if they can't.<p>
Smk122346  : Social Security is a tax. It is not a retirement vehicle. You transfer wealth from one to the other.<p>
Hoser lv   : Smk - agreed - more like a Ponzi scheme hiding as a tax. <p>
JKGlassman : I absolutely do not want the government investing in equities. I want individuals doing it. You're right, Sfwill, it would be much worse than the current system, even.<p>
REXNESocial SecurityIE  : So, why not sell the right to "manage" the Social Security retirement "accounts" to the highest bidder!?<p>
JKGlassman : REX, exactly right. But not allow just one manager. Do what they do in Chile. Let Americans choose their own manager from dozens of possiblities, the way we choose mutual funds today.<p>
Treyb69    : If they set up PSAs it becomes a true savings plan, even factoring in the large transition $<p>
Hoser lv   : Mr. G - with the U.S. dismal savings rate, what's the 
             odds most will save enough?<p>
JKGlassman : One reason we have such a low savings rate is that many Americans assume they don't have to save because Social Security will be there for them...<p>
Smk122346  : The next Ponzi is to issue bonds that have a guaranteed return, the hell with inflation.<p>
JKGlassman : We have to get back into the habit of saving. We have to get back to self-reliance, which is something that a privatized Social Security system would do.<p>
DEITHA     : Means testing might encourage less saving for own retirement.<p>
Treyb69    : Buy gold, at some point our awful fiscal policies will catch up.<p>
MIKEWON    : I know Chile is smaller but their system of privatization seems to be working with out the onvesting  for the people.<p>
JKGlassman : The Chilean system is a real success story. One thing that happened in Chile was this...  The system requires workers to put 10% of their pay into a private retirement account, like a mutual fund. But what happened was that workers got into the habit of saving! The savings rate jumped to over 25% in Chile.<p>
Treyb69    : What are some realistic solutions, and how long before we could see one?<p>
Hoser lv   : Yes, JK, the political issue of Social Security is like an "electric fence" - touch it and you die.<p>
REXNESocial SecurityIE  : A "Sallie Mae" type corporation should provide American's with an ownership opportunity in the organization that "managed" their retirement funds, wouldn't it???<p>
DNic880    : Will Social Security be alive for me in 2030?<p>
JKGlassman : DN, I am afraid that Social Security is unlikely to be alive for you in 2030, which is why you should start getting active politically on the subject NOW. <p>
Hoser, you say that Social Security is like an electric fence... Actually, that is changing somewhat. Steve Forbes in fact brought up privatizing Social Security during his brief campaign and got a good response, and people in Congress like Rep. Jim Kolbe (R-Ariz) are talking openly about it and getting re-elected anyway. I wouldn't despair., but the key is for young people to organize and oppose the AARP, etc. <p>
Smodim     : DN, and start saving like mad now!<p>
Smk122346  : A realistic solution is to elect those people who have solutions, like Forbes did!<p>
Treyb69    : I see it harder and harder with the % of elderly rising.  They have a large voting block. Alan Simpson (R) Wyoming, has a plan.<p>
JKGlassman : Trey, yes, Simpson has a modest plan, along with Bob Kerrey of Neb. that allows you to shift 2% of your Social Security money to private funds.<p>
Hoser lv   : JK - yes - but look at the presidential mud using Social Security as an issue for the elderly.<p>
MShults    : Why get active-our so called reps don't respond.<p>
JKGlassman : MShults, you said that politicians ignore you. My experience is different. Politicians cannot ignore organized voting groups, which is why they respond to seniors.<p>
Treyb69    : Young people do not have common goals/visions, that's our largest polictical weakness. <p>
JKGlassman : Trey, true about uncommon goals, but this is an issue that affects all you people.<p>
REXNESocial SecurityIE  : Get a clue.. young people have goals that are different, not uncommon.<p>
Treyb69    : JK, I know, but few too many people care about it, and vote on different issues (e.g., student loans).  This is much, much bigger....<p>
TGFGNUT    : What's chance Social Security will be changed from social insurance to a welfare system?<p>
JKGlassman : TGF, If Social Security is privatized, there will still be some provision for the very poor.<p>
DNic880    : Why cant I do my own savings and sign a release to let me out of this system?<p>
TGFGNUT    : How many people know there's a "social bias" in the Social Security benefit formula?<p>
JKGlassman : DNic, you ask the key question. Right now, you cannot opt out. You are not allowed. We want you to be able to opt out.<p>
Hoser lv   : JK - I'm so convinced the U.S. will continue to do the wrong thing, I'm making other plans. <p>
Treyb69    : Don't any of them, except for Kasich, want to do the 'right' thing? <p>
Valhal     : DN this scheme falls apart sooner than later if anyone is let out!<p>
MShults    : Do boomers care enough to organize??<p>
JKGlassman : Hoser, I sometimes despair of the US doing right, too. But look at what's happening today in Europe, with Germany and France at 11 percent unemployment-plus.<p>
Maelmoro   : Do you think there is a chance that the 1993 tax on Social Security payments may be reduced or eliminated?<p>
JKGlassman : Trey, I like Kasich, too, but there are some good Congressmen on this issue, starting with Jim Kolbe. I suggest all of you write him and tell him you support what he's doing.<p>
Smk122346  : I believe US unemployment, if accurately measured is around 10-11% as well.<p>
JKGlassman : Simpson, unfortunately, is retiring. But there is lots of support for privatization. I know that Gingrich is backing the Kolbe group. <p>
TGFGNUT    : It's like health insurance; if Feds didn't force people to pay for Social Security we'd have 40 million people without pensions....Oh woe.<p>
Treyb69    : Chris Shays, from my home state, is good too. <p>
JKGlassman : However you measure it, unemployment in Germany is at least twice what it is in US.<p>
JKGlassman : TGF, you raise a good point. One thing about Social Security -- even for a libertarian like me -- is that if we privatize it, we are going to have to make it mandatory. Otherwise, we will have to take care of millions of profligate types. <p>
Smk122346  : East Germany was a basket case.  Much like Arkansas
JKGlassman : Smk, the reason for high unemp in France, Germany and Italy, etc., is not E. Germany, it is the huge out-of-control costs of the welfare state that have been loaded on business;.<p>
BoBo462917 : What do you think of the inflation-indexed bond based on the CPI?<p>
TGFGNUT    : Making pensions mandatory doesn't sound very libertarian to me!<p>
JKGlassman : Bobo, inflation-indexed bonds, as I have said before, are a great idea. Are you asking specifically about the CPI as an index?<p>
Treyb69    : JK, BW just ran a blurb on how rich the dole's in Europe are.  No incentive to work.<p>
DNic880    : JK- What do you tell people who are putting money into this system will never see any of it?<p>
JKGlassman : Trey, not only is there little incentive to work. There is also little incentive for businesses to hire. It is too expensive, given the social costs loaded on businesses, to hire anyone for life.<p>
BoBo462917 : I guess I'm asking about the fundamental methodology behind it. Which includes the fact that it's using the CPI. <p>
JKGlassman : The CPI isn't perfect, but it's not bad.<p>
Smk122346  : Inflation indexed tax rates did not work.<p>
TGFGNUT    : JK...are you a card-carrying Libertarian?<p>
JKGlassman : As for my libertarian card: No, I'm not a party member, but my political leanings are in that direction.<p>
Treyb69    : Too bad everyone just couldn't be a productive member of society, no drugs, crimes, etc. I mean, what has our society become, awful!<p>
TGFGNUT    : But the CPI has added untold billions to the Social Security system!<p>
JKGlassman : TGF, the CPI is an imperfect measure of the cost of living. I completely agree.<p>
Valhal     : JKG: Doesn't the CPI overstate the actual inflation?<p>
Smk122346  : Too let the Feds legislate a problem away is not the answer.  Address it.  Solve it.<p>
JKGlassman : Yes, CPI overstates inflation because people respond to rising prices in one area of the economy by increasing their demand in another, and the CPI doesn't take that into account. One of the best ideas being floated last year was to adjust the CPI and thus bring down some of government's costs in the drive to balance the budget. I strongly supported that move, backed by Sen. Moynihan, among others.<p>
Smk122346  : That sounds like you just vetoed static budgeting.  <p>
JKGlassman : Well, I think we are winding down here. This has been a real treat. A last question from anyone?<p>
Smk122346  : When do you retire.JK<p>
JKGlassman : I am 49 years old. I hope I never retire, but I'll be 65 in, what?, 2022.<p>
WorthEdit3 : Thank you so much for joining us this evening, Mr. Glassman. I think everyone has enjoyed tonight's chat. A complete transcript of this event, will be posted in the Today box on our opening screen next week. Transcripts from all of Worth OnLine's live chat shows are available in the Software Library.<p>
JKGlassman : I've got to sign off now. Thanks everyone! <p>
WorthEdit3 : The Worth staff extends its appreciation to James Glassman for being our guest this evening.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
