	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>09/11/96 -- Michael Paolercio, CEO of Michael Anthony Jewelers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						WorthOnLne : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live chat show series. Our guest tonight is Michael Paolercio, CEO of Michael Anthony Jewelers, one of the largest publicly-held jewelry companies in the United States. By holding licenses for everyone from Looney Tunes to Barbie to all the major sports leagues, the company sells to some of the largest retail outlets. Tonight he'll be answering questions about the fine jewelry industry, the outlook for mass-market retailers, and the gold market.<p>
MAJewelers : Thank you Worth OnLine for welcoming us to Conference Call.<p>
WorthOnLne : To begin, tell us how Michael Anthony got started.<p>
MAJewelers : Twenty years ago, my brother and I had a dream to start a business together and build it into something that we would both be very proud of. Anthony has the jewelry background, being a bench jeweler and having had a lot of experience doing jewelry manufacturing. My background is in sales and marketing, having received my degree from City University of New York. I've had the opportunity to work in the textile industry, exposed me to the art of buying, selling, and making deals happen. <p>
Our first retail experience was in flea markets in the NY area, and in the front of my uncle's beauty salon in Manhattan. We took our first loft on 46th street in 1979 and attended our first jewelry trade show in 1980. Our first big break came in 1981, when gold prices started to drop dramatically from the all-time highs. We began a gold leasing program and transferred the risk of owning gold back to the banks and focused on being a jewelry manufacturer, not a gold speculator. <p>
The business continued to grow dramatically, and by 1983, our sales had topped $25 million and it was apparent that our capital needs would soon require outside financing. By October of 1987, our sales had grown to over $50 million. We were ready to do a public offering. We were successful in raising over $11 million dollars of equity financing to continue the growth and begin the acquisition of smaller and less capitalized competitors. In the last 8 years, we have acquired over 10 companies. Our sales have grown to over $150 million.<p>
WorthOnLne : Shlef asked about the outlook for the gold market. Can you give us any foresight on what's ahead?<p>
MAJewelers : Gold prices have been relatively stable the last few years. They have been within a trading range of between $375 and $420. Very recently, there has been a lot of pressure on gold prices because of the selling by the World Banks, and gold hit a low yesterday of $383 on the news that the IMF was selling 5 million ounces.<p>
Mls4025    : Is there any truth to the rumors about you're merging with a large West Coast gold company?<p>
MAJewelers : We continue to evaluate acquisition opportunities with other companies that manufacture and distribute jewelry products. We are confident that opportunities exist that will expand our customer base and add new product offerings.<p>
WorthOnLne : You just released second quarter earnings. What were they and what's important?<p>
MAJewelers : Sales for the second quarter were $27,706,000, an increase of $2,804,000, or 11 percent from sales of $24,902,000 in the prior year's comparable period. The net loss for the quarter was $625,000 or $.08 per share on 8,256,000 weighted average shares outstanding, compared to a net loss of $931,000, or $.11 per share on 8,502,000 weighted average shares outstanding in last year's comparable period. We are pleased to report an 11 percent increase in sales over last year, especially for our weakest quarter. Gross margins also increased over last year. <p>
Nakadi     : Is there a good jewelry index (maybe excluding gold) that one can use to evaluate this as an asset class and compare to other investments. <p>
MAJewelers : The World Gold Council provides quarterly statistics on retail sales for the industry.<p>
AJDOMAN    : DOES Michael Anthony manufacture outside of the U.S.? <p>
MAJewelers : Michael Anthony manufactures over 95 percent of its products in the U.S.<p>
Mls4025    : Do you see the continued consolidation of large retailers as big negative for your business?<p>
MAJewelers : First of all I don't think there is anything I can do about the consolidation in the jewelry industry or any other industry. The larger the players are, the more important the large suppliers are to them.<p>
TomsGems   : Does 18Kt gemstone jewelry sell better in the USA than 14Kt jewelry? <p>
MAJewelers : 14k jewelry is the predominant karat of choice of the American consumer with 10k being the second choice and 18k reserved and limited only to a very limited higher-end consumer.<p>
AndersonIV : Are diamonds in the si / gh range a good buy? I've heard that DeBeers will raise prices 10 percent.<p>
MAJewelers : I can't believe DeBeers would try to raise prices that dramatically in the short term. Historically, the increases have been in the low single digits. Where do you buy your diamonds?<p>
Mls4025    : Do you have any plans to sell directly to the consumer via the net?<p>
MAJewelers : Michael Anthony has no interest in selling directly to the consumer. It would be in direct competition with our customers. But we are setting up a Web site that will be activated within the next few weeks to answer all questions. You'll find product information, locations where you can buy the product, and up-to-the minute financial information about Michael Anthony.<p>
Mls4025    : How many licenses do you hold for karat gold jewelry products?<p>
TomsGems   : Do auctions online for fine gold/gemstone jewelry have any promise for the future?<p>
MAJewelers : TomsGems: I would be very skeptical to purchase any jewelry without having had the opportunity to properly inspect and appraise.<p>
AJDOMAN    : How large scale is the patent violators/ counterfeiters of your jewelry? <p>
MAJewelers : NBC's Dateline program profiled the jewelry industry a few months ago and featured Michael Anthony as a model for the industry in respect to quality karat integrity and compliance with trademark laws. There seems to be a constant invasion of counterfeit licensed products available to the consumer and the Jeweler's Vigilance Committee is investigating and prosecuting violators. We report counterfeiting to the licenser and try to find out who the counterfeiter is and press for help for the licensee.<p>
AJDOMAN    : What kind of money is transacted to acquire patent rights such as the NBA?<p>
MAJewelers : In addition to the significant up front fees, there are royalties that are paid on an ongoing basis. We hold almost 100 licenses, ranging from the sports professional leagues, to Warner Bros., to colleges all across the country.<p>
WorthOnLne : Are you introducing any new products in the near future?<p>
MAJewelers : We recently introduced a new line of gemstone jewelry featuring natural sapphires mined in Montana. This new line, The American Sapphire Collection, is consistent with our strategy of expanding the Company's product lines in order to increase sales of higher margin products.<p>
LEA LTD    : Are you the guy on QVC???<p>
MAJewelers : I have appeared on Home Shopping Network, but today my brother Anthony has a regular program once a month featuring USA Gold.<p>
TomsGems   : Is ultrasonic cleaning recommended for most gemstone jewelry? For opal & emerald jewelry?<p>
MAJewelers : Definitely not. Ultrasonic cleaning should only be used for all gold, and faceted stones only. You don't put in pearls, opals, or any other soft stone like turquoise.<p>
TomsGems   : Ultrasonic for only faceted gems?  What about sapphire cabochons, etc.?<p>
MAJewelers : I would be very careful about putting any unfaceted gems of less than 8 on the hardness scale in an ultrasonic cleaning machine.<p>
WorthOnLne : Who are your biggest customers?<p>
MAJewelers : WalMart, JC Penney, Service Merchandise, Sterling, Home Shopping Network...<p>
Mls4025    : What about Best Products?<p>
MAJewelers : They are a very small customer.<p>
LEA LTD    : My husband has a 14 karat gold bracelet that turns his arm dark colors...could it be 14 karat???<p>
MAJewelers : 14k gold very rarely turns someone's skin a darker color. If the person has had this happen before, it could be 14k. But if it doesn't happen with other 14k jewelry, it could be a fake.<p>
WorthOnLne : Has the company bought back any shares?<p>
MAJewelers : Over the past several years, we have repurchased over 500,000 shares and we currently have a buy back program in place for up to 750,000 shares.<p>
Mls4025    : What do you consider the biggest concern in your 
             business today?<p>
MAJewelers : That gold prices would begin to skyrocket, and that would cause instability in the marketplace.<p>
WorthOnLne : How does the price of gold affect your profit margins?<p>
MAJewelers : As gold prices increase, so does the cost of leasing inventory and financing receivables. This would hurt our profit margins.<p>
WorthOnLne : Is the jewelry industry cyclical like most industries?<p>
MAJewelers : I would think that the industry is cyclical in nature. But in the recent recession, gold prices have remained relatively stable, and sales of jewelry products continued to increase.<p>
NJones2785 : The gold supply seems to keep increasing because of tech improvements.  Shortage how, when?<p>
MAJewlers: I don't believe that there is a shortage of physical gold. With the constant selling of World Banks, I don't think supply will affect demand. Therefore prices should not increase.<p>
NJones2785 : Why else would your costs increase?<p>
MAJewelers : Increasing labor costs would increase the price of our products or decrease our profit margins.<p>
R 1 M S    : How much would the price have to increase before you're affected?<p>
MAJewelers : Gold would have to trade above $450 per ounce before we could see a decline in revenue.<p>
R 1 M S    : Do you see gold going to $450.00 an ounce in the near future?<p>
MAJewelers : I don't think so.<p>
Mls4025    : Do you offer any type of guarantee for your products?<p>
MAJewelers : MIs4025: Michael Anthony offers a lifetime warranty on all its products.<p>
Mls4025    : Has this guarantee increased the amount of returns in the past 10 years?<p>
MAJewelers : The amount of returns is such a small percent because the products are of the highest quality.<p>
LEA LTD:  What is your current rate of returns?<p>
MAJewelers : It is currently 10 percent to 15 percent of sales.<p>
WorthOnLne : What's ahead for the fine jewelry industry?<p>
MAJewelers : If Mother's Day is any indication of how Christmas will be, I think we will all be happy with the results. Many of our retail customers have given up spending advertising dollars in the off months and have plans to really blitz the air waves with TV and print advertising in Dec. when consumers are out there buying gifts.<p>
R 1 M S    : What about the price of Diamonds? <p>
MAJewelers : Diamond prices for the best quality goods have increased slightly. But the lower end continues to have pressure and therefore prices are dropping.<p>
NJones2785 : Saw recent story on U.S. sapphires.  Do you know the company?  Do you buy them?<p>
MAJewelers : We have recently signed an agreement with American Gem Corp. of St. Helena, Mt. to purchase millions of dollars.<p>
Mls4025    : Won't the loss of a week between Thanksgiving and Christmas hurt all retailers?<p>
WStras     : Would you be a buyer of gold now as an investment?<p>
MAJewelers : No, I would not. Unless it is a beautiful piece of jewelry for yourself or your wife, I think there are a lot better places to put your money than in bullion.<p>
LEA LTD    : Do you manufacture all your products in the U.S.? <p>
MAJewelers : 95 percent of our products are manufactured in the U.S.<p>
R 1 M S    : Where do you currently buy gold, diamonds, gemstones and do you have Tanzanites?<p>
MAJewelers : R1ms: All of our gold is purchased as 24k pure gold from a variety of gold banks and gold dealers. And, no, we don't have tanzanites. <p>
LEA LTD    : What other countries do you manufacture in???<p>
MAJewelers : We don't manufacture in any foreign country. But we do purchase a limited amount of products manufactured overseas.<p>
NJones2785 : How would layman learn to recognize quality gems without buying fortune's worth?<p>
MAJewelers : I'm sure there are classes available at colleges around the country, as well as plenty of books and trade magazines.<p>
WorthOnLne : Can you tell us what you predict the mass-market retail sector will do based on orders?<p>
MAJewelers : Worth: Right now we have received significant commitments from all our major retail customers.<p>
R 1 M S    : Are you buying here or abroad- Belgium - Where?<p>
MAJewelers : We buy direct from Israel as well as local importers.<p>
WorthOnLne : How do you see this upcoming holiday season shaping up?<p>
Mls4025    : Are those commitments for this year running ahead of this time a year ago?<p>
MAJewelers : I think we can see double digit increases from jewelry retailers this holiday season.<p>
Scottsli   : Does anyone have an opinion on Venture Stores ?<p>
MAJewelers : Scotts: Venture is currently a customer of Michael Anthony and our business is slightly ahead of last year.<p>
Seagulls   : Are you going to address the low price of your stock? The market goes up, yours  goes down.<p>
MAJewelers : Seagulls: The book value of MA shares is in excess of $5.50 and we are working hard to communicate that to Wall Street. With respect to other publicly traded jewelry stocks, MAJ has outperformed its peer group and we see ourselves continuing to outperform the group.<p>
NJones2785 : Do you think gold jewelry better store of value than bullion or coins?<p>
MAJewelers : On the one hand you can wear the jewelry, but on the other hand you cannot turn it into cash as easily as bullion or coins. But it's a lot more fun to wear!<p>
TomsGems   : As a rule, does fine gold/gemstone jewelry routinely come with a (GIA) grading or appraisal?<p>
MAJewelers : The GIA only does an evaluation as to the quality, color, and weight of a diamond or other precious gems. It does not establish retail or wholesale value.<p>
NJones2785 : I may have missed.  Do you have direct retail stores?<p>
MAJewelers : No, we do not sell directly to the consumer, it would be a conflict.<p>
LEA LTD    : Do you foresee any acquisitions to gain market strength for the future?? <p>
MAJewelers : We are always looking at acquisition opportunities. We talked about this earlier in the chat.<p>
R 1 M S    : Who does set the value- DeBeers ?<p>
MAJewelers : RIMS: DeBeers sets the value for rough diamonds. The marketplace sets the price of finished goods.<p>
TomsGems   : Who in the industry is "authorized" to appraise jewelry? Can a Graduate Gemologist appraise? <p>
MAJewelers :  A certified gemologist could clearly identify the quality, color, and possible weight of your diamond if he had the right equipment and there is a weekly report called the Rappaport that lists the wholesale value of diamonds to the trade. But only a range--they are not buyers or sellers.<p>
NJones2785 : Easy to find, but what's your stock symbol?<p>
MAJewelers : Our ticker symbol is MAJ. We are traded on the AMEX.<p>
R 1 M S    : How many shares are authorized and how many are sold?<p>
MAJewelers :  20 million authorized, and approximately 8.2 million outstanding.<p>
R 1 M S    : Preferred- common, or what is available?<p>
MAJewelers : Common stock only.<p>
MKlein7OO  : WILL Jan Bell survive?<p>
MAJewelers : Jan Bell is a good customer of MAJ, and they have one of the best balance sheets in the industry. We are optimistic about their future.<p>
WorthOnLne : Any last questions for Mr. Paolercio?<p>
MAJewelers : It has been a pleasure to be a part of the Worth OnLine Conference Call show. I look forward to coming back on in January to report on holiday sales.<p>
WorthOnLne : And thank you, Mr. Paolercio, for taking time to answer our questions this evening. That concludes this edition of "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
