		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>09/04/96 -- Clint Willis</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>EARN MEGA PROFITS IN MICROCAP STOCKS.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, September 4 at 8 P.M. EDT, Clint Willis joined Worth OnLine for our live chat show, "Conference Call." Willis is the author of several recent Worth cover stories, such as "Search for the World's Highest Yields," "Finding the Next Microsoft," and September's "Going Small." Following is a transcript of the live event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed are those of Clint Willis, and do not represent the views of Worth, Worth OnLine, or Capital Publishing.<p>
WorthEdit6 : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live chat show series. Our guest tonight is Worth magazine contributing editor Clint Willis--author of cover stories "Search for the World's Highest Yields," "Finding the Next Microsoft," and this month's "Going Small," a story about the potential for mega profits in microcap stocks. They're volatile and little-followed -- and if you don't see that as good news, you're out of your depth.<p>
Willis, founder of The Writing Institute in Portland, Maine, has written for more than 100 publications, including The New York Times, Travel & Leisure, and The Washington Post. He is also a former member of the New York State Securities Analysts Association.  Tonight, Willis will be discussing tactics for finding the small stocks with potential for the biggest returns on Wall St. Clint is using screenname WillisEdit. Please feel free to ask questions now.<p>
FHADI      : Clint, how important do you feel the number of outstanding shares is?<p>
WillisEdit : The key thing is the market cap, because that determines liquidity--the smaller the better.<p>
Tursillo   : Clint-liked your article on finding the next MSFT. Wondering about timing on buying a stock like that?<p>
WillisEdit : Timing doesn't matter--you're investing for a decade. <p>
Tursillo   : But sometimes you can be three years early or more. That's a lot of opportunity given up.<p>
WillisEdit : True. But the key is to be at a place where you have confidence. If that happens three years earlier, great. If not, you're still gonna make money in the long run.<p>
Tursillo   : So you are totally fundamental.  Do you look at relative strength or anything technical?<p>
WillisEdit : Tursillo--you got it.<p>
BeanPiez   : How do investment firm's health care info technology research analysts-- go about their research on H.I.T various vendors other than vendor presentations? Are there objective forums to help research specialized areas?<p>
WillisEdit : Yes, newsletters like California Medical Technology Stock Letter--but generally I think you're better off doing your own work on smallest caps.<p>
FHADI      : I'm following a few micros right now. one has a p/e ratio of 2.5. Can that compare to a blue chip? I mean if coke had a 2.5 p/e ratio I'd sell my car.<p>
WillisEdit : I see your point, so would I. My guess is that this smallcap has problems--but check it out.<p>
TThomas212 : Where should I begin to locate microcaps<p>
BeanPiez   : Yes TThomas212. Willis -- can you give two or three of the best ways to locate information?<p>
WillisEdit : I'd try computer screens like the ones described in the box with the article. After computer screens, try calling the companies directly, then suppliers and customers...You'll be amazed at how much info they'll give you on the phone.<p>
TThomas212 : Is there any publication that follows microcaps other than Red Chip Review?<p>
WillisEdit : Yes, but I haven't seen any nearly as good.<p>
WorthEdit6 : Article can be found in the Worth archives on Worth OnLine -- Intelligence, Archives...the article he just mentioned is called "First, Find the Haystack." from the September 1996 issue of Worth.<p>
Tursillo   : Clint-are you familiar with the Cabot Market Letter? Despite all the criticism, he has several hard and fast rules for looking for the same types of stocks you do.<p>
TThomas212 : Does Red Chip segregate the stocks by region?<p>
WillisEdit : I'm not terribly familiar with Cabot's letter; I've heard it's ok.<p>
TAnder4835 : What can I find in the library to help me<p>
WillisEdit : Occasionally you can do a clip search and find articles about a small company.<p>
Tursillo   : TAnder-a good library will have several investment newsletters.  Also, try the S&P stock guides (little brown or green books).<p>
WillisEdit : Tursillo--the newsletters in the library won't have the tiniest stocks. <p>
Tursillo   : Clint-how tiny are you talkin'? <p>
WillisEdit : I'm talking under $25 million market cap, man.<p>
Tursillo   : Oh-yes, you are right.<p>
BeanPiez   : Do microcaps suffer from the same cycles as larger cap stocks?<p>
WillisEdit : Not at all. These companies have their own problems/opportunities in their niches... that's why they're so fun to follow.<p>
TAnder4835 : Tell me more about screens for the micro. By the way, great article.<p>
FHADI      : Can you incorporate macroeconomic trends when analyzing stocks under $25 million?<p>
WillisEdit : Yes, you can--using similar principals. But remember, we're looking for niches here.<p>
BeanPiez   : Does it make more sense than focusing on a particular sector and learning its "ins and outs"?<p>
WillisEdit : No. Look for good companies that have a great common sense story and the cash and talent and market to carry it through. You don't need to become an industry expert.<p>
TAnder4835 : When I niche pick I look in my own backyard--MI--more information at hand.<p>
WillisEdit : Great strategy--also, you can go see the companies.<p>
TThomas212 : tander4835  I am interested in MI microcaps. What have you done to identify them?
Tursillo   : Clint-did you see the interview in an August issue of Wall Street Transcript about microcap managers? (Don't remember which week.)<p>
WillisEdit : What did it say?<p>
Tursillo   : Very detailed interview with several top microcap managers about their style, etc.<p>
WillisEdit : Were they smart?<p>
Tursillo   : I suppose.  It seems like microcap managers are a different breed.<p>
HAYVEN     : What is a good amount to invest in a small cap stock?<p>
WillisEdit : No more than you can afford to lose.<p>
TAnder4835 : How does insider trading effect microcaps?<p>
WillisEdit : Great question. Often, insiders own huge pieces of these companies--a good ...important... sign. But that could affect price movements.<p>
TAnder4835 : I check the Michigan Free Press and the Detroit News, then I check S&P for details. The newspaper gives good stories on small companies.<p>
WillisEdit : tander--wherever you're looking, I'd emphasize that your call to the company is key (and visit).<p>
FHADI      : Clint, can you use "value investing" with microcaps? Like watching a stock go from 3 to .50, then investing?<p>
WillisEdit : Fhadi--don't buy it just cause it's down. But sure, it's great to buy a good one when it's cheap. I didn't spend a lot of time worrying about valuations. These things tend to be bargains when the company is good, just because so few managers can buy them cause of liquidity problems--again, I'm talking about market cap under $25 million which is really really small.<p>
Tursillo   : Not to change the subject, but do you own any "next Microsoft" stocks besides those you put in the article?<p>
WillisEdit : I don't buy these myself--I can't; I'm a journalist. Anyway, that's a slightly different article, with a different approach. a tougher one, I think, for most people than this microcaps gag, which is really easy (if you will do the work).<p>
Tursillo   : Fair enough.<p>
BeanPiez   : Are there any good online resources for researching microcaps? Or even to follow them?<p>
WillisEdit : See the box, "First, Find the Haystack":  we mention Morningstar U.S. Equities on Floppy. Sorry--that's a disk--it's not online yet.<p>
BeanPiez   : Is there a place/resource where microcap stock prices are collected so that its easy to follow price changes?<p>
WillisEdit : The pink sheets for many of them. A broker can get you the info. But I wouldn't buy these with the idea of tracking prices daily. <p>
BeanPiez   : More based on fundamentals you talked about in the article?<p>
WillisEdit : That's right--who runs the company, do they have a niche, can they deal with competition... what would destroy them, are their products good, do they have some cash, are they really, really good at what they do.<p>
WillisEdit : Have any of you invested in firms with market caps below $25 million? If so, how'd you do?<p>
TAnder4835 : Yes, I did well with the help of h$H, he kept me abreast and I called the companies. A lot of the companies have Internet sites.<p>
WillisEdit : tander--good point. We didn't use those; are they any good?<p>
FHADI      : What is h$H?<p>
TAnder4835 : An investment service on the Internet , use Yahoo! to locate.<p>
WorthEdit3 : FHADI--you can find H$H at www.hh-club.com/. It is a subscription service which seeks companies priced at less than $1.25 per share.<p>
TAnder4835 : Re screens--how do you use them?<p>
WillisEdit : They let you screen for a variety of criteria. We looked for companies with decent earnings growth, low p/e's, good cash position and the like. What we found was this: few companies pass on all counts; instead, you'll have a fast-growing company with no cash or a really cheap stock with little growth. That's when you call the firm and try to scope out what they're up to...but the screens did help get us started.<p>
I've never understood why a low stock price tells you anything--it's low market cap that tells you a company's size as an investment.<p>
BeanPiez   : What's the most interesting thing you learned about microcap investing during your research?<p>
WillisEdit : The most interesting thing was that there are lots of great little companies (although far more bad little ones) that no one on Wall Street cares about--and they will talk to you until you're sick of their voices. It's just a great place for the small investor. You have to have some confidence in your ability to judge a management's character and intentions over the phone, but that's not as hard as it sounds. You can tell if someone's a fool pretty quickly. <p>
TAnder4835 : How do I set up a screen<p>
WillisEdit : It's pretty straightforward, but each program has its own directions. Just get access to a database program and then type in the criteria according to their codes and they do the rest.<p>
FHADI      : So, is stock price one of your least concerns with micros? <p>
WillisEdit : fhadi: price per se is not important--I don't care if a stock trades for $1 or $50 a share--value is another story. If a firm splits its stock 2 for 1, the price halves. Does that change its value as an investment? No.<p>
TAnder4835 : Are you talking to the CEO or PR? <p>
WillisEdit : Not the PR! Not the PR! Talk to the CEO. He or she (mostly he) will talk to you in 9 of 10 cases.<p>
TAnder4835 : Where do I get the database program, which is the best?<p>
WillisEdit : Call Morningstar at 800 866 3472 for Equities on floppy at $295 year monthly updates and $145 quarterly updates (I'd go with quarterly for my purposes--finding good looking stocks). <p>
BeanPiez   : Can you tell me exactly what market cap is? (Sorry, I know this is a basic question.) <p>
WillisEdit : Good question. Market cap is number of shares outstanding times share price.<p>
FHADI      : What key questions do you ask the CEO?<p>
WillisEdit : Ask them to tell you what the company does, why it does it better than anyone else, why no one else can come in and do it better and what their plans for the future are. How will they get bigger without attracting competition that will blow them away? Then sit back and listen.<p>
FHADI      : I've been sold a lemon by a good car salesman, what should I be picking out of the CEO's statement that will actually affect stock price?<p>
WillisEdit : You mean the statement in the annual report? Or just his statements to you on the phone or in person?<p>
FHADI      : On the phone.<p>
WillisEdit : You should be listening to the answers and then deciding if they make sense to you. If they just spout great news, that's not necessarily convincing. but if they are actually saying things that are interesting, that's a good sign. That seems vague, but the best policy is just to listen and decide if you think the story makes sense.<p>
TAnder4835 : Other than screens, is there a cheap way to pick?<p>
WillisEdit : Yes. Read the local paper and talk to friends in business, but the screens are by far the most efficient way to get a bunch of interesting names to call. Again, I'd stress you don't just buy a company that screens well. God forbid.<p>
TAnder4835 : Kudos to you Clint --thanks for the info.<p>
Vision1972 : Of your top eight microcap picks, which has the most life left?<p>
WillisEdit : Sorry, I don't closely  monitor 'em once the piece goes to the magazine. I'd call the companies before you invest.<p>
WorthEdit6 : That concludes this edition of "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Clint Willis for being our guest this evening.<p>
WillisEdit : Thanks--good luck everyone, and thanks a lot to Worth.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

