<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 08/28/96 -- James O'Shaughnessy, author of "What Works on Wall Street"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>08/28/96 -- James O'Shaughnessy, author of "What Works on Wall Street"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						OnlineHost : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's new live chat show series. Every week we give readers the chance to chat with leaders in money and markets. Check our site (Keyword: Worth) for a calendar of upcoming events. Find out what really does work on Wall street with our guest tonight --  James O'Shaughnessy, author of "What Works on Wall Street."<p>
"What Works on Wall Street" is an analysis of 30 years worth of CompuStat stock market data that shows how the 15 most popular investment strategies have actually performed over time. Tonight James O'Shaughnessy will talk about his results. His screen name is JPOSOCM. Mr. O'Shaughnessy will begin taking questions.<p>
Would you like to say anything before we post the first question, Mr. O'Shaughnessy?<p>
JPOSOCM    : Sure, I'm happy to be here on Worth Online, and I think we've found some exciting results from the past 45 years of data.<p>
Question   : How did you go about this project?<p>
JPOSOCM    : We used the S&P Compustat database going back to 1951. Compustat is the most comprehensive database available today. It covers over 10,000 stocks in North America alone. We then tested a large number of the Streets most popular strategies such as buying low PE stocks, high yield, high earnings growth, etc. The results are for the longest time period. We rebalanced the portfolios every year, to once again reflect a holding of whatever factor we were interested in.<p>
Question   : Where would you put money today for 4 year old granddaughter?<p>
JPOSOCM    : In the best strategy we uncovered -- that is called "Cornerstone Growth" in the book. It buys stocks with (1) back-to-back earnings gains over the last five years, (2) Price-to-sales ratios below 1.5 and (3) the best 50 stocks by price momentum. <p>
Question   : What does your research say about mutual funds vs. stocks vs. bonds? <p>
JPOSOCM    : Stocks destroy bonds over the long term, with even horrible stock stratetgies beating bonds by wide margins. The mutual funds with the clearest buying strategies are the best to look at, with those that say "trust me" bringing up the rear. Look for clear, concise statements about how they buy and sell stocks. The more strategic a fund, the better its results.<p>
Question   : Are the results from your book good forever or are they just fads of the moment?<p>
JPOSOCM    : Just the opposite of the fads of the moment. We cover over 44 years of performance data on a whole host of strategies. Fad stocks are usually easy to see by their high PEs, high PSRs and high price to books. The strategies we uncovered as the best usually buy just the opposite, with a focus on good value ratios, or good value and good relative strength.<p>
Question   : Buying 50 individual stocks is a little beyond my means.  Do you have any suggestions for finding a mutual fund which approximates the Cornerstone Growth strategy? <p>
JPOSOCM    : I can't comment on mutal funds because we have four in registration with the SEC.<p>
Question   : If your results are of the last 50 years, what does that say about my investing life time which only has about 25 years to go?<p>
JPOSOCM    : I think whatever your time frame, these results lead you to the best strategey for you if you only have 10 years left to go 'til retirement, you'll want to invest in a lower risk strategy, if more, you can opt for a strategy with more risk.<p>
Question   : In a highly valued market like the current one, how many stocks would have a price-to-sales ration of 1.5 like you use in Cornerstone Growth?<p>
JPOSOCM    : More than 100 stocks currently have eps gains for the last five years and PSRs below 1.5 out of the 1000s in Compustat.<p>
Question   : Do you have any comments on the Dow Dividend strategy?<p>
JPOSOCM    : I love the Dogs of the Dow. I studied that back to when the modern 30 stock Dow was born in 1928 and found that it beat the S&P 500 in every decade from the 30s to the 90s. It's also an excellent strategy for the individual investor to use since it buys only 10 stocks.<p>
Question   : Did you cover technical analysis in the book?<p>
JPOSOCM    : No, just the quanatitaive use of fundemental data, with the possible exception of price momentum.<p>
Question   : How can your average Joe use these findings?<p>
JPOSOCM    : Use them to know what to avoid and what to focus on. For example, if you've got a hankering to buy a stock with a very high PE or price-to-sale ratio, you'll take a look at the results of high PSR stocks and maybe take a second look. Likewise, you might pay more attention to the lower PE or PSR stocks since they did so much.<p>
Question   : Overall, what's the time frame one should hold a stock for? <p>
JPOSOCM    : We rebalanced these portfolios once a year.<p>
Question   : Does your book cover the pros and cons of sector investing?<p>
JPOSOCM    : No, we look only at underlying factors. I think you're much better off with specific factors instead of sectors.<p>
Question   : Is your book really a battlecry for Benjamin Graham's value investing?<p>
JPOSOCM    : Value ratios alone work very well, but we've also found some great growth strategies. Usually all the best growth strategies involve strong relative price strength. One of the best strategies buys cheap stocks (PSR<1) with the best price momentum.<p>
Question   : Do you have any strategy for someone who has no need for income, but rather wants to preserve captial with moderate growth oover a 25 year period -- with the intention of leaving it all to the kids?<p>
JPOSOCM    : Yes, I would suggest taking a look at what I call the Cornerstone Value strategy in the book. I buy market leading stocks with high dividend yields. Over the last 44 years, it has done about 4 times as well as the S&P 500 with a similar level of risk (when measured by standard deviation of return.)<p>
Question   : What do you think about the market vs. the savings of the Baby Boomers for the next 10 years?<p>
JPOSOCM    : I think that the boomers savings can only help the market over the next 10 years.<p>
Question   : My broker advises that I buy B shares to avoid paying fees if I hold for 5 years. Is this correct?<p>
JPOSOCM    : I'm not sure I'd have to see the fund.<p>
Question   : Name some of the cheap PSR stocks.<p>
JPOSOCM    : Some of the low PSR, high relative strength stocks are CompUSA, DELL, Gateway, Safeway, US AIR.<p>
Question   : How long have you been an investor in the stock market and what do you know about network marketing. Is it a good strategy?<p>
JPOSOCM    : I've been an investor on my own hook since 1979, a pro since 1988. Networking marketing I don't know about.<p>
Question   : What is your idea of a good solid investment?<p>
JPOSOCM    : If you are a long-term investor, you can't beat the stock market. Even if a bear is right around the corner. <p>
Question   : Have you discovered any market timing secrets?<p>
JPOSOCM    : The best market timing compares the market's earnings yield + dividend yield to T-bills. When they get too close, you might be in trouble.<p>
Question   : How much capital does one need to become involved in the stock market? <p>
JPOSOCM    : I would start with $5,000 if you are investing in mutal funds, more if individual stocks.<p>
Question   : I read both of your books and my question is will your Cornerstone Growth strategy work better rebalancing every 6 months instead of 12 months?<p>
JPOSOCM    : Slightly, but I think it's a wash after the transaction costs.<p>
Question   : Are there ways to use DRIPS to follow your advice or does rebalancing a portfolio every year make that difficult?<p>
JPOSOCM    : I think you could use DRIPS, provided you sell them when they no longer meet the critieria.<p>
Question   : If you rebalance the portfolio every year, have you analyzed the effect of capital gains taxes on your strategies?<p>
JPOSOCM    : I have looked at the costs, and we're trying to get it unifed for the next version of the book.<p>
OnlineHost : That Concludes this edition of "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Mr. O'Shaughnessy for being our guest this evening. Tune in next week and find how to make mega profits in microcap stocks. Our guest will be Clint Willis, author of Worth magazine's September cover story. Mr. Willis will be here live to talk about what he learned while researching and writing about these tiny stocks that offer the best returns on Wall Street. Join us on Wednesday, September 4, 8 p.m. EDT @ Keyword: WORTH. 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

