<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 08/21/96 -- Martin Gruber, Chair, Dept. of Finance, Stern School of Business at NYU</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>08/21/96 -- Martin Gruber, Chair, Dept. of Finance, Stern School of Business at NYU</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>MORE BANG FOR YOUR MUTUAL-FUND BUCK</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, August 21, Professor Martin Gruber, chairman of the Department of Finance at the Leonard N. Stern School of Business at New York University, joined Worth OnLine for a live Conference Call. 
Gruber is the author of a recent study that shows you may not be getting what you pay for from your mutual fund. During the hour-long chat, Gruber discussed the findings of his study and the relation of mutual funds to index funds. Following is a transcript of the live event, edited for clarity. The views expressed are those of Martin Gruber and do not represent the views of Worth, Worth OnLine, or Capital Publishing.<p>
WorthOnLne : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live chat show series. Every week we give readers the opportunity to chat with the leaders in money and markets. Check our site (Keyword: Worth) for a calendar of upcoming events. Our guest tonight is Martin Gruber, chairman of the Department of Finance at the Leonard N. Stern School of Business at New York University. Tonight he'll be answering questions about the findings of his study. The following is an abstract of Professor Gruber's paper "Another Puzzle: The Growth in Actively Managed Mutual Funds." <p>
"Mutual Funds represent one of the fastest growing type of financial intermediary in the American economy.  The question remains as to why mutual funds and in particular actively managed mutual funds have grown so fast when their performance on average has been inferior to that of index funds. One possible explanation of why investors buy actively managed open end funds lies in the fact that they are bought and sold at net asset value and thus management ability may not be priced.  If management ability exists and it is not included in the price of open and funds, then performance should be predictable. If performance is predictable and at least some investors are aware of this, then cash flows into and out of funds should be predictable by the very same metrics that predict performance. <p>
Finally, if predictors exist and at least some investors act on these predictors in investing in mutual funds, the return on new cash flows should be better than the average return for all investors in these funds. This paper presents empirical evidence on all of these issues and shows that investors in actively managed mutual funds may have been more rational than we have assumed."<p>
(The text of the whole article is available in the July issue of "The Journal of Finance.") <p>
Professor Gruber can begin to take questions now...<p>
To begin would you talk briefly about the general conclusions of your study of Mutual Funds?<p>
ProfGruber : One of the important conclusions is that past performance is an indicator of future performance. Funds that did well in the past tend to do well in the future. Another indicator is expense ratios. Funds with lower expense ratios tend to do better in the future. Another conclusion of the study is that actively managed mutual funds, on average, do about 60 basis points a year worse than index funds with the same objective.<p>
Vesta8     : Is this 60 basis points lower true for all types of funds?<p>
ProfGruber : No, this study is of domestic common stock funds.<p>
RedHeelr   : What do you see for International Funds, especially those for the Asia Pacific rim?<p>
ProfGruber : These funds provide an advantage to the investor because of diversification. They tend to move differently than the U.S. funds and thereby adding some investments in these funds to a U.S. portfolio can lower risk. <p>
RedHeelr   : What do you consider a lower expense ratio? <p>
ProfGruber : Let me talk about expense ratios on domestic stock funds. The average expense ratio is about 130 basis points per year. However, many funds are just out there with expense ratios of below 30 basis points per year. Anything below 130 has lower than average expense ratios.<p>
International funds and specialty funds tend to have higher expense ratios than domestic stock funds. Bond funds tend to have lower expense ratios. The expense ratio for a fund includes management fees -- that's the fees paid for professional management. These usually account for about one half of the expense ratio. The rest of the expense ratio is made up of administrative fees and may include 12b1 fees. 12b1 fees constitute advertising and marketing fees. The law allows the investor in funds to be charged directly for marketing fees, sales contests, or other advertising costs. They can give away television sets to salesmen and charge the fund holder for the expense.<p>
RedHeelr   : So if I see an ad for my fund in Worth, I'm directly helping to pay for it?<p>
ProfGruber : Well, it depends on whether or not the fund has 12b1 fees. Not all funds have them. This would be reported in the prospectus of the fund, where the maximum 12b1 fee will be stated. 12b1 fees can be as high as 75 basis points per year.<p>
RedHeelr   : What is the difference between the actively managed funds and index funds you mentioned?<p>
ProfGruber : Index funds do not employ analysts or portfolio managers. They simply duplicate an index. There are over 100 index funds offered to the public. There are funds that duplicate the S&P Index; there are funds that replicate the performance of the largest 400 stocks; there are index funds that replicate the performance of all bonds in the market; there are index funds that replicate growth stocks or value stocks. As an example, an S&P Index fund should offer almost exactly the same as the S&P Index. Because these funds don't employ analysts or portfolio managers, their expense ratios are usually very low. Index funds exist with average expense ratios below 20 basis points a year.<p>
AUTISM ASA : I appreciate your point about expenses, but there are many funds such as PBHG which have low expenses and no 12b expenses and have beat the indexes<p>
ProfGruber : One of my earliest points was that one of the indicators of good performance in picking actively managed funds that will do well is to pick funds with low expense ratios. A second indicator is to pick funds that have done well in the past.<p>
BeachBoyX8 : Many funds are new with no past.<p>
ProfGruber : It's very difficult to pick winners among funds that have no past. One of the problems is that funds that start up and don't do well tend to be merged in the funds that have done well, so that when one looks at the performance now of a fund that started a few years ago, what one would see is a record of the funds that are new and have done well. What you don't see is the record of the funds that started and did poorly. Current databases and lists of funds in business publications talk about the past performance of funds that exist today. In the past 10 years, 21 percent of the stock funds that existed 10 years ago no longer exist as stock funds. Lists of common stock funds will not contain information about these fund that did not continue.<p>
SUGAR711   : Prof, you indicated in your "promo" that the average manager could and cannot beat the S&P 500 average... why do you feel this way? my funds are all just doing fine, and I have a portfolio made up of 17 funds in 20 accounts.<p>
ProfGruber : Congratulations. What I said was that in the past, actually 30 years, as well as in the past 10 years, the average fund has not beat the S&P Index. I believe that with careful analysis using some of the factors I've already discussed, it's possible to find funds that do beat the S&P Index. The average investor over the past 30 years, has not done that. There are no doubt investors that have.<p>
RedHeelr   : Why do actively managed funds do worse than index funds with the same objective?<p>
ProfGruber : On average, they do worse because they engage in much higher transaction costs because they are trading -- that's what active management does --  and because they charge the investor much higher expense ratios so that the active manager has to have information sufficient to more than compensate for the extra  1 1/2 to 2 percent which the investor pays over and above what he would pay if he or she were to buy an index fund.<p>
BeachBoyX8 : Isn't the performance of the manager critical- i.e. Van Wagoner's new funds have been flying high.<p>
ProfGruber : The manager's performance is critical. Some managers have enough analytical ability and skill to compensate for the extra 2 percent. On average, all managers don't have enough skill to compensate for the extra 2 percent. The higher the expense ratio in a fund, the more skilled the manager must be to compensate for the investor paying such high expense ratios. Thus, the higher the expense ratios, the more advanced the investor should require in buying and selecting a fund.<p>
SUGAR711   : If one does their homework, they should be able to pick 5-star rated funds with great 3, 5, and 10 year recs.<p>
ProfGruber : In my paper, I show that if one were to select every year the 10 percent of all funds with the best performance, one would do slightly better than purchasing an index fund.<p>
SUGAR711   : Prof, I agree, but a good manager such as a Robert Stansky or a Michael Price beats the averages consistently, and all other talented managers should be able to do the same.<p>
WorthOnLne : If mangers that did well in the past, do well in the future, does that affect cash flow?<p>
SUGAR711   : 7000 funds out there,... <p>
ProfGruber : There's a direct relationship between past performance and future cash flows. The 10 percent of the funds which did best over the past year have cash flows of about 25 percent per year, while the 10 percent of the funds that did poorest have negative cash flows equal to 15 percent of capital per year.<p>
N090       : What is the best mutual fund?<p>
SUGAR711   : There is no one best mutual fund! Do your homework, and you pick the best fund for your needs and situation.....<p>
ProfGruber : N090--There IS one mutual fund that will do best next year-- I just don't know which one it is!<p>
WorthOnLne : Do you think the average individual investor has the time to do the "homework" necessary to pick high performing funds?<p>
ProfGruber : Some individual investors actually take pleasure in investigating funds to pick high performing funds. If an investor does not want to put any time and effort into selecting the funds he will buy, then index funds should be the preferred choice. History would seem to indicate that investors who are willing to look at past performance and expenses can, on average, do slightly better than index funds.<p>
Ronufer    : We read that international funds will outperform U.S. funds. When will we see this?<p>
MLTIPTON   : In starting out in mutual funds are there any funds without the minimum deposit?<p>
ProfGruber : I think there are funds with very small minimum deposits.<p>
MLTIPTON   : Who would you suggest to talk to?<p>
ProfGruber : The easiest thing to do is to go to the library, look up in the Morningstar service, or one of the other mutual fund reference books, such as Lipper, and they will list the minimum balance for all of the mutual funds. <p>
WorthOnLne : Morningstar has a site on AOL.  Keyword: morningstar.  You might fund some of the info you are looking for there.<p>
Ronufer    : What kind of bond fund belongs in a tax-deferred retirement account?<p>
ProfGruber : Ron--Certainly do not buy municipal bond funds because you can't take advantage of the tax savings. Both corporate bond funds and corporate bond funds have a place in such an account. {error}<p>
WorthOnLne : Do you recommend index funds over managed stock mutual funds? And if so, why?<p>
ProfGruber : As I've said earlier, it is possible to select a portfolio fund that outperforms index funds if one is willing to take the effort to study past performance and past expenses. If you don't want to make this effort, then I suggest index funds as the preferred vehicle. Again, let me say that I base this on the fact that for the past 30 years, and over the past 10 years, the average investor in mutual funds and the average dollar placed in mutual funds, has not done as well as index funds. <p>
WorthOnLne : What do you feel are the most important implications of your study of historical mutual fund performance?<p>
ProfGruber : The most important implication of my study is that there is persistence in mutual fund performance. That is that past performance tends to be an indicator of future performance. This persistence is clearest in the case of poor performing funds, funds that perform poorly relative to an appropriate benchmark. The persistence also exists with respect to good performance, although it's not as marked as it is with poor performers. Another important finding of the study is that actively managed mutual funds, while they have done slightly worse than index funds, they have underperformed index funds by less than the expense ratios. So that management, on average, in actively managed mutual funds has had stock selection ability, it's just been worth less than the fees they've charged the investor to get access to that ability. <p>
WorthOnLne : Then would you attribute the performance of *star* fund managers like Peter Lynch to extraordinary ability, or consistent good luck?<p>
ProfGruber : Either ability or luck!<p>
RedHeelr   : So, expense ratios, index funds and past performance. Any other findings?<p>
ProfGruber : The new money which has followed high past performance into funds has tended to earn a return about 20 basis points per year better than index funds.<p>
RedHeelr   : Here comes my ignorance--Basis Point?<p>
ProfGruber : A basis point is a hundredth of a percent, so that 100 basis points equals one percent.<p>
Thank you for your questions! <p>
WorthOnLne : A complete transcript of this event, will be posted in the Today box on our opening screen next week. Transcripts from all of Worth OnLine's live chat shows are available in the Software Library. That Concludes this edition of "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Martin Gruber for being our guest this evening.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
