	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>08/14/96 -- Samuel Stewart, founder and president of Wasatch Advisors Inc.</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, August 14, Samuel Stewart, founder and president of Wasatch Advisors Inc. joined Worth OnLine during "Conference Call," our live chat show series. Along with co-manager Karey Barker, Stewart manages the Wasatch mid-cap fund, with $180 million in assets. The fund invests in fast growing, small- to mid-sized companies with market capitalization of between $300 million and $5 billion. Stewart talked about his approach to tackling the current market and answered questions about specific industries and selecting a mutual fund. Following is a transcript of the live event, edited for clarity. The views expressed are those of Samuel Stewart and do not represent the views of Worth, Worth OnLine, or Capital Publishing.<p>
MSS1040    : What about biotech, especially CELI?<p>
WasatchAdv : Many biotechs have lots of hype.  We usually like to see earnings. <p>
Gjjjones   : Interested in a no-load mutual fund...check writing to use to buy and sell stock...any good suggestion for online trading?<p>
WasatchAdv : No direct recommendations regarding checks or online trading.<p>
Dianne4036 : When researching a stock, are there particular things you suggest looking for?<p>
WasatchAdv : Lots of ways to skin a cat, read The Money Game. We like to find small companies that will become big ones.<p>
WorthOnLne : What are your thoughts on the current market?<p>
OldHippie  : Just got a 25,000 dollar windfall...suggestions?<p>
WasatchAdv : Have to know more about your goals.<p>
OldHippie  : Want to safeguard some of it...half would be open to speculation.<p>
WasatchAdv : How long do you plan to invest, risk tolerance? Always suggest mutual funds for both diversfication and pro management, our Mid-Cap is good for speculation.<p>
LC 517     : Just got $150,000, need $10,000 in income yearly and make the rest grow? Help?<p>
WasatchAdv : Probably use conservative stock fund and use some income and some principal to meet need.<p>
LC 517     : Any way I can meet my goals without touching the principal?<p>
WasatchAdv : Likely, invest in Income fund such as Wasatch-Hoisington <p>
Ron 1 Putt : Into Eaton Vance India Fund (Heavy)--Down 30% Any Thoughts? <p>
WasatchAdv : Big political risk...but suggest you focus on long run...but forget that you are down and make fresh decision today.<p>
LC 517     : How do you feel about utilities stock?<p>
WasatchAdv : Utility stock would be ok but a bit trickier than you might think due to deregulation.<p>
Dianne4036 : Where are the stocks with the greatest profit potential?<p>
WasatchAdv : Would suggest that MOST investors use funds not stocks.  Funds with best potential are small, growth stock oriented.<p>
Dianne4036 : Why funds, not stocks? (I admit I don't have a lot of time to fuss with my portfolio.)<p>
WasatchAdv : Because competition is real tough...don't play poker with the pros.  This is a 24x7 business.<p>
LC 517     : Equity funds vs. tax free, free funds? <p>
WasatchAdv : Apples vs oranges, depends on yur needs.<p>
LC 517     : I want to double my $150,000 in five years.<p>
WasatchAdv : Money magazine recommended Wasatch fund for doubling in 5 years. This is a realistic goal for growth fund.<p>
LC 517     : What particular funds do you suggest?<p>
WasatchAdv : Our own, of course, that's where my money is.<p>
LC 517     : How do I begin investing with Wasatch as I am new to investing?<p>
WasatchAdv : Call 800-551-1700 for prospectus and investors kit.<p>
LC 517     : Are there fees involved?<p>
WasatchAdv : Our funds are all no load..no up-front charges...a management fee is deducted.<p>
JSbihli    : What size are mid-cap companies? Why would I want to invest there?<p>
WasatchAdv : From $500 million to $1 billion, companies still in process of being discovered by big companies like Merrill Lynch.<p>
Dianne4036 : The mid-cap one took a beating recently. What do you say to those investors?<p>
WasatchAdv : Good question...basically tell them our focus is long term and the MidCap is designed to have lots of volatility, big rewards require risks.<p>
JSbihli    : What are your biggest percentage companies in your fund?<p>
WasatchAdv : ESRX, MCHP, WCOM.<p>
JSbihli    : Do you think WCOM will venture with anyone? who? EDS?<p>
WasatchAdv : js: i've heard rumors about mfs, haven't heard eds<p>
Dianne4036 : What is "long term" in the fund world? And does that mean investors should time when they buy into one?<p>
WasatchAdv : To us it is 5 years. The best time to invest is 20 years ago, the next best is today.<p>
Dianne4036 : I'm 29, so what should my time frame be?<p>
WasatchAdv : dian: peter lynch used to say that he invested as though the market was going up every day because over the long run that's what it does.<p>
Dianne4036 : But everyone's screaming about the pending shakeout. It makes me want to stuff money in the mattress!<p>
WasatchAdv : Depends upon when you want the money...if for retirement, you've got 30 years.<p>
Dianne4036 : On average, how often do investors move their money from fund-to-fund in 30 years?<p>
WasatchAdv : dian: one of the reasons to go w/ a pro is to let them worry...Shouldn't be in stock market unless you are focused on long term. Better in the market than a mattress.<p>
Dianne4036 : But even as an investor in funds, I feel I must do my due diligence--making sure there's no churning..<p>
WasatchAdv : My rec: find a fund or 3 that you like and don't switch unless something drastic happens. Due diligence is good find a style that you believe in, not who has the hot hand.
JSbihli    : What is the value of your fund?<p>
WasatchAdv : Today's nav is 17.11 up .08.<p>
JSbihli    : What was your high this year?<p>
WasatchAdv : High was 20.61 on 5/15 and low 15.02 on 7/15..this is a speculative fund<p>
JLBVette   : Do you think there will be continued volatility in the market?<p>
WasatchAdv : jlb: bernard bauch (remember him?) said the market will fluctuate.  Was true then (1929)...still true today.<p>
DMKline    : What are the three main criterion that you look for in a midcap company?<p>
JLBVette   : What are your favorite stocks in your portfolios<p>
WasatchAdv : jlb: lrgest holdings are esrx, mch and wcom<p>
MWB125     : What is your opinion of T.Rowe Price mid-cap growth fund?<p>
WasatchAdv : Don't know who manager is but T Rowe is 1st class 
             organization.<p>
JLBVette   : What is your asset size?<p>
WasatchAdv : $130 million<p>
JLBVette   : Any plans to close fund?<p>
WasatchAdv : No, because the stocks it uses are bigger than aggressive (closed) and micrcap (closing).<p>
RJVVVVV    : I've got a 6 month old daughter, which of your funds should I go w/:  Micro/ Mid/Growth?<p>
WasatchAdv : Micro<p>
RJVVVVV    : Main reason why?<p>
WasatchAdv : Because the micro is our scarcest commodity..will close in a few months and also uses the smallest, rarest stocks.<p>
MAmizer    : CCEE or NMPS??<p>
WasatchAdv : ma: no opinion<p>
JLBVette   : What is your YTD return and return for month of July?<p>
WasatchAdv : Stop asking embarrassing questions... YTD: -6.45%. <p>
JLBVette   : I didn't mean to embarrass you. What makes you decide to buy a stock?<p>
MAmizer    : NMPS - worth looking into - FDA approval for bladder cancer test, highly accurate.<p>
Dianne4036 : What kind of asset allocation do you recommend for fund investors?<p>
WasatchAdv : We don't recommend allocating assets based on market conditions but based on goals.<p>
JLBVette   : Do you have any favorite sectors to buy?<p>
WasatchAdv : We look for small companies that we think can become big ones. Because we are growth oriented, we always tend to have lots of money in technology and health care.<p>
JLBVette   : Have you ever looked at KITS or PCNI?<p>
WasatchAdv : jlb: no<p>
Dianne4036 : When do you sell? Specifically, what fundamentals make you get out?<p>
WasatchAdv : Sell for two resons:  most important if we no longer believe in growth potential of company.. 2nd is if valuation becomes excessive.<p>
Ved Flyer  : What is your outlook for tech stocks for the next year?<p>
WasatchAdv : We like techs here, though there may be another down draft due to semi equipment.<p>
JLBVette   : What % of earnings growth do you like?<p>
WasatchAdv : Minimum 15 percent but most important is sustainability of growth rather than rate.<p>
Dianne4036 : What are the three most recent stocks you've decided to limit your exposure to?<p>
WasatchAdv : dian: one is heilig meyers due to disappointing sales, another pham<p>
JLBVette   : Do you like to see a lot of insider ownership?<p>
WasatchAdv : Love to see insider owning.<p>
JLBVette   : I like to buy low debt companies, what about you?<p>
WasatchAdv : Lots of ours have low debt, but we focus more on business prospects.<p>
Dianne4036 : pham?<p>
WasatchAdv : Phamis Health care info systems, large contracts slipping a bit.<p>
Dianne4036 : I see. What was your exposure and how big of a bite did those take from the fund's overall performance?<p>
WasatchAdv : pham was 5% and fell nearly in half before we sold, costing us 2.5%.<p>
JLBVette   : Was you fund positive before July?<p>
WasatchAdv : Slightly positive.<p>
BradT45527 : Could you comment a little on Heilig Meyers?<p>
JLBVette   : How old is your fund?<p>
WasatchAdv : 1992<p>
WasatchAdv : We like hmy due to its focus on smaller towns..kind of a mini Walmart.<p>
JLBVette   : Do you buy foreign stocks?<p>
WasatchAdv : A few.<p>
JLBVette   : What has been one of your most recent buys & what sparked your interest?<p>
WasatchAdv : Added to our mchp position<p>
JLBVette   : How many stocks in the fund<p>
WasatchAdv : 33<p>
JLBVette   : You take big bets on a few stocks then.<p>
WasatchAdv : Yes, we don't want portfolio to get stale..you pay us to be on top of our companies. Like mchp due to idea of embedded computers, in cars, in tv clickers, etc mchp is well-managed and was right on top of recent weakness before most anyone else.<p>
JLBVette   : What is your expense ratio, turnover ratio?<p>
WasatchAdv : 1.75%, turnover lower than you might think at 30%<p>
JLBVette   : 30% turnover, so you do hold onto your stocks for a while then.<p>
WasatchAdv : Yes, we hold for a long time while companies get big.<p>
Plouie     : Do you have an opinion on the semiconductor equipment makers?<p>
WasatchAdv : They are tempting here but it might be a bit early.<p>
Plouie     : I would tend to agree.<p>
OAbdulla   : What has been the return of DJIA since the Crash of 1987?<p>
WasatchAdv : I think Dow got down to 1700 so it's more than a triple off low.<p>
OAbdulla   : I don't understand your answer of more than a triple off low?<p>
WasatchAdv : 1700 to 5600<p>
OAbdulla   : Give me a percentage.<p>
WasatchAdv : 200%+<p>
OAbdulla   : Is that good according to history?<p>
WasatchAdv : Awesome..but don't usually get in at bottom or sell at top<p>
PJSDOG     : is there anyway to tell what a mutual fund is buying or selling on say a monthly basis, rather than waiting for a annual report.<p>
WasatchAdv : Hard to do consistently..we don't give out info and most don't.<p>
JLBVette   : Do you think your negative return will scare off potential investors, since overall market is positive.<p>
Sarjs4     : Sam, where do you see this market in October of 1996?<p>
WasatchAdv : Not much different from today, but we don't really focus on stock marke calls. Economy is healthy, inflation in check. So stocks should do ok. <p>
Sarjs4     : Do you like financial stocks, such as savings and loans, aka thrifts?<p>
WasatchAdv : We like some but you've got to be careful.<p>
Plouie     : Have you ever had an instance of company management misleading you? And what types of warnings signs may signal caution?<p>
WasatchAdv : More often unintentionally than intentionally. Best take on management is experience plus gut feeling.<p>
Sarjs4     : What do you think about thrifts in the California area? Do you hold any in your funds?<p>
WasatchAdv : We own a small loan business cfac based on la..like a thrift.<p>
Sarjs4     : You had a very impressive return last year. even with the market's current volatility, do you think you can duplicate it?<p>
WasatchAdv : sa: don't think we can duplicate 95 consistently..better to focus on long run goal of about 15 percent.<p>
RMan1604   : I put money into your fund in March.  Tell me it was just bad timing.<p>
WasatchAdv : I put money in, too..it was unfortunate...stick with it.<p>
KGlaz21458 : Which of your funds do you recommend most at the present time?<p>
WasatchAdv : Micro because it is closing soon.<p>
WasatchAdv : Thanks to all! Wife and kids await.<p>
WorthOnLne : The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Sam Stewart for being our guest this evening. Tune in next week and find out how to GET MORE MUTUAL-FUND BANG FOR YOUR BUCK. Are you getting what you pay for from your mutual fund? Probably not, according to a recent study by Martin Gruber, chairman of the finance department at New York University's Stern School of Business. Come chat with a mutual fuind expert on Wendesday, August 21, 8 P.M., EDT keyword: WORTH. Thanks for joining us. Goodnight.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

