<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 08/01/96 -- Charlie Silk</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>08/01/96 -- Charlie Silk</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>HOW TO PICK A WINNER ON WALL STREET</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On August 1, Charlie Silk, the man Peter Lynch called the "world's greatest amateur investor,"joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call." Faced with the age-old question "How do you find a good stock?," Silk set about trying to find good stocks among small companies. His search eventually led to Cook Data Services, in which he bought $10,000 worth of stock for $3 a share. Now known as Blockbuster Entertainment, which was selling at $450 a share when Lynch wrote his article in April 1994, Silk's $10,000 investment made him a millionaire. What follows is a transcript of the event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed here are those of Charlie Silk and do not reflect the opinions of Worth OnLine.<p>
OnlineHost : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live chat show series. Check our site (Keyword: Worth) for a calendar of upcoming events. Our guest tonight is Charlie Silk, the man Peter Lynch called the "world's greatest amateur investor." Silk will share some of his investing secrets and talk about what, when, and how to buy, when and why to sell, and all things in between.<p>
First we will hear a few comments from Mr. Silk.<p>
WorthSilk  : Fallen angels within the NASDAQ national market system can be a very intriguing arena to explore for interesting investment candidates. These downtrodden issues have the potential to become very attractive valuation investments. With further research and analysis, you may discover a gem which could again turn into a growth/momentum stock that could prove to be handsomely rewarding. <p>
The name of the game is knowledge. The more legitimate information you obtain and absorb, the better your chances are of realizing significant appreciation of your capital. Conversely, if you don't do your homework, the investment you make may be harmful to your wealth. <p>
My past studies have shown that the huge number of Initial Public Offerings (IPOs) and secondaries that have been underwritten since 1991 provide a vast universe of neglected stocks to explore. Since these stocks are under-owned by institutions, there is no incentive for Wall Street analysts to follow or report on them. Since I am a private amateur investor who is neither a registered rep or a registered investment adviser, it would be inappropriate for me to answer requests about specific stocks. Nor do I wish to discuss those securities in which I currently hold a position. <p>
What I hope to accomplish is to present to you my methodology in finding these pearls that are hidden in the vast NASDAQ universe of more than 5,000 stocks. In addition, I'd like to share with you my thoughts on where the market may be headed in this very volatile environment.<p>
Question   : How would you define a "fallen angel?"<p>
WorthSilk  : My definition of a fallen angel is a stock that is making a new low in price and has fallen at least 50 percent below its past 52 week high.<p>
This is my arbitrary technical measure which eliminates those stocks that don't have the volatility I'm looking for. Generally, they appear in abundance when there is a sharp correction in the market or during a bear market. For instance, from April 10 1996 to June 5 1996, I found only 70 individual stocks that meet this criteria. Only 2 were worthy of further investigation. The number is growing due to the severe selloff in the NASDAQ market.<p>
Question   : How do you screen stocks out of the universe for further investigation?  What criteria?<p>
WorthSilk  : I've developed a very quick and easy method to determine if I want to pursue a further detailed analysis of the stock. My parameters: <p>
1--what is the cash per share of the stock? Does the cash per share equal at least 40 percent of the stock price?<p>
2--If the total of the current liabilities and long term debt exceeds the total current assets, I immediately reject the stock from further consideration.<p>
3--After calculating the net current assets per share, a comparison of this value is made to the stock price. If the net current assets per share is approx. twice the share price, it may be worthy of further research<p>
4--Is the book to value per share at least 3 times the share price? If it meets a combination of the above factors, I call the stockholder relations spokesperson of the company and request all available published information on the corporation to be sent to me.<p>
Question   : When researching a stock, are there particular things you suggest looking for?<p>
WorthSilk  : Value investors buy stocks when prices are beaten down relative to earnings and other fundamentals. A low price doesn't mean that it is cheap. If the corporation has assets that aren't being dissipated, then the real issue is whether the knockdown price has been overdone. Cash rich companies can make great investments. They offer investors hard assets that hold up the value of the stock. The company's future is more important than its past.<p>
Don't get dazzled by a product. Don't get fooled by a fad. Don't let emotions get in the way. Study all the information you can get. Don't pay too much for the stock. The company's future is more important than its past.<p>
Question : Mr. Silk, where are the stocks with the greatest profit potential?<p>
WorthSilk  : My favorite market to find those stocks with the greatest upside potential is the NASDAQ market system. Very few analysts follow companies in this universe, and therein lie the undiscovered gems. A '92 study showed that 76 percent of NYSE companies are followed by more than 2 analysts. Only 38 percent of NASDAQ companies meet the same situation. The percentage of analysts following must have dropped to significantly lower numbers due to the huge increase in IPOs underwritten since 1992.<p>
Question   : When picking stocks, what should I be concerned with? <p>
WorthSilk  : There are many more people who buy and sell stocks based on simplistic thinking than those who devote their time to investigate the underlying facts. A tip could be hazardous to your wealth! You may be at the bottom of the information food chain. Learning how to do basic research just takes time. You can't read about it. You just have to do your homework. Be aware of the fundamentals behind the financial statements. Evaluate them as you would if you were buying a business. And finally, try to get the most assets and earnings power for your dollar.<p>
Question   : What can you tell me about when to sell stocks? <p>
WorthSilk  : Often people sell their winners and keep their losers. People don't want to admit they made a mistake. A good way to get rid of potential losers is to determine if the reason you bought it is no longer valid. If you get a negative earnings surprise, generally other disappointments may occur. Sell it as best you can. Few investors have the emotional psyche to hang on to the big one in order to get the huge payoff. It takes a strong mind and a willingness to go against the crowd. If you do your research and find the fundamentals are solid and improving, stay with the stock, especially if it is a sound company. If you have a significant gain and the market is moving up strongly, think of selling a portion into the rise. If the stock has made a strong upward move and the trading becomes very heavy with little further advance, sell a good portion of your stock, you may find that it could pull back 25 to 30 percent.<p>
Question   : What are your comments about the "current market situation?"<p>
WorthSilk  : Although the direction of interest rates has the most critical effect on the direction of the market, I feel there is a more important force at work at this time. You must be cognizant of how mutual stock funds dominate the stock market. <p>
Eighty percent of trading on the markets is now undertaken by institutions. An unprecedented amount of funds that have flowed into stock mutual funds since Nov. 95--about $170 billion in the last eight months. For the most recent period, Feb. to May 96, a very high percentage of the money went into aggressive growth funds--from 30 percent to more than 50 percent in some months. <p>
Aggressive growth funds mainly concentrate on momentum stocks. With this approach, most of their stocks are purchased when trading volume in a stock accelerates dramatically and with ever increasing price levels. The only other consideration is the supposed fast earnings growth of the company with little regard to other fundamental values.<p>
Question   : What is your feeling on dividend reinvestment plans?<p>
WorthSilk  : They are immaterial because very few companies on the NASDAQ pay dividends.<p>
Question   : Mr. Silk, please tell us your views on technology stocks.<p>
WorthSilk  : Technology represents 10 percent of the U.S.'s gross domestic product (GDP) and in less than 10 years it could double. High tech is the country's future. And it is going to keep growing. <p>
Computer networks--growth of 30 percent to 50 percent
PCs globally--growth of 15 percent to 20 percent
Global cellular phones--growth of 40 percent<p>
Anybody who is a growth-oriented investor has to consider high-tech stocks. The tech stock sector is one in which most investors do not understand what they own. They buy at too expensive prices and sell too cheap. They often panic in a market reversal. The momentum players have driven up many smaller tech stocks. They dive into the same stocks because they have the same stock picking criteria. When the high tech stocks start to become hot, they attract traders and the public. If these stocks come up short on fundamentals, especially earning disappointment or revenue shortfall, they are aggressively sold. There is no way that they all can get out on the same day. Prices melt very fast, especially on the NASDAQ market. At the time of market declines, there is no liquidity. Market makers will not absorb much stock since they don't have large pools of capital. These market makers are in the moving business--not in the storage business.<p>
Question   : Charlie...Is your method applicable to foreign stocks? If so, what country do see opportunities today? <p>
WorthSilk  : Israeli stocks on NASDAQ--there are 70--and the reporting criteria is similar to the U.S. and very easy to understand. Find the public relations firm that represents these companies in the U.S.<p>
Question   : Any other negatives on the horizon as far as you can see?<p>
WorthSilk  : From now until the end of the year, we are coming up the tax loss selling season. For most mutual funds, their tax reporting year ends Oct. 31. At that time the funds are obligated to pay out 95 percent of their net realized gains to stockholders. If the fund does not sell their unrealized losses, they would need to pay out more cash than would be prudent. When the losses are realized, the pressures will be put on those stocks that have declined significantly. The flood of sales would then overwhelm the market makers. Bids will melt for those fallen angels, depressing them even more.<p>
Question   : How about shorting small cap stocks? Is that part of your methodology?<p>
WorthSilk  : It is very difficult to borrow small cap stocks. If you can, you could be subject to a short squeeze if the stock runs up and delivery is demanded. You could lose your shirt, pants, and house. <p>
Question   : What would happen if there is a strong outflow from stock mutual funds?<p>
WorthSilk  : Since June 5 to July 17, a little more than 5 weeks, the NASDAQ composite index has fallen over 19 percent from top to trough.<p>
WorthSilk  : A bear market is considered to be a 20 percent or more drop from the high. The average cash reserves of the stock funds has fallen from a high of 9.2 percent in '92 to a 6.8 percent average in 1995. The absolute cash reserves are higher now because of the huge growth in stock mutual fund assets. When an aggressive growth fund has to redeem requests for withdrawals, the cash reserves may be inadequate to meet redemptions. At the same time, infusions of new net incoming money will stop. In order to meet redemptions, the fund has to liquidate more of their positions of the portfolio. This will prove to be a double whammy. The value of the fund's momentum stocks will be shrinking in value also.<p>
Question   : How do you create wealth in the stock market?<p>
WorthSilk  : The only way you can do it without starting with large funds is to compound your stock winners and avoid losers.<p>
At 50 percent after 5 parlays--$68,000
At 100 percent after 5 parlays--$320,000
At 200 percent after 5 parlays, it will turn into $2.4 million.<p>
Find value-oriented stocks selling for between $3 to $10 which are basically NASDAQ issues and which have become fallen angels. Eliminate from consideration those stocks which had serious revenue declines and/or very significant losses that would prevent a turnaround. Do due diligence in order to establish a buying entry point. If your entry point turned out to be too high, additional purchases at lower prices could be warranted. A sign of bottoming out could be indicated by huge volumes being traded with very little additional price erosion. This could be a classic case of accumulation. <p>
The best time to find these candidates is when there is a sharp market correction or while we are in a bear market environment. <p>
Question   : What are the danger signals at a top?<p>
Price to earnings ratio is high. The dividend yield is low--anything below a 2.8 yield is a warning. Rising interest rates caused by Fed tightening of credit. Unwinding of a speculative frenzy, especially when small investors jumped in with both feet. Sheer numbers of IPOs, while there are hints of a downturn in quality.<p>
It all signals that investors are being satiated with the abundance of IPOs when 50 percent of stocks fall below their 200 day moving average.<p>
Question   : What do you consider a low P/E ?<p>
WorthSilk  : I consider a low P/E to be under 10.<p>
Question    : Mr. Silk,  if P/E is the key indicator, how does one get the overall P/E of the market if there is such a thing?<p>
WorthSilk  : It's a toughie. Generally you can just look at the P/Es on the broad market. There is no one calculation that I know of.<p>
WorthSilk  : Reversal of cash inflows into stock mutual funds combined with cash levels at a very low percentage to total assets. Margin debt at very high levels. A top is near when volume behavior patterns such as: Volume continues strong but prices don't advance significantly; feverish trading in small stocks rising along with heavy volume; if volume lessens, it can be a problem--fewer buyers to help drive up prices; volume on down days are greater than volume on up days; much lower volume when stocks are making a new peak--a warning the demand for stock is weakening<p>
Question    : Is it wise to invest in the Japanese or foreign markets now?<p>
WorthSilk  : If you can read Japanese and understand their  accounting, maybe.<p>
Question     : What signs to look for that a correction is coming or a bear market is ending?<p>
WorthSilk  : Do your research and arithmetic. Look for good strong companies with strong balance sheets, an attractive P/E ratio, and significant market position for their products. Generally a bear market bottoms after a severe selloff on heavy volume. If investors are downbeat, it suggests that they have complete most of their selling and they won't inflict more damage. The bear market typically ends in the middle of a recession and when doom and gloom abounds. It is best to buy stocks when they are unpopular. The gutsiest investors, after a decline, play the small stocks for a rebound.<p>
Question     : What's your favorite sector right now?<p>
WorthSilk  : My favorite sector is beaten-down high-tech stocks with good cash positions.<p>
Question  : How can one get advice from you on a regular or irregular basis?<p>
WorthOnLne : You can send request for communication with Mr. Silk to me, WorthOnLne, and we'll forward it.<p>
WorthSilk  : I'm often asked about IPOs. As an individual investor, you generally can't obtain a portion of a new issue. Most of the offering stock is given to institutions which are predominantly pension or stock mutual funds. Investment bankers are trying to get the highest possible price for their corporate clients. Salespeople and traders at brokerage houses try to reward their institutional and large investors for past business. If it is truly a good deal, you won't get a piece of the action. If you are not a large customer of a brokerage house, and you are offered a piece of an IPO, it is probably that no one else wants it.<p>
Question  : Today AMAT traded mega shares and no change in price...is this what you call accumulation?<p>
WorthSilk  : If it is at its low price, it could be a sign of accumulation. But if it is it mid-point or high price, it could be distribution. <p>
Question  : Not to appear totally dumb, but distribution from whom to whom? Thanks<p>
WorthSilk  : You don't know who the buyers and sellers are.<p>
Question    : Do you feel financial consultants are helpful or is it better to invest on your own?<p>
WorthSilk  : You should really read as much as possible and get an awareness before you even consult with a financial advisor. You may end you knowing more than what he or she does!<p>
Question : What are the benefits of exploring the IPO after market?<p>
WorthSilk  : Since Jan. 1991 until the present, there have been about 3,000 IPOs. IPO stocks are not very liquid, and when the characteristics of the market changes, the exit door is going to be very crowded. A lot of the short term performance is psychology drive and hence it can lead to dramatic downside disasters. Sometimes it is best to wait a year or more before reexamining whether to buy or not to buy a once hot IPO. You must choose a fallen IPO very carefully. It may have stumbled for a very good reason. With careful research you may be able to find some whose decline is totally unjustified. You may find, with good analysis, an undiscovered gem.<p>
Question : Why do you put so much emphasis on the cash that a company has in the till?<p>
WorthSilk  : Cash is always king. Cash is never trash. Ample cash gives a company many options:<p>
1: They can repurchase outstanding by buying it on the open market or making deals with large holders
2: They can purchase technology or other assets that will complement or enhance their product lines.
3: They can receive an interest income stream 
4: They can buy another company--a danger enters here if it's in a non-related business.
5: They have no hard nose banker looking over their shoulder demanding repayments
6: They will never go bankrupt if they use their cash wisely.
7: The company may be an attractive acquisition candidate itself.<p>
It is important to measure the cash status each quarter. If the amount of cash is moving downward dramatically, and there is no reason forthcoming, ignore the stock from consideration, or if you own it, sell.<p>
Question   : Other than mutual funds, are stocks the answer to higher than 5.25 interest rates?<p>
WorthSilk  : This is a dangerous and volatile time. You had better be safe, not sorry. Keep your powder dry, and be ready to pick up good bargains in the stock market down the line when you will get better capital appreciation. Short-term bills or bonds are a safe haven now.<p>
WorthOnLne : This concludes this edition of "Conference Call,"  Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Charlie Silk for being our guest. Thank you all for the great questions!
					</font>
