	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/07/10 -- Don Phillips, President of Morningstar, Inc.</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>FINDING THE NEXT FIVE-STAR FUNDS</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On July 10, Don Phillips, president of Morningstar Inc., joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call." Phillips joined Morningstar in 1986 as the company's first analyst. In the February 1995 issue of Worth, he was named one of the world's 50 most influential market movers. What follows is a transcript of the event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed here are those of Don Phillips and do not reflect the opinions of Worth OnLine.<p>
OnlineHost : Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's new live chat show series. Every week we give readers the opportunity to chat with the leaders in money and markets. Check our site (Keyword: Worth) for a calendar of upcoming events. Our guest tonight is Don Phillips,  Tonight, Phillips will talk about mutual fund trends and performance records.<p>
Question   : What do you think of the Voyager Agressive Growth mutual funds family ?<p>
DonPMstar  : Hard call for the long term. Voyager has looked good in a very favorable market, but so too have a lot of funds.<p>
Question   : What are growth prospects for Health Science Funds? (TRP)<p>
DonPMstar  : The managers we talk with still love the demographics. Invesco runs a closed-end health fund trading a steep discount that's worth looking at.<p>
Question   : Please give details on how you plan to handle the new one-year stars.<p>
DonPMstar  : We plan on having the NASD realize they shouldn't ask us to calculate one-year star ratings.<p>
Question   : Why doesn't Morningstar rate Variable Annuities?<p>
DonPMstar  : We do rate VAs. Ask your library to subscribe to our service.<p>
Question   : How certain is the performance of an index fund will behave like the actual index?<p>
DonPMstar  : Indexing isn't rocket science. The funds from bigger complexes are fairly likely to look like the index minus the expense ratio.<p>
Question    : Hi I'm Bill Bales of Quote.Com,Inc.--are there funds that invest solely in internet stocks? Great job with Mstar--do you plan on going public?<p>
DonPMstar  : There are a few new funds planning on focusing just on the internet. I'm not so sure about the investment savvy of these outfits, but they are eager. I'd consider a more diversified tech play -- preferrably a closed-end tech fund at a discount like New Age Media.<p>
Question   : Hi Don -- Which fund family do you see as having the best track record in a growth-oriented fund for the long haul?<p>
DonPMstar  : A great choice would be Vanguard US Growth. Low expenses, big growth names, good mangement.<p>
Question   : What are your thoughts on the format of the recent PBHG Limited offering, especially the lack of information provided to shareholders in fund marketplaces?<p>
DonPMstar  : People were understandably upset. I don't think the fund industry has handled openings or closings of popular funds well. In PBHG's defense, the demand was unprecedented.<p>
Question   : What are your thoughts on the Boomers' effect on long term market growth?<p>
DonPMstar  : The demographics will clearly put upward pressure on the market. As boomers impose their preference for fund investing on the next generation through 401k plans, that will add more fuel to the fire. It doesn't mean we won't have big bear markets anymore, however.<p>
Question   : What are the 5 hottest mutual funds for the near term?<p>
DonPMstar  : If you mean in sales, look at Van Waggoner. A trend in motion stays in motion. It's the speculative stuff leading the pack. That's a very real cause for concern.<p>
Question   : Do you have a Web site or is one planned soon?<p>
DonPMstar  : For now, we're on AOL and Galt, and a few other sites.<p>
Question   : How does MStar keep track of new funds that are introduced?<p>
DonPMstar  : The funds send tons of advance notice lobbying to get included in our databases.<p>
Question   : How does Morningstar Principia (OnDisc) plan on competing with Value Line's Fund Analyzer on a price basis?  Will it be easy to sell a product that is slated to be 3 times more expensive?<p>
DonPMstar  : Principia does a lot more than their product. Look at our new Ascent product. It's more directly comparable and costs much less.<p>
Question   : What do you think the future is on Fidelity Magellan considering its bond assets and new manager?<p>
DonPMstar  : It'll be a more conventional stock fund. I think it has an outstanding chance of being in the top third of stock funds for the next decade, but little chance of being in the top 10 percent.<p>
Question   : When should I sell a fund ?<p>
DonPMstar  : When your needs or its core features change.<p>
Question   : You have mentioned 2 closed funds.  Do you like this kind?<p>
DonPMstar  : I love closed-end funds. Neglect implies opportunity. Interestingly, when I visit with fund managers I often see them using our closed-end publication for their own investing.<p>
Question   : Do you feel Garret Von Waggoner can keep up with all the new money being thrown his way?<p>
DonPMstar  : I think Garret will get sidetracked at some point by the asset growth. I also think he'll lose a lot of money in a bear market. I'd still like his fund in my portfolio.<p>
Question   : Where will growth be next year?  Large, small, mid cap?<p>
DonPMstar  : Small is still so hot, it may continue. As a contrarian, however, I favor yield oriented investments now. Have you seen some of the discounts on closed-end government bond funds? You can get a dollar's worth of yield for 90 cents. We spent so much of the '80s telling people not to look just at yield. Now we're telling them to remember it!<p>
Question   : How should a fund be closed?<p>
DonPMstar  : Close a fund quickly and neatly, but leave it open to current holders. PBHG in retrospect, should have held a lottery among current shareholders, perhaps.<p>
Question   : What do you think about the proposed SEC graphic disclosure rules in the Journal today -- seems like companies would be publishing information that would be a lot like what you publish.<p>
DonPMstar  :  More information is good. The problem is if there is one set of rules, rather than a free market system with lots of different systems, funds will jigger their procedures to fit the rules, which may not be in shareholder's best long-term interest.<p>
Question   : Suggestions on good reading material for a beginning investor interested in high risk?<p>
DonPMstar  : Phil Fisher's Common Stocks, Uncommon Profits. Also read Lowenstein's book on Buffett -- it's great.<p>
Question   : Tell 2 Best Aggressive mutual funds for one year investment.<p>
DonPMstar  : There is no such thing as a one-year investment. There are only one-year bets.<p>
Question   : What is your definition of the Sharpe ratio and how much emphasis do you place on it?<p>
DonPMstar  : The Sharpe ratio, like our stars, is a backward looking risk-reward ratio. It's a good starting place for fund analysis. Just don't stop there. Ask if the people, practices, and market conditions are similar enough that you can project past performance forward with any confidence.<p>
Question   : Why did you drop your monthly publication on the Morningstar 500?<p>
DonPMstar  : We still publish Morningstar Investor each month. The 500 was and is an annual complement to that newsletter.<p>
Question   : Why would someone buy into a bond fund now with the potential of interest rate increase on the horizon and therefore risk of principal? <p>
DonPMstar  : Is there ever a time with no risk of interest rate rises? Making a puchase decision based on one's view of macroeconomics can be hazardous to your wealth.<p>
Question   : Do you think 20th Century Ultra will continue to do well?<p>
DonPMstar  :  Ultra is a different fund than it was in the '80s. It now owns much larger stocks. It's still a fine fund, but it won't be as explosive--on either the upside or downside--as it was in '88 or '84.<p>
Question   : Do you find that a lot of funds within a fund family are redundant?  They seem to start a new fund just to attract more money.<p>
DonPMstar  : It'a a profit game!!! Yes... I think five shadings of the same style can be redundant.<p>
Question   : What is the ideal size for an aggressive growth fund before performance is affected?<p>
DonPMstar  : Depends on how the fund is aggressive. If it means buying small stocks, $500 million seems a viable cap for many fund managers. If it's trading big stocks quickly, you can probably go higher. It's also a function of the research staff.<p>
Question   : How can share holders let their "voice" be heard in regard to high expense ratios, procedures, etc??<p>
DonPMstar  : We as shareholders need to vote with our dollars. Expenses have risen because we haven't penalized high cost funds enough. I'd suggest not buying any fund with more than a certain expense ratio. For me the cap is 1.50% and going lower. There are plenty of fine funds left.<p>
Question   : How can I check on a fund manager's background, or history?<p>
DonPMstar  : We publish bios on managers in our reviews. You can also get some info in a prospectus or in public interviews.<p>
Question   : What do you think will happen to Mike Price's funds following the sale?  If Price leaves in a few years, which other fund managers would you say most closely mirror his style?<p>
DonPMstar  : Price learned from Heine, so the style can be taught. The question is how big will the funds get with Franklin's marketing muscle behind them. They've already lost some of the turnaround flavor as they've grown. I'd suspect they'll be very good, but more conventional value funds in the future.<p>
Question   : What do you think of Schwab funds in general?<p>
DonPMstar  : Schwab funds are basically commodity funds--indexes and straight forward bond funds. Thay are competently managed.<p>
Question   : What's the outlook for technology funds?<p>
DonPMstar  : The tech managers--who have to be in tech--still put on a good face. Diversified fund managers who can go anywhere--are paring back their tech exposure.<p>
Question   : What do you think is the best worldwide or foreign fund to purchase now?<p>
DonPMstar  : Tweedy Browne Global Value.<p>
Question   : How much money do you think you need to have for individual stocks to be a benifit over a fund?  Many funds have charges that can amount to over 25% in a 5 year period -- not to mention the commissions they have to pay on 50 --100% portfolio turnover?<p>
DonPMstar  : The commission a fund pays works out to far less than you'd pay. A typical stock fund incurs about 30 basis points a year in commissions. Thus, part of the answer comes down to how often you trade.<p>
Question   : Thoughts on selling a fund when the manager leaves, ie: Fidelity Growth's Bob Stansky being replaced by L. Greenberg??<p>
DonPMstar  : I'd definitely encourage you to hold stocks as well as funds. Greenberg, fortunately, is a known commodity. He's done great at Emerging Growth. I see no reason to sell at this point.<p>
Question   : Is this a good time to be looking at global funds?<p>
DonPMstar  : Yes. You've probably seen your domestic exposure swell with the recent run-up. I'd be looking abroad now to diversify.<p>
Question   : Bottom line - where can you put 5 to 10 thousand and double your money in 5 years ???<p>
DonPMstar  : Las Vegas.<p>
Question   : Don do you feel that people should be relying on the Morningstar ratings to purchase a mutual fund only?<p>
DonPMstar  : Of course not. The ratings are a computer screen. They have utility, but they aren't gospel. They also aren't the devil as our competitors will tell you<p>
Question   : Does your star rating indicate past performance or future?<p>
DonPMstar  : The ratings are a grade on past performance.<p>
Question   : Are there any funds that focus exclusively on so-called "penny stocks"?  If so, how have they performed generally?<p>
DonPMstar  : There was one. It was a dog.<p>
Question   : What are some of new products that M* is planning to offer?<p>
DonPMstar  : We're expanding our Principia line. We have a great new module called advanced analytics that lets you see how a fund's investment style has changed over time.<p>
Question   : Which funds are the future 5 stars?<p>
DonPMstar  : I'd look for smaller funds run by proven managers. Janus has a slew of them, as does T.Rowe Price and Fidelity.<p>
Question   : Do you think that this is the end of the bull market?<p>
DonPMstar  : There certainly are signs that the bull market is long in the tooth. My favorite was a manager who called me recently livid over the fact that our analyst pointed out that a P/E ratio of 50 on his fund might mean high risk going forward! <p>
Question   : How does the load charge of a fund affect your ratings? <p>
DonPMstar  : We deduct the maximun sales charge from our ratings.<p>
Question   : What percentage of funds actually beat the market averages?<p>
DonPMstar  : It depends on if the market is rising or falling and              if small or large stocks are leading.<p>
Question   : Any new funds "on the horizion" worth considering?<p>
DonPMstar  : Funds tend to better the market when small or international do better than large domestic stocks. There's such a cottage industry around hot new funds. I'd spend my time looking for underappreciated older ones. Some are closed-end funds. Others are value funds left behind the sizzling growth funds of late.<p>
Question   : Will MStar manage money by investing in their 5 star fund portfolios?<p>
DonPMstar  : I don't think you can be an objective observer of the money management industry if you are also a participant in it.<p>
Question   : Don , how do you feel about people who chase after the 5 star fund constantly moving several times a year?  Please comment.<p>
DonPMstar  : It's a dumb thing to do. Some people will always look for shortcuts. They bring up the rear.<p>
Question   : What is the typical backgroud of the folks that write the brief commentaries in your reports?<p>
DonPMstar  : Our analysts are generally history or literature majors with advanced degrees from top schools. They are proven analytical thinkers. Some however are lawyers and MBAs. We hire the person, not the degree.<p>
Question   : Do you think the average 401k/IRA investor really understands the funds they have chosen?<p>
DonPMstar  : No. But at least they are investing which gives them the chance to learn.<p>
Question   : What is your opinion of a fund lead by a "team" approach, where several portfolio managers specialize in sectors, versus one central fund manager in the top position?<p>
DonPMstar  :I prefer a sigle manager, but there are some great organizations, most notably the American Funds Group, that work successfully in a team structure. There is no one right way to run money.<p>
Question   : With the large amounts of money moving into mutual funds many of the best performing...ie aggressive funds, may very well close so as not to have any positions so large as to effect a stocks price, do you see the number of funds continuing to expand?<p>
DonPMstar  : We will have more funds. I'd take the sign of many people chasing these small, aggressive funds as a sign of excess and not chase them. <p>
WorthOnLne : Mr. Phillips, many of our readers want to know: Which are five star funds of tomorrow?<p>
DonPMstar  : Don't focus on guessing tomorrow's hot funds. Investing is a means to an end, not an end in itself. Focus on meeting your goals, and you'll have a five-star portfolio.<p>
OnlineHost : That Concludes this edition of "Conference Call,"  Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. Thank you for joining Worth OnLine and Don Phillips for this evening's chat. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Don Phillips for being our guest this evening.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
