	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>06/26/96 -- Greg Dorsey, Editor of Dollarwise Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On June 26, Greg Dorsey joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call." Dorsey, editor of the Web-based service DollarWise Investing, specializes in underfollowed, undervalued stocks that sell for less than $25 a share. The seven stocks Dorsey recommended buying and selling during DollarWise's first few months rose an average of 42.8 percent, with an average holding period of less than two months. Prior to DollarWise, Greg worked with several financial newsletters that focused on low-priced small stocks and mutual funds. <p>
What follows is a transcript of the event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed here are those of Greg Dorsey and do not reflect the opinions of Worth OnLine.<p>
WorthEdit3 :  Welcome to Worth OnLine's chat series, "Conference Call." Tonight's guest is Greg Dorsey, editor of the Web-based service DollarWise Investing. During tonight's "Conference Call" Dorsey will talk about the current outlook for small stocks and how to analyze them. Again, welcome to Worth OnLine's "Conference Call" series. I'd like to invite Greg to begin to answer questions now. Enjoy the chat.<p>
Lewis1000  : What a day in the markets! Is this the beginning of the end? Might as well cut right to the heart of it.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Hardly Lewis. Just a much needed correction which should end soon.<p>
Lewis1000  : So you're a bull. Okay. Now we know.<p>
GREGDORSEY : It's not so much I'm a bull, Lewis. Look for a rally to the old highs and a deeper correction later this year.<p>
Lewis1000  : Why do you say that?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Lewis, the threat of rising short-term interest rates due to an accelerating economy should send stocks--which are expensive here--south.<p>
SHARON DE  : Greg, do you specialize in any particular area?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Well Sharon, small stocks are my passion, especially ones priced less than $25.<p>
MACBLAST   : Mr. Dorsey, do you have advice for new people getting into the market?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Mac, start by dollar cost averaging--buying equal dollar amounts each month--into funds.<p>
SHARON DE  : BW likes Woodside Petroleum out of Australia at $5+. Do you know it?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Sharon, sorry don't know it. But I like oil drillers here: Nabors, Schlumberger, Ensco.<p>
Dianne4036 : Techs took a beating today. What are your thoughts on the future?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Tech stocks are a little oversold Diane, but I'm not convinced they're at a bottom. I would wait for further signs that demand is picking up.<p>
Teebu      : Mr. Dorsey, what do you know about the Brandywine fund? Is it looking good? Feeling good?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Teebu, Foster Freiss is a great stock picker. You'll do well with the fund.<p>
MauryC7092 : What are some of the small stocks you like and why?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Thanks for asking Maury. Oil stocks, they're very cheap -- Nabors, Schlumberger, Ensco. Select biotech -- e.g. Vertex Pharm, Immune Response; certain software companies -- Manugistics, MDL Information Systems.<p>
SHARON DE  : Do you think America Online (AMER) will be joining your $25 & under category soon?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Sharon, I wouldn't buy AMER at these prices. I don't like the stock.<p>
Emj11      : Why don't you like AOL?  My mom just bought that.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Well Emj, AOL are certainly wonderful hosts, but I think there is more downside risk before the stock moves significantly higher.<p>
Emj11      : Why are these biotech stocks so good?<p>
GREGDORSEY : The biotechs have been beaten up and the most exciting drugs that will be developed in the next few years will come out of these dynamic biotechs. Look for big drug companies to start angling to buy these smaller companies up.<p>
SHARON DE  : Greg, any IPOs you particularly like right now?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Sharon regarding IPOs. I generally avoid them since most trade below offer prices 6 months later.<p>
MauryC7092 : What do you think of Advance Polymers: APOS.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Maury I don't know APOS well, but they're with Dow Chemical, could be a boon to the company.<p>
Dianne4036 : Novice question: Are the criteria any different when looking for good "small" stocks?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Excellent question Diane. You have to do more homework since there's much less coverage by Wall Street. Look for high insider ownership and high and rising operating margins and strong free cash flow.<p>
Emj11      : Have you heard of Macromedia and what do you think?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Emj Macromedia is expensive, relative to earnings, and insiders are selling--not good.<p>
Lewis1000  : Is it your feeling that the 10...15...20 year bull (depending on when you start counting)... is still at work here? What could  make it end? By end, I mean a significant, much more that 25 percent correction.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Lewis a 25 percent correction isn't out of the question within the next 12 months. Higher inflation will set it off.<p>
Bugsy40    : Hi Greg: I've always thought the stock market should be handicapped like the races. Is it possible to pick stock on the basis of odds, e.g., the odds are 3 to 1 IBM will rise in the next 30 days? <p>
SHARON DE  : Bugsy, what a great idea.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Bugsy, if you want odds stick to Vegas.<p>
Bugsy40    : Greg: Seriously, think about it theoretically. When you pick a stock, aren't the chances of your guessing right quantitative? (And thank you Sharon).<p>
Lewis1000  : Bugsy, I think you can really do that already .There are some stock analysis tools that give percentile chances for upward or downward movements.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Settle down Bugsy. Stock picking is quantitative. But  it's not the same as a casino. Your best bet is long term--something impossible to do at a craps table.<p>
DDelores   : What do you think of IOMEGA, long term prospects?<p>
GREGDORSEY : IOMEGA has a great product but it's overpriced here.<p>
Bugsy40    : I saw IOMEGA for $185 at Mac Warehouse, I don't think it is overpriced.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Not the product Bugsy, the stock.<p>
Lewis1000  : Although, the price of the product is a huge factor for IOMG. They are cutting the price in half soon.<p>
SHARON DE  : Do you know/like Xoma?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Sharon, Xoma is working on an interesting product but it's cash strapped--a risky gamble.<p>
Emj11      : As far as earnings are concerned, what do I look for? I am a beginner. (MACR)<p>
GREGDORSEY : Emj you have to ask yourself "Is 50 percent a year growth sustainable?" It's doubtful. So don't pay too much of a premium in terms of the P/E.<p>
Emj11      : What is a normal growth rate?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Emj I look for companies that can grow at 20 percent annually long term. With blue chips that number is typically lower.<p>
Emj11      : How do I compare growth (EPS) by quarter of previous year?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Emj, you want to compare them to the same quarter a year ago and on a sequential basis.<p>
Lewis1000  : Greg, do you think earnings growth is more/less important than price-to-sales ratios with small stocks?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Lewis both are equally important. Without sales earnings won't follow. Unlike earnings, sales can't be manipulated through accounting tricks.<p>
BRBroker   : Greg -- are you in the market (equity) at all?  If so, where?<p>
GREGDORSEY : BR to avoid any conflicts of interest I generally trade only stock index futures.<p>
Lewis1000  : For small stocks, aren't we looking for companies with growth potential, rather than the most efficiently run organizations?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Interesting query, Lewis. I've seen a lot of small companies with great growth potential blow it because of lousy management.<p>
Lewis1000  : Are small stocks effected more by a strong U.S. dollar or a weak one?<p>
GREGDORSEY : The impact of a changing dollar, Lewis, is less important to small companies than large ones, since large companies generally have more overseas sales. But small firms overseas have less sophisticated hedging practices (in general) and can be more adversely affected by currency swings.<p>
Lewis1000  : So a play on small stocks is really a play on America, no?<p>
GREGDORSEY : God bless America, Lewis. It's your patriotic duty: buy small companies.<p>
Emj11      :  How much should a new investor start of with?<p>
Dianne4036 : I'll add to that question: And how should they diversify with small stocks?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Start with whatever you have Emj. You can start with as little as $25 a month with many solid funds like Meridian, Fidelity Low Price or Baron Asset. Dianne, small stocks should only be a part of your portfolio, but a larger part if you're a long way from retirement. IBM and Mircrosoft were once small stocks.<p>
Matt5001   : Greg -- are small stocks actually a smart idea for the neophyte investor?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Matt, there is a world of difference between small stocks that I'm talking about and penny stocks. Small stocks are a worthy investment for folks looking for long term growth as their key investment goal.<p>
Emj11      : Is buying 25 shares of a stock ridiculous?<p>
GREGDORSEY : No Emj. If that's what you can afford in a decent company buy it. You have to start somewhere.<p>
DPCopeland : Greg -- How many individual stocks would be the minimum to achieve reasonable diversification?<p>
GREGDORSEY : DP start with 3 or 4 diversified funds, then go into stocks. You want to hold at least 8-10 stocks to be reasonably diversified.<p>
RonaldJ118 : Greg: What's happening with Greyhound (bus)?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Ronald, Greyhound looks likes a dirty dog.<p>
WMstressed : Greg: Do you follow Top Sourse Tech (TPS)? If so 3-6 month outlook?<p>
GREGDORSEY : WM, TPS is moving closer to turning a profit. I don't follow the stock closely enough to say much more.<p>
WMstressed : Thanks, I share the same view on profitability...<p>
Skybird246 : Do you generally hold stocks for long term or set targets for taking profits?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Hey Skybird. I generally buy with a 3-year target in mind. But if they continue to produce I stick with it.<p>
Skin935    : What are the prospects for Read Rite?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Skin Read Rite is a commodity play. Don't be fooled by its P/E. It'll always trade at a low one.<p>
RonaldJ118 : Bought AMHD, ANLG, & AXC for long term...New products from them on market.  Buy, Sell, Hold?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Whoa, CNBC flashback Ronald. Sorry, I don't follow any of them regularly.<p>
Skybird246 : Yo Greg! If I buy high quality and stay with them, then should I hold on through corrections?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Yesiree bob, Skybird.<p>
RonaldJ118 : What small-mid companies do you recommend now--for short and/or long term?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Ronald, I especially like MDL Information Systems, Manugistics and ADAC Labs are my favorites for the next 3-5 years.<p>
Skin935    : Your opinion on IVAX?<p>
GREGDORSEY : IVAX looks good Skin, but it's a little pricey here.<p>
Hey Skybird and everyone else--you can check out my site at www.investars.com.<p>
All right hard core investment mavens--what other questions do you have?<p>
MauryC7092 : How does Page Net--PAGE--look to you? <p>
GREGDORSEY : Maury PAGE is well positioned but the stock is a darling of institutional investors. I'd wait for it to fall further before buying.<p>
WMstressed : Greg: Are any of the stocks you recommend optionable?<p>
GREGDORSEY : Generally no WM. I don't think in terms of the options market when choosing my stocks.<p>
RonaldJ118 : CAER, NOVL, IMAT, -- also on my list...any good words on these or are they too small?<p>
GREGDORSEY : As far as I can tell Novell isn't moving product. Earnings gains will be hard to come by. IMAT and CAER I haven't a clue Ronald.<p>
RonaldJ118 : Own BAX and CK--good companys? Prospect for long term? What target price should I sell?<p>
GREGDORSEY : You've certainly got your hands full of stocks, Ronald. Both BAX and CK are good companies in good industries.<p>
RonaldJ118 : With $5,000. --what 2-5 stocks would you recommend. Actually, this is Ron's wife, I'm the stock freak.<p>
GREGDORSEY : Good for you, Ron's wife. Questions like these typically get me in trouble. So instead of answering you, I'll ask you to stop by my web site. I'm offering a free 3-month trial.<p>
Well, folks, my pregnant wife is waiting for me at home. I'm afraid I should wrap it up.<p>
WorthEdit3 : Thanks for joining us tonight, Greg! You've been a very informative guest, and have covered a lot of ground for our readers. For any of you who may have missed part of the chat, you can find a transcript of tonight's chat in the TODAY box on our opening screen later in the week. And Greg will be back for a future Worth OnLine Conference Call. Thanks for coming!<p>
GREGDORSEY : Bye all. Thanks.
					</font>
