	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>06/19/96 -- Finding the Next Microsoft</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On June 19, Sean Donahue and Carol Pickering, the researchers who discovered "The Next Microsoft," joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call." Donahue and Pickering did the research and reporting for Clint Willis's June 1996 cover story, "Found: The Next Microsoft." What follows is a transcript of the event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed here are those of Sean Donahue and Carol Pickering and do not reflect the opinions of Worth OnLine.<p>
WorthOnLne : Welcome to Worth OnLine's chat series, "Conference Call." Sean Donahue and Carol Pickering, the researchers who discovered "The Next Microsoft," are here in place of writer Clint Willis, who could not be with us tonight. Sean and Carol did the research and reporting for Worth's June cover story, "Found: The Next Microsoft."<p>
The article set out to identify the next stock that could earn Microsoft-caliber returns. After a long process of investigation and elimination, the following four companies that emerged as standouts were: CyberCash (Nasdaq:CYCH), Geoworks (Nasdaq:GWRX), Vical (Nasdaq:VICL), and Isis Pharmaceuticals (Nasdaq:ISIP). <p>
Sean ("WorthSean") and Carol ("WorthCarol") proabably know more about these four companies than any of us. Tonight they will talk about these four companies, their research techniques, and how you can find the "next Microsoft." <p>
MrGreen99  : GWRX has had a huge seller in it lately. Where was the stock when you first found it?<p>
WorthCarol : Geoworks was at 29.50 when we first started looking.<p>
WorthOnLne : GWRX was at 31.25 at market close today. Since the "Finding the Next Microsoft" article appeared as the cover story of Worth's June issue Geowork's (Nasdaq:GWRX) stock has risen 6 percent. (Data as of 6/18.)<p>
MrGreen99  : GWRX was at 45 two weeks ago. 14 point drop.<p>
STONE221   : With a number of different companies all developing technology for Internet money transfer, why do you think CyberCash will be the one to succeed long term?<p>
WorthCarol : They have a higher level of security than any other of its competitors. It has set up strong relationships with banks that process 85 percent of credit-card transactions<p>
Jacs Galls : OK. Who is the next Microsoft and why?<p>
WorthSean  : That would take a long time to answer, but in a nutshell, Isis Pharmaceuticals could achieve Microsoft-like returns if its products are approved and make it to market.<p>
Jacs Galls : WorthSean have you heard of Fuisz technologies?<p>
WorthSean  : No... <p>
Jacs Galls : Thay make a pill that dissolves intantly with or without water. Tylenol will use technology as well as many other contracts worldwide. I think they have a shot!<p>
JAsta37986 : Does anybody feel that NSCP has a chance at being the next MSFT?<p>
WorthCarol : Netscape hasn't made any money yet. No one knows how they will make money on their browser.<p>
JAsta37986 : How could you possibly say that NSCP does not know how to make money when they had 55 million in revenues!!!!! <p>
STONE221   : What about the deal that Netscape has with Verifone to develop Internet secure money transfer?<p>
WorthCarol : We don't have any info on the Netscape-CyberCash partnership.<p>
IvanM59    : Tell us about MRVC.<p>
WorthSean  : MRV communications is a little company that makes high-speed ethernet switches and fiber-optic drivers. They use declassified Israeli military technology (I hear) and are supposed to
have some of the finest products available, but they are in a market dominated by huge companies like Ascend and 3Com.<p>
Ma1428     : What will it take for ISIP to be the next Microsoft?<p>
WorthSean  : It would take a breakthrough in their drug technology, a breakthrough on the order of a cure for some type of cancer. That drug, when patented and marketed, would be a huge seller, and we all know how much companies can charge for pharmaceutical products.<p>
Ma1428     : How big can it become and how long will it take?<p>
GVissman   : Why has CYCH had the great rise and now is falling rapidly?<p>
WorthCarol : Unfortunately, we've been working on other stories since this came out so I'm not quite sure.<p>
Jacs Galls : Which one of four has most institutional support? <p>
WorthCarol : Geoworks or CyberCash.<p>
HLouie7914 : Anybody buy ISIP yet? Any info on the stock? What would be good target price to purchase ISIP; $20?<p>
WorthSean  : Louie, I'm not a professional stock analyst, but I might wait until it dropped below 20 again.<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : Can Isis increase on patents alone? <p>
DELTA 453  : What about Fore Systems (FORE)? Anybody up on it?<p>
HLouie7914 : Anybody on SEXI (systems of excellence)? Stock grew 
about 500% over a 2 week period.<p>
CBLenke    : Has anyone heard of a company called Telechips?<p>
WorthCarol : (CB) No?<p>
Liesl96    : Can you tell me a little bit more about Isis?<p>
WorthSean  : Isis is the leader in antisense technology, a form of gene-based drug discovery and delivery<p>
Brane MD   : Sorry, what does the new drug from ISIP promise to do???<p>
Ma1428     : ISIP closed 19 5/8 2day.<p>
HLouie7914 : Just recently, ISIP jumped to $24 and settle back down. Anybody know why?<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : Go to Isis homepage to find out more.<p>
Jacs Galls : I like Geoworks Op System for smart phones.<p>
Jilpeb     : What does Geoworks do?<p>
Greg332    : Are there any other companies that supply a service on the Internet like CyberCash?<p>
Wall St000 : Greg: 1st USA and Sterling.<p>
WorthSean  : Greg, yes. Checkfree, Digicash are a couple.<p>
WorthCarol : greg: Digicash and Checkfree, but they're doing slightly different things than CYCH.<p>
JAsta37986 : Hey greg 332 -- yes look at DIGICASH.<p>
Wall St000 : I am a very large holder of CYCH and have read your article.<p>
Greg332    : I have never heard of Cybercash's competition.  Have they been around a while?<p>
Wall St000 : Greg: All IPO this year I believe.<p>
Jacs Galls : What Mutual Fund support does Geoworks Have?<p>
WorthCarol : Jacs: It may be important, we just are not aware of fund support. We didn't research that.<p>
PBrown2213 : What does VICAL do?<p>
WorthSean  : Pbrown. Vical is another biotech company. They do something called gene thereapy, which replaces defective genes in human cells. The technology can be applied to cancers, inflammatory diseases, and possibly AIDS.<p>
PBrown2213 : Re: Vical. Others like CHIRON are doing gene therapy too...why is VICAL different? <p>
WorthSean  : Pbrown...they don't use viruses to deliver the genes to the cells...much safer.<p>
JAsta37986 : Hey Worth, Carol or Sean do you know of @Home net? I think that the @Home Network will be much bigger than MSFT ever was or will be. @Home is building a cable Internet that will eventually replace the current Internet.<p>
WorthCarol : Jasta: We heard word on that. Supposed to be cool.<p>
Ma1428     : What is the likelihood of ISIP having market cap of 60 billion as Worth suggests in the article... what would it take to get there?<p>
WorthSean  : Ma1428, In what time period?<p>
Ma1428     : Next ten years... I am patient.<p>
WorthSean  : Ma1428, ten years may be enough, but in that time period, 20 billion maybe. It all depends on the success of the drugs in clinical trial<p>
Wall St000 : Carol: I saw quite a bit of volume on CYCH at Junes issue. Is there any idea after the Canadian deal as to CYCH earnings this quarter??<p>
WorthCarol : wall: no idea.<p>
Jacs Galls : When do you think Geoworks will see bottom line improvement?? <p>
HLouie7914 : Carol and Sean, do you own any of the stocks we are talking about? If so, how much? <p>
WorthCarol : Hlouie: no, unfortunately we don't.<p>
Jacs Galls : Geoworks -- have any deals put together yet?<p>
BigTimothy : Carol and Sean, should I look into biotech for the best return over the next 5 years?<p>
WorthCarol : Big tim: yeah, we think it's a safe bet.<p>
Bugds      : WorthSean?: Who is doing the clinical trials? ie, Medical Center names or private? <p>
WorthSean  : Bugds, I'm not sure.<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : Sean,Carol Do any analyasts follow Vical and/or Isis?<p>
WorthSean  : Johnd. Yes, David Sone at Cowan & Co.<p>
Greg332    : How do the services of CyberCash and their competition differ?<p>
WorthCarol : Greg: Digicash is trying to create digital money. Checkfree doesn't believe anything is safe on the Internet. They don't have half the security CYCH does.<p>
Greg332    : Doesn't everyone think that the Internet is not safe for transactions at this time? How does Cybercash secure its lines?<p>
WorthCarol : Greg: Certainly, but CYCH is doing a better job of convincing people.<p>
Greg332    : Do you think that eventually the Internet could be secure?<p>
WorthCarol : With 1065 bit logarithic technology. They had to receive Defense Department clearance, they're the only ones to get it. <p>
BigTimothy : How do you evaluate the biotech when I don't have the expertise ? ? ?<p>
WorthSean  : BigTimothy, try Jim McCamant's Medical Technology Stock Letter <p>
WorthOnLne : Jim McCamant will be a guest on Conference Call on July 24 at 8:00 p.m. EDT.<p>
WorthSean  : Jim is a smart man. He's a great person to talk to about Biotech.<p>
WorthOnLne : June issue Isis Pharmaceutical's (Nasdaq:ISIP) stock has risen 86%. (Data as of 6/18.) Isis was at 20.5 as of market close yesterday.<p>
HLouie7914 : Are there reasons not to invest in ISIP?<p>
JAsta37986 : @Home could make NSCP IPO and MSFT IPO look paltry!<p>
KCLA227    : Carol and Sean, the next Microsoft will be a tech or biotech stock?<p>
WorthSean  : KCLA 227, I think biotech.<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : Does Isis have plans to manufacture any of the antisense drugs?<p>
WorthSean  : Johnd, yes, they plan on manufacturing some of their own as well as licensing the technology.<p>
HLouie7914 : Carol or Sean, are other analysts big on ISIS?<p>
WorthSean  : Hlouie, Paul Boni at Mehta and Isaly in New York<p>
BigTimothy : Have you ever heard of Applied Microbiology ( AMBI ) ??<p>
WorthSean  : Big Tim, no, not yet anyway<p>
BigTimothy : Sean & Carol, I really like your writing style - High Content And Good Humor !<p>
WorthCarol : bigtim: thanks<p>
HLCjr      : Wrting style won't make us any money....<p>
WorthSean  : HLCjr, it may make me some money.<p>
HLCjr      : Cute Worthsean...<p>
CBlain4082 : #1 company to invest is international automated 
             system SYMBOL IAUS watch them .<p>
BigTimothy : The BOOK you guys reference in the article, is it Summer Reading ? ? ?<p>
WorthCarol : Bigtim: Sure Tim, take to the beach!<p>
BigTimothy : Cool, I'm going next week to Ocean City MD. I will pick-up a copy.<p>
BERT3825   : How much does that 86 percent rise in Isis's stock have to do with your story?<p>
WorthSean  : BERT, about 25 million for ISIP.<p>
SHumph9524 : What about the prospects for Oracle Corp.?<p>
WorthCarol : shump: Can't help.<p>
HLouie7914 : the next microsoft will be SEXI (500% growth in two weeks)<p>
TAGjek     : I am with you HLouie! GO SEXI!<p>
Bacardi 1  : What does that stand for? SEXI?<p>
TAGjek     : Systems of Excellence<p>
HLouie7914 : They are in video conferencing with PC systems. Any news on SEXI lately? <p>
TAGjek     : Hlouie.. check out news by ticker in Portfolios for today's news on SEXI.<p>
WorthCarol : Hlouie: We didn't research SEXI.<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : Worth, I don't think you're correct, when the magazine hit the stand ISIS was already up!<p>
WorthSean  : Sure, ISIS was between 11 and 13 when we started looking at it, but it had been higher back in the early 90s when biotech was everyone's darling.<p>
WorthOnLne : Any sense of the impact of Worth's article on the stock price? On that of the other companies mentioned?<p>
WorthCarol : I think that the Worth article had a strong impact on all of these stocks one way or the other.<p>
Wall St000 : WorthOnLne: Yes to your question on impact on stock price.<p>
WorthCarol : Wall: I don't see how any press wouldn't have an impact.<p>
JOLLOR     : What does Geoworks do?<p>
WorthCarol : jollor: Geoworks has an oem technology that is being used in smart phones and other consumer computing devices.<p>
BigTimothy : What do you ( Sean & Carol ) think about the Internet computer?<p>
WorthSean  : Big Tim, I don't think it's as great as some say. Everyone needs to store some data at some time or another, so a simple connection won't help too much. What will you download into?<p>
BigTimothy : Yea, but what about large companies???<p>
WorthSean  : Big Tim, I like Intuit a lot, they're pretty big.<p>
BigTimothy : I have a position in SunRiver Corp ( SRVC ).<p>
BigTimothy : Sean & Carol, how can you BUY a stock that is NOT making MONEY ? ? ?<p>
WorthCarol : big tim: do some research.<p>
WorthSean  : Big tim, you're making a bet on the technology, the quality of the management, and the size of market.<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : Vical was the same thing, a piece showed recent price it was 16. 11 time of publication. Need to figure how to get Worth info earlier! <p>
Wall St000 : Carol: Your feelings on VeriFone in regards to CYCH. Same owners we know. But company wise?<p>
WorthCarol : I think Bill Melton's experience definitely helps CYCH.<p>
HLouie7914 : sean or carol, how about ICOS and the fact that Bill Gates own over 10 percent of the company<p>
WorthSean  : Hlouie, he must see something there. I like them, but they don't have a unifying, patentable technology for delivery of a therapy like Isis and Vical do.<p>
HLouie7914 : If GATES invests in something it must be worthwhile, right?<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : I'd like to hear more of ICOS it real cheap<p>
BigTimothy : Sean & Carol, for biotech: How many drugs do you look for in the pipeline? ? ?<p>
WorthSean  : Big tim, I don't know a hard and fast rule, but the more the better, and many different applications is always better, in case one or two or more don't make it to human trial.<p>
WorthOnLne : Could an "average" person get the access to info (talking to CO execs, etc) that you did?<p>
WorthCarol : Info. for the average joe. Calling venture caps. is pointless. They'll ignore you. Try newsletters: Red Chip Review, California Technology Stock Letter and Medical Technology Letter.<p>
Johnd 2ba5 : How far away is Isis from manufacturing? Thought all were in clinicals? Approval? <p>
WorthSean  : Johnd, I can't remember exactly, I haven't been following them since we finished the story.<p>
Triad      : Any news lately of MRVC?  It had quite a run up last week or so.<p>
WorthCarol : triad: Sorry no info. We haven't followed these stocks for a couple months.<p>
HLouie7914 : Carol or Sean, can Isis develop a cure for the AIDS virus?<p>
WorthSean  : Hlouie, I don't think anyone's making that claim yet, but they may be looking in to it.<p>
WorthEdit1 : HLouie--you may want to check out "Robert Gallo Wants To Fight" from the same issue as the MSFT story.<p>
HLouie7914 : If someone found a cure for AIDS, wouldn't you think that company would just skyrocket?<p>
WorthSean  : Hlouie, obviously. But I don't think Isis has a cure for AIDS as one of their focuses. It's mostly anti-cancer, anti-inflammatory application<p>
BigTimothy : Carol & Sean, what is next industry to follow the biotechs over the next 5 to 10 Years ? ?<p>
WorthCarol : Telecom, Internet.<p>
WorthSean  : Big Tim, Someone mentioned "photonics".<p>
BigTimothy : If you say PHOTONICS you are talking about Lucent Technologies. Right ? ?<p>
WorthSean  : Big Tim, maybe. They hadn't yet split off when I was doing my research so I didn't follow them<p>
ShAq54     : Carol or Sean : where can I get detailed information on a regular basis on public companies?<p>
WorthCarol : sha: Newsletters.<p>
ShAq54     : Where do I get newsletters on a daily basis?<p>
WorthCarol : Sha: Daily, I don't know. Any of the ones I mentioned are monthly.<p>
Triad      : What are the best critera today to find the MSFT of tomorrow?<p>
WorthCarol : Triad: Strong management, proprietary tech/oem.<p>
WorthSean  : Triad, look for a company with a defacto monopoly in a huge, growing industry.<p>
Triad      : Do you have any industries that you would currently recommend?<p>
WorthCarol : The ones we like--telecom, internet, and biotech. <p>
WorthEdit1 : I'd like to thanks Carol and Sean for graciously agreeing to participate in the chat tonight in Clint Willis's absence.<p>
WorthSean  : Goodbye everyone, thanks for coming.<p>
WorthCarol : Thanks.<p>
WorthOnLne : Tune in next week for Greg Dorsey (Wed. 8 p.m.), who will talk about small stocks the Street doesn't follow, and Art Bonnel (Thur, 8 p.m.), manager of the #1 Morningstar rated mid-cap fund.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
