	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>06/18/96 -- Rudy Maxa (Savvy Traveler), author of "Europe When It Sizzles"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On June 18, Rudy Maxa joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call." Maxa, a travel writer and author of "Europe When It Sizzles" from the July/August issue of Worth, gave readers tips and advice on traveling throughout the world. What follows is a transcript of the event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed here are those of Rudy Maxa and do not reflect the opinions of Worth OnLine.<p>
WorthEdit3 : Welcome to Worth OnLine's CONFERENCE CALL. Tonight, we're joined by travel writer Rudy Maxa. His screen name is SavTrav. Good evening, Rudy. Welcome to Worth OnLine.<p>
SavTrav    : Thank you so much.  Nice to be here. <p>
KY BUILDER : I would like info on apartments in Italy, wine country/Florence/classical music areas?<p>
SavTrav    : One of the best package tour companies for wine tours in Italy is called Campioni Italiani de Veneto.  You may call them at 310-373-2226. As for renting, you may find farmhouses, grand houses, smaller places, and so on by contacting Italian Rentals at 202-244-53445! For general info on Florence, go to the American Express "ExpressNet section" here on AOL (keyword: Amex) and click on Travel Info and browse!<p>
Rabbit7442 : Thanks for any tips for a single traveler.<p>
SavTrav    : Tips for the single traveler:  Can you be more specific?  What part of the world? And what kind of tips?<p>
Rabbit7442 : Ireland, best way to see country without car. Also cruises to Alaska.<p>
SavTrav    : Well, there are only two ways to see Ireland without a car: bus or train. The train system in Ireland isn't as extensive as it is in, say Great Britain, but it could work for you.  There are, of course, bus tours as well. Call the Irish Tourist Board at 212-418-0800 for more details about options. There are some bargains if you're thinking of cruising Alaska.  Now is an excellent time to consider booking to the northwest.<p>
MARTSAND   : We will be touring the south of France. What is best way to get from Perpignan to Barcelona?..<p>
SavTrav    : Don't know Perpignan so I can't help.  What's it near?<p>
MARTSAND   : Perpignan is 30 miles south of Carcassonne<p>
SavTrav    : Jeez, Carcassonne. . . I'd take the train to Toulouse and train it to Barcelona presuming you're on a leisurely schedule.  If you're in a hurry, fly.<p>
KY BUILDER : What village would you recommend in the Italian wine country for a one month stay?<p>
SavTrav    : There are so many wondeful villages in Italy, it's hard to choose.  But if you go about a 90-minute drive north of Venice, you're in Asolo, a charming town with nice places to stay and great, hilly drives. I'd choose Asolo, but there are other options, of course. <p>
Rabbit7442 : What is the best time of year to travel to Irish country?<p>
SavTrav   : Best time of year to travel in Ireland is summer or early fall or late spring.<p>
WorthEdit3 : In the July/August issue of Worth, you give some great tips on traveling through Europe during the peak season. What are some of the best-kept secrets?<p>
SavTrav    : (I'm starting to get envious of some of these trips.) Well, if you're headed to Europe or even Asia, Inter-Continental Hotels has put out a free booklet called "Concierge Confidential."  The hotel company polled its concierges and asked them for their secrets.  It's a great resource.  You may get it free by calling 800-327-0200. Also, if you're in Paris and you MUST see the Mona Lisa, you can avoid the long lines at the Louvre by going around to the back entrance on the Seine side of the rear wing.<p>
Rodreupert : Is there anywhere in the U.S. that is like country and you can just relax?<p>
SavTrav    : I just got back last week from the Napa Valley. That, and Sonoma County are pretty darn relaxing places to me!  No glitz, lots of great food (and, of course, wine). The coastal areas of Oregon, northern California, and Washington are pretty swell, too.<p>
Lewis1000  : Will Europe ever be cheap enough for Americans to travel there again?<p>
SavTrav    : I think Europe will be cheap again, if only because history seems to swing back and forth when it comes to currency fluctuations. I admit it's been a while since the U.S. dollar was king!  But the time will come again, I think.<p>
SavTrav    : Meanwhile, consider Turkey--the best bargain these days in Europe. Another Europe tip: Book your London theater tix before going over.  Call Edwards & Edwards at 800-223-6108.<p>
RSteinau   : My wife and I are planning a ten year anniversary trip to Europe, any ideas?<p>
SavTrav    : An anniversary in Europe?  You can't go wrong. Obviously, Paris, the city of love comes to mind immediately.  But the Amalfi coast of Italy, or the lake region around Lake Como will make you fall in love with life all over again.  And each other.  Depends on the time of year, whether you two are city or country types.  Whether you like pasta or foie gras! I think the most important thing about a romantic getaway is choosing your accomodations correctly.  Check out the Relais & Chateaux catalogue.  Any of their member properties are almost guaranteed to be first class and romantic. Details: 212-856-0115.<p>
Lewis1000  : How about using the internet to buy remainder airline tickets just before the date of travel? Does it work?<p>
SavTrav    : OK, the Internet and remainder airline tickets. I have never used the 'Net to buy consolidator air tickets.  You may well find a travel agency that specializes in consolidator tickets that advertises on the 'Net, however. But almost any agency these days can help you with that. I don't honestly know that there's any advantage of looking on the 'Net, but not having tried, I'm not about to argue one way or another. <p>
Anybody thinking about visiting Asia? Whoops, I forgot this session is supposed to be about Europe.  Oh, well.  I'm game for anything.<p>
Lewis1000  : Thailand's always been an interesting idea.<p>
SavTrav    : I LOVE Thailand, especially the north and the south.<p>
Lewis1000  : Ever been to Vietnam?<p>
SavTrav    : The people are among the most kind and gentle, the cuisine is legendary, and the prices out of Bangkok are favorable. I have not been to Vietnam.  Almost shouldn't call myself a travel writer these days but I was about to go this spring until a family member took ill and I had to cancel. But I only hear good things.  One warning: Be sure you have lodging before you go to Vietnam, as the hotels are apparently always full! And, of course, you'll need a visa.<p>
Lewis1000  : What's the most beautiful, wonderful, interesting place you've ever been?<p>
SavTrav    : Wow, that's a big question.  Beautiful: some parts of the south of France, in the hills. Interesting: Got to be Asia; Hong Kong, Macao, rural Thailand. Wonderful, well, I think I'd choose Kenya, on safari. For a city boy like me, seeing the expanse of African sky, the range of wildlife, and the fundamental feeling that we may all have sprung from that soil was powerful. But, don't get me wrong: I had a fabulous time in the Napa Valley last weekend, too! I do appreciate the western mountains of North Carolina, the Floriday Keys, and so on.<p>
Lewis1000  : What's the right amount to budget for a trip to Europe--A moderate level trip?<p>
KelDuke    : $6000<p>
Lewis1000  : $6000? For what? A night at the casinos in Monaco?<p>
KelDuke    : ya<p>
SavTrav    : Well, a moderate budget for Western Europe would be about $150 a day, I think, if you're careful about where you stay and you avoid expensive restaurants.  You can stay in places for less than $100 a night all over France--the French Government Tourist Office has a free book (it's $18 if you wait and buy it in France) with listings.  Then eat at bistros and you could come in well under $150.  Of course, I'm speaking from the vantage point of a 46-year-old man who isn't willing to do the hostel thing anymore! My daughter could probably do France for $40 a day.<p>
KelDuke    : I would on at least $200 a day.<p>
WorthEdit3 : What do you consider a good deal on an airfare from NY to London?<p>
SavTrav    : Airfare this summer between NY and London on the major airlines is right now about $700, I'd estimate, on average.  But scheduled charters could deliver you to and from for a couple of hundred dollars less. The drawback of scheduled charters is that if something goes wrong--if a plane is delayed because of weather or mechanical difficulties, there's usually no back up. Which means you spend a lot of time--sometimes an extra day--waiting.  But the price is often right.<p>
Lewis1000  : It's hard to do something like that when time is right.<p>
SavTrav    : For info on scheduled charters, check the small ads in the Sunday travel sections of major newspapers, such as the NY Times in this case.<p>
Lewis1000  : Are they all reputable?<p>
KelDuke    : DEPENDS ON WHO YOU ASK<p>
SavTrav    : There have been people stranded when a charter has suddenly closed shop, but I don't think it's a major problem these days. Of course, ValuJet was a big success just about six weeks ago!<p>
Lewis1000  : How about becoming a courier in order to travel  cheaply?<p>
SavTrav    : Becoming a courier is an excellent way to travel very cheaply (but with no check-on luggage) if you have the luxury of time.  As you may know, you can't exactly pick and choose your schedule.  And the more flexible you are, the more last-minute you can leave, the less you'll pay.  For more info, check out Kelly Monaghan's excellent book on the subject, available in most travel sections of bookstores or by calling 800 356 9315. Courier flights are best for students, retired folks, or people who have summers off!<p>
Lewis1000  : Is Mexico known for not having great food?<p>
SavTrav    : Mexico offers fabulous food, you just have to take certain precautions by staying away from fruit you don't peel yourself, salads that aren't prepared at restaurants or hotels that use purified water to clean them, and by drinking only bottled drinks.<p>
Lewis1000  : I went to Ixtapa and went to every four star  restaurant and it's not that the food was bad, it's just that it was so mediocre.<p>
SavTrav    : Possible, very possible; I don't know the restaurants of Ixtapa.<p>
KHick23415 : Any suggestions, business in Brussels either August or October...which month is best and why.....<p>
SavTrav    : Either month is fine for Brussels, though October will obviously be cooler. And less crowded with tourists, as August is prime time for tour groups. I'd choose October if I had to choose.<p>
KHick23415 : Are the prices different?<p>
SavTrav    : The tip is already figured in the meter of Brussels taxis, so don't overpay. And if you're going downtown from the airport, take the 20-minute ride on the shuttle train to Brussel's Central Station for only $3 each way.<p>
Lewis1000  : Ever been to Israel?<p>
SavTrav    : I have been to Israel several times, yes; one of my fave places.  Along with Jordan and Egypt.<p>
KHick23415 : Yes, we stay at Hotel President, near Nord Station. Great hotel and reasonable with Sabena.<p>
SavTrav    : Then you're in good shape, KHick.  Lewis1000, I  remember being quite moved by visting Masada, and Jerusalem is a great walking town, at least the old part.<p>
Lewis1000  : I agree. Jerusalem is a great example of good urban planning.<p>
SavTrav    : If your'e thinking of visiting Isreal but the air ticket is a problem, check out Tower Air's flights from JFK in NY.  Also, World Airlines (in a code-share deal with Continental) is offering a companion half price ticket between NY and Tel Aviv until the last day of July, I believe.  I write about it in my weekly travel column posted here on AOL this wk.<p>
KHick23415 : What is the cheapest way to go from Brussels to Cork, Ireland?  Also how long does it take?<p>
SavTrav    : Never have gone to Cork, so I can't help with time. You could obviously fly, or you could take the Chunnel train to London and fly or train from there.<p>
Lewis1000  : You mentioned Turkey earlier. Wasn't there an election recently where a fundamentalist Muslim took a high office? Would that affect Americans touring there?<p>
SavTrav    : Turkey has long been struggling politically, with fundamentalism being a factor, yes. But so far, I know of no problems being encountered by Americans visiting.<p>
Lewis1000  : Are Belize and Costa Rica still the hot places in Central America?<p>
SavTrav    : Belize was hot about ten years ago and still is (in all senses of the word), particularly if diving is your passion.  Costa Rica became hot about four years ago and continues to enjoy a boom among Americans who like its nearness, its stability, its Pacific coast and its prices.  The tourism infrastructure, however, isn't as developed as it eventually will be.  That, of course, can be a plus for many people.  Most lodging along the coast is simple and functional.  Don't expect luxury resorts!<p>
KHick23415 : When visiting Brussels, to what outlying areas should I bring the teenagers?  Luxemborg?<p>
SavTrav    : Bruge is the most famous town outside of Brussels for touring--its canals and architecture are delights. The teens will especially like the fact the national food is french fries.  With mayonnaise. Vendors cook 'em up and sell 'em everywhere! Remember, Amsterdam isn't too far from Brussels, if you have the time to visit, as well. Watch for pickpockets this summer in big European cities.<p>
KHick23415 : Any suggestions on feeding the teenagers on a reasonable budget while in Belgium?<p>
Lewis1000  : Is Nicaragua the next hot spot in C.A.?<p>
SavTrav    : Don't stop on the open road even if someone suggests there's something wrong with your car. Well, for teens in Belgium you got your French fries, as I mentioned. There are plenty of reasonable places to eat with the usual teen bulk food!<p>
I don't know if Nicaragua is on the brink of being "hot."  Again, little tourism infrastructure there so far. I have not been, so I speak only generally.<p>
Lewis1000  : Is Eurail still the best way to get around Europe on the cheap?<p>
SavTrav    : If you're visiting a lot of cities, yes, it is. There are so many various kinds of Eurail tickets these days, however, shop carefully.<p>
KHick23415 : Be sure to buy the tickets, in Belgium they don't always check, but fines are steep if caught.<p>
Lewis1000  : You sound like you've been through that, KHick.<p>
KHick23415 : Almost, got on 1st class with 2nd class ticket, they got a bit annoyed, but no fine luckily.<p>
SavTrav    : In England, you can buy a Britrail pass.  For info, call 800-677-8585. Always buy Britrail and Eurail passes in the U.S. before going abroad.<p>
In Russia, don't be shy about yelling and pushing if you're in a public place, and people start crowding around you.  They're about to go through all your pockets! And leave no visible luggage in parked rental cars,  ever.<p>
Lewis1000  : I heard Russia is in dire dire straits. Have you seen any of that your own eyes?... Alchoholism, of course unemployment, you name it.<p>
SavTrav    : Yes, I've visited Russia, and there are people in dire straits there, no question. Which is why crime is a problem. If you stick to major cities and keep your wits about you, however, you'll be fine!  St. Petersburg, for me, is well worth the visit.<p>
KHick23415 : Yes my brother recently visited, said bring toilet paper and soap, and jeans for barter...<p>
Lewis1000  : That was the old USSR.<p>
KHick23415 : No, this was last month.<p>
BoxOf64    : NY here, and wanting to go to Vegas. Should I do a Travel Agents pkg or make my own arrangements?<p>
SavTrav    : As for that Vegas question:  check an airline for a hotel/air deal!<p>
WorthEdit3 : Thanks for joining us tonight, Rudy! You've given a lot of great travel advice to all of us. For those of you who missed part of tonight's chat, we'll have a transcript available in the TODAY window of our opening screen.<p>
SavTrav    : Thanks for having me!<p>
WorthEdit3 : Thanks again, Rudy. Good night.<p>
SavTrav    : Good night!<p>
WorthEdit3 : And thanks to all of you who joined us this evening.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
