		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>05/01/96 -- James Dines, Editor of "The Dines Letter"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On May 1, James Dines joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call." Dines, author of "Mass Psychology" and editor of "The Dines Letter" since 1960, talked about investing in precious metals, market timing, and mass psychology. What follows is a transcript of the event, edited for clarity. The opinions expressed here are those of Mr. James Dines and do not reflect the opinions of Worth OnLine.<p>
WorthOnLne : 
Mr. James Dines (screen name DinesLtr) is going to begin tonight's Conference Call by giving us a bit of background information, and answers to some of the most basic questions about his three topics tonight: market timing, mass psychology, and investing in precious metals. Mr. Dines will begin to answer your questions after his initial introductory comments. Please hold questions until he is through.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
1) Precious Metals -- According to Dinesism #10 (The Dines Wolfpack Theory), gold, silver, platinum and palladium move together. The Dines Letter has been more optimistic on gold shares than gold bullion. All portfolios should retain a "core position" in golds and silvers for these two reasons: a) golds often move opposite to the rest of the market (Dinesism #7, Dines Rule of Gold Countertrend) so golds are a hedge against a market decline and b) there is a low-key currency crisis going on (see crash / Mexican peso last year, and crash of dollar against Japanese yen).  <p>
2) Market timing -- The Dines Letter has been bullish all the way up, and remains optimistic as of this time. We are in a "singularity" where the whole world is opening up to free markets, stock-purchase awareness, and the Internet -- the greatest invention since the printing press. This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to make money on Wall Street. <p>
3) Mass Psychology -- My new book " Mass Psychology," my third and final business book, has already been called a "classic" as have the first two books. This is a "Mass Psychological Market," approaching mania proportions that might end badly, so our next sell signal is crucial. Mania is societal, witness incredible sums paid at Jackie Kennedy's garage sale, spread of legalized gambling (daintily called "gaming" and "entertainment"), and the frantic rise in commodity prices. This is all historic. <p>
LoLoLAW    : 
Where do you think the S&P 500 will be by 12/31/96?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
I expect Standard & Poor's to keep rising until it breaks its Major Uptrendline.<p>
DRHCH      : 
What's the percentage gain in gold for the last quarter?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
First quarter gain, gold bullion - 2 percent -- DIGSA: 29.3 percent. The market's leading group, believe it or not<p>
DWillis782 : 
What do you think about a South African gold fund as an investment?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
I like the South African golds as part of a diversified gold portfolio.<p>
ISSherman  : 
How long do you think the bull market in small caps will last?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
ISSherman--Longer.<p>
PaulRCus   : 
Mr. Dines. I hold some shares of ABX and coins as well. Should I increase both or only one?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
ABX very bullish. Coins not as bullish but not as leveraged as gold stocks.<p>
RBussert   : 
Is it foolish for the small investor to time, or with a 15 year horizon, just hold?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Definitely use timing.<p>
Garsrese   : 
What is a major Uptrendline?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
I'd have to show you a chart of it. Subscribe to the Dines Letter.<p>
DRHCH      : 
How much is one 1922 silver dollar U.S. worth today, Mr. Dines?  I have hundreds.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Silver coins -- price it with a coin store. <p>
FundWrap   : 
Mr. Dines, China recently cut interest rates -- citing decreased worries over inflation. If China were to relent on their austerity program that they started in July of 1993...what impact would that have on stocks there?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish on China from 1979 to 1992, and now still bearish.<p>
FundWrap   : 
What if China were to loosen monetary policy -- would that make you bullish?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
We would turn bullish on China if stocks developed Uptrends.<p>
Matgot     : 
What is your opinion on telecommunications sector funds assuming a 15-year time horizon?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Matgot: telecommunications sector bullish, but don't think 15 years as this is a mania.<p>
JSHDFR     : 
What do you think about CBOE's new gold index? Better to buy an index or individual stock?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Our Gold Index is much better, and prefer individual stocks.<p>
Zooy       : 
Are you aware of the surge of Iomega on the NASDAQ, and if so, what are your thoughts?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Iomega is an example of a mania and is in an Uptrend.<p>
RBussert   : 
If the  bull market's a baseball game, what inning are we in?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
If the bull market is in baseball -- 7th inning.<p>
BS22039    : 
What is your thoughts on AOL stock?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Thoughts on AOL stock -- Bullish and in our Supervised Lists.<p>
WESEV9     : 
WHEN DO YOU EXPECT XAU TO BREAKOUT TO THE UPSIDE?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
XAU -- Imminently.<p>
RQTBL1     : 
Why do you believe the XAU will break out imminently?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
XAU - Because its components are in Uptrends.<p>
DRHCH      : 
When will the baby boomers crash in their expectations for mutual fund investment?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
At the bottom of the next bear market.<p>
Zooy       : 
But how long would you guess this Uptrend for Iomega will last?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Longer. <p>
Rexkay     : 
How do you feel about copper, oil, natural resources in general?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish on natural resources for last three years.<p>
DCarl43677 : 
What do you think of IBM?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
IBM - short term bearish, long-term bullish.<p>
DMF MA     : 
What are your thoughts on Analog Devices?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish with a stop at 23.<p>
Matgot     : 
What are your thoughts on REITs, both commercial and residential properties?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
I've been bearish on real estate since 1989.<p>
FundWrap   : 
Dines...what role does fundamental analysis play in your stock selection?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Fundamental analysis has a heavy role.<p>
EdS9000    : 
The Magellan Fund has really pulled back on tech stocks and gone to cash, etc. Just a bad guess?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Vinik has his own opinion.<p>
FundWrap   : 
Vinik had to redeploy a lot of money -- 20 billion worth. I think he made a bad bet on interest rates...and he also has too much cash still. That is the problem when the elephant tries to tip-toe out of a 20 billion dollar position.<p>
PaulRCus   : 
Mr. Dines, what about Glamis Gold shares?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Glamis  -- not my favorite gold stock. Stillwater Mining looks fantastic and written up in last issue of The Dines Letter.<p>
DMF MA     : 
Any thoughts on Pier One?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Pier One -- bullish stop 11.<p>
RBussert   : 
How do you feel about asset allocation strategies like constant ratios, etc.?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Asset allocation -- a function of market ignorance. Better to know what you're doing.<p>
Rexkay     : 
How do you see Latin America in general and Mexico in particular?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish on Latin American and especially Mexico because their currency is so cheap and everybody is bearish.<p>
Jake8551   : 
What is your feeling on video conferencing, where is it going?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish, but Internet will absorb it.<p>
Jake8551   : 
What do you mean, Internet will absorb it?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Internet will absorb video conferencing by the nature of the Internet rather than by separate companies.<p>
LEure      : 
What is your feeling about biotechs in general and Interneuron in particular?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Biotechs -- exceptionally bullish, but InterNeuron due for profit-taking pullback.  Try to buy below 32.<p>
DGeorge164 : 
Please explain the increase of the past several years in money supply to inflation.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Huge question but they are connected.<p>
Lagarhead  : 
Do you think EDS will be able to deliver shareholders value after the spin-off???<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish on EDS, but more so on General Motors.<p>
Peretz42   : 
Have of you heard of Dayton MNG on AMEX?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Dayton Mining -- bullish Uptrend but try to buy below 6.<p>
CAyers4207 : 
WILL STOCKS LIKE IOMG AND ZTEC LAST?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
IOMG & ZTEC for the moment - yes.<p>
LEure      : 
Why do you feel asset allocation is a result of market ignorance? <p>
DinesLtr   : 
Asset allocation is a mechanical system that replaces judgment.<p>
Rexkay     : 
if you have to have bonds-what duration?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bonds -  short term.<p>
HBrilliant : 
Do you recommend 10-15 percent of assets in gold as others do? How does that balance with gold stocks?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Percent asset in golds varies depending on individual risk. For example, elderly should not even be buying green bananas.<p>
Sattar001  : 
Mr. Dines what about UTX?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
United Tech -- bullish stop at 95.<p>
Majorrbc   : 
Is picking the best movers in the DOW a good investment strategy?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Yes.<p>
PaulRCus   : 
What about Cisco?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Cisco - a bullish leader making new highs in Major Uptrend.<p>
Christowin : 
How about Bay Network?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bay Network -- should have been sold long ago because broken Uptrendline with deteriorating Relative Strength.<p>
LEure      : 
How would you approach a retirement 30 years from maturity? <p>
DinesLtr   : 
With skepticism that it can be done intelligently, but be cautious after this bull market ends.<p>
LEure      : 
Why skeptical?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
LEure: Because 30 years is too far to judge.<p>
Zooy       : 
How do you think LeBow's loss with RJR will effect stock? RJR appears to be floating in limbo. <p>
DinesLtr   : 
I prefer Philip Morris to RJR.<p>
PaulRCus   : 
How about REITs in general and Health REITs in Particular?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
REITs bearish, we are unenthusiastic about real estate.<p>
RBurger72  : 
Do you like Pan American Silver at "9"? <p>
DinesLtr   : 
Pan Amer Silver -- Definitely, one of the outstanding silver stocks.<p>
SmallRhino : 
Are you bullish on titanium plays? RMI Titanium or TRE?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
No, markets are still extremely bullish.
Titanium play too publicized, probably due for a profit-taking pullback.<p>
HBrilliant : 
How do you feel about a platinum play for the near term?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Platinum -- exceptionally bullish, and smart way to play it is Stillwater Mining, the only leading producer outside of South Africa.<p>
JLoggie184 : 
What is the best metal play now? <p>
DinesLtr   : 
Stillwater Mining & Penoles (largest underground silver mine in world).<p>
Sattar001  : 
What about Eli Lilly?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Eli Lilly bullish, with stop at 58.<p>
JAROD30    : 
Will real estate ever (within the next 10 years) make a comeback?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Yes, it will make comeback but not visible yet.<p>
CAyers4207 : 
HOW MUCH RETURN SHOULD A PERSON LOOK FOR FROM 100,000 FROM A BROKER?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
As much as possible.<p>
DWillis782 : 
What do you think of investing in the Eastern European Markets? <p>
DinesLtr   : 
Too risky. If you can't make money in the US, you're hiding in too much tall grass.<p>
LEure      : 
Where would you sell Interneuron? Lots of promising drugs emerging.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Not clear, and due for a profit-taking pullback, but should work higher later.<p>
MIKFIK     : 
Have you read David Marantette's Goldstock Letter?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
No<p>
MIKFIK     : 
David Marantette's Webpage is at (http://www.goldstock.com) if interested.<p>
FGuiffreda : 
What is your long term outlook for Johnson & Johnson?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Very bullish and in our Supervised Lists.<p>
RGreig     : 
What is your opinion on Motorola?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Motorola: disappointing and can do better elsewhere, but if held leave a stop at 50. A rise to 65 would be more encouraging.<p>
Cosmed     : 
Regarding the economy -- isn't a rate hike more likely now than a rate cut?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Rate hike already in the market and should be ignored. If interest rates rise, dollar will go up and it would be bad for international corporations.<p>
DGeorge164 : 
Do you still favor Royal Oak and ASA Ltd.?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Royal Oak & ASA -- Yes.<p>
JAROD30    : 
Will interest rates rise? If so, how much? And will they ever come back down?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Interest rates are in a Uptrend and until that ends, we have no change.<p>
JOHNVBACH  : 
Opinion on Zenith? Short term?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Zenith: very bullish. But wait for pullback before buying more.<p>
EdS9000    : 
A quick opinion on Goodyear? Thanks.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish along with entire automotive industry, stop at 49.<p>
LWigg79564 : 
What do you think about Physicians Sales & Services?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Physician Sales - in Consolidation, unexciting, decent growth, if held, stop at 20.<p>
JAROD30    : 
What's your feeling on the Mexico market and its opportunities for us?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish on Mexico and recommend Mexican Fund on NYSE.<p>
PaulRCus   : 
Outlook for Enron Oil and Gas, Please, Mr. Dines.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Enron -- Bullish, along with whole oil exploration group, but due for pullback, with stop at 24.<p>
Nickpel    : 
Your outlook for gold for the next year?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Outlook for gold bullion -- not as bullish as gold mining shares. The Dines Letter flashed a Major buy signal on gold stocks on 9 Nov 92. 
And still in Major Uptrend.<p>
JSHDFR     : 
What do you think The Dines Plan's biggest benefit is over the current tax system?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
The Dines Plan is discussed in my new book "Mass Psychology," featuring 50 percent tax cuts and privatization of broad sectors of government such as prisons. One of our big recommendations has been Corrections Corp., in a phenomenal Uptrend, 60 times your money so far.<p>
MARTSAND   : 
An opinion on Omnicare(OCR).<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Omnicare : In powerful Uptrend, with stop at 50.<p>
FundWrap   : 
What is gold supply like right now, relative to historical numbers?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Gold supply almost never changes as gold is indestructible. But demand fluctuates radically depending on investment fever. Also ex-communist masses can now buy gold for the first time in many decades.<p>
JOHNVBACH  : 
Short term on Home Depot,  earning report May 16th.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Home Depot -- unenthusiastic, but if held, stop at 40.<p>
ZX300LM    : 
Would US Air with STEVEN WOLF in charge be a good buy?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Steven Wolf, very unpopular, but US Air in Uptrend along with airline stocks.<p>
Stockdoc   : 
MESA Air included in that airline bull move?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Mesa Airlines -- bullish with rest of group, stop at 10.<p>
FundWrap   : 
What do you think of Japanese automakers now? Is this a good time for them?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
No strong opinion, because it depends on currency fluctuation. Not in newspapers yet, but yen rising and should be bad for Japanese business. I'm so old I remember when the yen was hardly an urge.<p>
RGreig     : 
Your opinion on Oxford Health, with a P/E in the low 60s?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Oxford Health: bullish, a close stop at 42, conservative stop at 36.<p>
Jamellah   : 
Mr. Dines, is the life insurance industry a growth industry?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Life insurance moves with banking and utilities, both under pressure because of prospect of higher interest rates. But we added American International Group at 70 on 10 Apr 95. Now 92 and still very bullish, stop at 87.<p>
RQTBL1     : 
Since the Japanese Yen is a controlled currency why won't the BOJ put a lid on any substantial increase in the value of the JY?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Manipulated currency difficult to forecast but trend of yen is now up.<p>
FGuiffreda : 
What is your long term outlook for Walt Disney?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish, but conservative for moderate growth.<p>
Stockdoc   : 
Do you like Horsham (HSM)?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Okay for diversification into Barrick, oil refining and German real estate, but I prefer owning Barrick directly.<p>
JOHN EE1   : 
What's in store for us Friday when the unemployment figures come out?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Unemployment figures irrelevant, as market is in Uptrend.<p>
LWaldmanmd : 
Your  position on IBM?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
IBM is short-term downtrend and in long-term Uptrend, along with whole high-tech group.<p>
Ravioli    : 
Your opinion on high tech,  i.e. Motorola, Microsoft etc.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Motorola already answered, and Microsoft due for short-term pullback, but long term is outstanding.<p>
BILL65SAIL : 
How long do you think Uptrend is going to last?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Uptrends impossible to predict, but of the 33 "Dinesisms", number one is that an Uptrend will continue until it actually ends. We prefer to act after trends get penetrated.<p>
KLS29613   : 
Zoltec has been hot lately.  What do you think of it longer term?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Extremely bullish, but getting frothy. Use close stops.<p>
Costello69 : 
What do you think of MCI?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
MCI fairly bullish, but leave stop in at 25.<p>
Serpay     : 
Do you have an opinion on Activision, listed on the Nasdaq?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Activision in long consolidation since September and would not buy until after Upside Breakout.<p>
JohnMattB  : 
What kind of outlook for the transport stocks such as Roadway, Arkansas Best and the industry in general?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Outlook on transport stocks: extremely bullish.<p>
JOHN EE1   : 
That bullish outlook on transports would seem to indicate a drop in rates....no?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
No, good business, when it is good enough, overwhelms the cost of interest rates.<p>
FundWrap   : 
When will gold hit $850 again, and what about the Russian reserves?  Further, just how strong is demand for retail gold in Asia? <p>
DinesLtr   : 
Do not have exact date. When you find out please let me know.<p>
FundWrap   : 
Dines...will do, I am thinking year 2100 : )<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Retail gold in Asia is very strong to hedge against inflated currencies, and is a form of speculation. Plus, buying off their women for whatever they did wrong.<p>
KLS29613   : 
What do you think of OrthoLogic's prospects?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
OrthoLogic - exceptionally bullish with very high Relative Strength and sharply rising sales.<p>
JFlem173   : 
Do you have a favorite among the international integrated oil companies?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Yes. We added Royal Dutch to our Supervised List on 10 Apr 95. Now at 142 with stop in latest Dines Letter at 128.<p>
DWillis782 : 
Do you think gold will reach $500 this year?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
I doubt it, but it will eventually get much higher than that.<p>
Serpay     : 
How high on the long bond , Mr. Dines?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
I'm not clear, but looks higher for the moment.<p>
JHollan115 : 
When will HWP come down to 94 again?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Hewlett Packard (HWP): very bullish on charts and fundamentals, and is a buy, but do not have the exact date of 94.<p>
KLS29613   : 
Where do you see Zytec going? HCI Group gapped up the other day.  Is it starting an?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Zytec another red hot stock, with rising Relative Strength and volume, strong fundamentals. Let your profits run. <p>
WorthOnLne : 
HBrilliant asked earlier this week on the message boards: "The potential financial crisis facing America will cause either massive inflation or deflation. Which do you foresee?  What will its impact be on gold?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Inflation first and deflation later, and flight to gold will be historic as outlined in my book "Mass Psychology."<p>
MaxLea     : 
What about K MART?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Trying to form an Uptrend from lows reached early this year, but this is much too hot a bull market to fool around with retailing stocks.<p>
HKhosravi  : 
Your opinion on PHYCORE -- short term and long term?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Phycore: Bullish, good sales and earnings growth, in consolidation since November, hold with stop at 39.<p>
FundWrap   : 
What is the inflation-adjusted value of gold at today's price versus price of gold in 1990?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Gold adjusted for inflation is at rock-bottom levels before the 1976 bull market.<p>
BILL65SAIL : 
Where do you think Compaq will be two months from now?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Compaq -- terrible chart action. Will avoid.<p>
PrudyPad   : 
Do you foresee a correction soon in the stock market?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
No market correction in sight yet.<p>
KLS29613   : 
Johnson & Johnson has been stagnant all year.  Any idea where it's going?<p>
Giri Lam   : 
Will high grain prices hurt companies like Deere? Because three years of crops have been sold forward? <p>
DinesLtr   : 
Deere: chart is extremely bullish and unless it gets below 40, will hold. As pointed out in my book, don't think, look.<p>
Jeremi2029 : 
What is your opinion of Gandalf Technologies?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Disappointing sales decline, and if you hold it, I would leave stop in at 12, but look at it again if it has an Upside Breakout at 16. <p>
ISSherman  : 
What does "stop at" mean?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
A stop is automatic order to sell if a certain price is reached. Read Engel's book "How to Buy Stocks"<p>
MaxLea     : 
Would you invest in Germany now?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
No. Too much socialism<p>
Dholi7913  : 
Some Neural net programs are calling for DJIA to 4000 near end of the year.  What do you think?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Neural net programs have been wrong all the way up.<p>
UMWAJD     : 
What is your long term view of natural gas stocks?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bullish for the long term, along with whole energy complex, commodities and other real goods such as gold and oil.<p>
Topeca2    : 
Amati Communications (AMTX) --what is good price to buy now?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Exceptionally bullish and would let profits run. <p>
MarkT706   : 
Bell Sports gapped up today, do you see significant upside?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Bell Sports -- no opinion.<p>
Stockdoc   : 
Any opinion on global growth of wireless industry Nextell, Geotek, Ericsson, Airtouch Etc.?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Wireless industry headed for phenomenal growth, and the whole group is a buy. We even like General Motors for that reason.<p>
Stockdoc   : 
GM Hughes and Direct TV still in Uptrend.<p>
TFTAY      : 
What's your view on Semi Stocks like INTC, MOT, NSM, and CY?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Semi stocks -- unenthusiastic with poor tape action. Wait for their bull market to resume.<p>
AHegde     : 
What is your outlook on small and mid cap stocks in the next 3-6 months?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Small stocks still outperforming blue-chips and no change in sight.<p>
RQTBL1     : 
Kindly address the IMF sales question. <p>
DinesLtr   : 
IMF sales are baloney. Note that the US has not sold any gold in a half century and prices it at $42.50 in a show of unreality. Denial is more than merely a river in Egypt.<p>
AReyes2586 : 
What will Apple be at in 6 months?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
I do not like Apple.<p>
Sue1290    : 
Are Webs going to make closed end international funds obsolete, or increase discounts?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Webs will have huge impact on international funds, but won't make them obsolete. <p>
ISSherman  : 
Your opinion of TLAB?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Tellabs in Uptrend, but not overly enthusiastic.<p>
AHegde     : 
What do you make of the inflation worries?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
We flashed a buy signal on the commodity indices in Nov 92 and the public is just discovering it.<p>
HERBASSIST : 
Will silver catch up to gold in its 1980 ratio?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Silver will catch up and surpass gold in coming years. It is dirt cheap at $6.50, with a cost of $8 to bring it out of the ground. Last time I was this bullish on silver was 1960 when silver was at 92.5 cents. Adjusted for inflation, silver is now free.<p>
JLL001     : 
Where can you buy gold coins?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
You can buy gold coins in coin shops. <p>
JPolhe6814 : 
Pharmaceuticals will keep going?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Pharmaceuticals will keep rising. <p>
Giri Lam   : 
Silver has much more industrial use than gold....good economy nec for silver bullion?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Only partially an industrial metal, so has semi-monetary value.<p>
Rebesovice : 
Do you expect TEL MEX go up ?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Am bullish on TEL MEX, but so much overhead. Supply that going will be tough. Can do better elsewhere. <p>
Armhead1   : 
How do you feel about Pepsico?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Pepsico: decent blue-chip to buy, with stop at 56.
You've exhausted me.  This will be the last question. Read The Dines Letter! To subscribe: call 800-84-LUCKY.<p>
HERBASSIST : 
What is your best silver stock?<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Am so sure silver will rise with gold because of the Dines Wolfpack Theory that all precious metals move together, that in 1960 I baptized silver "the poor man's gold." Dangerous to buy only one silver stock so I prefer a basket. Penoles is my favorite, largest underground silver mine in the world and totally unknown to modern investment world as of yet. I first recommended it at $1.95 on 28 May 93 and so far it has only doubled, so plenty of room left. Also, Silver Standard and Pan American.<p>
RQTBL1     : 
To Mr. Dines - I just bought Prechter's book and thought that yours was too expensive; you have just changed my mind. Thanks!<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Prechter' s book is excellent and belongs in everybody's library.  My book is not "too expensive," but you mean the price is too high. At $59 a book it is a bargain because it is the only book on the subject and took me over 30 years to write. Order it at 800-550-1000.<p>
WorthOnLne : 
Thank You all for participating in tonight's chat with Mr. James Dines, of The Dines Letter.<p>
DinesLtr   : 
Ask Worth to have us back again some other time!!! Good Night.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
