WorthJubak : 
How are you thinking about playing merchant banks?<p>
DewDood    : 
Jim, what sectors are up-and-coming?<p>
HChang1000 : 
Hello. Do you think dollar will decline to 110 yen?<p>
WorthJubak : 
Hchang1000: I think the yen is actually stronger than it should be in the short term--12 months.<p>
HChang1000 : 
Thanks , Jim<p>
DewDood    : 
Jim, where do you think the Dow will be at the turn of the century?????<p>
WorthJubak : 
DewDood: you know the rule to success in forecasting--do it often.<p>
Realdonna  : 
Jim:  Think health care is generally a good long term buy and hold considering demographics?<p>
WorthJubak : 
It's hard to bet against an aging US population. But I'd look at some small caps here.<p>
DryClean10 : 
Small caps with a weak dollar? Isn't the thinking the opposite?<p>
WorthJubak : 
Dollar is actually strengthening short term which will hurt the Mercks, Pfizers.<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
I probably missed part of this conversation, but has anybody looked at the DJ Utility average? The DJ Utility average has been a great forecasting tool for interest rates and then stocks.<p>
WorthJubak : 
We look at a measure from Investech that tracks utilities and financials--negative signs.<p>
DewDood    : 
Jim, would you weight your long term retirement savings towards blue chips or small caps????<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
Small caps, mid-caps, balanced, growth & Income- Depending on time frame.<p>
WorthJubak : 
Pooterputt, what about a mix of bonds and small caps?<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
Neg. signs. Gotcha!!  Market looks pretty toppy if economy is beginning to boil<p>
WorthJubak : 
Pooterputt, well I certainly would guess that this is near a top for the brokerage stocks.<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
Be careful of bonds if not holding to maturity. Values can fluctuate rapidly; is shown 1st quarter.<p>
WorthJubak : 
Pooterputt, sure. But you can build a really efficient portfolio using them and aggressive stocks.<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
And, banks?  Only consolidation candidates will outperform if rates stay up. Good point on portfolio to retire.  Just remember to hold bonds to maturity. Small caps go.<p>
WorthJubak : 
I heard Michael Metz recently call banks a zero sum game. Made sense to me.<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
PE's pretty rich.  Lot's of consolidation coming. 1995 was a great year if you had 'em. Cash, treasuries, small caps, mid-caps.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 
Jim, you've written about the dangers of a market bubble. What should investors do to prepare?<p>
WorthJubak : 
If it's a bubble those who buy sound companies for reasonable prices will do best.<p>
ENavori    : 
Jim do you mean sound companies with low PEs around 10?<p>
WorthJubak : 
ENavori, I always wonder why good companies trade for PEs of 10. But Intel did not so long ago.<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
Buy when everybody hates stocks. Sell when everybody loves em.  Now maybe the time!!<p>
WorthJubak : 
It's important to remember too that dividends from stocks have historically helped boost returns.<p>
RDent86967 : 
Jim, what do you think about HCA Columbia as an investment opportunity?<p>
WorthJubak : 
RDent86967, I'd  read a lot of glowing comments on HCA. How rich is the price now?<p>
RDent86967 : 
Sorry, don't know price of HCA, but thanks for comment.<p>
POOTERPUTT :
Total return, meaning dividends & growth will work in any market.
Look at INTEL today. Up 4+.  Has been as low as 52 in the past 60 days. Now 64!! Love it.<p>
WorthJubak : 
Pooterputt, Intel seems to show that long-term investors can profit from the Street's short-term focus.<p>
POOTERPUTT : 
You got that right. Own it at 52, Holding for the long-haul. The street hated it. Too cheap.<p>
RTAnders55 : 
Jim, how do you view Latin America--short and long term? By country? As a whole?<p>
WorthJubak : 
RTAnders55: So hard to judge these countries as a whole. Especially when so much risk is political.<p>
JSHDFR     : 
Good question RTAnders--what about Venezuela?<p>
WorthJubak : 
JSHDFR, institutional guys seem to hate Venezuela because the government is trying to control currency movements.<p>
PERCHING   : 
Jim, UHS is at @52, near high, up 87% in 95. What're your thoughts?<p>
WorthJubak : 
Perching: I'm not familiar with that symbol. What's the company?<p>
PERCHING   : 
