<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 04/10/96 -- John Koten, Editor of Worth magazine</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>04/10/96 -- John Koten, Editor of Worth magazine</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, April 10, Worth's editor, John Koten, joined Worth OnLine for a live CONFERENCE CALL. During the hour-long chat show, Koten discussed the market, investing, and the economy with readers. <p>
WorthEdit1 : 
We are pleased to have Worth's editor, John Koten with us here tonight.<p>
ConsultLar : 
Good evening<p>
JohnK333   : 
Hi.  JohnK333 is my screen name.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 
John, let me start off the discussion by bringing up a topic I'm sure is on everyone's mind. With the recent market mahem, many are wondering, as the May cover story asks, "Should This Market Be Trusted?"<p>
JohnK333   : 
There's good reason to be worried about the market right now.<p>
ConsultLar : 
This may be a significant momentum shift.<p>
JohnK333   : 
We have been in the midst of a historic runnup in stock prices.  There's rarely been anything like it. It's fairly easy to understand how we got to where we are.  A lot of the runnup has also occurred amidst a long-term secular decline in interest rates. 
But now, it looks like the decline in interest rates is bottoming out.  So the question is, can the market keep going up, or is it already overvalued?<p>
ConsultLar : 
Some parts of the market are like Vegas.<p>
SSGuest    : 
It's foreign money that is keeping the US afloat.<p>
JohnK333   : 
I agree with SSGuest, to an extent.  One thing that is keeping the market up...or has been...has been the lack of a better place to put it. And that is really the big question everyone faces right now.  The stock market is sky high.  But where is a better place to go?<p>
JSHDFR     : 
What do you think about prospects in Europe?<p>
JohnK333   :
I am less than excited about Europe. European business is about ten years behind what has been happening in this country.<p>
JSHDFR     : 
Do you agree with Rogers, then, that Africa is the place to go?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I would only go to Africa on Safari.<p>
ConsultLar : 
People have shot memories and want 20-30% returns to keep going.<p>
Matt5001  :
If the US stock market resembles Vegas, where does that put "emerging markets"?<p>
SSGuest  :
Does that mean we can play the European markets like it's 1986?<p>
JMoff0456:
I have heard the Pacific rim, minus Japan, is a good investment. <p>
JohnK333   :
I think Jim Rogers may be right. But I think it would require a huge amount of homework to know the best places to put your money. SSGuest-I would, to an extent. I think Europe is going to be a great investment down the road. But I think Japan may be a very good place to go. I think it will move up faster and sooner than Europe. But there are still big banking problems to work out in Japan. That seems easier, to me, though, than a major revolution in the way of doing business that Europe still needs to go through. <p>
JSHDFR  :
Do you see all of Asia as a good place to invest, or just Japan?<p>
JohnK333  :
I like a lot of Asia. I think it is a better place to go than Europe. <p>
DDWARE  :
How about Thailand?<p>
JohnK333  :
I don't know enough about Thailand to answer your question. I just sent a reporter to Thailand to find out more about it, though.<p>
DDWARE  :
Thanks.<p>
ConsultLar :
What about investing in bonds?<p>
JohnK333  :
We have a good column in the latest issue by Susan Lee about how to invest in bonds. <p>
ConsultLar  :
Thanks.<p>
SSGuest  :
Do you think the Commerce department will survive Ron Brown's death? And does it matter?<p>
JohnK333  :
I am not sure how well the Commerce Department will survive Bill Clinton.<p>
ConsultLar : 
John any specifics here at home, "invest in what you know"?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I can't talk about specific stocks for reasons that only Worth's lawyers can explain. And nothing I say should be construed as personal investment advice.  I don't know your individual needs well enough.<p>
ConsultLar :
Understand.<p>
GeorgeJW   : 
I've heard mixed reviews on health care, Baxter etc. What are your thoughts?<p>
DDWARE     : 
How about specific industries?<p>
ConsultLar : 
But what about market sectors?<p>
BEAN11163  : 
HI JohnK. You guys are doing a great job at Worth.<p>
JohnK333   : 
Thank you, Bean.
Regarding sectors or areas. Jeff Vinik is now making a huge bet on mid-cap stocks.<p>
BEAN11163  : 
Is Fidelity Megellan engaging in market timing?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Bean.  I think so, yes.<p>
Mmcnally1  : 
Will mutual fund holders ever panic out of the market and at what level of the Dow will they?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I think two things will stop fund investors from a panic.  1. Stubborness. 2.  The fact that so much money is now coming into funds through 401(k) programs.
At the big fund companies....as much as half of the money they are getting comes from defined benefit programs.<p>
JOglejr    : 
What do you think will happen with telecomm stocks, specifically BellSouth?<p>
BBryant527 : 
I don't know, can I trust this market????<p>
WorthEdit1 : 
Sorry, JOglejr, John has explained that he cannot answer questions about specific stocks or the Worth lawyers will come after him.<p>
RHalp56026 : 
But isn't the stock market beginning to look like a confidence game?<p>
JohnK333   : 
RHalp56026--How long can this market ignore soaring commodities?
By the way, I am not saying that I think the market will go up or down.  I wouldn't want to insult anyone's intelligence in this room.
What I mean: No one really knows what the stock market is going to do next. And I wouldn't believe anyone who says otherwise.<p>
BEAN11163  : 
Is it not the policy of Fidelity to not engage in market timing?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Bean.....it depends upon how you define market timing.<p>
Mitzrayim  : 
John, do you think bonds and stocks can de-couple? When?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Stocks and bonds are going to have to decouple if the market is going to go higher over the coming year.<p>
Phil517    : 
Having survived 10/87, I think it's the pro's who'll panic, not us little guys.  Agree JohnK?<p>
Mitzrayim  : 
Having survived 1974, it looks like 1974 is starting again.<p>
DINAROB    : 
Mitz--why?<p>
SteveS3184 : 
1974--oil embargo--the start of hyperinflation...not really like today.<p>
JohnK333   : 
I agree that there is a lot of reason to be pessimistic.  I thought the market would wait until after the election to crash.  But in some ways, I think, the election may already be over.<p>
Bugsy40    : 
John, Hi. Who will be the better president for the market: Clinton or Dole?<p>
JohnK333  :
I think Clinton is going to win. I don't think Dole offers enough of an alternative. I also think it is hard to tell what Clinton is going to be like as a lame duck.<p>
BEAN11163  :
Oh god.<p>
DINAROB   :
Any thoughts about the retail sector?<p>
OligoNuk  :
Is the market on a fault line--have we felt tremors or is the worse yet to come?<p>
STOUFFMAN  : 
John are you recommending to pull out of stocks?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I think whether or not you want to be in stocks depends upon your time horizon. I would not want to be in stocks--at least not heavily--for money that I needed a year from now. I would stay in stocks if I had a long-term time horizon. I also would pay a lot of attention to my portfolio right now--making sure that the stocks that I hold represent good values in terms of the company's fundamentals.<p>
K3321   : 
The baby boomers must stay fully invested if the majority expect to have enough money to retire.<p>
BBryant527  :
John, are you currently bullish on the present market or not?<p>
JohnK333   : 
For the short term...the best place to go is in a bank CD.  That's for all time horizon's up to one year. <p>
OligoNuk  :
When is that bill going to go through that lowers capital gains taxes?<p>
Mitzrayim :
Oligo, never.<p>
BEAN11163  :
Right again, Mitz.<p>
JohnK333  :
The capital gains tax cut looks dead right now. Which I think is really bad news. <p>
BEAN11163  : 
John K, if Magellan is market timing, then Vinik is pretty Bearish.<p>
K3321      : 
Nothing ventured, nothing gained.<p>
JohnK333   : 
K3321--you are correct. It is the only chance they have of earning a great retirement. Vinik is bearish. He has been since the end of last year. <p>
BBryant527   :
Which investing styles could be winners in the present market?<p>
JohnK333   :
I'll answer BBryant's question. I think fundamental investing is a really good approach right now...and there are two things I would pay a lot of attention to. First, I think historic price-to-earnings ratios are a good thing to look at when valuing stocks in this market. A good idea might be to avoid any stock rating at a price-earnings ratio above its highest average annual p/e ratio going back to, say, 1979. Second, set a target price at which you will sell the stock. You can do this by estimating the annual growth rate for the companies earnings over the next five years by using a source like Value Line. Take that figure an apply it to per share earnings. Use the historic price-to-earnings ratios I mentioned before to caluculate how high the stock might get if future earnings grow as expected and if the market rewards the stock with a high p/e. Basically, that's your new target selling price.
Of course, you need to monitor the numbers along the way to make sure your target still makes sense, or if you need to readjust the caluculation.<p>
BBryant527 : 
OK, so you would look for stocks with low P/Es relative to where they have traded in the last 20 years? Sounds like very reasonable advice. Thanks much.<p>
Mitzrayim  : 
JohnK, what about if inflation heats up?  Doesn't that change the whole ball game?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Yes....inflation would change the whole ball game. It would cause interest rates to rise....Greenspan to throw on the brakes.  And the stock market to tumble.  Commodities prices are sending a warning right now about inflation. But they don't gurantee a return of inflation. Because they don't account for as big a percentage of what we buy as they used to. And because they will have to rise a lot before things get so expensive that workers start asking for pay increase.<p>
JSHDFR     : 
Will you post this chat tomorrow like you did with Nawrocki's? I missed a part. Thanks.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 
JSHDFR--yes, we post the transcripts of all our chats. Thanks for coming by!<p>
OligoNuk   : 
So it looks like gold might be a good investment after all?<p>
KADAB      : 
JOHNK...When do you see interest rates falling again?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I don't really see interest rates coming down significantly for a long time.<p>
KADAB      : 
Thanks.<p>
Mitzrayim  : 
JohnK, if "they" don't account for as big a percentage of what we buy, than the increases in commodity prices will be more easily absorbed-- leading to higher prices, no?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Mitz...I am not quite sure I understand your question.<p>
Mitzrayim  : 
JohnK, if corn only makes up a small part of a loaf of bread, than an increase in corn prices would be more easily passed along, leading to even higher corn prices - maybe?<p>
JohnK333   : 
No.  Mitz, I think that because higher commodity prices will be more easily absorbed...prices of finished goods will not rise as much. We didn't raise the price of the magazine when paper prices shot up.<p>
Mitzrayim  : 
JohnK, if demand for finished goods does not decrease, won't prices on finished goods continue to rise?<p>
RalphH6397 : 
Johnk333 you didn't have to as subscriptions increased.<p>
Oilstar    : 
That's because Peter Lynch took a pay cut to absorb the paper cost increase!<p>
JohnK333   : 
We don't pay Peter Lynch at all.<p>
Jplank1    : 
Thanks, JohnK for the chat and good advice.<p>
JohnK333   : 
You are welcome Jplank1.<p>
DwightB620 : 
JohnK333...would you say that it is still a good time to roll over in to stock mutual funds?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I think it is still a good time to be in stocks if you have a time horizon of longer than 1 or 2 years.<p>
RalphH6397 : 
JohnK333--comment on the role of money supply on inflation worries. Doesn't seem to be a problem.<p>
TOWERAM    : 
JohnK333, How much of the current market environment is being driven by hedge fund speculation vs fundamental issues?<p>
RalphH6397 : 
TOWERAM, my guess is more than we realize.<p>
REH1059449 : 
JohnK -- where do you stand re load vs. no-load?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I like no-load funds a lot better than load funds.  Very few fund managers can earn the loads they charge giving better performance.<p>
REH1059449 : 
John -- doesn't it make more sense to evaluate funds by LT performance and not expenses which are included in the performance stats?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Yes....REH1. Still, over time....the expenses tend to eat into the returns.<p>
JWatk28989 : 
John333, do you feel think that the global market is more positive than the U.S. based on recent<p>
JohnK333   : 
I think the U.S. market is still more positive than the global market. But I think the global market will beat the U.S. over really long time horizons....like 10-15 years.<p>
JWatk28989 : 
Thanks.<p>
GarySpFc   : 
JohnK333,  How do the various international regions look in the near term?<p>
FINPOWNEWS : 
What is the overall view of the Dow Thursday and Friday?<p>
JohnK333  :
I would say people are nervous about the Dow...for Thursday and Friday.  This hasn't been a good week.<p>
DwightB620 : 
JohnK333...Do you predict the end of the Bull Market direction soon?<p>
Hathgolf   : 
After 3--how do you see the next 2 weeks with all the earnings coming?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Some people think the market is going to 6500 soon.  I think it will get there, but I now think it may take longer than most market analysts think. And I think it may drop aways below where it is now before it rises again.<p>
JFlynn4940 : 
Isn't it a good time for global funds?<p>
JohnK333   : 
It is a good time for global funds if you are really scared about the very short-run for the U.S. markets or if you want to invest for the very long haul.<p>
Peretz42   : 
What do you think of gold?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I think gold is a good long term investment because of high worldwide demand for gold.<p>
StephenKoc : 
What do think of the energy sector?<p>
JJohnK333   : 
I like the energy sector.  I wouldn't be surprised to see higher oil prices given. What other commodity prices are doing right now?<p>
TSAD700    : 
Any thoughts on options market such as sugar or crude?<p>
JohnK333   : I can't give advice here about the options markets.  You need to be a daily player to mess with that stuff.<p>
FINPOWNEWS : 
What about 7% on the bonds tommorrow. Which way once line is crossed will it head?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Back in 72, higher grain prices were the first sign of rising inflation. Oil prices came second--although everyone only remembers the high oil prices.<p>
TOWERAM    : 
72-74 inflation was sparked by oil.<p>
DwightB620 : 
Thank you JohnK333 for your input and time!<p>
Cymbion    : 
JohnK...too much money chasing little earnings growth=much volatility?  Next year's outlook?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Stock prices are probably ahead of earnings now.  I agree.<p>
GarySpFc   :
JohnK333,  I'm still curious as to your thoughts as to what will happen when mainland China takes over Hong Kong?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Regarding China.  I don't know.<p>
HPHolcomb  : 
John, what's your prediction on interest rates?<p>
JohnK333   : 
I already gave a prediction on interest rates. The general direction is up.<p>
TOWERAM    : 
Again, what is your justification for higher rates?<p>
Matt5001   : 
Toweram, two words: Alan and Greenspan.<p>
JohnK333   : 
From here on out.  I think the long-term decline in interest rates has pretty much run its course. Also...right now Greenspan has no political incentive to do anything, to stimulate the economy.  He's a guy who believes in zero inflation.  And we still don't have that!<p>
RYackee    : 
What stock would you buy right now for a wild flyer?<p>
JohnK333   : 
If you want to find a wild flyer read the feature on the search for the next Microsoft in our June issue....coming to your homes and newsstands soon. I also think microcap stocks are a good place to look for wild flyers.<p>
Dan WRBQ   : 
John, is now a good time to sell some shares in stock funds to raise 50% cash?<p>
JohnK333   : 
Dan WRBQ--Maybe.....I would say if you are older...yes.  If you are young, I'd just stay in the market and ride it out.<p>
JohnK333   : 
I'd like to thank everyone for coming here tonight.  I'd like to do this more often and figure out a way to answer so many different questions all at the same time. Your questions have been very stimulating and thoughtful.  Exactly what I expect of people who read our magazine.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 
Thank you, John, for conducting such a spirited chat! And thank you everyone for your great questions. We'll be hosting chat shows weekly--check out the site for more information. And subscribe to our *FREE* weekly E-mail newsletter, "A Week's Worth." It has a schedule of our daily online-exclusive features, special live events, and stories you won't find on the site. Thank you all.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

