	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>04/09/96 - Global Investing into the Year 2000</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Recently William E. Holzer, Managing Director of Scudder, Stevens & Clark, Inc., Boston, spoke to a group of investors about "Global Investing into the Year 2000." The event, which took place on April 9 in Boston, was sponsored by Worth and Giorgio Armani. Following is a transcript from the presentation:<p>
Missy Godfrey: Good evening. Thank you, thank you. My name is Missy Godfrey, and I'm the publisher of Worth magazine. On behalf of everyone at Worth, I'd like to welcome you this evening. I'd like to thank everyone at Armani for entertaining us in this spectacular space, it really is quite lovely. We're very pleased to be part of this program. For those of you who are familiar with Worth magazine, you know that we pride ourselves on bringing you financial intelligence each and every month. We particularly enjoy bringing all that to life when we can--to bring the experts to you live and bring our readers together to share in their insights. <p>
And it is with great pleasure this evening that we bring you one of the true experts in the field. We'll be hearing William Holzer, who is the managing director of Scudder, Stevens and Clark. He is the product leader for the firm's global investment products, overseeing the firm's management of global mandate portfolios. He is the lead portfolio manager of the firm's global products and a member of the firm's currency committee. As I mentioned, he is one of the all-stars in the field. I'm sure that's why you all came out this evening. And so, without further ado, I'd like to introduce William Holzer. Welcome.<p>
William Holzer: 
Thank you for that kind introduction, and it's very nice to be with you all this evening. I have a few comments, but before that, I thought that I would share something: When I was a little boy, my father told us the story, he comes from southern Germany, and he told us the story about the local baker's shop. The local baker Mr. Katzenberger took on a new apprentice. And the new apprentice was as keen as mustard, and he completed all his tasks in double-quick time and always reported back to the baker and said, "Mr. Katzenberger, what can I do now, Mr. Katzenberger, what can I do now?" And he'd send him off and make him clean the windows or take inventory, etc. . . and it went on for quite a while, until eventually the baker lost his temper and said, "Go hang your backside out of the window!" And with that, the apprentice disappeared. But he came back some hours later and the baker said, "Where have you been?" and he said, "I did what you told me to do." And the baker said, "No." And he said, "What did the people say?" And he said, "Oh why they said, 'Good morning, Herr Katzenberger.'" <p>
I guess the relevance of that, if there is any relevance at all, is that I was hanging out in my office reading the newspaper, when somebody dropped by and said, "Willie, it's time for you to think global, forget about all this international stuff. Think global." And I guess that was a challenge. Tonight I've been asked to talk about the global outlook through the year 2000. <p>
Of course, it's always best to take one's cue from history, and I thought I'd step back a little while to put the foundations down for the talk, and I'd start in the middle ages and do well. Back then, when people came off the land, when there was an agricultural surface that allowed them to do so, they went to live in cities so they could specialize in trades to become candle makers or carpenters or whatever. And if they did that one thing all day, they could be more productive. And to do that all day, they needed their food, their bakers near, their better stores nearby so they didn't have to interrupt their work. So the village or the town was the unit organization that supported the economies, the expert economies, in the state of the day. <p>
And then we got steel works and textile mills, so we needed countries, because they need bigger markets. Then we got the United States where they put down, I guess in 1861, the Union Pacific Railroad which linked both coasts. So you could get in the age of the railroads, all the products -- the wheat and the iron and steel -- around the country, and you could have an integrated market once one other thing happened: once you had financial markets, the commodity market in Chicago, the financial markets in Boston and New York. <p>
Now, the markets generated prices and the prices told the producers what the consumers wanted and the prices told the entrepreneurs what the investors wanted. So you had the perfect setup here, so that the United States could exploit the economies of scale of the day, because they had information, because prices are information. And if you want to understand that, think about Russia. In Russia, they have no market, therefore they have prices, therefore they have no information and in the end of course, they've got no economy. <p>
So now we've come a long way down the road, to perhaps a few years ago. Now, something else has happened, the technology has moved on. So what are the technologies that are relevant? What is the unit of organization that exploits those economies? Our answer is that it's all about telecommunications and computers and the type of organization that exploits the economies of scale that those technologies offer: it is the global corporation, which quite simply, is the corporation that is organized to produce anywhere, to sell anywhere and to raise capital anywhere. <p>
So, that was easy, that was just one morning's work at the desk. The first morning. The conclusion was, that all we needed to do was look around the world and find out which were the corporations that were organized globally or that were growing themselves in that way, because those would prove to be the best investments. And kind of a funny thing happened then. We got the list together, and the list all spoke English. The great global corporations of the world, and think of the one's that you're familiar with, they all speak English. Even the Swedish ones, if you go to visit them, business is done in English. US companies, UK companies, Australian companies, even New Zealand had a couple, New Zealand has 3.5 million people and 62 million sheep and they can still boast a global corporation, which is more than plenty of European corporations could boast. <p>
What was the explanation? The first explanation was that these places had inhospitable home bases, all English-speaking countries have loads of inflation, people consume too much, they import too much and they're fairly skilless people in general. But that didn't wash, we took it a step further and really the answer is a little bit philosophical. But what the answer is, is that these are the countries of the world where the rights of the individual are paramount. And where the rights of the individual are paramount, you let them speak through the marketplace so they generate prices and information. And that optimizes the production of goods. <p>
So, what about the other places in the world? Think about the places in the world that are not like the United States. Where obligation and duty are the dominating philosophy. Where they keep all their savings safely at home, they don't use it to consume stuff and import stuff, yet they insist on exporting stuff and inflation is definitely a no-no. And those places are the places that don't have global corporations. <p>
So far, we've established the definitions so we can go forward and the definitions are: The global corporation that can do anything, anywhere. And these two types of countries in this one global world, and we'll characterize those types of countries as the Light side, and let that be us; and we'll characterize the other types of countries where duty and obligation and where the politicians and the bureaucrats allocate the resources, not the marketplace, as the Dark side; and think about the world that way. <p>
So let's go to the year 2000 now. Think about change from here. Let's do two types of change, let's do quick-paced change and slow-paced change. Let's think about the slow one first. The thing that drives the world through this price mechanism where people speak freely to the producers and the entrepreneurs is what people want and value most. The group that's most powerful is going to make its voice felt most greatly. <p>
In the '80s, it was the Yuppies, the population bulge, and it wasn't restricted to the United States but it also goes for Europe and, in a modified form, Japan also. They all wanted their houses at the same time, so it inflated the price of the houses and then they went to the bank and leveraged those houses and filled them full of consumer goodies, and that's what created the great demand for the Japanese producers and those with a lot of the imports that we took in, of course, cars and VCRs and all the rest. Now, think about those people. They were a little bit older, what did they want most? My guess is that they want a healthy, wealthy retirement, and to get that, they'll have to save more, if they save more, they have to spend less. Think about that, that's important when you consider the state of the world today, because the great wave of money that's coming to the Mutual Fund industry, doesn't necessarily represent new savings, it represents the move of liquidity from bank deposits into long term investments. <p>
The United States saves 4 percent of GDP and the house rides along. The house inflation looked after people's savings and financial welfare and now the inflation they created for themselves in the stock market is doing the same. And if we do save, where are we going to apply the savings? Well, of course, that's why we reinvented the emerging markets that we used to call the LDCs (the Lesser Developed Countries). We've given them a new name. And we need them. Why? Because if we're not spending, we need somebody to do that spending, and they've got the mirror-image demographics. They've got young people that want their first marketplace job, that want their first sets of material possessions. There's a beautiful match here. But you need a matchmaker of course. In former times, the banks tried to be the matchmaker and recycle the Petrol dollars into those parts of the world to get them to grow. And, having worked as a credit analyst, I know how efficient we were at getting that money down to Latin America. <p>
The catch was, of course, that we never got any of the principle back and that's why the thing never worked. But we're trying again now, and we've got these global corporations that can get the money out of global markets, and get the money into those places. We've got managements to make sure they don't rip the money off and stick it in Swiss bank accounts, but actually put the factories up. And these managements are responsible to shareholders. So that tells you a little bit about the next few years, I hope. And there's another thing, the one that I referred to earlier, fast-moving change. And that's why you've got to understand the difference between the Light side of the world and the Dark side of the world. Because, on the Light side of the world, that's where all the inventiveness is, where you unleash the possibilities of the individual. <p>
The analysts dragged me kicking and screaming to Silicon Valley, and it's an amazing place. It's like the center of the world, these people know no limits to the amount of technology they can unleash. They know no limits to distance or commercial possibilities. And these are people, the managements, that come from all over the place; they're not just Americans, but they're people that come to live and work there, to participate in this huge amount of wealth creation. But of course, the wealth creation isn't a gift. What goes with it is wealth destruction. We have to free-up the resources to give these new companies that are being born. And that's socially disruptive and we create companies in garages and they compete with other companies in garages, and I guess some of the garages eventually fall down. <p>
Now, to understand the Dark side, what they do, well, they approach a little bit differently because they've got different relationships to one another, different obligations, as we mentioned earlier. And I guess they're not too inventive, historically. A Japanese analyst, I guess he nearly fell down dead when I said, "The last thing the Japanese invented was the tea ceremony," and it wasn't meant to be an offensive comment, but I guess what the process is, is observing what is happening on the Light side of the world and seeing what succeeds and what fails, and selecting the best of things, then allocating to the selective few. The bureaucrats they say, "You NEC or you Fujitsu, you can develop this chip or this computer," or in Germany, perhaps tell the big rich electricity companies that they can develop the new telephone systems. That's very efficient, it can be done without laying people off, they can be moved within an organization, and this is a very efficient way to run a society of course. <p>
Now, the other part of it that's not so good, let's keep within the argument's bounds, is that the bureaucrats and the politicians call the shots. They don't listen to the marketplace, and then the marketplace doesn't speak, and the marketplace can't receive those global signals that allow one to exploit the economies of being global. The economies are scared of being global. That's a problem, so that's where we find ourselves today, with the United States having a huge bull market, where it's unleashed the technologies, it's benefited by reallocation of resources from the old companies as they wind up and sell assets, and that money is transferred through the stock markets to the great new company. But that has largely taken place and they've been watching and they're beginning to see what the possibilities are, and I would submit that these are the places in the world where there are great possibilities of appreciation, stock markets, if one takes the four or five year view. <p>
It said on the little piece of paper I received, that I would be shown around the store when I arrived here, and I was and it's a beautiful place. And it reminds me of when Einstein went to heaven, being such a special guest, he was met by some people and they introduced him to some fellows and these fellows said, "meet Mr. A, he's got an IQ of 350," and Einstein said, "Mm, we must talk about theology some time," and they went on and introduced him to individual B, with an IQ of 250, "Oh we must talk about thermonuclear dynamics a little bit when I've got a moment," and they went on a little further and he met individual C, with an IQ of about 50-60, and Einstein says, "Hello, pleased to meet you, how'd the stock market do today?"<p>
So I don't know too much about the future, but a little analysis that I've gone through suggests to me as a global investor that companies that look around the world and harvest savings as people change their lifestyles, will prosper, they organize themselves well. It strikes me that companies in any industry, that organize themselves to do business globally will do very well. It strikes me that emerging markets must succeed. If we're not going to consume, they must consume. Who knows how mature their political infrastructures are, how well they can absorb the cash they take in. <p>
But, just as we saw the meltdown in Mexico in 1994, that was followed by a second wave of money, admittedly donated by Mr. Clinton, but of course, he understood there was more to lose by Mexico going under. And that was proved true time and time again, until the experiment works, I guess. Over the next few years, I think the Dark side countries may have better investment policies, especially Germany, where there is huge hidden wealth in their stock market, where they're only beginning to do the rationalization of their big old companies, that we embarked upon in the UK. and in the United States fifteen or twenty years ago. They've got new technologies to pick up and bolt on to their old outdated technologies.<p>
I thank you very much for your attention.<p>
Q:
You mentioned Mexico. Mexico seems to be a scenario where everything gets worse and worse. Do you think we've reached the bottom in Mexico or do you think at some point there will be another grey cloud or perhaps a silver lining? <p>
A:
That's a big question. My analysis of Mexico in the broader sense, would be that they have very much a Dark side economy, an elitist economy in which a small group of people harvest most of the fruit. And, a lot of that fruit is not reinvested in Mexico, but reinvested in other places. It's therefore difficult for me to understand how they will achieve self-sustaining growth. They've had a number of chances, if one goes back through history. The second point would be that its culture is dominated by a thought process that gold and land represent wealth, and if you invest your profits in gold and land, they don't create further production, and they don't create further demand. So, I find it very difficult to understand that Mexico as a country can have a self-sustaining dynamic. I can, however, understand that there is abundant labor that is considerably less expensive than that here, and we will want to take advantage of that, as corporate investors. Do we think that the thing has gotten to the bottom? If one can assume that the politics of Mexico will remain stable, it probably would have. I don't make any assumptions on the politics in Mexico given incidents that are reported. <p>
Q:
Would you comment on the dollar in the next five years? <p>
A:
In the introduction, it was mentioned that I'm on the currency committee, but it wasn't mentioned why I'm on the currency committee. I'm on the currency committee because I opened my mouth and said I didn't think anybody could forecast currencies, to which they said, "Right, you're on the committee, get to it." The idea that I mentioned earlier that people in the United States will tend, on balance, to save more in the future than they have in the past. That should bode well for the dollar, which starts at a very cheap base in a global context, and if the general health of the corporations in the United States is an indicator, that would support the argument. So, if I had to bet, I would tell you that the US. dollar would be a stronger currency. <p>
Q:
You were talking a while about Germany, and I'm not quoting, about an untapped resource, or what might be happening there? Could you indulge me a little about what you think might be happening? What do you think is happening in the German corporate sector, the stock market?<p>
A:
My appreciation of it, is Germany understands that the way that it's run its economy in the past, is not a suitable way of running the economy in the future.  In the past, they had huge personal savings in the household sector which were redirected through the system to pay for the absorption of East Germany. Therefore, they no longer feel quite as comfortable with their future as they did before and they have further concerns; their population is aging very rapidly indeed, and they have the implicit demand somewhere to create jobs in those eastern countries. Why? Because if they don't, a lot of those people would like to live in Germany, and have the right to, and that would put a strain on their social security systems. So, they realize they must change, but creating a consensus in a big country like that is difficult and takes a long time. The Bundesbank understands this and says we must deregulate this economy, not lower interest rates to create jobs, but that will take a while. <p>
Meanwhile, the corporate sector has understood what's at stake. Why? Because they compete with other global corporations, Byron Hertz competes with Dow and DuPont and ICI and all the rest in the world, and they can't let the rest of these companies get ahead by having access to global capital markets, and let the whole thing slip and slide. So they've watched what the Swiss are doing. The Swiss in their own quiet little way have made rapid progress in changing a culture that was very, very dark and hid everything and didn't have open accounting, or what used to appeal to global investors. <p>
Why? Because everybody from Latin America hid their money in Switzerland, and they had interest free deposits from wars going back to the Napoleonic war, but things changed. The corporations got so big, the Sandover, the Ceiba-Geigy, and the Nestle's of this world, they realized the Swiss capital market was longer big enough. They were global corporations, that appealed to global capital markets. <p>
And they've opened themselves up to investors, "we'll give you the information, you can assess the prospects and you'll probably like what you see." And they've done this and it's been beneficial to stop. And the Germans, who are only a little way down the once polluted Rhine from Oslo have seen it and they're making their move. And the German stock market is fascinating because it represents not the German economy, but it represents the technologies of the 1950's and 60's, the airlines, the department stores, the plumbing companies, they're all technologies that are pass and they understand that they must come up to date, and they are doing the reorganization and restructuring, and it's just begun. <p>
Q:
Are there any emerging markets that we or I do not like? The second part of the question is do we take a top-down approach to assessment of those countries and those investment possibilities?<p>
A:
The first part of the answer is, that Mommy said, if you can't speak well of somebody, don't speak of them at all. The second part of the answer is probably more interesting, because it's a topic with which I and, I guess, we struggle. You know, they're emerging markets, because since time began, they've always failed so far. And they used to be called LDC's (Lesser Developed Countries) so, what's going to make them successful now, just because investors throw money at them? Will they be socially and politically mature enough to usefully employ that money, to recirculate it, to create a demand for the next set of capital investments in those places? That's a very challenging question. So the top-down approach says you do evaluate the social maturity of those places, of their approach. So, that's one observation. <p>
A second observation that might be useful is to remember where this money is coming from. This capital is coming from our savings, and we get it there in one of two ways: either through global portfolios, for example, where we can choose from around the world, or through global companies, Proctor & Gamble or Coca-Cola, and they can look at these places and assess the risks and reward implicit in the investment, and I would suggest to you that when Coca-Cola or Proctor & Gamble or IBM goes to the negotiating table with the governments of X, Y, Z little country in Latin America or Asia, the negotiating power lies with the global corporation, and they will seek to invest there, in order to get out more than they take in. <p>
If that's true, how do you successfully develop an emerging market? I don't know the answer, but it was part of the question, and let me give you the favorite one we have is South Korea. Now, that got started on a shoestring as the US left the money because of the Cold War. But once that initial impetus had been created, it's been a closed economy. They don't welcome foreign investment, they try to repel it. Because if they create something good and something that will prosper, they'll want it themselves, of course. So to invite all comers to buy your assets doesn't indicate much good faith in your own assessment of your own chances, does it? So, that closed economy thrives because all the surplus that's created in the productive process is channeled back to capital investment. The main idea to invest every little, and they don't care where the money comes from, as long as it's capital investment, and they've climbed that technological ladder from sneakers and textiles, right to the point where Samsung's the world's leading top producer, and that's one market. <p>
And, I guess China does some interesting things that hold promise. They don't just sit down at the negotiating table with the first guy who shows up, they always invite one from Europe, one from the US and one from Japan. And they chisel them down, so there isn't enough left over that perhaps they can retain something. They've got a very Dark side regime, I don't think we need reminding. So, perhaps that'll work. But we shouldn't be over-optimistic or over-simple about the possibilities, we're riding the crest of the wave, and we shouldn't mix up fashion with good investment.<p>
Q:
Would you share your opinion on the Japanese market economy?<p>
A:
The assessment is that in the 30 or 40 years since the second world war, the formula that made that an unbelievably successful achievement in terms of physical wealth creation, that formula no longer works. Why? Because, they've become such a big portion of the total of the global economy, they therefore need another formula. The other formula would be because they are so large to be an integral part of the global economy. To achieve that, a couple of things, kind of big things, have got to happen. Firstly, the old ways have got to give ways to the new ways, and a younger generation with a different outlook has got to take the helm. And, that's the beginning. It's easy when one interviews government officials, there used to be an old grey and indulgent double-talk, now they're young and to the point when they address comments to you. That's so one can have a changing in the order in the bureaucracy in the political sphere, and that seems to be going kind of slowly. <p>
The other thing that's got to happen, is Japan has got to integrate itself into the global markets. But of course, the Yen is so high and prices are so high in Japan, that if they did that, prices of a lot of things would go down very quickly and cause a lot of distress. Vested interests wouldn't be too pleased. So, now for that to happen certainly would be disastrous for everybody concerned. So, it's got to happen over a long period. So we're going through a multiyear adjustment process as Japan invents its formula and caters to the new circumstances. <p>
Q:
The West German shared stock prices have been doing quite well in the last 12 months, you say.<p>
A:
It's the very first step in a long process that will go a long way, there's lots of hidden wealth, there's lots of reserves upon which to draw. I went some years ago, to the Munich Reinsurance Company in Munich, and we visited them in their head office which looked like a palace, it was such a beautiful building. And, I commented that they must indeed have taken over an old palace, and he said, "No, we had these headquarters built in 19 something-or-other for the company when it was established," and I said, "Well, was it in the balance sheet?" He said, "Oh, it's been written down to one Mark," and I said, "What, one Deutschmark?", and he said, "No, one Reich mark." <p>
Thank you very much, ladies and gentlemen. <p>
Missy Godfrey: And who said finance can't be entertaining? That was more than entertaining though, I think it was informative and insightful for everyone. I hope you all enjoyed it as much as I certainly did, sharing in his information, and the intelligence that he brings to his investing. <p>
Good night.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
