	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>04/02/96 -- Tom Nawrocki, Worth magazine columnist </b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>BALLPARK FIGURES</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Tuesday, April 2, 1996, Worth OnLine columnist Tom Nawrocki chatted with readers live during CONFERENCE CALL: BALLPARK FIGURES. The one and one-half hour event covered topics ranging from paying college athletes to boycotting stadium concession stands. Follows is a transcript of this event. <p>
WorthEdit1 : 	
We are very pleased to have Worth OnLine columnist Tom Nawrocki with us tonight. Tom has written about everything from office betting pools to interleague play in his online-exclusive column, "Ballpark Figures." In fact, Tom, you had a rather controversial stand on the interleague play issue. Why did you think it was a pointless gesture?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The marquee matchups between, say, the Yanks and Mets will take place every three years. Most of the interleague games will be of the Expos/Rangers or Pirates/Twins variety. These don't promise to be any more popular than the rivalries we currently have, which will occur less frequently with interleague play. And the TV money figures to be less than expected.<p>
WorthEdit1 :    	
Why are they doing it then?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The owners are desperate for a way to compete with other sports. They basically feel the need to make a splash. I don't think, four years from now, there's going to be much excitement about interleague games.<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
I love baseball, but the owners need to make some money.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The owners are making plenty of money.<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
Well, think about it: six , eight , one , million goes to everyone on the roster, then lease for the stadium.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
But they're raking in enough to cover those salaries easily. Stadium leases will be dropping steadily as more cities compete for teams. In Baltimore, the old Browns are basically getting paid to play there.<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
Well, I know that ticket prices have gone up, but with an average of19,000 people, they need money. I work for the owner of the Detroit tigers. Our area needs to make money so he will not lose his butt.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
What do you do for the owner of the Tigers?<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
No, part of the same company.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Isn't Detroit going to build a new stadium for the Tigers?<p>
Ray4611011 : 	I do not know.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, do you think the players and owners will reach a long term agreement, and will it include a luxury tax?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Probably just a token luxury tax. The owners can't impose their position anymore after last year's judicial ruling so they'll have to compromise.<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
Why don't they market their team like merchandise?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
That's a good point, Ray. Especially during the strike, the owners badmouthed their own product!<p>
Ray4611011 : 	Yes, and you saw what happened last year.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Would Mike Ilitch talk about how bad Little  Caesar's Pizza is?<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
I do not think so; that is his bread and butter.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
But Jerry Reinsdorf said he wouldn't pay to see the White Sox play. If he wouldn't, who would? <p>
RobPgt     : 	
I'm interested in turning my interest in sports into some easy cash.  Any thoughts?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Rob Pgt, have you been to Vegas?<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
We pay for those salaries.<p>
NawrockiT  : 
But Ray, the owners charge as much as the market will bear for tickets. If Cecil Fielder gave his salary back, your ticket price wouldn't go down.<p>
Slider3307 : 	
Problem is, people love sports so much, they will almost pay anything.<p>
Ray4611011 : 
Yes, I know, but TV contracts are high.<p>
Slider3307 : 	
It is an artificial market.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Maybe that's a problem, Slider: too many fans.<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
No, not enough.<p>
Slider3307 : 	
They could charge 50 bucks a ticket and I would still want to take my son to the ballgame.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
That's why ticket prices can go up and parks still sell out.<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
Yes, so will I but enough is enough--not like before, I'd go to twenty games, now maybe two or three.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Slider, would you take your son if it was $500/ticket?  It's a market like any other.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, baseball tickets throughout the country average $12 whereas football and NBA tickets average in the 30's.<p>
Slider3307 : 	
Rob, it is a market, but would you pay $5 for milk? No, you would say that is outrageous.<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
And look at the stars: how much is Ted Williams worth today?	<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The Knicks charge $1000 for a courtside ticket, but they sell them all.<p>
Slider3307 : 	
But you will pay $4 for a dog at the game.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Bring your own food to the park!<p>
Ray4611011 : 	
But they only seat 15,000 people while baseball needs 50,000 to 80,000 people to sell out unless it's Wrigley.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The clubs have a monopoly on food sales that we fans can only break through boycotting.<p>
Ray4611011 :  	
Not really--they get about 10 percent of the money, the owners of the Astros. The city owns the dome.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, are you advocating a ball park boycott on food and concession sales...?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Why not? The food is way overpriced, and it's bad. And the only way it will change is if people stop buying it.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, think a $2.50 hot dog is a little steep?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Sportswriters get free food in the press box, so they have no idea what us fans go through. That's why we need to take it into our own hands.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
NawrockiT, you mean you have to watch the games like the rest of us?<p>
NawrockiT  : 
They don't let me in free, sport.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, do you think the owners now have an advantage since NO ONE wants to go on strike again?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
No, the owners definitely do not have the upper hand. The have to bargain in good faith now since the judge ruled against them last spring. Their lack of bargaining basically caused the strike.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Do you think college athletes should be paid?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
John Thompson makes a boatload of dough for Georgetown. Why shouldn't Allen Iverson get a little of that money?<p>
SHJStroud  : 	
I agree completely.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
He's the one pulling in the fans, not John Thompson.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Should Iverson have to go to class?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
If the NCAA regulated payments to athletes (say, $1,000 a month), it would be aboveboard. Did you go to all your classes in college? Iverson has a scholarship. What he does with it is his business. He should have to be enrolled in school, but there's a lot of guys enrolled in school who just major in drinking.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
You think $1K/month is all Iverson is worth.  If they are going to be paid, shouldn't it be based on what they can demand in the market?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Then you get into a bidding war among the colleges. It would become the minor leagues. Whatever college budgeted the most money would get the most players.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Exactly.  Wouldn't that be fairer? Iverson would reap the benefit he confers on GU.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Iverson would then be reaping that benefit for USC or Florida or whoever was willing to pay the most.<p>
Lmcreation : 	
It would be major league, not minor league with all the money to be made.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
This token payment scheme is the worst solution. Takes away any sense of college athletics being special while still exploiting the players.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Georgetown still has to keep its prestigious law school afloat. They couldn't afford $1 mil for Iverson.
How would it make college athletics any less special?<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Moreover, for many of these college kids it's the only chance they have at real cash.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
That's what I'm saying: Give them enough to live on.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
They get that now.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
But don't make college a bidding war for the top high school players. They *don't* get that now! Cash payments are illegal!<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Why? Schools make millions off these kids' talents.  And then they dismiss them without an education.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Whose fault is it that they don't get an education?<p>
RobPgt     : 	
But, they do get scholarships that cover room, books, tuition, and food.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 	
The only reason they don't get an education is that they don't show up at class!<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Should college basketball be strictly a minor league for the NBA?<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Cut the hypocrisy.  Yes.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Doesn't that take away what's "special" about college athletics?<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Yes.  But at least it would then be fair to the kids.<p>
RobPgt     : 	
Get the man off their backs.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
What we need is a minor league for the NBA, then. I don't want my alma mater, Northwestern, paying $4 mil a year to keep a basketball team afloat. If we went to your scheme, there would be 25 basketball schools competing for the NCAA title and 100 that bow out of any real competition. I think people like college basketball because it's *their school* competing.<p>
Jess14000  : 	
And wouldn't it start to look a lot like pro ball if they got paid?  What would be so special about college ball then?  What would be the distinction if they got paid what the 'market' could support?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Not if they all got paid the same thing. A uniform stipend. Nobody would notice the difference except "the kids", as Rob Pgt is wont to say.<p>
JSHDFR     : 	
Even now, with regulations, so much is done under the table: two big football players at my school just happened to have the same exact make, year, model cars. What do you think would happen if athletes were all the sudden allowed to accept cash payments? Wouldn't it go over the top?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Not if the NCAA regulated it. Goodness knows they regulate everything else about college athletics. It could be like a work-study payment. Consider sports these kids' on-campus job. What's wrong with that?<p>
Edialeda   : 	
What do you think the Cleveland Indians will do this year? Is this the one, 1996?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The Indians will win the AL pennant. Not much doubt about that. They have already sold every ticket for every game this season. And people say baseball's in trouble. I just tried to buy some tickets for a Rockies game in late June. A Thursday night game, and I couldn't get four seats together. Baseball is almost entirely recovered from the effects of the strike. I think that when the owners and players do reach an accord, it will be a minor story.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 	
What about the bitter aftertaste? <p>
NawrockiT  : 	
That's already dying off, and a full year's worth of games will do a lot to make people forget.<p>
WorthEdit1 :	
But there's still people griping about the $4 hot dogs.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, did you see the Phillies owner Mr. Giles on CNBC the other day?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
No.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
He thinks that baseball is about 85 percent back, and won't fully recover until a long term agreement is signed and a luxury tax is in effect.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Why should the fans care whether a luxury tax is enacted? That won't bring people back.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
I think he thinks it will even the playing field.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
How could the playing field be any more even? The Mariners and Reds aren't big market teams and they were in the playoffs last year. The Yankees and Mets aren't exactly awash in glory over the past few years.<p>
WorthEdit1 :	
Tell me about your running days. You say you've finished the NY marathon--twice. Is that so?<p>
NawrockiT  :	
Yes, that's correct.<p>
WorthEdit1 :	
What was your time in the marathon?<p>
NawrockiT  :	
1995: 4:14.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, you think that Toronto's 15 million in salaries is equal to Atlanta's 50 million? And that those teams compete fairly?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Toronto has won two World Series this decade. I'm not crying for the Blue Jays.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
I see.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Do they have to win every year for fans to consider them competitive? I don't think there's much connection between market size and ability to compete. Even the much-maligned Expos had the best record in baseball in 1994. It's very possible to have a winning team on a budget. Just five years ago, people were saying the Indians were going broke. Look at them now.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, so if a team wants to spend 150 million a year, it shouldn't matter.<p>
NawrockiT  : 
I agree. Because they *won't*. It's not worth it to someone to spend that much on a winner.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
Maybe Bill Gates will get a team.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
All the money in the world can't buy a winner.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
Bill Gates vs. Warren Buffett. What a matchup.<p>
JSHDFR     : 	
Do you think some of these high salaries are inspired by a player's infamy rather than talent?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Yes.  Deion Sanders wouldn't be worth $35 mil if he wasn't on TV every five seconds. <p>
WorthEdit1: 	
What about Ken Griffey's $8 million? Worth it? Why not?<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
That could be what makes those $5 hot dogs.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The Mariners wouldn't have a shot at the playoffs without him, would they? And they certainly wouldn't have any personality without him.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 
What about someone a notch below. What are they worth?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
They're worth whatever the market will bear. I'm a capitalist.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, so in that case, money does help buy a winner.<p>
NawrockiT  : 
Not as much as the ability to judge talent. By the time a Steinbrenner throws $5 mil at somebody, he's probably past his prime anyway. Better to be a good judge of talent than obscenely wealthy.<p>
Jess14000  : 	
Then there's always a Bobby Bonilla who's paid a bunch and doesn't deliver right away.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Well, whose fault is that?<p>
Jess14000  : 	
It seemed like all the hype over his salary could have been part of why he wasn't able to fit in with team mates, play well., etc.. What do you think?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Bonilla did just what could be expected of him, but the Mets expected more because they paid him so much. Paying a guy $6 mil doesn't make him a better player. Bonilla was the same player with the Mets he always had been. The expectations were too high.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, what do you think about Art Modell. Now that's capitalism.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Art Modell is more of a socialist than a capitalist. The Baltimore government is giving him a stadium; you call that free-market capitalism?<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, I call capitalism going where the best deal is.<p>
JNealon7   : 	
How can the NFL promise teams to one city, while they can't protect a historical team like Cleveland from moving away?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
I don't think even the NFL knows how it's going toput a new team in Cleveland. That was just a PR ploy. They'll probably give them an expansion franchise.<p>
DCP3820593 : 	
Do you think the NY Yankees will move into Manhattan or New Jersey?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
There's no room in Manhattan for a new Yankee Stadium.<p>
WorthRoom  : 	
NawrockiT, putting money first and tradition and history second.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
So it would have to be Jersey. But I don't think it will happen for many many years. The Yanks have a very sweet lease with the city.<p>
DCP3820593 : 	
They say near the water down about 11th street...<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
In the meat packing district? How would they fit a stadium and parking and all that down there?<p>
JNealon7   : 	
I don't know why they want to leave the Branx. The Stadium seems just fine.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The area isn't even that crime-ridden, despite Steinbrenner's poormouthing. I don't know why he keeps bashing his own product.<p>
DCP3820593 : 	
The mayor of NY is a big Yankee fan and he will do everything he can to keep the Yankees.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
They're not going anywhere before the end of the century. Whitman in NJ keeps boasting of her cost-cutting, so she's not going to find a stray $200 million for a park for the Yankees.<p>
DCP3820593 : 	
They even talk about moving the Yankees to Yonkers near Yonkers Raceway.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Yonkers is poor. There's no way it could afford to build a stadium unless the state got involved, and the state isn't going to participate in moving the Yankees out of New York City.<p>
MRD1947    : 	
Will the players and owners ever reach an agreement?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Yes. Before too long, I think.<p>
DCP3820593 : 	
The city will just have to float a bond to pay for 
the new Yankees stadium.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
There's a lot of closed-door negotiation going on, which is the best way to deal with it.<p>
DCP3820593 : 	
The governor does not want the Yankees to go to NJ he will do whatever he can to keep the Yankees.<p>
JNealon7   : 	
What do you think is the best example of money screwing up sports?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Who said money screwed up sports?<p>
JNealon7   : 	
Or enhancing the games?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Money has always been a part of sports. It's just more visible now.<p>
MRD1947    : 	
Try and get an autograph from a player.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
A lot of those autographs get sold for $$$. I don't know that I'd give something away for free so someone could turn around and sell it.<p>
JSHDFR     : 	
Then what's the difference between selling an autograph for more and scalping a ticket?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Nobody's giving away tickets for free. But we demand that athletes sign autographs for free.<p>
JNealon7   : 	
Do you think soccer can be a viable pro sport?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Well, they've been trying to make it one for 20 years now, and it hasn't made it yet. I think we have enough sports already. When was the last time a "new" sport leapt into America's mind?<p>
JNealon7   : 	
What about basketball?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The NBA's been around since the '40s. College basketball was popular before that. A lot of schools have soccer programs. But nobody pays any attention to them. Nobody pays any attention to college baseball either, so I don't think that's the problem.<p>
JNealon7   :  	
Do you think that the world cup in the US was a success?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Yes, but a lot of foreigners came here for the games. And it was a one-time event. That novelty wears off quickly. I think the World Cup would always be a hit in the U.S.<p>
JNealon7   : 	
I hear that Univision (Spanish network) is going to start broadcasting U.S. league "futbol" soon.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Let's go Yanks, most expensive team money can buy!!!!!<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
The Yankees' best players are their cheapest ones: Bernie and Derek Jeter. Ruben Sierra's really expensive, and he's no good. You don't need pricey players, just good young ones. <p>
JNealon7   : 	
Do you think hockey can rise above where it has been for the last 20 years?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
It's kind of sad that hockey is leaving Canada for the Sun Belt, but it can succeed there. I was in Dallas last summer, and saw a bunch of kids ice skating. They looked like hockey fans.<p>
Smaf712    : 	
I'm a Orioles fan.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Are you excited about the Browns coming to Baltimore, Smaf?<p>
Smaf712    : 	
I can't wait.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Are you upset about all the money the city has spent on them?<p>
Smaf712    : 	
I wish they would stay in Memorial Stadium. And they are the Ravens, not the Browns.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Sorry. Ravens it is. Too bad they can't be the Colts.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
The Orioles will fight for a wildcard with Boston while the Yanks win the east.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
The Colts, let's hear it for them!<p>
JNealon7   : 	
They tried to buy the Colts name.<p>
Smaf712    : 	
I wish that it was.  I hope this guy is not another Irsay.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
He is another Irsay! He just Irsayed Cleveland. Or is that Irsaid?<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Did Baltimore fans actually vote for the Ravens?<p>
Smaf712    : 	
Yes, we really did choose that name.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
How did that come about?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
I bet their primary color is black, since that moves the merchandise.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Is everyone happy with that choice or were there other names in the running?<p>
Smaf712    : 
There were two other names.  One was Americans and the other Marida's.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
What's "marida"?<p>
Smaf712    : 	
Got me.  Where are you from?<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
NY.<p>
Smaf712    : 	
Were you at the New York opening today against Cleveland?<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
It was in Cleveland.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
No tickets available, my good man. Cleveland's sold out for the season.<p>
Smaf712    : 	
Sorry. I forgot.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
And they say baseball's in trouble.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
True, baseball is alive and well in Cleveland,  as well as Baltimore.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
And Colorado, and Chicago, and Boston...<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
And in Chicago - at least on the North side.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
True.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Wrigley's pretty easy to fill.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
And Comiskey is pretty tough.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
And it's got that hip cachet that Sox Park will never be able to take away. The White Sox need a good team to sell out. The Cubs just need Floppy Hat Day.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
I was there yesterday, and nothing beats a day at Wrigley--nothing.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Especially if you missed work.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
They don't even need to sell the team. They can sell the park. Do you think that's why the Cubs always stink? They don't have an economic need to develop a good team.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Cubs are horrible.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
That's true -- but don't get me wrong,  I want winning baseball and so do all true Cubs fans.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
But do the Cubs owners care about winning? Sometimes I wonder.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Well, you'll have to move for a winning team.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
They're already getting every last penny possible out of that franchise.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Come to NY, you'll have 2.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
They signed George Bell, Danny Jackson, Dave Smith, Candy Maldonado -- they spend money.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
When was the last time both the Mets and Yanks had a winning season? 1986, right? <p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
86.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
They just don't pick the right guys -- McPhail and Lynch will change that.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Dave Smith and Candy Maldonado are hardly Barry Bonds.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
In response to Tony -- hurt, hurt, hurt, too old.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
There is only one Bonds.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
They seem content to roll along with the Todd Zeiles of the world.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
iam4zoo - that's my point. The Cubs didn't have the right management, now they do.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
It's not a matter of spending money. It's a matter of being committed to winning.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
McPhail is good, with what he did with the Twins, but what about Lynch?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Building a farm system , scouting, all that. When was the last time the Cubs had a really hot prospect? Shawon Dunston?<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
Brooks Kieschnick. Let's see what Lynch has -- he did a good job of transforming the team last year. <p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Well, we can hope. Contrast that with all the Indians home-grown talent: Belle, Thome, Ramirez...<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
That's why the Yankees haven't won in the past, they traded their farm system for old players.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
That's why having tons of money doesn't win pennants. It's mostly under-30 guys who win pennants for you. The Indians built their dynasty by locking up young players.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
And pitching.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Indians used a little of both.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
But the first step is to accumulate all that young talent, and the Cubs haven't done that.<p>
IAM4ZOO    :	
Ryne is not the answer.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
They got a decent young staff and McRae, Gonzalez, Sosa.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Believe me, I'm rooting for them. A wildcard is not out of the question.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Sosa and McRae, good picks, who's Gonzalez?<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Luis Gonzalez. Left fielder. Too bad he's not Jose Gonzalez.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
Luis Gonzalez -- he is not top shelf but a good player.<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
They have a decent outfield then.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Do you think Ryno came back for the money? Or for the love of the game?<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
No -- I think he came back to play.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
People complain that Rickey Henderson misses 30 games a year. Why don't they complain about Ryno taking a whole year off?<p>
IAM4ZOO    : 	
Ryne Sandberg is to Chicago what Don Mattingly was to the Yanks.<p>
TonyBBall  : 	
My son needs to go to bed -- sorry see ya later. <p>
NawrockiT  : 	
Good night, Tony Jr.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 	
I'd like to thank Tom Nawrocki for coming by for a chat tonight. And thank you, everyone, for your great questions.<p>
NawrockiT  : 	
You're very welcome. Any time.<p>
WorthEdit1 : 	
Remember to check out Tom's regular column, "Ballpark Figures," only on Worth OnLine.
					</font>
