	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>04/01/96 -- "The Next Ten Years"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On April 1, 1996, top investment experts met in Las Vegas for the ISI Money Show. In "The Next Ten Years" panel, sponsored by ISI and CNBC, panelists discussed their predictions for the stock market in the next decade. Panelists included: Elizabeth Bramwell, president and CIO of the Bramwell Funds;  John Dessauer, editor of John Dessauer's Investor's World; James Dines, editor of The Dines Letter; Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock Letter; Don Phillips, president of Morningstar; and Jim Rogers, author/investor. Sue Herera, a CNBC anchor, served as moderator of the panel. Follows is a transcript from this event:<p>
Sue Herera: It's wonderful to see everyone here. It's such a large group this year, which has been just absolutely so enjoyable for me, to get a chance to meet everybody, and many of you are return participants in the seminar, which we love. It's so nice to catch up with all of you. Many of you have made a lot of changes in your lives in the last year since I've seen you and it's a pleasure. And, I think this hour and a half is going to be a lot fun. At least I hope so. <p>
We have a very distinguished and wonderful panel to answer your questions, and I'm also going to ask them some specific questions. This is not an easy panel to be on, The Next Ten Years. Most of us are having trouble with the next month in this market --ten years and they agreed to come -- so I think we should give them some credit for going out on a limb in many cases. What I'm going to do is ask a few questions to each -- some have some fairly interesting predictions for you. The idea behind this is to help you create well and if you have created well, congratulations, and we're going to help you preserve that, I hope. So the idea is to give you some guidance and help you to a wonderful and better future financially. <p>
Now, I'm also going to be taking questions from the audience, so we're going to do a little talk show, a little panelist, I'm going to be running up and down with the microphone, so bear with me. So think about questions that you might have for the panelists, after I kind of get some opening remarks from each of them. It may take me a few minutes, but I'll get to you, and give you the microphone and you can ask your questions, because I think many of you, depending on your particular area of interest, might have questions that perhaps I haven't thought of before, that haven't been addressed by some of the speakers that you've had a chance to hear so far. Are you having a good time so far at this seminar, I hope? Good. I think when we did the promo at CNBC it was, "The perfect opportunity to mix business with pleasure". So, we hope you've had a chance to do that. <p>
Let me introduce the panelists to you. Michael Murphy, Editor of the California Technology Stock Letter. Many of you already know him from appearances on CNBC, as well as in the printed press and other media. Next to him is John Dessauer, Editor of John Dessauer's Investor's World; I will have the privilege of being with John on a later panel as well. Next to him is Jim Dines, and he is Editor of the Dines Letter. Next to him is Don Phillips, President of Morningstar; and then Elizabeth Bramwell, and she is President and CIO of the Bramwell Funds. Then, Jim Rogers, author and investor and very interesting story teller, so I have a few questions for Jim.<p>
So, without further ado, that's the panel and we'll get started. Michael, I'm going to just kind of go in order because that's probably the easiest way for me to do it. Let's start, Michael, with you and your area of expertise. I think what's interesting about this panel, really, is that we have such a wide variety of areas covered here. Jim obviously has been around the world, he invests in a way that many people do not, by going to the country, going to the bank and buying particular currency. He has a specific area and method of investing. Liz covers a much broader area than that in the markets. And, we have Don, of course, who follows the fund area. Jim has many areas of expertise. John, worldwide investor and, I think Michael, perhaps technology is a great place to start, because it has been such a huge area of growth in many sectors of the technology sector itself. I know technology is a tough call, but if you had to put your finger on the hot issues for the next few years, what would they be?<p>
Michael Murphy: Well, in technology, I think if you divide it into two parts, medical and electronics, the medical part of technology, clearly for the next ten years, is going to be totally driven by the biotechnology revolution. A lot of these companies that a lot of people have forgotten about (because the stocks went through a three year bear market through about the middle of last year) have made a lot of clinical progress. For the next ten years, I think it really belongs to those companies. The big drug companies are investing in those companies and are counting on those companies to come up with the new products. So there's a tremendous amount of opportunity in biotech. <p>
The other half of technology, the electronics part, really divides into two parts there. The personal computing-related part, and the communications part. The communications part has grown steadily, grew right through the last recession at 35 percent a year. It's going to keep growing at 35 percent a year. You all, I'm sure, have heard the statistic that half the people in the world have never made a telephone call; ten years from now, everybody will have made a telephone call. So that means a lot of infrastructure has got to be put in place, and a lot of services. Unfortunately, United States companies pretty much lead the world in those areas. <p>
In the personal computing area, there is going to be a lot of ferment and a lot of change. PC's are going to continue to sell as they are. There are about 150 million installed today. There are at least 250 million more people around the world who have the income and education to buy one that haven't bought one yet. And, the prices are going to get structured down into lower and lower priced machines. There will be a $500 Internet machine, their $200 machine you carry around in your hand. The technology is going to continue to spread. My guess is that all of technology for the next ten years is a pretty good bet. The surest part of the bet is in telecommunications and in biotechnology, but there's going to be plenty of opportunities in personal computing during that time span.<p>
Sue Herera: Michael, when you said the big drug companies are going to start looking at the smaller, perhaps more innovative companies, do you then see an increase in takeover play aspect there, because you're looking at the big companies? Or are you looking more at buying the smaller companies themselves? <p>
Michael Murphy: Well, you're right, I hope they don't get taken over too early. We just had one bought out, Athena Neurosciences, and you know, we made eighty percent on the stock, but I think it was bought out too early. We could have made a lot more if we had gotten through to the point where they had actually developed the drug and gotten it introduced and sharply increased the value of the company. We want to be in the biotech companies that are going to be taken over, but I wouldn't argue with somebody who has more conservative money owning certain drug companies that sort of understand this model of putting money out into the biotechs. <p>
For example, when I look at good biotech companies, I almost always find Merck & Co. [NYSE: MRK] or SmithKline Beecham [NYSE: SBE] or Rhone-Poulenc Rorer, Inc. [NYSE: RPR] or Upjohn Co. [NYSE: UPJ] in there, investing in specific products. Of course, from their point of view, they're going to wait three years, five years, whatever it takes, see what works. They'll help get the product ultimately through the FDA, get it into the market, they have the rights to sell it, and then they'll buy those companies out. They may pay 500 million or a billion dollars to take a company over five years from now, but from their point of view, that's lower risk than actually doing the development themselves. <p>
Right now today, if you X-out the top seven biotech companies -- the Amgen [Nasdaq: AMGN]-Chiron Corp. [Nasdaq: CHIR]-Genentech, Inc. [NYSE: GNE] kind of company -- the next fifty companies, the total market capitalization of all those companies, is less than one year annual R&D [research and development] spending at Merck. So they could just buy the whole industry if they wanted to. But, they're not going to do it. They are going to just wait and see what works out, and we would rather buy the biotech companies that have a chance to go from development stage to functioning pharmaceutical companies, and then get bought out. <p>
Sue Herera: John, why don't we turn to you now. As you travel around the world, there is so much changing, it's almost impossible to keep up with at this point. To say to you, what's coming up in the next ten years? is certainly not an easy question. What do you see on the forefront?<p>
John Dessauer: Well, the first thing I would say is, is my microphone working? Good. It's okay. The past is prologue, so we start, nobody knows what the future will hold. A good place to start guessing about the future is to look at the past and the present, particularly at our mistakes. And, I think the greatest mistake made by myself and a whole army of other people was made in 1989 when communism collapsed as an economic entity, the Berlin wall came down, and we all thought that Mikhail Gorbachev and perestroika had it right, that you do political reform first and economic -- in other words, democracy -- and all will be well. <p>
Deng Xiaoping in China had the opposite idea, and at the time, I thought he was just plain wrong. You know oppressive communism, brutal people, that kind of thing, we thought China would never make it. Well, now we're quite a long way into the process, and I've spent a lot of time now in China. I'll be going back again the 24th of April for another three-week tour out into the countryside to see the one part of coastal China that I haven't visited yet. From my visits to China, it's quite clear that we were completely wrong in 1989. We can look at Russia today, and some parts of the Soviet Union are doing fine -- Hungary, Czechoslovakia -- but Russia itself is a total mess. I'm told by people there that the Russian Mafia takes 2 percent of the gross in every business in the country today. When you get into that kind of a situation, I mean it's going to be an awful problem getting out of it. So I don't hold a lot of hope for the Russian stock market any time soon. <p>
But on the other side of the globe, both China, and I was recently in Vietnam as well, you can see that Deng Xiaoping did unleash that kind of grassroots economic movement, so China today probably looks like what the United States used to look like back at the start of the industrial revolution, with a big difference. They have modern technology to move them on their way. Lots of challenges, lots of problems facing the development of China, but there are seven hundred and fifty million Chinese. Sixty percent of the population under the age of 25. Ninety percent literacy rate and I am personally, totally convinced that that bunch of folks out there, wandering around China, will shape the future for the global economy; not just for the next ten years, but probably for the next twenty. Their basic philosophy is to work hard, get rich, and live a long time. They're all little Warren Buffetts and I think they're really going to succeed.  But just imagine, three countries like the United States with people Sue Herera's age, 25 and under. Nothing is smooth and there are ups and downs and the rest, but I think if you take that idea home and keep it for the next ten years, it'll keep you out of trouble.<p>
Sue Herera: I've always loved talking with John. Jim Dines, next. You said you have some very interesting predictions. What's going to happen?<p>
James Dines: Well, the truth is that I went through the futurology chapter in my book on mass psychology and I picked out eight predictions that might be profitable to you, and I thought I'd go through them. But first, I'd like to emphasize that nobody one hundred years ago could have seen where we are now and you have to understand that the future is inherently unbelievable. And, you need to be flexible in terms of accepting what might happen. So, maybe it's merciful that we don't really believe what is right in front of us.<p>
The first prediction reminds me of 1962 when gold was at $35, and I said it would surpass the price of the Dow-Jones Industrial Average. Seventeen years later it came true and when gold hit $850, it was acknowledged in Barron's Magazine's editorial. And now I'd like to predict again, that gold will once again get above the Dow-Jones Industrial Average. So all portfolios should have a substantial position in the precious metals. <p>
Sue Herera: Gold or gold stocks?<p>
James Dines: I prefer gold stocks over gold bouillon, thanks for pointing that out, Sue. I was just mentioning to Sue before, I first began working with her when I was on station FNN in Los Angeles in 1980. We've been working together for 16 years and it's always been a pleasure. I thought she was thirty, but I guess she's twenty-five.<p>
In my speeches for the last twenty years, I've pointed out that humanity began in East Africa and it's always seemed to go Westward: Mesopotamia, Greece, Rome, France, England, the US, Japan and the Five Tigers. In 1979, I went to the People's Republic of China as a guest of the Chinese government, and came back saying that the 21st century would someday be called the China Century. I agree with John on the bullish potential on that, and I said that it would continue Westward into India and then eventually Africa. Now, why it should move Westward is a mass psychological, interesting query, but I'm not bullish. We turned bearish on China in 1992 for the short term, and I'm still bearish on China. <p>
Three: I view computers as a transitional product toward what I call the "Coming Age of Robots;" they'll be doing most of the world's work. There's a time not far distant when all nations will be economically independent. There won't be enough work for everyone, which will have a phenomenal impact. It's just beginning in the US, there are not enough jobs for everyone, and this is what we have to confront. Combined with what I expect to be a radical extension of human life, I certainly agree with Mike on that. I think biotech is a very important area. There will not be enough work, and clearly a radical new political order will be the primary feature of the next century.<p>
Four: Most of the Internet's attention is directed toward its usefulness and information spread, but I believe it will be the vehicle for Mass Contagion on a level never seen before. You've just gotten a glimpse of it with Netscape, and next will be with Yahoo!. Nothing will be busier than a so-called idle rumor and it will be wondrous to behold how rumors without a leg to stand on get around so fast. Especially gossip, which, of course, is the art of saying nothing in a way that leaves practically nothing unsaid. <p>
Five: I first began to predict in 1985 that within 20 years, physical immortality would become possible. I cover this in more detail in my book, but I'm very interested in the disease called progeria with its radically premature aging, proving to me that there's a genetic clock that can go wrong. I therefore also predict physical immortality by 2005. <p>
Six: I count the fifty-year cold war as World War III, and I've been predicting that World War IV would be a religious war, mostly within religions, and bombs are already going off everywhere on that. But the world is still in denial, and they even describe Yugoslavia's war between their three religions as an ethnic conflict. I say that denial is more than just a river in Egypt. <p>
Seven: Something radical will happen with energy and the governments will eventually seize all oil reserves for military purposes with prices above $100 a barrel. I'm very bullish on oil. <p>
Eight: And finally, the four-year cycle in the stock market is very important. Cycles, I cover that a lot in my book on mass psychology. See, cycles are very important to my work. There was a bottom made in 1957, '62, '66, '70, '74, '78, '82, '87 (that was one year late), '90 and '94, which means there are bottoms every fourth year in the stock market. Therefore, the next important market bottom should be in 1998, suggesting a market top, not later than 1997, possibly even this year, but probably not. There are other cycles in my book I study, like the low point of each decade tends to be reached within the first few years. I learned that from my old friend Edison Gould, who of course got it from Edgar Lawrence Smith, who wrote that book in 1904. Which means that we've already hit the low point for this decade, I'm still very bullish on the stock market. And that's all, thank you.<p>
Sue Herera: So, by the year 2005 I should be thirty, thirty-two and live forever, right? Don, you're next. What should we be doing for the next ten years?<p>
Don Phillips: Well, I think in the fund arena, the game has changed a bit. I think over the last decade, clearly you've seen a move from individual stocks to mutual funds as being the investment vehicle of choice. And, I think the baby boom generation has embraced mutual funds. I think for no small part, because mutual funds make saving and investing seem like something that the baby boomers are very good at, and that's spending. You know with mutual funds, you've got brand names, you've got even dollar prices, you even have sales: "Buy us now while we're waiving the load." So it's exactly like spending, which is a skill that the baby boomers have spent their lifetime perfecting. And now you get to apply it to the savings arena. <p>
But I think there's been a shift now from funds to portfolios. And that's the real challenge. No one's buying their first mutual fund. It's a game in progress. And, certainly things like 401(K) plans and variable annuities force this issue. I think the shake-up you saw at Fidelity a couple of weeks ago was in response to this. The tag against Fidelity in the 401(K) arena was sure, you get Magellan, and it's a good fund, but if you buy Magellan, and then Contrafund, and Blue Chip Growth, you're really getting the same portfolio, warmed over three different times. And, I think some of the competing groups were going in and saying look, we've got a more disciplined line-up and people can really build a portfolio around us because if we call something midcap, it'll be midcap. If we call something value, it'll be value. <p>
That's the response to what's happening in the marketplace. People are thinking about constructing an overall portfolio, not just buying "a good fund". And the problem with this is there are some mathematics involved that aren't very favorable. I mean, you see Fidelity moving in this direction with personal advisory services. You also had in the Journal recently that Vanguard's getting into the financial planning arena. What they're doing is they're recognizing that just offering the funds isn't enough, they have to show people how to construct an overall portfolio to meet their goals. The problem with this is that it's an extra service that demands an extra fee. And the typical mutual fund/expense ratio has been rising over the last decade. <p>
Just within Chicago, Harris Associates, a top quality organization, in the '70s launched the Acorn Fund. And, it was designed that if it was successful the assets would rise and the expense ratio would decline. The expense ratio on that is now about 60 basis points. The same organization launched the Oakmark Funds in the '90s and it's designed such that if it's successful, its expenses would decline to about 1.4 percent or so. And that's the C-change in the fund industry over the last two decades. You don't aim for 60 or 70 basis points. You aim for 150, because that's what the market place will bear. Now, the issue is what happens if you start taking out that 150 basis points that the typical stock fund manager is charging, and you layer another service for assembling the portfolio on top of that? <p>
Merrill Lynch and some of the wire houses are talking about wrap-free programs with no-load mutual funds. If you start adding 1.5 percent to 1.5 percent and ending up with something, say, at 3 percent a year, I think you've got a real tough situation for the investor. Because, what might you realistically project forward over the next decade for bonds? I think you'd take the current coupons, say maybe 6 or 7 percent. For stocks, historical average, maybe 9 percent. Now if you're asking someone to pay something in the neighborhood of 2 to 2.5, 3 to 3.5 percent to get access to security markets that are going to deliver 6 to 9 percent, you're asking someone to forfeit anywhere from 1/3 to potentially half of their return from these markets just for having access to them. And that's something that's going to have to shake out. There's going to have to be a lowering of these fees or vastly superior service somehow, because otherwise the mathematics mean that the investor can't win. And, ultimately, if the investor doesn't win, no one wins. <p>
Sue Herera: Okay. Liz, you're next. You can really address a variety of issues here, from individual stocks to funds. We've talked a lot, just between the two of us about technology. We were having a discussion at lunch about the Internet and how that has dramatically changed the way we all are certainly doing business. What are you going to be watching, and perhaps buying or looking at in the next ten years?<p>
Elizabeth Bramwell: I think the next five to ten years are going to see more change than we've seen heretofore. I think it's a real challenge for a human being to adjust to change and I think, get ready. I think it's only going to intensify. I think the likelihood of people having multiple careers is greater today than ever, I think the phenomenon of part-time work is a permanent feature that's going to be developed even further, and that's not necessarily all bad. So I think there are trends there on an investment side, but at any rate, I think it's exciting to have multiple careers going forward. I think, assuming the free trade stays in place, that the standard of living is going to continue to rise around the world, and the middle class will continue to expand. So it's going to be a good environment for selling American-made goods and services in other parts of the world. I think electronics will continue to develop and be increasingly pervasive. I'm struck by the fact that today, the cost of electronics and an automobile are greater than the actual cost of steel. So we have just an increasing penetration of this kind of thing going forward.<p>
I think, in terms of communications, that more and more of it's going to go online. I was kind of struck in looking at the last Procter & Gamble quarterly statement that they announce that this is going to be their last printed quarterly statement. Now we have a big consumer company, taking their pretty blue quarterly statement, with orange Tide boxes floating across it, and doing away with it for cost reasons, saying "we'll be happy to send you the material, just call our 1-800 number and we'll either fax or send it to you." So, and having done that, you get a cold black and white piece of paper. So, from a marketing point-of-view, I kind of wonder, but from a cost point-of-view, I guess it's something else again. At any rate, later this year, P&G will put its material online, on the Internet. <p>
I think we're going to see this more and more. I think the funds have had a real place in terms of investment portfolios and so forth, but I think as the information is more easily disseminated to the world, that it's also going to become increasingly possible for individuals to structure their portfolios from scratch with individual stocks. There will be a certain group who'll reach a point where I think they'll have all the information that the professional analysts and the portfolio managers have. It'll be online and easily accessible, so it's not to say that professional money managers are going to be replaced, because you know there is an increasing need for that, too, but on the margin. I think also some people will sort of take off and say, "why do I have to buy the index on here or whatever," and will go from there. <p>
I think going forward, a lot will depend on what the political structure is. I think that by 2006 there will be a substantial move to privatize the Social Security system, and the form that it takes will depend on who is in the White House, and who is in Congress. And, I think in the next five, within the next Administration, something will be done on Medicare, because now, two years ahead of time, the expenditures have exceeded the revenue increase, and this is after having raised Medicare tax a couple of years ago and taken the cap off of it. So, I think it's been a substantial tax and basically, I hope they don't do the same thing with Social Security. <p>
Sue Herera: Okay, I'm almost afraid to ask Jimmy about the next ten years. It's either going to be great, or we're going to hell in a hand basket, one of the two. <p>
Jim Rogers: Both.<p>
Sue Herera: Both? All right, Jim. <p>
Jim Rogers: Well, a lot of things are going to happen in the next ten years, but I will try to limit myself to the investment world. First, the last twenty-odd years we've had a bull market in paper assets, stocks; and we've had a bear market in physical assets -- raw materials, natural resources, call them what you will -- that is in the process of reversing. We're about to have a multi-year bull market in raw materials, and we're going to certainly make a top in stocks, somewhere in the next quarter or the next year, or whenever, and the place to be will be in raw materials and natural resources. <p>
You should also know that there will definitely be a recurring currency crisis and the US dollar will get worse and worse over the next ten years. Sometime in the next ten years, we'll have exchange controls in the United States, so I certainly urge all of you to be sure you have some of your money out of the country now, but certainly going forward during that ten-year period, because there is going to come a time when it will be either illegal or very expensive for you to get your money out of the country. And the countries which will be doing well will be Latin America. Basically, the best countries will be the ones that are well-managed, natural resource-based countries, such as New Zealand, Chile, Australia, Malaysia may be one of those: the countries that have a natural resource-base and are well-managed. We'll see great resurgences in Africa, South America. The great country of the 21st century will be China. The best investment advice I can give you is to teach your children and grandchildren Chinese. If you don't want to teach them Chinese, teach them Spanish, because those are going to be the two great languages of the 21st century. I guess that's enough for right now.<p>
Sue Herera: Okay. Are we ready for questions? I think what I'll do is, I'll try and start at the bottom level and work up. I won't even have to do the treadmill tonight, this'll be great. Oprah Winfrey must have a blast doing this! Okay.<p>
Question: Mr. Murphy - Have you ever heard of a biotech firm called MedImmune [Nasdaq: MEDI], and if so, what do you think of it?<p>
Michael Murphy: Well, I have heard of MedImmune. I actually don't follow MedImmune, because it's an East Coast company, and I try just to follow companies that I can get to and get back. But, I will tell you, I have looked at it enough to know, first of all, that it's fairly cheap still -- even though it's come up -- it's fairly cheap. The way to look at a biotech company -- any biotech company -- is to look first to see if it's a quality company, that they have partners that are big drug companies, that they have a scientific advisory board that makes sense and comes from big institutions. Secondly, just look at how much money they've spent on their science, on their research and development over the last five years, and compare that to what the total market capitalization is today. If you can buy a biotech stock for five-times or eight-times (or sometimes even less than that) what they've actually spent, just on their science without any credit for administration or manufacturing or any of that, mostly they're pretty good deals. And if they have good quality scientific partners, especially if anyone has recently come in, looked at their science and invested money or signed a deal, that's reasonable assurance that they've got something real that can get through the drug development process. Then, if you buy a package of those, because they're not all going to make it, that's the way to participate in this whole upturn. <p>
Question: Where will the strength be in international banking in the next ten years? Can you identify any certain entity that will be better than the other?<p>
Sue Herera: I guess that plays, John, perhaps to you, or to you, Jimmy?<p>
John Dessauer: I think of the same time twenty years ago, when I worked for Citicorp and I ran their European money management operations and lived in Switzerland. In those days, John Reid was considered a radical. He was going around Europe and elsewhere in the world, acquiring a consumer banking operation. That's the strength of Citicorp today. And I suspect it will remain a strength of the big banks going on into the future. We'll see more consolidation, and we will see it in other parts of the world, not just in Asia, but in parts of Europe. <p>
Banco Santander, for example, the big Spanish bank bought Banesto when it got into trouble a couple of years ago. And Banesto is now on the verge of delivering the profits for Banco Santander that they expected in the first place. Why? Because retail banking is beginning to develop in Spain. You lift standards of living around the world, the first thing that happens is you start to see consumer banking really develop. So that's the area I would focus on in banking, looking out into the future. Big banks have the muscle power, big banks that are international in scope and that are focused on consumer banking in the developing world.<p>
Sue Herera: How about you Jimmy? <p>
Jim Rogers: Well, the major change: your child, your children are never going to see the inside of a bank, because banking is all going to be done electronically in the next decade. There is a bank in England right now, which was only founded five years ago, and it already has two percent of the English banking market. It doesn't have a single branch. Not a single branch. The English change spouses more than they change their bank, that's a true statistic, I mean the English just, they never change their banks. They'd more likely get divorced than change their bank. But, this bank within five years already has 2 percent of the English banking market. It's all going to be electronic in the future. Your bank may be not even in the United States, your bank may be who knows where. <p>
All these bankers buying-up bricks and mortar are going to wind up, many of them wind up failing, because the future is electronic, and it will be very international because you can be anywhere, and your clerks can be anywhere when you're doing it electronically. The sound banks will be the ones who are investing in this technological change, rather than bricks and mortar and loan officers, and the really sound ones will be in places that have sound currencies going forward -- Switzerland, Denmark, Ireland, Chile, New Zealand. Countries with currencies that will remain sound where people will want to put their money as a stable source of value. That will not be the United States. <p>
Question: Is that the smart card concept that we don't have here, but is very widely accepted in Europe, when you talk about electronic banking? <p>
Jim Rogers: Well, that's part of it. If you think about it, all you really need your bank for, what most people need their bank for, is to get cash. Well, this bank in England which has no branches at all, but has 2 percent of the nation's bank market, they just have all these ATM machines. You just go down and stick your card in, whatever kind of card it is, and you take out your money. The rest of it can all be done electronically, you pay your bills electronically, you make your deposits electronically, you don't need bank deposits any more, as we know them.<p>
Sue Herera: Alrighty. Let's move on.<p>
Question: Mr. Rogers, you mentioned the currency crisis and I was wondering if you could comment on how you see that scenario unfold?<p>
Jim Rogers: Well, the way some of you probably remember that pound sterling used to be the world's reserve currency, and the world's medium of exchange, and when sterling got into trouble, there was a currency problem every year. And every year the world's bankers got together and they solved the currency problem. Well, every year, they came back. That's the way it's going to unfold here, sometimes you'll be in outlying currencies, like the peso or the Swedish krona or something like that, but basically, there's a dollar problem. The politicians are debasing and devaluing the currency, you will see, I don't know, maybe this fall will be the next one, fewer and fewer people will take the dollar, the dollar will go down again. The bankers will all get together to try to figure out the way to prop up the dollar, there'll be a rally, but over the next few years, every year you will basically see a tax on the US dollar and it will continue to erode in the international markets. <p>
Ultimately, some politician is going to be elected and he's going to say, "There is nothing wrong with America, America is the strongest country in the world, we are the richest country in the world." He's going to ignore the fact that we have gigantic foreign debt, and he's going to say, "There's nothing wrong with the dollar, the problem is those journalists who keep writing about problems with the currency, and if they wouldn't write about it, things would be okay. And the other problem, those evil financiers on Wall Street. Those greedy investors, you know if they didn't stop sending the money out of the country, we wouldn't have a problem." And he's going to say, "All of you Americans, we are good, hard working, loyal citizens, we're not doing this to hurt you, we're doing it just to hurt the evil financiers on Wall Street." <p>
And that's when they'll put exchange controls on, at which point, the dollar will collapse again, because it won't work in the long term. When the dollar makes that final bottom, though, it might be the time to buy. In the meantime, you should have money out of the country. Now, it is legal, honest and moral to have money out of the country, as long as you pay your taxes, and I commend all of you to be patriotic, I suggest you send some of your money out of the country. Help the politicians out. They want the dollar to go down, they think it's good for the dollar to go down, that's a disaster in the long term, this has never worked in the long term for any country in the world to debase and devalue the currency. Even the French, the French did it for forty years, they said, "We'll compete with the Germans and we'll compete with the Europeans, we'll just debase the currency." Even the French have given up this absurd policy. So, it doesn't work in the long run, but the politicians will do it, continue to do it, there'll be recurring crisis. Now it's legal and honest and moral, send some of your money out of the country and be patriotic.<p>
Question: Hi, Michael, I remember you were saying yesterday that there were more Wall Street analysts that followed steel stocks than semiconductor stocks, I believe. That being the case, certainly there must be even less for biopharmaceuticals. When do you think there is going to be a change in the philosophy and the people who, the analysts, Wall Street-types, and so forth, may think that there's a bigger future in biopharmaceuticals than toys or whatever?<p>
Michael Murphy: Well, the number I gave was about 90 percent of Wall Street analysts still follow stocks in the old economy, the mass production economy, or even the older economy, the Industrial economy. And, I think the change might come in the next economic downturn in this country, because the old economy -- the mass production economy, specifically, the consumer economy -- I think is in a lot of trouble. The demographics are against it. Growth is very slow. The companies in that business that do well are the ones that have a large overseas component to their earnings, companies like Coca-Cola or something like that. But, those who are locked into the US economy are, I think, having tough times now, and they are showing earnings growth basically by one-time cost-cutting, which can't continue forever, and they're going to get nailed in the next downturn. And at the same time, my suspicion is that in the next economic downturn, the technology will grow right through it again, just at telecommunications did in the last one, and you'll have telecommunications and PC's and biotechnology going through.<p>
In the specific case of biotechnology, in the ten years up to 1994, we had 30 drugs approved, biotech drugs. So we averaged about three a year. Last year, we had six approved. This year, we'll have about 18 approved. Next year, about 30. So we've hit the hockey stick in terms of drug approvals where these companies can change from being development-stage companies. So a lot of folks don't want to buy. Understandably, they're risky. They change from that into small pharmaceutical companies and then we start seeing the acquisitions. And, my guess is that whole process takes about another 3 or 4 years. We're just starting a group of mutual funds, or following a group of mutual funds, and the first one in the series, after some debate, we decided to make a biotech fund, not a broad-technology fund, because I think the timing is so superb right now, to get those stocks bought before we start seeing this flood of approvals. This is really the time to be doing it.<p>
Question: Hi, my question is for Jim Rogers. Since most of us aren't in the position where we can travel all around the world, how would you best recommend investing in individual countries, would you go through webs or would you go through mutual funds?<p>
Jim Rogers: Well, the very best way to invest in a foreign country is to invest in that country directly. Most foreign countries in which you would invest have banks or brokers that have offices in the United States and you can open many of these accounts by mail. You don't have to go Denmark to open a brokerage account in Denmark, normally. So you can do it that way and then buy shares directly. Failing that, you can buy shares in many companies. They trade in the United States, or many of your brokers will buy you shares in say, Ireland, if you want to buy Irish shares; some firms are starting to specialize in this. There is a firm in St. Louis that's called Mark Twain bank, now I've never done business with them, so I don't know if they're any good or bad, but I do know they specialize in this, and they will buy you shares in just about any country in the world. They will also open money market funds for you which are guaranteed by the FDIC, believe it or not, so that you can do this. <p>
Shares are the best way, better than mutual funds. Webs, and for those of you who don't know what a web is, there are two new instruments which have just been created in the last two weeks: One is known as a web, and one is known as a country basket. They trade on the New York Stock Exchange and the American Stock Exchange. You essentially can buy the indexes in about 19 different countries, in other words, if you want to buy Australian, you buy the Australian country basket, you call up your Merrill Lynch broker, whoever your local broker is, and tell him you want to buy that index and he can do it. You pay for it in dollars, you get your money in dollars and everything else. I suspect that they are going to change international investing in this country dramatically because they are so accessible and they are so terrific. I've never bought or sold one yet, but I suspect I will. <p>
Another reason that they're better than mutual funds, with all due respect to mutual funds, indexes out perform something like 70 or 80 or 90 percent of mutual fund managers in the world so, unless you know the really good one, then you should just buy the index and here's a way that you can buy the index in just about any country you want to. If you don't want to do that, if you think you've found a fund manager whose better than just buying the index, than mutual funds are an acceptable way to do it, but be sure you know something about the fund manager. Remember, all fund managers are not good. The most important part of any investment is who's managing the money.<p>
Question: My question is for you also, Mr. Rogers. You mentioned to take money out of the US now, before restrictions come on. What is the best way to do this?<p>
Jim Rogers: Get on your motorcycle and get yourself a tall young blonde, and go. <p>
Sue Herera: You know, I should have something to come back with, but I don't. It'll just get us in trouble.<p>
Jim Rogers: I know it would. And be careful. No, I don't know, the countries which run sound currencies, you know in the old days you had to run a sound currency if you were a country, the 19th century for instance. But now, most politicians have learned how to debase currency so there are only say ten countries left that have a sound currency. I don't know if you go skiing on your vacations, if you do, maybe you should consider skiing in Switzerland or Austria instead of Colorado. If you like the beaches, maybe you should consider going to the beaches in New Zealand or Ireland, or someplace that has nice beaches.<p>
Sue Herera: A little chilly, Jimmy.<p>
Jim Rogers: I know, I was trying to think of another place with good beaches. Go there. You know, Time magazine once called me the Indiana Jones of finance. I'm going to blow my cover right here, I'm going to tell you how simple this is: If you open a bank account in your home town, or brokerage account, the way you do it is you walk in, you give them identification and you give them a check and you have an account. You know how you do it everywhere else in the world? You walk in, you give identification, and you give them a check. You too, can be the Indiana Jones of finance. You can wheel and deal in any country you want to, just go there on your next vacation and do it. If you don't want to do it that way, there are some mutual fund companies now that have money market funds denominated in foreign currencies. That is a second way to do it, it is not a very good way as far as I'm concerned, but if you don't want to go on vacation to one of these countries, consider that or go to Mark Twain bank. Sometimes you can do all this by mail. You'd be astonished at how the world has opened up now, or the Internet for all I know.<p>
Question: I have a question for all of you. It may be a little simplistic but for the next ten years, if each of you could only pick three stocks, what would they be? <p>
Sue Herera: To buy? You want both long and short? This could take a while, hang on to your questions, why don't we start with you Michael, we'll start at that end and work down.<p>
Michael Murphy:  Well, actually, at this point you have choices I think in both the PC side and the biotech side. And if you're only going to buy one, you buy the absolute best quality company that's beaten down on the PC side, that's Intel. You know at $57 a share, I think it's an absolute gift and they can't push the stock below $50. How ever hard they try, it probably won't go below $55. <p>
I'd pick two on the biotech side, and since we're talking ten years, I'm trying to balance out that long, if it was shorter term, I'd do more electronics, but I'd take Intel in electronics, and on the biotech side I'd take VICAL [Nasdaq: VICL] which is the leading company in gene therapy, which is a fundamental basic technology that is going to be used widely curing diseases. And, I'd also take Human Genome Sciences, Inc. [Nasdaq: HGSI] which is a company, I actually wouldn't buy that stock today, it's a little high, but if you're giving me a ten year period, they're sequencing the human genome and they're going to wind up with about half of the patents on human genes, which is a pile of intellectual property, that they can just take out and exploit every which way over the next ten, twenty years.<p>
Sue Herera: How much would it have to drop before it looked attractive to you?<p>
Michael Murphy: I'd like to buy the stock in the mid-thirties and it's kind of floating around forty-plus, so you know how Wall Street is, the slightest bit of bad news one day and they could knock it down very easily.<p>
Sue Herera: Okay John, you're next.<p>
John Dessauer: Well, ten years is a long call, but on Wall Street we do have to create a portfolio at the beginning of every year, and then you're not allowed to change it during the year. And, last year, I was fortunate enough to be the winner of that contest. Eight stocks, all US, by the way, last year, 100 percent US, were up 63.3 percent. This year, we submitted a portfolio of ten stocks and there were four newcomers in there and no repeaters from last year. A total of ten, four were foreign stocks, and I don't know how you're doing so far in the first quarter of 1996, but I got the score this morning from Wall Street Week and that portfolio is up 23.27 percent so far in 1996. So, year by year, I'm okay. But, ten years out, that's a tough one. Because I remember a company my father was associated with called Xerox. And, in the early 1970s Xerox was a hot stock, and believed to be a company that would do very well. In 1973, before the break, Xerox was $174 a share, it's about $112 today, and there have been no splits. The company has done very well. <p>
So you really have two problems when you look down ten years. One of them is to get a company that does well, the other is to get a stock that the rest of the world will recognize as well as you. So, even though I'll give you three ideas for ten years out, I'd say you've got to really look at them more often than that, maybe every six months or so and see if the future still looks okay. But, the three I would pick, you need a China-play in there, and I think the style becoming recognized as one of the better China-plays is Charoen Pok Phand. That's not a little company, it's over a billion-dollars in market cap. I refer to it as the chicken-feed company, and through about eighty-five joint ventures in China they're involved in the feed for chickens, raising chickens, Kentucky Fried Chicken franchises. Its majority share is owned by a Chinese family in Thailand, but a lot of the shares are owned not only by people like myself, but the Templeton Organization, and I think Fidelity has taken a bite out of Pok Phand also. <p>
Next, I agree with Michael. You've got to be in telecommunications somehow. There the choice gets tougher, though. I mean, I think I would pick again a company that's certainly global, and the phone business, that would be maybe a company like Cable and Wireless [NYSE: CWP]; or in the equipment business, a company like Ericsson [Nasdaq: ERICY], and their stock is down today, and therefore buyable today. Ericsson out of Sweden, ERICY over the counter. I think I've gotten to know Lars Renquist fairly well anyway, and I think he's one of the true visionaries in the business when in comes to technology.<p>
And finally the question we had before, banking. I believe that the world's going to be a better place, rather than a worse place. My choice would be a bank like Banco Santander [NYSE: STD], a big Spanish bank that, by the way, now owns 11 percent of the sixth largest bank in the United States as well as First Union. <p>
Sue Herera: All right, Jim. What do you like?<p>
Jim Dines: First of all, I'm very proud to be on this stage with a lot of really good long-term talent, there is a lot of experience here and I'm sure they would agree with me that The Dines Letter feels that this is a market we've never seen before, that something very unusual is happening now, and there are a number of brand new factors involved. <p>
The first one is that the world is growing up economically as never before, and this is a brand new situation. Managements have never been so motivated for shareholders value, the buyoffs, the layoffs, anything; and, yeah, Mike is right, the old economy is dead, but you know you're getting companies like Eastman Kodak, and General Motors and Allied Chemical that are taking these old prosaic industries and bringing big profits, so you can make a lot of money on these stocks. <p>
I want to talk to you people. You know, a lot of you are beginners in the stock market. You're coming into the market for the first time, you're turning from the poor results in real estate in recent years, and you're pouring into the natural entry place, which is mutual funds, for those who are too lazy to pick their own stocks. But I want you to understand that we are now in a special time. Even the government is thinking of putting Social Security money in the stock market. This is the end of a great mania, and there's a lot of interest, I noticed, in the audience to Jim Rogers, on the international markets. You mean you can't find anything good to invest in, in this country? You want to go to Uganda and buy a bank there? <p>
I'm not sure, you know you better think about sobering up, because this is a very dangerous business, and a lot of you people have never seen a bear market before, and we're going to have one sooner or later. My mass psychology book talks about how all gamblers secretly want to lose, you know, and a lot of people who are betting the rent money are going to have a very moving experience. And, sooner or later, we're going to have a bear market, some terrorist will blow up a nuclear device in a city or a Japanese bank will fail or something weird will happen. <p>
I want you all to reflect before you go crazy on the stock market, that sooner or later, there will be a stampede out of the market. And when it does, there will be not enough buyers around to buy all your mutual funds. You will have the same problem with mutual funds that you had with real estate, and that is the liquidity. So, I think you should consider being a little conservative also. So, having said all that, I will certainly agree with Jim Rogers about getting money out of the country, I've been telling my subscribers that for years and that is to get the money out of the country and invisible it. Because things are going to happen on the currency market and that will be tied into gold. <p>
So which of the three stocks do I like most? First of all, I would pick one gold stock in that group and I would stay with it. To me, the management is more important than the product. I'm very into management. I find that high quality managements, the stocks are always overpriced and you buy them before they always get more so. So, I would stay with Barrick Gold [NYSE: ABX], we got in that stock about 10 and it's about 30 now and I think it's going to 100. The second one would be oil and to me the smartest oil management is Royal Dutch Petroleum [NYSE: RD]. And, don't worry about the high price of the stock, that's another beautiful blue chip you can put in any portfolio. And the third one should be in technology, and it's got to be a company that's going to make it, and I tell you who I bet on, Bill Gates. I think he's smart as hell. Even though he missed the PC revolution he's waking up to the Internet, moving very quickly, signing deals with a lot of other alliances, a lot of other companies. I almost picked America Online instead of Microsoft, you pick either one because they're both good. But those are my three.<p>
Sue Herera: All right, Don. Where are you going to be?<p>
Don Phillips: Well, you said we were allowed to pick funds instead of stocks. <p>
Sue Herera: Yes, yes, that's a given. Unless you want to go out on a real limb?<p>
Don Phillips: I would buy a contrarian, blue chip quality-oriented domestic fund, akin to say Sequoia which is closed, so maybe I'd recommend a Clipper fund, managed by Jim Gibson or Selected American Shares, run by Shelby Davis who just has a spectacular long term record in New York Venture. I'd buy a natural resources fund, T. Rowe Price New Era would be a good choice there or Vanguard Energy. And, I'd buy an emerging markets fund and I'd look for someone with a proven track record there, and there are really two names since Jimmy isn't gracing us with a closed-end fund that he's running. I'd look for John M. Mussey, who runs the Colonial Newport Tiger Fund, I think he's exceptionally bright, and obviously Mark Mobius at Templeton. The opportunity to buy Mobius at Templeton in the closed-end arena, a couple of his funds like the Templeton Dragon fund are selling at double-digit discounts, and I think that would be a very attractive investment over the next decade. <p>
Sue Herera: All right, Liz what's on your wish list?<p>
Elizabeth Bramwell: Okay, well I think I would have something in the drug area. And, I think looking out on a ten-year basis, which is an interesting framework, I think I would choose Roche, which is a Swiss drug company which owns Genentech, so we could go into the biotech area. I think one of the global franchise consumer companies. . .I guess I'd go along with Coca-Cola, though it's at 82 or so at this point in time, but on a ten-year basis I think all the little wobbles kind of wash out and a high-priced stock can continue to be a high-priced stock and clip along and in the low penetration in the multiple parts of the world. And then I think in the industrial area, I would pick a company that really supplies numerous industries, and I think I'd probably go along with something like Illinois Tool Works [NYSE: ITW], which is the largest fastener company.<p>
Sue Herera: Now Jimmy, all your money is out of the country, so you won't be buying any stock, right? <p>
Jim Rogers: No, I will give you three, I will play the game. I would buy the CRB Index, I would buy the Goldman-Sachs Index and I would buy any stock in Venezuela. Any stock in Iran would be better but it's illegal for Americans to buy Iran now, so, if you're foreign, you can buy any stock in Iran; failing that, any stock in Venezuela.<p>
Sue Herera: All right, let's move down here. CRB Index, Goldman-Sachs Index and any stock in Venezuela. Fair enough. All right, here we go.<p>
Question: My question is for Jimmy Rogers. I happen to agree with you that we're in a cyclical market for commodities, because I don't think you could have an emerging country that needs to build roads and houses, etc., etc., it needs basic materials. But I want you to tell me where I'm wrong because I disagree with you about wage pressures, because I know you're an inflationary person at this point. You think commodities and wages are going to drive up inflation, and I understand the commodity, but we're going through a historical period, as Jim Dines said, with a shift of labor. Unless we get population control under control, we're going to have too many people for the amount of positions that we can support. And I think that's what's going to happen, is that the emerging markets, wages are going to go up, but the developing markets, wages are going to go down, so that on balance you're going to have not a lot of wage pressure. Where am I wrong?<p>
Jim Rogers: Traditionally, the way that inflation has worked is you've had the prices of things go up and then the spouse goes down to the supermarket and comes home and says, Spouse, you've got to get more money because the price of eggs has gone up, or the price of bacon or whatever. The wage pressures come after the pressure of things, of paper, whatever it happens to be, that's the way it's always worked in the past. Your argument is that there is all this labor out there. Well, let me explain to you. <p>
They've all seen Dallas on TV now, they all want to live like we do. They all want to buy a pair of tennis shoes. They want to buy it. If you think they're just going to sit out there and work for a dollar a day, so that we can sit here and not have inflation, let me introduce you to the real world. Because all those people who are now coming into the world economy, are going to compete with us to buy, as well as to sell things, and they want to have a better life, too. Just to give you a couple of examples, as you may know the world inventories of everything are at the lowest levels in recorded history, oils, zinc, lead, grains, everything, we're going to have bad crops before long, I don't know when or where, we're going to have some dislocation before long. <p>
It is the official policy of the Chinese government, right now, one of their next immediate goals, and that's for everybody in China to have two more eggs a week. Well, you say, big deal, we can go across the street and buy two more eggs no problem with that at all. Now this is not some pipe dream that the Chinese have, they want to do it now, 'cause they want to benefit from all this new prosperity they have. If they get two more eggs per week in China, that will consume the entire grain crop of Australia, and Australia is one of the five largest grain producing countries in the world, their entire crop, not the extra crop, the entire crop. So you have enormous demand pressures coming, you have enormous supply problems in the world. Everybody is going to be trying to buy when there is a very narrow window and very narrow inventories. That will lead all the way to wage pressures.<p>
Question: This is for John Dessauer. There is a negative article written in Forbes on Vietnam, I think it was March 25th of this year (if I may say, it wasn't too negative), in discussing how the government is stifling foreign investment through their demand of joint ventureship, the understanding being that it's important for Communist government to embrace the foreign investment coming in, in order for the society to proliferate as you were saying. Can you comment on that?<p>
John Dessauer: It's a problem not just in Vietnam, but everywhere you've had Communism before. The basic problem is that everything is owned by the state, right? All companies, all land, all farms, all private property belonged to the state. And so now the problem is, how do you get rid of the state ownership, it's now a problem peculiar to Vietnam. By the way, we've seen all the privatizations in France, haven't we, too? And privatizations in the UK and elsewhere, Europe went through this period where the government acquired everything and then you have to get it back in the private sector. And there is a debate, Vietnam is probably ten years behind China in evolving the official political approach to how to make the transition from the state owning the factory to private enterprise. But, I can tell you from visiting with government officials last fall there, that I'm quite impressed with their official long term plan. <p>
Now let me say something, when I go to China in a few weeks time, I'm going with a  Chinese gentleman who grew up during the cultural revolution, a very intelligent Chinese gentleman. He said to me on the phone from Shanghai the other day, he said, "When you go to Shanghai, we want to go and talk to the economic officials, right?" I said, "Right." He said, "But not to the top people here," and I said, "Why not talk to the top?" And he said, "Because in Asia, the top people, they never know anything, you've got to go and talk to the people who are getting it done." Here too. So when you talk to the people who are getting it done in China or Vietnam, you see a very intelligent plan. <p>
There's a lot talk about when will Vietnam have a stock market, and the information I got is, that they are going to follow the Taiwan model, that as they privatize the good businesses now owned by the government, the shares are going to go to the people of Vietnam and literally the stock exchange in Vietnam will be for the Vietnamese, and only later will the stock exchange open up to outside investors. So I think what you read in the press is often true as far as it goes, it just doesn't go far enough, and I wouldn't get too hung up on the problems that these countries in Asia are facing in their transition from Communism to an open market. <p>
Question: I've seen some reports that the next big craze in computers is going to be 3-D computer games. And, with this it will drive the memory requirements of the computer way up. Do any of you have any comment on this and the current sell-off of computer memory stock? <p>
Sue Herera: It sounds like you, Michael. <p>
Michael Murphy: Yes, at least let me start on that one. Well, that's certainly true, 3-D is an expensive graphics application that has lived on sort-of $20,000 workstations for the last five years, and like everything in technology, it now gets squeezed down and pushed onto an add-on board, onto PC's and then probably five years from now, Intel will add it into their chip, and it will be part of the microprocessor. So it is one of the big drivers, like video teleconferencing, which happens to use a lot of the same software and hardware. <p>
We just recently, in fact in the last issue, recommended Diamond Multimedia as a way to play. It's an add-on board company. It is just one, though, of several new applications, including voice recognition and videoconferencing that are going to continue to drive this whole electronics, computing/communications thing for the next five or ten years. The reason that you keep getting new things driving it, is because the cost of doing the computing comes down so fast, that stuff you can literally do only today on a super-computer, you know within the next ten years you'll be able to do on a home computer sitting on top of your TV set. It's just inevitable that you'll get there from here. <p>
I don't see any reason for this to slow down and what a lot of the panel has said, and maybe the last thing we ought to leave you with is, it is managements that really ultimately make the difference, because the whole world is changing. A lot of things are changing fast, and the products that people make today, are not the products they're going to be making ten years from now. The places they do business aren't the places they are going to do business, maybe even the industries they're in, won't exactly be the industries they're in. But, if you can find those really good managements and associate your capital with them at reasonable prices, that's the way to cope with the rate of change for the next ten years. <p>
Sue Herera: I wish we had more time, so we'll just have to do it again next year. I want to thank all the panelists, you guys were terrific, it's been such a pleasure. I'd like to thank you all for coming. I hope that the rest of your seminar experience has been as good as it has been so far, it's been terrific for me, and I think all the panelists have enjoyed it as well. Thanks for a great time, we had a wonderful time with you, and I hope the rest of your afternoon is terrific.
					</font>
