	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>03/25/96 -- Liz Macdonald, Worth magazine Financial Editor</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>IT'S TAX TIME</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Monday, March 25, 1996, Worth Financial Editor Elizabeth Macdonald joined Worth OnLine for "Conference Call: It's Tax Time." The hour-long live event focused on tax reform and the IRS. Following is a transcript from this event.<p>
WorthRoom: Tonight we have Elizabeth Macdonald, Worth's Financial Editor on taxes.<p>
WorthEdit1: We are pleased to have Liz with us here tonight. She  comes to us fresh from testifying before the House Ways  and Means Committee.<p>
TJF SRQ: Is she up for realty-related tax questions?<p>
WorthEdit1: Liz is here to talk about tax reform and the IRS.<p>
TJF SRQ: Teaching an elephant to tap dance, eh?<p>
Macdonald: You ain't kidding, TJF. Here's a little anecdote about me.  I've been writing about the IRS for the last 9 years. The  IRS got so angry with me at one point, its national  headquarters sent a memo out to all of its offices across  the country which said, "If Elizabeth Macdonald calls,  don't speak to her." I tried to use that memo to get a raise, but of course,  that didn't work.<p>
TJF SRQ: Well Liz, it's nice to have friends in high places.<p>
Jess14000: What annoys you most about the tax system?<p>
Macdonald: THE most annoying thing is this: When taxpayers call
  the IRS to get answers to their questions, and I'm  referring to its 800 help line, if the IRS gives taxpayers  erroneous answers, taxpayers get slammed with a  penalty, but they can't get those fines lifted unless the  IRS sent that information in writing. Now, I was on  CSpan last Wednesday talking to callers about this, and  lo and behold, the editor of Money Magazine, Frank Lalli  was on with me, and he said, "Well, we got advice from  the IRS in writing." Well, I said, you're Money Magazine,  of course they're going to write back to you. Fat chance  regular taxpayers can even GET THROUGH-7 out of ten  times, the lines are busy. Anyway, the point is, taxpayers  are all too often stuck dealing with a truly abysmal  system.<p>
TJF SRQ: What annoys me most is the thought that tax breaks only  benefit "the rich." I happened to get a call from the IRS many years ago over my caller I.D. system.  I now call right in to their local office on that "secret" line.<p>
Macdonald: Woo woo, what's that secret line all about? Can you give it to me?<p>
TJF SRQ: Caller I.D. solves lots of problems! How successful will tax reform be without spending  reform?<p>
Macdonald: Awesome question, TJF. Here's the deal. The federal  income tax costs individuals $501.2 billion, and that's  just from individuals. For corporations, it costs about $150 billion. The government collects the rest from  excise taxes and the like. So, it collects about $1.3  trillion or so each year. But, it's spending about $250  billion or so more than what it collects. So what you've  got is a usurious system and a government that sticks a  crowbar in our wallets, but won't get off public feedbag.  Remember the government replaced the billions in the  Social Security trust fund with IOUs. So you're right, spending reform is a must, but it can go hand in hand  with tax reform, too.<p>
TJF SRQ: Given the choice, I would opt out of social security and  invest on my own. Your thoughts?<p>
JAKE585: I may be a little bit cynical, but I don't think any thing of significance will happen on taxes.<p>
Macdonald: Well the question is whether fiddling around with S.S.  privatization would give all of us an easy street  retirement. Currently, a privatization task force  populated by the likes of Robert Ball, former Social  Security Administration chairman, is split between  privatization and keeping the status quo. Currently, the  system pays $336 billion a year to some 43 million  beneficiaries, and the system is due to slide into the red  beginning in 2013, and completely by 2020.<p>
 Five of the panels 13 members are privatizers. They  would slash workers 6.2 percent S.S. tax to 1.2 percent  and require that they invest the remaining 5 percent in  Personal Savings accounts, which you'd set up at a bank,  brokerage or mutual fund. You could then invest in any  asset, (including junk bonds) and after age 62 begin  drawing down. The thing is, we've been paying this tax all  along, right? And the government always bailed out  if you make a bad call in your own PSA. Will the  government then bail you out, which is the ethical thing  to do? No word yet on what they're deciding about this.  But I'll tell you, these personal investment plans have  been around since the dawn of the 80s, and that's always been a major sticking point.<p>
STheis8654: Elizabeth, can you guess for me the date and possible  amount of any capital gains tax relief?<p>
Macdonald: Well, STheis 8654, you won't see any capital gains relief  until after the election. The last version offered by  Congressional republicans would have sent about $27  billion back, but don't hold me to that number, over five  years or so. Anyway, the interesting thing about the way  the Republicans wrote this capital gains tax cut is this:  They set it up as a 50 percent deduction, for an effective 19.8 percent rate (half the top effective 39.6 percent  bracket). So, what that means is, and this one's a doozy,  is that it's an above the line item--taxpayers would  factor that deduction in when calculating their adjusted  gross income. So, if this deduction then	effectively  lowers AGI, what does that mean for taxpayers? You got  it--a lower threshold to hurdle for medical expenses (currently you can only deduct medical expenses that  exceed 7.5 percent of your AGI) and for other write-offs.  Mum's the word on this one, let's not let Congress know  about this break, okay?<p>
WorthRoom: Liz, what do you think of the portion of the debate on the  flat tax involving the home mortgage interest  deduction? Some say it will not matter, others say that  it will have damaging effects on the real estate market.<p>
Macdonald: Well, ignore those who tell you it won't matter. It  sure as heck will, by as much as a 15 percent drop in  property values. Now, you probably saw the DRI-McGraw Hill report on it. But what's really interesting too, about  the flat tax debate is that banks won't have to pay taxes  on the interest income it, or they, rather, receive, so  many believe rates will drop, too, thereby making it  easier for first time home buyers. I think the market can  survive this fall off, especially given the boom in home  purchases if rates do fall. I know it's a hot and  controversial debate though, one that has many  established economists stumped. But even so, the  difference in tax exempt and taxable bonds, many  economists believe, is a premium taxpayers are  willing to pay. So, the thinking is, rates could fall to tax-exempt level, which is about 6 percent or so. I'll be watching this one, and write me if you have any more  thoughts about it.<p>
SSGuest: What are some of stupid things taxpayers do that  taxpayers do to clue the IRS in on the fact that they're  cheating?<p>
Shooter925: Elizabeth:  Any tax reform currently on the table for  single parents, i.e. child care deductions, college tuition,  etc.?<p>
WorthEdit1: First we'll take the tax cheat question, then we'll go on  to the single parent one.<p>
Macdonald: YAY! A question about the IRS, my favorite subject.
 Stupid tax tricks abound, say the IRS auditors I  interviewed for our April story. You remember when  Ralph Kramden lapsed into his trademark hummuna  hummuna when the IRS called him in for not signing his return? Well, the IRS loves to catch taxpayers  twitching or biting their nails, as that's a dead giveaway  something is wrong with a return. But here are the others  boneheaded things they love to nail taxpayers for:  Sympathy plays are quite common. Many taxpayers think  crying will wipe out their bills. Wrong. One auditor told  me she gives taxpayers a tissue and tell them yeah,  right, get on with it. Another is trying to be friends with  the auditor, by, say, talking to them on a first-name  basis. Auditors hate that, as I would too, if someone got  chummy with me too fast. But here's the best one I heard:  Many taxpayers try to alter the canceled checks they use  to justify write-offs by putting in a number ahead of the  others appearing in the check amount box and on the  check amount line. For example, instead of a $75 check,  it miraculously becomes $575. Get it? Guess what? Every  time a bank cancels out a check, it prints the correct amount it was cashed for below the signature line in the  bottom right hand corner. Whooooops!<p>
WorthEdit1: Now we have a question from Shooter925, who asks if  there are any tax reform breaks for single parents such  as child care deductions or breaks for college tuition?<p>
Macdonald: The Contract on the American Family, WHOOPS with the American Family has a $500 family tax credit in it, but  that's currently stalled in Congress. Clinton just offered  up a tax credit for families who earn $75,000 or below,  but it starts out as $300 in 1996 and increases to $500  by 1999. He also proposed a $5,000 deduction for  education and training beginning in 1996, and increasing  to $10,000 by 1999, thereby turning $41 billion back to  voters. And that's the operative word here-- As you'll  remember, Clinton is one of the biggest flim-flammers ever to hit the Capitol. And besides, why give parents a  tax break that their children will have to inherit later on  any way? Just like Clinton's vaunted middle class tax  cut, which is WHY WE ELECTED HIM IN THE FIRST PLACE, I  don't put much stock in all this talk of transparent tax  cuts. Boy, it gets me so mad even thinking about it. I probably won't get a good night's sleep now, so let's drop  this one, okay?<p>
WorthEdit1: JugOPunch has a question about tuition reimbursement. Should he file for an extension hoping Congress extends  exemption, or report it as another income on line 21?<p>
Macdonald: JugOPunch, so far, Congress has not attached a rider
 to any legislation that would extend the $5,250  education reimbursement. And that's truly upsetting to me. But let me say this about filing extensions. I had  heard for the last 5 years that the IRS won't audit  returns that are filed with an extension, meaning, those  returns filed after April 15th. I could never get  verification for this, but I'm happy to say I finally did.  Some former IRS workers now say that any returns filed  after mid-June likely won't be audited, because the IRS  will have already scored those that came in on time and  sent along those returns to one of its 63 district offices  for audit, (a district office houses the IRS audit team). I  had always thought that to be an old wives tale, but now  I'm more convinced it's true, and it makes perfect sense.  But keep reading the Wall Street Journal (we're a  monthly, not a daily, sorry) for more updates on the  education reimbursement, okay? I'll stay on it, too.  Thanks.<p>
JugOPunch: Thanks, I just would prefer not to inform the IRS about  the tuition until I absolutely must.<p>
WorthEdit1: We have about five more minutes. Any questions?<p>
RBinzIV: Any tax relief/credits on the horizon for children sent to private/parochial schools ?<p>
Macdonald: I heard testimony on the hill about the need for tax
 relief for parochial school tuition, but it went nowhere.  But I'll tell you this--this IRS is on the look out for  taxpayers who deduct this tuition as a charitable  write-off. That's just a sidebar comment from me, I  want to keep you posted about what's going on. Thanks  for the good question.<p>
RBinzIV: Thank you Elizabeth, Good night.<p>
WorthEdit1: We have one more question from Jess14000. Will tax  reform actually happen?<p>
Macdonald: Well, the whole tax reform discussion reminds me of a
 quote from George Bernard Shaw, "If you laid all the  economists in the world end to end, they'd never reach a  conclusion." So, that about says it all. Expect to see  Congress collapse the number of brackets, and move  toward some flat tax style measures. The current code is  hated by one and all, as "it makes more liars out of  Americans than golf has," to paraphrase Will Rogers. And  no, I don't brush my teeth with Bartlett's Book of  Quotations. But I do sincerely hope, hope, hope for  considerable reform, because we simply can't go on like this.<p>
WorthEdit1: I'd like to thank everyone for being here tonight. Great questions. In the words of... oh, never mind. But seriously. Thank you Liz Macdonald for being with us  tonight.<p>
SSGuest: Thanks, Liz.<p>
WorthRoom: Thanks Liz!!<p>
DAnliker: tks<p>
WorthEdit1: Thank you all for being here. We are planning on making  these chats--we call them "Conference Call" a regular  feature on Worth OnLine.<p>
Macdonald: And thank you all for a great conversation. Good night! 	
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
