	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>03/20/96 -- Tax Hearings, Washington, D.C.</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>WORTH GOES TO WASHINGTON<p>
Read through these dispatches to see what happened throughout the first day of the hearings. Then head to the Worth OnLine message board, TAXES ON TRIAL, to post your own opinions about tax restructuring and questions for Elizabeth Macdonald.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						9:36 a.m.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>TAX REFORM: PHASE ONE</font></b><p>
Today's hearings begin the first of three phases of the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax reform. The first phase focuses on the problems with the current code. The second hearing, on March 27, will look at the impact that changing the code would have on the overall economy. Starting in April and continuing through the fall, the committee will hold three to five hearings a month examining the impact of tax reform on various sectors of the economy. Last year, the Committee heard three days of preliminary hearings on proposals to replace the current Federal tax system.<p>
Presiding over these hearings is Committee Chairman Bill Archer (R-Texas), who has stated that his goal is to see a new code signed into law "during the first year of the next president's term." Archer is a supporter of the consumption tax.<p>
The hearings are taking place in the main Committee hearing room in the Longworth House Office Building on Capitol Hill where invited witnesses will testify during two panel presentations. After the members of each panel present their testimony, the floor will open up for a question and answer period.<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine.<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim will be filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout the day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.<p>
9:58 a.m.<p>
Live from the House Ways and Means Committee tax reform hearings in Washington, D.C.:<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>DIGGING UP ROOTS</font></b><p>
During a photo-op session with the press, House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer displayed the original 16-page income tax bill that was signed into law by President Woodrow Wilson in 1913. (The tax code was so controversial that President Wilson was exempted from paying the tax if he signed it.) "This small 19-inch baby is the original document that grew up to become today's monster," Archer said while reaching under the podium to hoist the current multi-volume forms and filing instructions.  <p>
The 1913 income tax law was aimed at the rich. Citizens who made less than $20,000 were exempt--$20,000 in today's terms is the equivalent of $100,000. <p>
Ironically, Archer pointed out, the original tax bill represents the very roots of the tax law that he plans to dig up and throw away.<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim will be filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.<p>
Live from the House Ways and Means Committee tax reform hearings in Washington, D.C.:<p>
10:20 a.m.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>EVEN THE PROS ARE CONFUSED</font></b><p>
Before hearing from the first panel of witnesses, Archer explained that he intended today's tax hearings to be bi-partisan and in-depth. The witnesses were invited to talk about the complexities and problems with the current code to help the Committee consider "fairer, simpler, less intrusive proposals for tax reform," he said. <p>
Net week, leading economists will testify on how a change in the tax system can lead to a stronger economy.<p>
The first witness was Frank Lalli, Managing Editor of Money magazine. After Congress passed the sweeping tax reforms in 1986, Money gave an open-book exam to 50 vounteer tax preparers. The exam, given in January 1988, gave a financial profile of a hypothetical family. The volunteers were asked to prepare tax returns based on the information. The results, according to Lalli: The 50 pros computed 50 different amounts of tax that the same family owed. The tax bills varied by nearly 50%--from $7,200 to about $12,000.<p>
However, critics on the Hill and at the D.C. publication Tax Notes say that the Money test was inordinately difficult and does not represent the typical American taxpayer's return.<p>
Lalli also asked the committee to review the results of a January poll of taxpayers across the country that Money conducted. The majority (84%) agreed that the U.S. tax system needs a major overhaul. Fifty nine percent said the number-one goal should be fairness. "Despite the push for a flat tax, 64% of the taxpayers said the rich should pay more tax than others," Lalli said. The poll stated that 33% favored a flat tax,16% liked a national sales tax, and 19% wanted a plan to tax income minus savings. "And let me add this note: Most taxpayers (59%) said tax reform will not influence their votes in November."<p>
However, the Money poll findings were based 'on a small sample' of taxpayers, says a Money editor, and therefore may be of limited use and unrepresentative of the American public at large (Money would not say how many taxpayers were polled).<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine.<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout the day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.<p>
10:42 a.m.<p>
Live from the House Ways and Means Committee tax reform hearings in Washington, D.C.:<p>
<p><a name="SUB4"><b><font size=+1>HIDDEN COSTS</font></b><p>
Compliance with the entire federal tax system will cost Americans almost $225 billion in 1996, according to today's second witness, Arthur P. Hall, Ph.D., senior economist for the Tax Foundation. The rules and regulations for the Federal income tax alone account for approximately $157 billion of this cost, according to Tax Foundation figures.<p>
"One way to comprehend the magnitude of this is to imagine wantonly destroying every vehicle produced by the Ford Motor Company and more than one-third of the vehicles produced by the Chrysler Corporation," Hall said. <p>
"The cost of complying with a tax system is directly related to the complexity of the system," he said.  "The Flat Tax and the USA Tax System immediately eliminate complexities and, therefore, their attendant compliance costs." Hall strongly advocated dumping the income tax in favor of a simpler version of either of these taxes. <p>
However, says Worth's Financial Editor Elizabeth Macdonald, advocates of reform "still need to honestly deliver the facts about these proposals." For one, says Macdonald, the flat tax proposed by Rep. Dick Armey (R-TX) would not abolish all deductions, as currently touted. For example, one deduction not only survives, but increases--the business entertainment deduction, which would increase from 50 percent to 100 percent, according to officials in Armey's office. <p>
Furthermore, the large standard deductions in Armey's flat tax, and the two proposed by former presidential candidates Steve Forbes and Phil Gramm would effectively knock a large swath of taxpayers out of the tax system. For example, Forbes's exemption for a family of four would be roughly $36,000. "What that means," says Macdonald, "is that these families would get to vote for and receive government services, but would not have to pay a nickel in taxes."<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine.<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout the day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.<p>
11:04 a.m.<p>
<p><a name="SUB5"><b><font size=+1>THE MAGIC NUMBER</font></b><p>
What is the maximum tax Americans are willing to pay? According to a Reader's Digest/Roper Center poll, Americans believe that the most a family of four should pay is 25 percent (including income, Social Security, sales, and property taxes). Under the current system, the average family of four with an income of $200,000 pays about 39 percent, according to The Tax Foundation.<p>
Would a single mom on welfare answer differently than the head of an affluent family of four? Actually, no. And the overwhelming unanimity of the 25-percent benchmark was what witness Rachel Wildavsky, senior staff editor of The Reader's Digest magazine, emphasized during her testimony in front of the House. <p>
"Male respondents to our poll thought that 25 percent should be the top for any family. So did female respondents. So did respondents earning $75,000 per year or more. So did respondents earning less than $30,000. So did blacks, whites, conservatives, liberals--I could go on," she said. "If you asked whether the ocean was wet you'd probably find this kind of unanimity."<p>
The magazine published the results of the October 1995 survey in February in an article entitled "How Fair Are Our Taxes?" <p>
The Reader's Digest poll also showed that most Americans believe that they are overtaxed. No surprises there. But they believe their neighbors--both poor and rich--are too. What's more, the survey refuted the supposed beef working- and middle-class Americans have with their affluent counterparts. "Our poll found no support whatsoever for the claim that affluent Americans are not paying 'their fair share,'" Wildavsky said.<p>
During the question-and-answer period, Representative Sam Gibbons (D-FL) said that the 25 percent figure was unrealistic: "That would take a revolution of the tax code because the needs of government are greater than 25 percent of the American citizen's income."<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.<p>
11:22 a.m.<p>
<p><a name="SUB6"><b><font size=+1>IRS ABUSES</font></b><p>
"The government always promises not to misuse information," said this morning's final witness. Then David Burnham, author of "A Law onto Itself: The IRS and the Abuse ofPower," went on outline how the IRS has in fact become "the nation's single most powerful instrument of social control."<p>
"The use of the IRS and its information for improper political purposes has gone forward on the basis of direct orders from the most senior officials of the government, including several presidents," Burnham said.<p>
His list of abusers included John F. Kennedy, under whose leadership the IRS stripped tax exempt status from conservative groups that spoke out against his administration. Under Richard Nixon, Burnham said, the IRS formed the Special Service Staff, a secret IRS unit that for a short period of time audited political dissidents.<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.<p>
12:57 p.m.<p>
<p><a name="SUB7"><b><font size=+1>PANEL 1 RECAP</font></b><p>
In Part 1 of "Worth Goes to Washington" witnesses before the House Ways and Means Committee talked about the inefficiencies of the current tax code and the abuses of the IRS.  Worth has written extensively on the topic.<p>
In October 1995, Worth reported that the current income tax is riddled with $500 billion in loopholes permitting some millionaires to pay no income taxes whatsoever. "Cheats rip off the government by roughly $127 billion each year, while honest taxpayers spend more than $100 billion a year to figure out what they owe," wrote Elizabeth Macdonald in "Tax Reform Unplugged."<p>
How do these overwhelming numbers affect the individual taxpayer? The second panel of witnesses before the House Ways and Means Committee will offer testimony that will illustrate the extraordinary effect the current convoluted code has on ordinary taxpayers.<p>
The first witness is Worth's financial editor Elizabeth Macdonald. Stay tuned for excerpts from her testimony.<p>
1:16 p.m.<p>
Live from the House Ways and Means Committee tax reform hearings in Washington, D.C.:<p>
<p><a name="SUB8"><b><font size=+1>MACDONALD ON THE STAND</font></b><p>
The second panel of witnesses began with Worth financial editor Elizabeth Macdonald, a specialist in income tax issues. She appears frequently on CNN and CNBC, as well as on the CBS Evening News, the Today Show, and National Public Radio.<p>
She joined Worth in 1994 after nine years with Money magazine. She has won seven major business journalism awards, including the Gerald Loeb Award for her series on the Internal Revenue Service.<p>
Macdonald has written extensively about the problems with the current system of tax collection. Her most recent story, "Putting a Face on Fear" in the April issue of Worth, looks at the real live human beings behind the terrifying, all-powerful IRS. <p>
During her testimony before the House panel, Macdonald outlined her opinion as to the main problem at the IRS: a division that has driven a wedge between taxpayers and the government. "I firmly believe that this division is largely rooted in the IRS's intrusive, stone-cold, and intractable behavior," Macdonald said. "As a result, the American tax system is losing its sense of fairness and its moral suasion."<p>
Rather than endorsing a particular method of tax reform, Macdonald instead focused on the fact that no matter what system is implemented, one problem remains. "We'll still need a tax collector," Macdonald said. "I have decided to try to explain how the IRS's lack of concern is embedded in the rigid way it conducts its business of collecting taxes."<p>
Macdonald emphasized the bureaucratic overload prevalent in the managerial structure at the IRS. Anecdotally, Macdonald described the bureaucratic impediments that face IRS management. "This may be why top IRS officials seem driven to distraction on the agency's problems -- getting them to move on a project is the equivalent of squeezing 1,000 crickets into a jelly jar."<p>
Macdonald concluded with a suggestion to the lawmakers: "Make it a job requirement for the top IRS posts that an applicant have a management or even a military background, someone who knows what it's like to handle tens of thousands of people," she said, and reminded the panel that most IRS commissioners are tax lawyers. "They're probably perfectly good lawyers, but I truly do wonder about their managerial abilities."<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring. <p>
1:38 p.m.<p>
Live from the House Ways and Means Committee tax reform hearings in Washington, D.C.:<p>
<p><a name="SUB9"><b><font size=+1>IRS AS PEEPING TOM</font></b><p>
Harvey Shulman, general counsel for the National Association of Computer Consultant Businesses, urged Congress to close the IRS's "peephole on America." <p>
"Unfortunately, our tax system delves too often into almost every aspect of the day-to-day transactions of America's businesses," said Shulman. Shulman has been a lawyer for mid-sized and small businesses, with gross revenues of between one million and one hundred million dollars, many of which are high-tech professional services.<p>
As Worth reported in a June 1995 story, "Privacy and the Self-Employed," the IRS believes that employers, eager to reduce administrative and benefit costs, intentionally mis-classify many employees as independent contractors. Independent contractors who pay their own payroll taxes often come under fire of the IRS because of their supposed propensity to cheat.<p>
Shulman was one of two lawyers for JasTech, a Cleveland-based computer-consulting firm that was slapped with a $287,000 assessment for failing to send in payroll taxes for 65 computer programmers in 1993. The programmers, who were originally classified as independent contractors, were reclassified by the IRS as JasTech employees. The reclassification, according to the Worth story, was based on 60 returns filed by the workers.<p>
Shulman and attorney Craig Etter filed a Freedom of Information Act suit in federal district court to get the workers' returns using a loophole in the privacy law. By January 1995, the Justice Department had released confidential IRS material from 48 returns to the attorneys.<p>
In his testimony, Shulman concluded: "In the debate over tax reform, the 'right to privacy' must receive the highest priority. We can no longer embrace a tax system that depends upon government sponsored financial voyeurism into the lives of America's individuals and businesses."<p>
The basic problem, says Worth's financial editor Elizabeth MacDonald, is that "the rules governing employee classification are the most subjective and arbitrary in the code. The IRS relies on a loose conglomeration of case law, workers' compensation law and employer tort liability rules as well as the agency's rules. It's an administrative nightmare."<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.<p>
1:59 p.m.<p>
Live from the House Ways and Means Committee tax reform hearings in Washington, D.C.:<p>
<p><a name="SUB10"><b><font size=+1>ONE FAMILY'S IRS NIGHTMARE</font></b><p>
Ann Cook is an ordinary taxpayer whose family was literally swept away in an extraordinary IRS nightmare. Worth wrote about Cook and her husband Frank in a March 1995 Worth story, "Breakdown at the IRS" by Elizabeth Macdonald, who testified earlier. <p>
Her story, as reported in Worth, is as follows: The Cook's were harassed for ten years by the IRS. It seems that the agency didn't register the family's move from the West to the East Coast, even though they notified the IRS in writing that they were moving to Hartford, Ct. from Seattle. That year, the IRS audited the couple's 1982, 1983, and 1984 returns and sent them a bill in Seattle for $6,300. The Cooks never received it and the IRS interpreted their silence as tax delinquency.<p>
Not until 1989, despite repeated phone calls and letters to the Hartford office, did the couple receive written notice of the audits the IRS conducted. Ironically, Frank Cook claims he had complete receipts for the deductions the agency disallowed back in 1985. Ultimately, the IRS seized $35,000 in salary and savings. The Cook family, including three children, was reduced to living for an entire year on $150 per week.<p>
"Our anger is directed not at the fact of being taxed," she testified, "but rather the process which allows such travesties to occur. We suffered the indignity of being put in a position of impovershment, literally overnight."<p>
Today, more than 10 years later, the Cooks the IRS continues to have a $25,000 lien against them.<p>
When questioned by Chairman Archer about what kind of tax she believed would be best she replied: "I don't think it matters what kind of tax you have--flat, consumption, income. It is the agency that is collectiong the taxes--the IRS--that is the real problem."<p>
Signing off from Washington, this is Dayana Yochim for Worth OnLine<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring. <p>
2:18 p.m.<p>
<p><a name="SUB11"><b><font size=+1>Q&A WITH CONGRESSMAN CHRISTENSEN</font></b><p> 
As the tax reform hearings before the House Ways and Means Committee wrapped up, Worth OnLine conducted an exclusive interview with Congressman Jon Christensen (R-Neb). One of the big issues raised during today's testimony was the IRS's out-of-date methods of distinguishing  between employees and independent contractors.<p>
Congressman Christensen has sponsored a bill, HR1972, that would simplify the 20-point test the agency has laid out to determine who is an employee and who is an independent contractor. <p>
The bill he proposes would pare the current 20-part test down to three points. <p>
They are: 
1. Who does the employee take orders from--how independent are they from the entity?<p>
2. Where has the investment for the business and equipment come from?<p>
3. Does a contract exist between the two parties?<p>
Q: Why do you want to abolish the 20-point test?<p>
A: For example, one of these tests is, how much time do you spend atthe work site? The answer determines whether you are an employee of the company. The question is outdated. Given the telecommunications revolution, more people are working at home. <p>
Q: What is the status of the bill right now? <p>
A: We have held a few hearings already. We are holding the major hearing in early May with House Ways and Means. We urge all America Online and Worth OnLine readers to contact their congressmen and make sure they are a co-sponsor of HR1972. This is a truly bi-partisan bill.<p>
Q: Who is effected by this bill? <p>
A: It is an issue that is near and dear to people's hearts. Computer people, florists, home programmers. Silicon Valley applauds the movement. I am constantly getting suportive E-mails from workers there. <p>
Q: Who is opposed to this bill? <p>
Opposition is labor unions: They would much rather have the employee status. <p>
Even though helping small business is an important part of the Clinton administration's agenda, it will be hard to get it through because the core constituents from labor unions oppose the bill.<p>
Worth OnLine reporter Dayana Yochim has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring. <p>
2:40 p.m.<p>
In Worth OnLine's final dispatch of the day, Worth's financial editor Elizabeth Macdonald sums up the first day of tax reform hearings in front of the  House Ways and Means Committee.<p>
<p><a name="SUB12"><b><font size=+1>THE LONG AND TORTUROUS ROAD</font></b><p>
At the end of the hearings, it was clear to all who attended that Congress has embarked on a long and torturous road to fulfilling Archer's dreams of torpedoing the present system. <p>
It clearly showed as well the cast of characters who will be charged with the task of reforming the system, as well as the influences on Congress's decisionmaking. From the cranky, anti-government David Burnham, author of a book about the IRS, "A Law Unto Itself," who refused to answer the panel's questions about the efficacy of a flat tax, citing journalistic objectivity; to the sincere efforts of Reader's Digest's testimony about what the American public wants in a tax system, Congress got an earful.<p>
In the final analysis, the best example of the frustrating obstacles Congress faces in reforming the system came from one of its own members, Rep. Charles Rangel, (D-NY). Near the end of the hearing, Rep. Rangel asked the panel what annoys taxpayers the most about the present system. When the Reader's Digest representative answered "high rates," Rangel hollered, "But that's never going to change." Stay tuned. --Elizabeth Macdonald<p>
Worth OnLine has been filing up-to-the-minute reports throughout day from the House Ways and Means Committee hearings on tax restructuring.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
