<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 03/01/96 -- Peter Lynch Cybercast from Detroit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>03/01/96 -- Peter Lynch Cybercast from Detroit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Friday, March 1, Worth Magazine OnLine cybercasted Peter Lynch live from Detroit. In a speech delivered to automotive executives, Lynch spoke about his views on the economy, investing strategies, and the stock market in general. <p>
Peter Lynch is probably the best known stock picker of our time and certainly among the most successful. He was portfolio manager of Fidelity Investments' Magellan fund for 13 years, starting out in 1977 with $20 million in assets and winding up his tenure in 1990 with more than one million shareholders and assets in excess of $14 billion. During that period, Lynch delivered an average annual return of just over 29 percent. <p>
Lynch has served as executive vice president and director of Fidelity Management & Research Company and managing director of FMR Corporation. He has also written three best selling books on investing, "One Up on Wall Street," "Beating the Street," and his latest, "Learn to Earn: a beginner's guide to the basics of investing and business" (Simon and Schuster). <p>
Since 1992, Lynch has written exclusively for Worth magazine. A complete archive of his work is available only on Worth OnLine. <p>
During his speech in Detroit, Lynch offered advice and insight helpful to people both within and outside of the automotive realm:<p>
ON AUTOMAKERS:
Chrysler was the biggest position in the Magellan Fund for four years, and [it] went up tenfold and made for four easy years, I'll tell you that. I always have a sweet spot when I see a minivan going down the road.<p>
ON STOCKS:
Know what you own. You can't believe how many people buy stocks and have no idea what they own. This is the kind of stock people like to invest in: a relatively simple company -- they make a one megabyte S RAM, C mos bipolar risk floating point data IRO, 16 bit dual port memory, wet (SOEPL), four megaflop pale silicone emitter, a high band -- six gigahertz, double mentalization communication protocol and I sink nus, four wave, lead memory, token ring...If you own a piece of junk like that, you will never make money. Never. A silicon emitter? You will have no idea, but people buy stuff like this all the time. It just amazes me. These are people who are careful when they buy a toaster or something, and they'll hear about one of these things on the way to work and put $10,000 into it before sunset. And I bought companies like Dunkin' Donuts that I can understand. You have a recession and you don't have to worry. You don't have to worry about Korean imports or that somebody invented a new doughnut.<p>
If you come away from this with one thing, know what you own. You ought to be able to explain to a 7th grader in three minutes or less why you own this stock. What's the story? Not 'the sucker is going up' ... That is not the reason you own the stock. I tried that. That didn't work, either.<p>
PREDICTING THE MARKET:<p>
It is futile to predict the economy, predict the interest rates, predict the stock market ... Most people in the room were around in 1980, 1981. Did anybody tell you that we were going to have a 20 percent prime rate ... 12 percent unemployment, 14 percent inflation? I didn't get that phone call. I always said if you spend 13 minutes a year on economics you haev wasted 11 minutes.<p>
If you can predict interest rates correctly three times in a row on $10,000 you could have a billion dollars. There are not that many billionaires around. No one can predict interest rates.<p>
Now, I want to be very fair. I'm talking about forecasting the future. If I own a lot of auto stocks, I want to know what's happening with used car prices. If I own hotel stock, I want to know what's happening with inventories. This is stuff you can figure out. I want to know what's happening with inventories.<p>
'We're going to have a recession,' those people tell you that. 'That is totally wasted.' It is like predicting the weather three months in advance. Not in Arizona, just in New England or the Midwest. It doesn't work.<p>
You can't believe how much time people spend on predicting the stock market, the economy, interest rates. If you can predict interest rates correctly three times in a row on $10,000 you could have a billion dollars. There are not that many billionaires around. No one can predict interest rates. <p>
INVESTING:
You have plenty of time. People are so amazingly impatient to buy something. You could have bought Wal-Mart ten years after it went public. Very conservative person, you say? You could have made 30 times your money ... Microsoft, you could have made 25 times your money ... You have plenty of time to do the stuff. You don't have to do it in one minute.<p>
Check the facts rather than all the stuff about what is happening with the stock, has it gone up or down. You shouldn't care. You just say, what's the story? ... Eventually they always come back.<p>
People have great information. Imagine all the people who knew when Smith-Kline introduced a product called Tagamet ...  One year after it was on the market, all the people whose wives, husbands, mothers, fathers were cured of ulcers by Tagamet could have bought Smith-Kline and made 15 times their money .. But all the people in the pharmacies are buying oil drilling stocks. <p>
FAULTY MINDSETS:
Now I would like to get out dangerous things people say about stocks. Here's a good one: It's gone down this much already, it can't go much lower. I remember when Polaroid went from 140 to 110 and people said, 'If Polaroid goes below 100 back up the truck and buy it up.' They don't know anything about Polaroid but they said it's a good stock, all this technology, if it gets under 100, buy it. It went from 140 to 95 -- I mean, how much lower can it go? So you bought it. Within 12 months, the stock was 16. This is a company with no debt, it was overpriced at 100. They just introduced the camera no one wanted that didn't work and it was expensive, and other than that they were doing well. But they bought it just because it went from 140 to 90. <p>
I told people to buy Kaiser Industries and I said, 'The stock has gone from 29 to 16 -- how much lower can it go?' We then bought the largest block ever, I think, in the history of the American Stock Exchange -- 15 million shares at 14-3/4. At 10 I called my mother and said, 'Mom, the stock has gone from 29 to 10 -- how much lower can it go?' It went to 9,8,7,6,5,4 ... it happened fast so I kept my job. But I knew the story and I said there is something wrong. <p>
I was early on this at 14-3/4. At 4, the company is 25 million shares and the whole value of the company is a hundred million dollars, they own all of Kaiser Broadcasting, they owned Jeep at that point. Kaiser had no debt. Now, it's very hard to go bankrupt. Without any debt that would really be a challenge. So I knew. So we hung onto it. If you understand the story, when it goes down, it doesn't bother you. It bothers you a little bit, but at least you understand what you own and then you can buy more of it.<p>
Even a worse one to it: If it's gone up this high, how can it go any higher? This I think will surprise you. In 1951, Philip Morris sold for 12 cents. In 1975 it was a big stock at that point, 50 fold at that point. Now ten years later, the stock is up to 60 cents. This is adjusted for splits. And people said, here is a company, the industry is going less than one percent a year, I made five times my money, it's gone from 12 cents to 60 cents, I'll sell. I mean, how much higher can it go? The stock went up another 150 fold. This really hurts if you do the math and put $10,000 in a stock and all you can lose is $10,000. But if you miss the guys that go up 100 fold, the math is very bad.<p>
In the late '70s, I found out that in California there were one quarter as many McDonald's as there were Bank of America branches. You know, they were wrong. The company went overseas, they did breakfast and they opened three McDonald's a day. People 20 years ago said there were too many and the stock couldn't go any higher. It's only gone up a hundred fold since then. Check the facts rather than all the stuff about what is happening with the stock, has it gone up or down. You shouldn't care. <p>
LYNCH'S STOCK PICKS:
I can't really comment on individual stocks. If I said something, I might change my mind a few months later. I really would rather you learn something about it -- if you know something about memory chips or logic chips, and you see all of a sudden there's a shortage of memory chips, you have an edge. If you don't know anything about memory chips you shouldn't be buying the technology.<p>
LYNCH ON THE U.S. ECONOMY:
I think the key thing in America is the fact that the country is getting better, you know, we reduced our deficit. Our debt is a percentage of the GNP. Our deficit is a percentage of the GNP. Everything is getting better in this country, on all the fronts except for taxes. I mean, it would be easy -- I think we ought to set the capital gains the way it is in Japan. Zero. That would be a nice one. That's not flat, that's just zero. <p>
You know, we've had 2,000 companies come public the last three years in the United States. That is two a business day. Raised over a hundred billion dollars. That's an incredible thing for our country. Hire more employees, more efficient equipment, paid off bank debt, buy more plants, add services. That's an amazing positive. We've had 2,000 companies come public. Only 3,000 companies on the New York Stock Exchange, gives you an idea. I don't think 2,000 companies have come public in Europe since Charlemagne. And Europe has double-digit unemployment right now -- they're where the United States was in 1982 and 1983. Just starting this exercise. We've been into for 15 years. <p>
I think taxes are way too high. But the most important thing is, it's all screwed up. If you put a wing on your house and borrow money to put a wing on your house, the interest is tax deductible. $30,000 in a bank account, the interest in taxable then. What the hell kind of incentive is that? Savings equals investment. What we save in America goes into investment. What they save in China goes into investment. In Taiwan they waive 20 percent of what they earn, invest 20 percent into the economy. Singapore might be 30 percent. We could have saved a lot more, and we're telling people not to do it. It's not good for our children or our grandchildren. 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
