	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 01/22/97 -- Jack Robinson, manager of the Green Century Balanced Fund</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>01/22/97 -- Jack Robinson, manager of the Green Century Balanced Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On January 22, 1997, Jack Robinson joined Worth OnLine for a live "Conference Call." Robinson is President of Winslow Management Company and serves as subadvisor to the Green Century Balanced Fund, a unique type of mutual fund invested solely in environmentally-responsible companies. For calendar 1996, the Fund returned 25.02 percent to its investors, and was ranked No. 2 out of 277 unscreened U.S. balanced funds by Lipper Analytical Services Inc. In addition, the fund was ranked No. 1 for 1996 out of the 45 socially-responsible mutual funds. The following transcript is edited for clarity. The opinions expressed are those of Jack Robinson, and do not necessarily reflect the views of Worth OnLine, Worth magazine, or Capital Publishing. <p>
WorthEdit3:     Good evening, and welcome to Worth OnLine's CONFERENCE CALL series. Tonight, we're joined by Jack Robinson, President of Winslow Management Company. Winslow serves as subadvisor to the Green Century Balanced Fund, a unique type of mutual fund invested solely in environmentally responsible companies. Welcome, Mr. Robinson (he's using screenname JRobin3133). I'd like to begin by asking you to describe the criteria you use to determine which stocks to purchase for the Green Century Balanced Fund.<p>
JRobin3133:     We use 4 criteria:  environmental screen, technical, quantitative, & fundamental research.<p>
GRI CRS1:     When will Hewlett take off?<p>
JRobin3133:     GRI:  Hewlett Packard (NYSE: HWP) is environmentally responsible but selling at a multiple in excess of its grow rate.<p>
MAMANOGUE:     Would you buy a tobacco stock?<p>
JRobin3133:     MAM:  No, we would not buy a tobacco stock, they are the next asbestos candidates.<p>
MAMANOGUE:     Agreed. Thank you.<p>
JRobin3133:     MAM:  Also, tobacco creates toxic runoff problems.<p>
Almintas:     Mr. Robinson, why did you decide to concentrate on environmentally responsible companies?<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  Green companies have 3 financial advantages:  stronger balance sheets, lower costs, and high revenue opportunities.<p>
MAMANOGUE:     What about a chicken company -- also toxic runoff?<p>
JRobin3133:     MAM:  yes, chicken companies are a problem but not free range chickens.<p>
Almintas:     JR, what reason do you see for that?<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  environmental companies have lower contingent liability and enviro costs average 6 percent. So, you reduce costs, minimize liabilities, and develop green products for a growing market.<p>
NVME345:     Is the green fund a socially-responsible fund or just a name?<p>
JRobin3133:     NV:  It is a green fund. Green companies also tend to be socially responsible.<p>
NVME345:     JRobin do you have any opinion on Computer Associates (NYSE: CA), Nautica (NASD: NAUT), and Abercrombie and Fitch (NYSE: ANF)?<p>
JRobin3133:     NV:   CA having troubles.<p>
WorthEdit3:     Some say socially-responsible funds shun big returns by shunning big companies. What's your opinion of "big business" as green companies?<p>
JRobin3133:     Worth:  Socially-responsible (SR) and environmentally responsible (ER) companies come in all shapes and sizes, from IBM (NYSE: IBM) to Wild Oats (NASD: OATS).<p>
Almintas:     JR, does socially responsible approach help in fund sales?<p>
JRobin3133:     Al:  It can help in sales. 9 percent of all managed money is socially responsible in one way or another.  That is one in every ten dollars under management is pro-active.<p>
Almintas:     JR, are green companies currently so attractive due to a certain favoritism from government side? Partially?<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  We look for companies driven by economics not regulation.<p>
Almintas:     Yes, but the government has impact upon economics.<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  Impact, yes, but frequently negative.  You can't depend on them .<p>
Tex61:     JR, what is in store for the international funds over the next few years?<p>
JRobin3133:     Tex:  international green fund outlook is very positive.<p>
Almintas:     JR, do you invest internationally?<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  yes, we do using ADRs. As well, the market for environmental goods and services is international. It is especially big in Germany.<p>
WorthEdit3:     What are some of the companies that lead the Green Century Balanced Fund to a 25.02% return in '96?<p>
JRobin3133:     Worth: Leading companies include PEV = Philip Environmental (NYSE: PEV), Thermo Electron Corp. (NYSE: TMO), Memtec (NASD: MMTCY), Checkpoint Sys. (NYSE: CKP).<p>
Almintas:     What companies are the biggest investments here and abroad?<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  global environmental companies include TMO, MMTCY, Xerox (NYSE: XRX), PEV.<p>
Tom575:     Any comments on the stock markets condition now?<p>
JRobin3133:     TOM: We are fully invested.  It is unhealthy not to be.  Most all signals remain go.<p>
Tom575:     I just went to 100 percent cash for now. I think we are going to have a pull back soon in the stock market<p>
JRobin3133:     Tom, anything is possible but there are always good values.<p>
Almintas:     Do you think that environmental laws will become more demanding in the future?<p>
JRobin3133:     AL: Absolutely.  The worse it gets, the greater the regs. We like companies that go beyond compliance and are finding competitive advantages from environmental management.<p>
SANDBOB:     Can you define socially responsible, please?<p>
JRobin3133:     BOB:  SR includes multiple factors such as defense, tobacco, military, community, diversity, and of course, the environment.  Our focus is the environment because you can measure it in dollars and cents.  It is tied to the bottom line.<p>
Almintas:     JR, I must confess that earlier I used to look at SR funds as a sales maneuver because the SR companies often would emerge under governmental initiative, i.e. not fully open to free market, and SR funds tend to be not such good performers.<p>
JRobin3133:     AL: That is part of the problem with "SR" companies.  You need to dig under the PR veil. Historically, SR managers have been tree hugger driven rather than financially driven.<p>
Almintas:     Sorry, what's "tree hugger"? I am not an American.<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  Someone extreme in their thinking rather than financially savvy.<p>
SANDBOB:     Largest holding, JR?<p>
JRobin3133:     SAND:  Our largest holding is NOKIA (NYSE: NOK.A), telecommuting at its best equals energy savings.<p>
NAPPER214:     I'm becoming interested in the area and topic of a cashless society. One stock in mind Cybercash (NASD: CYCH). Any additional comments?<p>
Almintas:     NAPPER, there are cashless people, but not societies.<p>
Almintas:     What's the fund's turnover?<p>
JRobin3133:     AL:  last year 60 percent.  The more volatility, the greater the turnover.<p>
JHugick:     Just rolling over a 403B, How long should I dollar cost average into the market? (Age 35)<p>
JRobin3133:     JHug:  At least another 20 years.<p>
EstVill:     JR, Are there any Websites you can recommend that cover SR equities?<p>
JRobin3133:     Vil:  Look up www.greenmoney.com<p>
WorthEdit3:     Your criteria includes an environmental screen. What do you look for specifically?<p>
JRobin3133:     Worth:  We look at toxic emission release, water conservation, energy, recycling. Also look at re-engineering of environmental management systems. Sustainable investing, we call it. We seek sustainable solutions to environmental problems.  For instance, we would not invest in a solid waste company because trash=cash.  We look for a solution rather.<p>
KCLTEG:     What is the best thing to invest in?<p>
JRobin3133:     KCL:  Water.  There is only so much of it and the demand goes up everyday.<p>
Tina 57:     How does one invest in water?<p>
JRobin3133:     Tina:  Memtec and Ionics (NYSE: ION) have the best technologies in water.<p>
Tina 57:     Do you invest in Bandag?<p>
JRobin3133:     Tina:  We like Bandag (NYSE: BDG) from an environmental point of view.  Recycling tires makes sense. Problem with Bandag is slowing growth rate.<p>
WorthEdit3:     What are some large companies you *won't* invest in, based on their environmental practices?<p>
JRobin3133:     Worth:  Companies we avoid:  Exxon (NYSE: XON), of course, GE (NYSE: GE), Raytheon (NYSE: RTN), Alcoa. They all have environmental liability, risks and problems. Steel companies, heavy metals are problems areas.  We avoid defense. Another area we like are organic and natural foods.  The industry is growing at 18 percent compared to mainstream supermarkets at 3 percent.<p>
WorthEdit3:     What are some names in that area?<p>
JRobin3133:     The two public companies that promote sustainable agriculture are WFMI and OATS.<p>
Tina 57:     Which do you prefer--WFMI or OATS?<p>
JRobin3133:     Tina:  Today OATS.  It went public at 25 and is now at 14.  Good value and big growth.<p>
KSaplin:     I am so confused in investment the fund market is crazed.... What should I do? How much and where would you invest to get a million in 20 years?<p>
JRobin3133:     KSAP:  Go green, of course.<p>
KSaplin:     What about ConAgra?? Will ConAg sell its beef division and would that make it more or less green??<p>
JRobin3133:     KSAP:  ConAgra (NYSE: CAG).  The problem here is big agriculture, monoculture, chemically dependent food. As well CAG sells well in excess of its growth rate. Watch out.<p>
FRobe10065:     What do you think about JTS?<p>
JRobin3133:     Frobe:  JTS (ASE: JTS) -- It certainly did well today.<p>
Milliams:     I am interested in funds that invest in companies that don't use animal testing.<p>
JRobin3133:     Mill:  We like that but it is difficult to screen for since the FDA requires it in cases.<p>
BMcclin775:     How long do we hold on to Puck?<p>
JRobin3133:     BM:  A triple in 2 months certainly sounds good to us.   Get your bait back!<p>
KSaplin:     What about IBP???<p>
JRobin3133:     KSAP:  BEEF -- IBP (NYSE: IBP) uses growth hormones, methane air emissions, and is energy inefficient.<p>
WorthEdit3:     On a larger scale, what impact do you think green funds can have on companies that aren't using good environmental policies?<p>
JRobin3133:     Worth:  We invest in a category called "best in class" & environmental turnarounds.  Every company can be environmentally responsible if it wants to be.<p>
Milliams:     It seems to me that as long as there are too few green funds, they would have little effect on the overall "green" policy of larger companies.<p>
JRobin3133:     Mill:  Ultimately every good analyst will use a green screen.<p>
Milliams:     That just seems overly optimistic to me. I certainly would long for such analysis.<p>
JRobin3133:     Mill:  We are optimistic by nature but not overly so in this case.<p>
Van thor:     Hello, Jack. Do you have any thoughts about WHFI- Wholesome & Hearty Foods (NASD: WHFI)?<p>
JRobin3133:     Van:  Great product, but only one of them.  No growth.  Look at Worthington Foods (NASD: WFDS).<p>
Tina 57:     Didn't Calvert start the divestiture movement out of South Africa?<p>
JRobin3133:     Tina:  Calvert was a forerunner.  An effective way to bring about change. Environment is next.<p>
Van thor:     Thanks. How can I get a prospectus for your fund?<p>
JRobin3133:     Van:  Web site address :  www.greenmoney.com/winslow. E-mail us from there.<p>
Van thor:     Thanks, I'll send for a prospectus. Do you have any specific sectors in which you concentrate ?<p>
JRobin3133:     Van:  Yes,  water, recycling, technology, telecommunications, alternative energy and sustainable agriculture. One last thought:  Galileo Corp. (NASD: GAEO).<p>
Shapisaac:     Is there any type of general or generic cataloging of green or otherwise socially responsible companies?<p>
JRobin3133:     Shap:  General cataloging....no. That's our opportunity.<p>
WorthEdit3:     Thank you, Mr. Robinson, for taking time to join us for this evening's edition of Conference Call. And thanks to our audience for joining us this evening, as well! <p>
JRobin3133:     Thank you everyone for your good questions.  Go green!!<p>
WorthEdit3:     Tune in tomorrow for Conference Call: Technology '97 at 8 p.m. EST. Thanks again everyone! Good night!

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

