<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 01/15/97 -- Peter Crane, author of "Mutual Fund Investing on the Internet"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Transcripts>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>01/15/97 -- Peter Crane, author of "Mutual Fund Investing on the Internet"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, January 16, Peter Crane, author of "Mutual Fund Investing on the Internet," joined Worth OnLine for a LIVE "Conference Call." During the chat, Crane discussed online mutual fund trading and information. The opinions expressed within are Peter Crane's, and do not necessarily represent those of Worth OnLine, Worth magazine, or Capital Publishing. <p>
WorthEdit1:     Welcome to Worth OnLine! Our guest is Peter Crane, author of "Mutual Fund Investing on the Internet." His screen name is ... PeteCrane, oddly enough. Let's start by talking about some of your favorite online resources. When doing fund research, do you go to one comprehensive site, or lots of smaller ones that specialize in certain types of data. (And don't hesitate to drop names!)<p>
PeteCrane:     I prefer the giants. The little ones may not be there when you check back! http://networth.galt.com is good<p>
WorthEdit1:     What does Networth offer?<p>
PeteCrane:     Fund profiles, NAVs, finance articles, and more. They're integrated with Quicken's financial network www.qfn.com which has insurance, banking, and other info and companies. It's still not a must-see (few on the Web are), but it'll be one to watch.<p>
WorthEdit1:     Okay. What's your second stop on the 'Net?<p>
PeteCrane:     www.fidelity.com and www.vanguard.com have tons of stuff as well. The articles/info brochures alone would take someone a year to read (already up). News is one of the best things to start with when looking for finance on the Web. wsj.com (Wall Street Journal) and www.nytimes.com have great business news. www.bloomberg.com is one for fund junkies and www.cnnfn.com is excellent as well. I must add www.worth.com is great too:-) I haven't fully explored the AOL Worth area, but I will.<p>
WorthEdit1:     Do any of these sites have "cookies"--ie. customized information for each user--yet?<p>
PeteCrane:     Some do, but I wouldn't worry about them (the cookies I mean).<p>
WorthEdit1:     It's easy to get inundated with information. Any suggestions for those drowning in information online?<p>
PeteCrane:     Keep it fast. Go online for specific tasks and info. Check a few URLs, surf a few more, then go read! (for now).<p>
WorthEdit1:     Let's talk a little about message boards before we get back to some good sites.<p>
PeteCrane:     Newsgroups and chats are downright dangerous for taking advice. Always triple check your investment suggestions. There are two big newsgroups misc.invest.funds and misc.invest.mutual-funds, which have some interesting stuff.<p>
WorthEdit1:     Don't you think news ever breaks on a message board before it's out to the general public?<p>
PeteCrane:     I hope not, because that could be insider trading.<p>
WorthEdit1:     Gotcha.<p>
PeteCrane:     But investors should stay far away from rumor nyway.<p>
SSilver400:     Could you discuss the very popular mutual fund service on Compuserve?<p>
PeteCrane:     A lot of fund groups have areas on Compuserve. I avoid it though. I hate the numbers! (e-mail addresses)<p>
SSilver400:     The WSJ did a big article a few months ago about the very popular mutual fund service on Compuserve.<p>
PeteCrane:     I cover Compuserve in my book, but it's about 2 pages (AOL is 10!)<p>
Wayne Gal:     Will all the political hyperbole and rhetoric around the Congress have an impact on the economic situation due to the infighting, and affect the market?<p>
PeteCrane:     I think the balanced budget process, if it happens, will be big and great for investors of all kinds (I think a lot's already priced in though)<p>
Charter4U:     Interested in three fund companies, Putnam, MFS, AIM, any opinions?<p>
PeteCrane:     I like Putnam and AIM.<p>
JMFELAK:     Any opinion on the Biltmore Funds??<p>
PeteCrane:     JM- I'm not familiar. (That's a bad sign though - I don't like small funds, the expenses are usually high.)<p>
JMFELAK:     I'm invested percentage-wise highly in emerging markets.  A good strategy?<p>
PeteCrane:     I'd suggest 20 percent max, even for Mr. Vegas. I'd prefer a diversified international with SOME emerging markets.<p>
WorthEdit1:     AIMoos posted a good question on our message boards: He wants to know how long to hold onto a former high-flying fund that has trailed for a few years. It's the old... "When should I get out?" question...<p>
PeteCrane:     If the fund has done what it said it would (like value, etc.), keep it, else move. I think selling after an area underperforms for a few years is often the worst thing.<p>
SSilver400:     What net sources do you like to help make overall asset allocation decisions?<p>
PeteCrane:     SS- That's the hardest part, and the thing investors should spend 90 percent of their time on. I'm a buy-and-hold forever kind of guy:-) Some sites have allocation tools, but the good ones won't be built until late '97.  I think the old adage: 100 - your age is the best one (stock percentage). If you're 40, put 60% in stocks, etc. Everyone should have bonds, too, contrary to some. Buying and holding has tremendous tax advantages, which few investments can overcome. "Mutual Fund Investing on the Internet" has three chapters on funds and allocation:-)<p>
SSilver400:     Re: no asset allocation sites until late '97-What's causing the delay?<p>
PeteCrane:     No one wants to give the info away (and that's what it takes out there ->)<p>
BILLBO36:     Any thoughts about McDonald's?<p>
PeteCrane:     BI- I prefer funds (except for speculators) but I do like those blue-chips. They can even add diversity to a portfolio of funds.<p>
CKal689:     Name some blue chips you are fond of..<p>
PeteCrane:     CK- I prefer blue-chip funds, like Fidelity Blue Chip Growth or Vanguard US Growth. Any big growth fund will do though. But what the heck, Hewlett Packard, Motorola, and RD Shell!<p>
SSilver400:     Is your book available in bookstores, ...Uncle Pete?<p>
PeteCrane:     Yes, lots of Waldenbooks, Lauriats doing a promo, and of course, www.amazon.com. I can be found during the week at http://www.indexfund.com, the book's site.<p>
WorthEdit1:     Do you prefer any one of the search engines over the others?<p>
PeteCrane:     I've begun to dislike ALL of the search engines; it's a wild goose chase! http://www.hotbot.com (Wired's) and http://www.excite.com are decent though, and Alta Vista.<p>
Wayne Gal:     Everyone should be using ALTAVISTA, it's the BEST.<p>
PeteCrane:     Alta Vista does have tons of stuff. I can't wait until they improve the algorithms, though.<p>
Mondino:     How do you think a stock like SHARPER IMAGE is going to do.  It's listed as $3.20<p>
PeteCrane:     Buy for the long haul -- will the company be around in 20 years.<p>
CKal689:     I'm retiring pretty soon and the choices are overwhelming; any suggestions?<p>
PeteCrane:     Stay balanced, Fido Asset Manager Income or Vanguard Wellesley Income, maybe. But dollar cost average in: move 1/4 first then the rest over 5 years.<p>
CKal689:     Seeing my CFP next week and I'll fly a few things by him. I'll let you know what they are! Or rather what he suggests.<p>
PeteCrane:     Give him hell CK:-)<p>
WorthEdit1:     The Fools like those Index funds. What about you?<p>
PeteCrane:     I'm an index fanatic. I say index everything: stocks (international and domestic), bonds, REITs, cash even!<p>
WorthEdit1:     Your favorites?<p>
PeteCrane:     Vanguard Balanced Index is my favorite all-in-one fund, but Total Stock Market is next. I bet even Fidelity will add to their index lineup in '97 (they have Market Index now, an S&P 500 fund).<p>
WorthEdit1:     Okay, so I've got to ask... There are so many funds underperforming the S & P, why not expend the energy to research individual stocks as long as you're online ferreting about?<p>
PeteCrane:     Because the stockpickers are trailing the index too! Research investment strategies (and life strategies) not investments themselves. As the man said, allocation! Most stockpickers and fund managers will do okay, but they'll have spent a lot of time to hit the mean (someone's got to do it!).<p>
Wayne Gal:     How much of the index is subject to the technology stocks?  Does this distort the index?<p>
PeteCrane:     Way- It's around 10 percent, but they rebalance it occasionally! (Standard & Poor's or whomever's index it is)<p>
SSilver400:     Many investors pay advisors 1-2 percent to run no-load portfolios.  Do you see this moving to net?<p>
PeteCrane:     SS- The whole industry's growing so rapidly, that they'll do well despite the fees. But the cost'll probably be lowered into the 0.5-1.0 percent range (we hope).<p>
WorthEdit1:     So, Peter, do you touch on software at all in your book?<p>
PeteCrane:     Some of the browser and overall PC stuff, yes. I cover the Netscape 3 vs. Explorer 3 battle. I usually use Netscape 3 and Netcome, but do AOL just for the chats!<p>
WorthEdit1:     Soon AOL chats will go across the 'Net, too.<p>
PeteCrane:     Excellent, really?<p>
WorthEdit1:     Yup--saw a demo of the new software. Readers will even get to pick their seats!<p>
Wayne Gal:     What do you look for in the emerging markets funds? What about the emerging technologies?<p>
PeteCrane:     They're two different beasts, emerging markets are international (small countries); and the emerging technologies applications that will impact finance such as BANKING. Emerging technology (or growth) are small US companies. Be careful. A sexy story is always dangerous<p>
SSilver400:     Why can't someone charge .5-1.0 percent for it?<p>
PeteCrane:     SS- I'm hoping to do index allocations for .3 someday!<p>
Wayne Gal:     Grand Casino's  What do you think about the stock in the Stratosphere on the strip in Vegas?<p>
PeteCrane:     I don't like most stocks that've gone up; I'm a value person. Casino stocks especially make me nervous. I wouldn't buy 'em for that fact alone! (the fact they're casinos -- implying gambling) You know their accountants get tempted:-)<p>
WorthEdit1:     What about theme funds--ie. The Internet Fund, The Couch Potato Fund? Too gimmicky?<p>
PeteCrane:     The Internet fund I despise, yes way too gimmicky. Those outfits I wouldn't trust as far as I could throw my 386 (old, of course) :-)<p>
WorthEdit1:     Wow... You feel strongly about this.<p>
PeteCrane:     Those Internet Fund guys didn't even have a website when they issued a release. I savage them in the book (the Kentucky guys). Internet funds are more dangerous than individual stocks. I advise avoiding both (unless it's a tiny portion of a well-diversified portfolio).<p>
WorthEdit1:     Why can't a fund investing in companies that catch trends do well?<p>
PeteCrane:     It can, but trends move like the wind.<p>
WorthEdit1:     So we should all stay with slow, boring funds? ; )<p>
PeteCrane:     For the most part, yes.<p>
WorthEdit1:     What's the riskiest fund you would recommend?<p>
PeteCrane:     Vanguard Index Emerging Markets (I have 25 percent in my IRA) -- at least it's diversified! An aggressive growth, like Fido New Millennium, is okay too for up to 1/4 (max).<p>
AKohli8657:     Can anyone recommend any stocks?<p>
PeteCrane:     AOL<p>
Wayne Gal:     Multi-level marketing seems to be a growth area in this country.  Why haven't we seen some funds investing?<p>
PeteCrane:     That's even before "gambling" on my 'sectors to avoid' list. <p>
Wayne Gal:     Good answer, and I agree!<p>
PeteCrane:     (Though as an index convert, technically I advise investing EVERYWHERE).<p>
RandyM105:     Will Latin America Funds remain strong this year?<p>
PeteCrane:     I think capitalist fever is here to stay, I love 'em, but keep it tiny (10 percent max of portfolio).<p>
KAPAR4:     Starting out - new to investing....would like to go aggressive ...any suggestions in mutual funds?<p>
PeteCrane:     Start with a balanced fund, and move in slowly! Buy Lotto to take your aggressions out. Investing should be most patient!<p>
LLD II:     Your opinion of Fidelity EquitII fund?<p>
PeteCrane:     LLD- It's excellent. Blue-chip, conservative, even some bonds. It's not the time to go aggressive. The market's averaged almost 15 percent in the '90's! If you must buy stocks, at least keep it diversified and conservative.<p>
REBERRY1:     Even though EquitII just changed managers?<p>
PeteCrane:     REB- Yes, the manager matters about as much as two lines of the prospectus. Sector and allocation (and the fact that you're invested) are all.<p>
KAPAR4:     Isn't 15 percent good??  Would it be best to buy current top yielding stocks?<p>
PeteCrane:     KAP- It's a little too good, if you know what I mean.<p>
KAPAR4:     Would now even be a good time to buy in or maybe we should wait till it comes down a tad.<p>
PeteCrane:     KA- It's always a good time to buy, but a little at a time! (Every month is a good time to buy)<p>
LLD II:     We have three utilities - AEP, DOM R, UNELEC - sell or keep?<p>
PeteCrane:     LL- Keep, forever.<p>
LLD II:     RSell and then dollar-cost average in a mutual fund?<p>
PeteCrane:     LLD- I'd diversify gradually.<p>
KAPAR4:     Where to start? <p>
PeteCrane:     Start with a balanced (stock AND bond) fund.<p>
KAPAR4:     Is one investment house better than the other?  T.Rowe or Fidelity?<p>
PeteCrane:     It depends. I like Fidelity better, but T. Rowe is excellent (both are great). (Vanguard is my only other favorite, and USAA).<p>
KAPAR4:     What's the major difference, pro or con?<p>
PeteCrane:     Fidelity is selection, T. Rowe is strong in straightforward and international funds.<p>
KAPAR4:     Got numbers for your picks?<p>
PeteCrane:     Which picks?:-)<p>
KAPAR4:     Vanguard and USAA.<p>
PeteCrane:     See your local newspaper!<p>
KAPAR4:     Wall Street Journal?<p>
PeteCrane:     Section C.<p>
KAPAR4:     thank you:-)<p>
PeteCrane:     (Friday's edition has the 3- and 5-year #'s)<p>
KAPAR4:     How do you like Dunkin Donut stock with the onslaught of bagel intro?<p>
PeteCrane:     Go for it! ;-)<p>
KAPAR4:     Really??????<p>
PeteCrane:     0...<p>
KAPAR4:     What's that mean...?<p>
PeteCrane:     I'd limit any stock to 1-2 percent of overall holdings, but your guess is as good as anyone's. Bagels are spreading like mad ... they even have stores in Holiston, Ma. now.<p>
WorthEdit1:     Thank you for joining Worth OnLine and Peter Crane  for this evening's chat.<p>
PeteCrane:     Thanks and goodnight all! (Excellent)<p>
WorthEdit1:     The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Mr. Crane for being our guest.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
