	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>01/04/97 -- Ken Kurson, the Worth Advocate</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Wednesday, January 8, the Worth Advocate, Ken Kurson, joined Worth OnLine for a live CONFERENCE CALL. Kurson is also the editor of Green magazine, a personal finance magazine for people in their twenties. The following is an edited transcript of the evening's chat. The opinions expressed are those of Ken Kurson, and do not necessarily represent the views of Worth OnLine, Worth magazine, or Capital Publishing.<p>
WorthOnLne:     Welcome to "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live chat show series. Check our site (Keyword: Worth) for a calendar of upcoming events. Our guest tonight is Ken Kurson, who answers readers questions in the Advocate column in Worth magazine. Kurson is also the editor of Green magazine, a personal finance magazine for people in their twenties who never thought they'd actually need a personal finance magazine. He is using screenname "WAdvocate."<p>
Wadvocate:     You are all my children. Speak!<p>
Wadvocate:     Contest: Who can tell me what kind of car the original Allserve vehicle "MacRobbie" was? Winner gets a free subscription to Green.<p>
WorthEdit1:     I believe that this is Ken's way of soliciting questions from the audience.<p>
Golfer903:     Mutual fund hedges for 1997?<p>
Wadvocate:     Who likes Utah minus 5-1/2 tonight against Milwaukee?<p>
Wadvocate:     Good question Golfer. I like Microcaps. Here's why: Traditionally, microcaps are on a 6-8 year bull cycle that trails the bigger caps. After bigs put up two consecutive great years, there's almost no value left in the whole S&P 500. So where does that leave the average investor, who doesn't want to leave a hot market, but can't afford the bigger plays? Answer: microcaps. But it'll be a selective market, especially after so many IPO disappointments.<p>
Golfer903:     Any ones in particular you recommend?<p>
Wadvocate:     Well, I don't wanna get stuck recommending a particular microcap stock.<p>
Golfer903:     Get stuck.<p>
Wadvocate:     OK, OK. One stock I've been following is Specialty Teleconstructors (SCTR). But it's already had a hell of a run (3-14) and I won't say how much more room's left.<p>
Wadvocate:     Firefly, there's a great song by American Music Club called Firefly. <p>
FireFly255:     What is a good home base business to get into?<p>
Wadvocate:     Well, beware of the millions of spams you get on E-mail. Most only enrich the company spamming. Basically, and I hate to resort to clichs, if it sounds too good to be true...<p>
JBLMcBride:     If you also could recommend any specific mutual funds on the subject!<p>
Wadvocate:     I think the Wasatch MidCap is going to come roaring back to life this year.<p>
Mpact2000:     Is there any way to defer a gain from stock to '97 if it was sold in 96?<p>
Wadvocate:     Mpact: No. If you sold in '96, you gotta pay in '96.<p>
Mpact2000:     Trade date is law?<p>
Wadvocate:     Well, you'll get a list of all short- and long-term gains from your broker... I don't think they send it to the IRS, but I certainly wouldn't want that safe hanging over my head.<p>
Golfer903:     How high will the Dow go in '97?<p>
Wadvocate:     Dow '97: 6950. I should add, I think it'll be higher than 6950 mid year, but will close the year around there.<p>
Golfer903:     What mix you recommend for some who just retired?<p>
Wadvocate:     Just retired -- what age, risk tolerance?<p>
Golfer903:     62, medium risk.<p>
Wadvocate:     Well, I'd certainly have to know lots more about your situation, before dishing serious advice, but a thumbnail sketch might look something like 35 percent in a Blue Chip fund, another 10-15 percent in some high-yielding stocks, another 35-40 percent in govvies and the rest in laddered CDs.<p>
Tuku2400:     What's your interest rate forecast?<p>
Wadvocate:     Interest rate: I predict two small increases, totalling .5 percent, in Spring and Fall.<p>
DFMAN:     Any thoughts on high tech...would now be the time to lock in profits?<p>
Wadvocate:     Well, depends what you mean by high tech. If you mean what I call "Blue Chip" high tech (Intel, Motorola, IBM), I see more room and more resiliency to a market downturn. But anyone who's an also-ran in market share's gonna get hammered by the next Nasdaq dip.<p>
JBLMcBride:     Is there a particularly good international fund you would recommend?... Or is a global fund better?<p>
Wadvocate:     My fave international fund is Founders Worldwide Growth. As for international vs. global, I don't think there's so much difference. Basically, so many companies are so diverse geographically, that interests bleed across borders.<p>
PapasPeach:     Married couple -- 30's, self-employed, children's college being taken care of as we speak, on only debt mortgage -- now where do we start???<p>
Wadvocate:     College paid for? Count your blessings! Well, if your house is financed at an acceptable rate, I'd use any extra to finance your retirement, first through tax-deferred options (IRA or Keough)<p>
BRICK069:     What is a world equity fund?<p>
Wadvocate:     World Equity fund means a stock mutual fund that can invest all over the world, including US.<p>
User351575:     How do you feel about the merger between 20th Century and Benham?<p>
Wadvocate:     20th and Benham -- Well, the industry is consolidating as marketing costs and economies of scale make it a survival of the biggest environment.<p>
RMiddagh:     What is your opinion on the future direction of gold?<p>
Wadvocate:     Gold: A decent hedge considering I expect interest rates to go up. But still an underperformer over the long haul.<p>
BD723:     Do you think Raytheon should be bought or held?<p>
Wadvocate:     Raytheon's made some good moves lately, but defense in general's gonna be tough as its biggest customer (um, us!) cuts back.<p>
Pagesix:     Pathetically-performing Far East mutual funds ... hang in or bail out?<p>
Wadvocate:     Far East: Well, I wouldn't invest today, but I might feel differently if I already had. Sorry!<p>
RIMJITA:     How does an annuity differ from a stock or mutual fund and what are its pros & cons?<p>
Wadvocate:     Annuity is an insurance product, attractive only for its guaranteed payout. Mutual funds and stocks are notable for their fluctuations.<p>
Mpact2000:     What do you think about Hilton's new bedfellow Bally?<p>
Wadvocate:     Hilton and Bally: Good idea for a merger but gambling sector going to hit some walls -- where else to go?<p>
PDin2:     Hi! What would you do? Wife leaving company in April, '97. Should she make changes to her 401k account now...or wait till 4/97 to roll-over her mutual funds to an IRA then?<p>
Wadvocate:     It doesn't really matter when she changes her 401K plan.<p>
NITEX7:     What about NIKE?<p>
Wadvocate:     Nike: Great stock. Getting into skates, other clothes. What a juggernaut.<p>
AABordy:     Is ValuJet too risky to consider right now or is their recovery worth a shot?<p>
Wadvocate:     As for ValuJet, I just talked to a former pilot there (laid off after the crash) and he says it's a great company. But as a stock, I think it and SunJet and all the rest are in trouble, from a stock point of view. The other airlines have successfully raised prices and can be so cutthroat on price competition where routes are in competition that it's so hard to be an independent. Yes, Southwest and others can pull it off, but I'm wondering whether even USAir and TWA will survive, let alone Valujet.<p>
RIMJITA:     Does a guaranteed payout on an annuity necessarily mean lower risk with lower return?<p>
Wadvocate:     Annuities almost always mean lower returns than you'd get investing in the same stocks that the annuity holds. That's why they can guarantee the payout.<p>
Pagesix:     If your broker asks for discretionary authority (and has made money for others) would you?<p>
Wadvocate:     I would not give discretionary authority to any broker. But that's me -- some people feel very comfortable with that.<p>
BlimeyFish:     Commodities trading worth it? <p>
Wadvocate:     Commodities can be very "worth it" -- if you've got the time and liquidity to ride out what will inevitably be very big bumps.<p>
JRobin3133:     How do you know if a broker is honest?<p>
Wadvocate:     Honest? Well, a lot relies on the same instincts you'd use to hire any professional -- doctor, lawyer. Check his record through NASD. Get rec's from friends.<p>
Mpact2000:     How about cable TV, modems, and telephony stocks, any favors ?<p>
Wadvocate:     Cable: I like TCI now. Now that Malone's rolled up his sleeves, I don't think many people can touch him. And satellite has started to slow...<p>
Pagesix:     Your opinion of NASDAQ and the bid/asks system that seems to make the NYSE look honest?<p>
Wadvocate:     Well, Nasdaq has worked hard to clean up the discrepancies between the bid/ask and they've gone in the right direction. But there are still more companies on that exchange than on the others that take advantage of its low capital requirements to do stuff that hurts investors.<p>
DTodd61986:     As a participant in an employer profit sharing can you also contribute to an IRA?<p>
Wadvocate:     401k contributors can (and should!) contribute to IRAs. But their IRA contributions won't be tax-deductible (though returns will still be tax-deferred)<p>
CAD92:     If IOMEGA projected sales to be $1 billion why is the stock going DOWN ?<p>
Wadvocate:     Iomega: Cause it was WAY overvalued. Sales are not the only issue; profits matter too. Iomega makes a great product (I own a Zip drive). But it's still a non-diversified line and a way overpriced stock.<p>
SHCOREY:     What does it look like for the GAP?  thanks<p>
Wadvocate:     Gap seems impervious to the retail-sector blahs, but it's a rough sector nonetheless.<p>
TWOCOASTRS:     General question:  should I choose a loaded mutual fund vs. non-loaded?<p>
Wadvocate:     Loaded vs. non-loaded: I say, choose the fund you like best on a total return basis. If it has a load, pay it, if not, double plus good.<p>
Carl7430:     What is the best and easiest to use tax software?<p>
Wadvocate:     Tax software: I'm a MacInTax fan, but that's cuz I'm a diehard Mac user.<p>
SLIMMER:     I wanted to know how far in advanced a person should be thinking about rolling over a 401K<p>
Wadvocate:     By "rolling over" I assume you mean changing companies. Right, slimmer?<p>
SLIMMER:     I'm not sure.  I won't be 59 1/2 for 5 years, but I don't know anything about what I should do when that time comes.<p>
Wadvocate:     Well, you need to start researching, and a financial pro might be a good idea.<p>
SLIMMER:     Is it too soon? I mean, I have 5 years<p>
Wadvocate:     Definitely not too soon, Slim. Make sure to check with NAPFA for credentials on any financial planner, and stick to fee-only guys, rather than those who earn commissions by pushing particular products.<p>
PDin2:     Similar problem as Slimmer, only I have 3 months! Markets up..should I move money to fixed income account now anticipating needing to roll-over or hold on till April? Do I have to pull 401k money out of company account, or can I leave it in the account after leave company<p>
Wadvocate:     If you're 59, PDin2, you should definitely have at least a portion of your dough in fixed income investments<p>
TheMacs:     I need info on research material on technical trading in the market.<p>
Wadvocate:     Technical analysis is hard as hell to pull off, but Jim Dines is a pretty good timer. He puts out a newsletter from California.<p>
Sidney121:     What do you do about a student loan that, quite simply, you just can't pay right now?<p>
Wadvocate:     Sidney, ask for a deferment. Almost always granted. It'll be easier if you contact them before they have to hunt you down.<p>
JammKid:     Fave sectors for '97?<p>
Wadvocate:     Fave sector: Energy.<p>
Badelman12:     Extra 100/month. Should I put toward mortgage or invest in market. <p>
Wadvocate:     I'd invest the extra hunge in the market. Unless your home's financed above 9% or so...<p>
Pagesix:     What percentage of your personal equity holdings in AOL? <g><p>
Wadvocate:     My personal equity holdings, Page 6? Zip! What am I, the Motley Fools?<p>
OGonzalez:     Should I include in my portfolio index funds?<p>
Wadvocate:     Gonzalez, index funds are becoming very popular, as they should after a couple great years in a row. But they'll ride out a dip harder than a lot of non-index funds.<p>
SSQR33:     What's the best kind of investments for starters?<p>
Wadvocate:     For starters, I recommend a growth stock mutual fund -- something like Dodge & Cox Stock.<p>
SSQR33:     But what about stocks so my money can grow with a high interest rate?<p>
Wadvocate:     You don't earn "interest" on stocks SSQ, but you do hopefully get capital gains.<p>
Snaved5:     What about US bonds?<p>
Wadvocate:     Young folks shouldn't overdo it on bonds -- too high an opportunity cost.<p>
PeterDeos:     How do you feel about the natural gas stocks, i.e. CNG, ENE, NFG, etc.?<p>
Wadvocate:     I'm not as crazy about Natural Gas as I am electricity. Watch for dividend cuts closely.<p>
BLACKXBIRD:     Hello again, Ken.  Will publicity kill the "Dogs of the Dow" strategy & similar, you think?<p>
Wadvocate:     No, it won't kill Dogs. Those companies are all in the DJIA and are way too big to be affected by the small money being added because of publicity.<p>
OGonzalez:     What you think about Fidelity Blue Chip stock for '97?<p>
Wadvocate:     I like but don't love Fid Blue Chip. I bought some for my mom and have been pleased but not delirious.<p>
Mpact2000:     What affect do you think Dereg will have on energy producing giants?<p>
Wadvocate:     Dereg's gonna mean lots of juicy buyouts for even crappy co's (Lilco, for ex).<p>
LisaAJM97:     What do you think is the best way to pay off high debts?<p>
Wadvocate:     Pay off high debts: Best way is to pay highest rate debt first.<p>
WorthOnLne:     That concludes this edition of "Conference Call," Worth OnLine's live weekly chat series. Thank you for joining Worth OnLine and Ken Kurson for this evening's chat. The Worth staff extends its appreciation to Ken Kurson for being our guest. A complete transcript of this evening's event will be placed in the Today box on our opening screen early next week. Transcripts from all of Worth OnLine's live chat shows are available in the Worth OnLine Software Library. Again, thanks for joining us this evening. Goodnight.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

