<html>
  <head>
    <title>Demographics and Retirement Investing for the 'Tweener Generation</title>
  </head>
  <body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000">
<table cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5 width=550>
<tr>
	<td width=390>
 <a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Message%20Boards>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>

	</td>
	<td width=150 valign=top> </td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=390 valign=top>
<center>
<p>
<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
<pre>
</pre>
</center>
<blockquote>
    <center>
      <h1>Demographics and Retirement Investing for the 'Tweener Generation</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:AlexNC@cris.com">Herbert Alexander</a> on February 08, 1997 at 15:19:11:<p>
Shouldn't there be an investment paradigm or strategy that addresses the retirement needs of a new generation of investors, the Tweeners?  Today's market is driven by the retirement savings plans of the Baby Boom generation.  Boomers, who are now advancing in years and income, have a tremendous appetite for stocks (and bonds) as they build reserves for the looming winter of retirement years.  This heavy demand by a huge cohort of the population has created the persistent bullish trend of the market.<br>The 'Tweeners, that cohort of the population born between the Boomers and their Generation X progeny, will likely face an entirely different market as the comparatively affluent Boomers begin to convert savings to income for retirement expenses.<br>'Tweeners face the challenge of being in a trough of the population-wave in the US.  With adequate information, they should be able to employ this unique position in a successful retirement-savings and investment strategy.<br>Please offer your comments on this issue. <p><br>
<br>
<p><hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
</blockquote>
</td><td width=150 valign=top>
<center><img src="/imgs/messageyellow.gif"></center>	</td>
	</tr>
<tr><td width=390><center>
