<blockquote>
    <center>
      <h1>A Career In Stocks</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:sunish@udel.edu">Sunish Amin</a> on February 04, 1997 at 22:26:30:<p>
Dear Mr.Lynch,<p>	I am a 19 year old who has been <br>investing in stocks ever since I was in <br>9th grade.  For the past four years, I <br>have managed my parents 401k, IRA, and <br>Savings Account.  The return on my <br>investment in stocks has outpaced the <br>gains produced by the S&P500, DJIA, and <br>NASDAQ INDICIES.<br>	I had made up my mind, since 9th <br>grade, that I want to be a Mutual Fund <br>Manager.  I think about stocks day and <br>night.  In my free time I research as <br>many stocks as possible.  I am aware of <br>the fact that a portifolio manager has a <br>60-70 hour work week and that a M.B.A <br>degree is a must. I know I have the <br>hunger and dedication to do the job and <br>to do the job well, but I would like <br>some of your guidance.<br>	Do you think that attending a top <br>business school is a must? <br>	I noticed that you received your <br>B.S. Degree from Boston College and then <br>you went on to attain your M.B.A from U <br>of Penn.<br>	I am a freshmen at the University of <br>Delaware and I would appreciate it if <br>you could offer me some guidance as to <br>what course of action I should take?<br>	I am very thakful that you have <br>taken your time to read this letter and <br>to offer my gratitude, I give you this <br>stock tip as a small favor.<br>1.	CULP INC.(NYSE:CFI,$16.5)- The <br>company is in a very boring business, it <br>makes mattress tickings.  It is regarded <br>as a cyclical company, but in fact the <br>company is taking the cycliality out of <br>its business by expanding overseas. The <br>evidence of this can be found in its <br>international sales, which are up about <br>35% this year.  Its earnings are growing <br>at 20% and it trades at a PE of about 14 <br>times 96 earnings.	Furthermore, the <br>company just issued 1.6 million shares <br>to reduce its long term debt and to <br>expand production capacity.  The newly <br>issued shares may dilute earnings <br>somewhat in the short term, but the <br>company is positioning to be a big <br>winner in the future.<br>
<br>
<p><hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
