<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:amanda@propartners.com">Amanda Druckemiller</a> on September 22, 1996 at 00:55:00:<p>
People often say that a stock is <br>overvalued if the PE/EPS Growth <br>Ratio is greater than 1.0, and <br>attribute this guideline for value to <br>Peter Lynch.  If you could please pass <br>this request on to him - I would like to <br>understand why this provides a good <br>guideline to a stock's value.  I can see <br>that the PE ratio measures cost per <br>dollar of EPS.  I understand EPS Growth <br>rate, but I do not understand the <br>significance of the relationship of PE <br>ratio to the growth rate.
