<blockquote>
    <center>
      <h1>Investment Education</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:ectj@fhsuvm.fhsu.edu">Dr. Tom Johansen</a> on September 17, 1996 at 14:50:37:<p>
I teach investments at <br>Fort Hays State <br>University in Hays, <br>Kansas.  Last semester in <br>the second level course, <br>Investment Theories and <br>Strategies, we studied <br>theories the first half <br>and strategies of famous <br>money managers the second <br>half.  Each student was <br>assigned a different <br>manager.  They were to <br>complete a written and <br>oral report on that <br>manager.  I referred to <br>these reports as the MMR <br>(The Man, the Method, the <br>Results).  I began the <br>oral reports by <br>presenting Benjamin <br>Graham, Philip Fisher, <br>and Warren Buffett.  The <br>managers the students <br>presented were:  Paul <br>Cabot, Philip Carret, <br>Mario Gabelli, Peter <br>Lynch, George Michaelis, <br>John Neff, T. Rowe Price, <br>Julian Robertson, Jim <br>Rogers, William Ruane, <br>George Soros, Michael <br>Steinhardt, John <br>Templeton, John Maynard <br>Keynes, and Robert <br>Wilson.  What do you <br>think of this approach, <br>since I do not believe <br>that many professors are <br>doing this?  Do you have <br>any suggestions for other <br>managers (or analysts) to <br>study?  Thank you.<br>
<br>

<p><hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
