    <title>ethics</title>
  </head>
  <body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000">
<table cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5 width=550>
<tr>
	<td width=390>
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Message%20Boards>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>

	</td>
	<td width=150 valign=top> </td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=390 valign=top>
<center>
<p>
<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
<pre>
</pre>
</center>
<blockquote>
    <center>
      <h1>ethics</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:danaloha@aol.com">Daniel Berman</a> on September 11, 1996 at 15:01:29:<p>
Dear Mr. Lynch,<br>			I have great respect for <br>you, because beyond being a <br>star stock-picker, you seem <br>to place a high value on your <br>family and on work for <br>charity.<br>    Other stars, like Michael <br>Price, also talk about their <br>concerns with families. Yet, <br>I hit a brick wall even <br>getting a direct response <br>from fund managers like Price <br>or Tweedy, Browne, re the <br>subject of ethics, and <br>specifically Nestle. To my <br>mind, individuals who would <br>find the actions of companies <br>like Nestle abhorrent and <br>unthinkable, can't be <br>bothered to take a moral <br>stance against a company <br>which does what they would <br>never themselves do.<br>    I can understand an <br>argument for tobacco, namely, <br>come on, anyone who smokes <br>has to know the risks. But <br>Nestle was boycotted <br>worldwide by church <br>organizations for their <br>infant formula sales <br>practices. They dressed up <br>their sales agents in third <br>world countries to look like <br>health professionals, and had <br>them push free samples of <br>infant formula on mothers as <br>being healthier than mother's <br>milk. They give enough free <br>samples to last until the <br>mother's milk dries up. These <br>impoverished families then <br>try diluting the unaffordable <br>Nestle formula with water in <br>order to make there be <br>enough. The United Nations <br>estimates one and a half <br>million third world babies <br>die each year as a result of <br>this infant formula <br>merchandising.<br>    Nestle finally agreed to <br>stop the practice. And they <br>did, until the international <br>boycott group disbanded. Then <br>they started again. I noted <br>in the review of Nestle's <br>CEO's book that he says a <br>corporation's only duty is <br>profit and this supercedes <br>any responsibility to the <br>environment or to the world.<br>     I know it's unstylish in <br>the hip, modern world of <br>investing to be impassioned <br>about morals, nonetheless I <br>passionately implore you to <br>explore and discuss both <br>Nestle and other ethical <br>issues in your column.If you <br>do, I would be delighted to <br>locate documentation re the <br>anti-Nestle case.<br>  Thank you for considering <br>my point of view.<p>Respectfully yours,<br>   Daniel Berman<br>
<br>

<p><hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
</blockquote>
</td><td width=150 valign=top>
<center><img src="/imgs/messageyellow.gif"></center>	</td>
