    <center>
      <h1>&quot;Understanding&quot; a business</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:jschwarzie@aol.com">Jeff Schwarz</a> on August 31, 1996 at 20:15:32:<p>
I would like to ask a question in reponse to Worth Online's invitation to ask you <br>questions for future issues:<p>You (and also Warren Buffett), insist that a before you invest in a stock, you <br>must understand the business.  Can you define "understanding" a business?<p>For instance, do you mean understanding how capital is allocated and made,<br>or do you mean understanding the manufacture of the product, or how the<br>service is supplied? What aspects of a business do you need to understand<br>to "understand the business"?<p>In other words, in one of your books, you state that you did not invest in Home<br>Depot because you do not understand tools and housework.  But Home Depot<br>is just a retialing industry; you understand retail, no?  Do I need to know how to<br>manufacture sneakers to invest in a budding retail superstore named "Sneaker<br>Stadium"?<p>I work as a computer programmer.  Do I "understand" the software industry? <br>Or is there more that I need to know?  I am curious about all the aspects of a<br>business that an individual needs to understand to invest in that business.<p>Thank you.
<br>

<p><hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talktoworth/lynch/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
</blockquote>
